<HEADER>
A6390 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PILOTS-F16-AZR &LR;      09-26 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOTS-F16-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOT SHORTAGE MADE WORSE BY F-16 WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Luke Air Force Base is under the gun to churn out more
fighter pilots at the very time when its aging fleet of F-16s is
shrinking and under duress.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's West Valley base, the world's largest for F-16
training, is boosting class sizes to offset one of the worst Air
Force pilot shortages ever. In the past four years, Luke's
basic-training class increased by nearly a third, to 168 pilots
from 113.
</P>
<P>
   And although Luke normally sends up more jets in a day than
other bases do in a week, a continuing string of crashes keeps
grounding the fleet, playing havoc with the &UR; Air Force's stepped-up
training schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Now, questions are being raised about Luke's ability to handle
the increased load while struggling with an unprecedented number of
jet engine problems and its worst accident rate in more than two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to send folks up in airplanes that aren't
safe,'' assured Lt. Col. Bill Gonzalez, commander of Luke's 56th
Training Squadron.
</P>
<P>
   But officials concede the base is in a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, there was a glut of pilots and so few new
trainees that Air Force instructors outnumbered students. Fewer
than 500 new pilots were trained in 1995. This year, the Air Force
wants to train double that many.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials admit that the military underestimated its
future need for pilots after the Cold War ended. It also didn't
foresee the flood of pilots bailing out of the service just as the
U.S. military stepped up its role in overseas conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force estimates it is 200 pilots short of what it needs
this year. &QL; 
LUKE `AT CAPACITY'
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of new F-16 pilot training falls to Luke, though Air
National Guard units in Springfield, Ohio, and San Antonio have
begun training F-16 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Luke officials think they can handle the crush as long as the
base gets the engine parts it needs _ and more jets are not lost to
crashes or mechanical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working at capacity now,'' said Capt. Richard Douglas, a
classroom instructor and pilot at Luke. ``We have cockpits we need
to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, fliers are training in jets that are nearly 20 years old
and increasingly plagued by engine malfunctions that have caused
more than half the recent crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Although in each case the pilots safely ejected, six $20 million
jets have been lost since last fall, and another was seriously
damaged Sept. 20th.
</P>
<P>
   Without extra money to speed delivery of new parts, Luke must
rely on stepped-up inspections to detect potentially deadly
problems. &QL; 
INSUFFICIENT INSPECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Not all those inspections have proved effective, as Air Force
reports obtained by The Arizona Republic reveal.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force investigators faulted Luke inspectors in at least two
of the base's seven recent accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, officials said inspectors either had not installed
or had incorrectly installed a landing-gear pin that might have
prevented the April crash of an F-16 jet.
</P>
<P>
   Another investigative report said the base's inspection
procedures for augmentor ducts were ``ineffective.'' The ducts
provide engine thrust. Cracks in the part were blamed for
back-to-back crashes of Luke jets in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   Duct inspections have recently been improved to a level ``one
step short of a laboratory,'' said the base's commander, Brig. Gen.
John L. Barry. But the more rigorous process forced the base to
ground its entire fleet at once, pushing training back more than a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Each delay leaves instructors scrambling to rearrange flight
schedules and classes so pilots can graduate in time to get to
their next assignments. Pilots can be sent into combat within three
months of leaving Luke.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Air Force higher-ups) consider it our job to meet
timelines, and so do we,'' Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   The base has broken a few traditional practices to accommodate
the time crunch, Gonzales said, including consolidating classes and
sharing resources to allow extra time for inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Barry was the first to fly after each of the recent accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important that they (pilots) know that I'm not going to
put them in an airplane that's not safe to fly,'' Barry said. &QL; 
AGING FLEET
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are questions about the safety of older jet engines
pushed to the limit every day.
</P>
<P>
   Since last fall, there have been 18 military accidents involving
the single-engine F-16s. Luke pilots flew seven of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did bother me some that we were flying with many known
engine problems at Luke,'' said one Luke officer, who requested
anonymity for fear of retribution. ``Why could we not fix them? was
my main concern. I realize the Air Force accepts the risk, but what
bothered me most was: Why could they not accept the responsibility
when a jet went down?''
</P>
<P>
   The most troubling issue involves the augmentor duct, an engine
part used in nearly all of Luke's fighters. The Air Force did not
begin individual inspections of the ducts until a string of minor
mishaps in recent years was traced to cracks in them.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the base completed its first inspections of the
ducts, one of the parts that had been examined fell off a jet
during a February training mission. The jet plunged to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Barry responded by asking maintenance crews to closely
re-examine a duct they had inspected immediately after the duct had
fallen off the other jet. Inspectors found nothing unusual, and the
duct went back into service.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, that jet fell out of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The cause: Cracks in the augmentor duct.
</P>
<P>
   New, more intensive procedures implemented after that second
crash have detected cracks in more than one-tenth of the engines in
Luke's 200-plus jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has set aside $128 million over the next two
fiscal years to deal with those and other problems identified in
the Pratt &AMP; Whitney engines.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert May, the Air Force's propulsion product group
manager, doesn't expect the base to receive any new augmentor ducts
until next spring.
</P>
<P>
   It could take a few years to replace the old ducts with new
versions designed to prevent cracking. Until then, the base will
continue stepped-up inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Barry thinks the inspections will prevent future crashes caused
by the same malfunctioning part.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sept. 20th crash is still under investigation, it
appears to have been caused by an electrical system malfunction,
not the augmentor duct. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jennifer Barrett can be reached at (602) 444-7113 or at
jennifer.barrett(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
