<HEADER>
A6391 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR--GRANDPRIX-HNS &LR;      09-26 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR--GRAND </SLUG>
 PRIX-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Montoya sets track mark in Houston
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It was clear early in the second qualifying session Saturday that
the 1998 track record on the downtown Houston course was not going
to be around by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing to determine was which driver would go fast
enough past the record to win the pole for today's Texaco/Havoline
Grand Prix of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Montoya saw in the slower qualifying session that his time
from Friday would not hold up. Adrian Fernandez beat it to take the
top spot before the faster cars took the track. And Bryan Herta
briefly had the quickest lap during the last qualifying session.
</P>
<P>
   But Montoya was not to be denied, earning the pole with a
track-record lap of 93.651 mph on the 1.53-mile, 10-turn course. It
was the seventh pole of the season for the 24-year-old Colombian,
tying the CART rookie record set by Nigel Mansell in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point (records) don't mean as much to me,'' Montoya
said Saturday. ``Maybe 10 or 20 years from now I will remember them
and say, `That was good.' But for the moment, I'm just trying to
win the championship. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya earned a point for winning the pole and leads Dario
Franchitti by 29 points entering today's race. Montoya can clinch
the FedEx championship if he is 44 points ahead of Franchitti at
the end of the race, but it won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti will start on the outside of row 2 in the No. 27 Kool
Green Honda/Reynard. He was one of six drivers who bettered the
track record Greg Moore set last year (92.377 mph) in qualifying
for the inaugural Houston race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got blocked on my best lap today, when my tires were at
their best,'' Franchitti said. ``After that I was pushing really
hard, but we didn't have the car to get to the front.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez had the pole after the first session with a lap at
91.943 mph, but he knew that wouldn't hold up when the quicker cars
came on the track. Nine drivers would better that speed, and the
first was Montoya on his second lap.
</P>
<P>
   But Herta, who will start next to Montoya on the front row, was
on the pole for a moment when he turned a lap at 93.037 mph before
Montoya had a lap to better him. Then Montoya bettered himself
before the session ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really funky session,'' Herta said. ``I had a good
lap going when Christian (Fittipaldi) went into the tires (bringing
out a yellow flag). I was getting so frustrated that I was yelling
on the radio to Bob (team owner Bobby Rahal) to try to get some of
the frustration out.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tracy was feeling no frustration, improving his starting
spot from ninth Friday to third after the final qualifying session
with a lap at 93.006 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of being on the track at the right time
and being lucky that we didn't get the rain,'' Tracy said. ``I was
able to put together a couple of clean laps without traffic, which
is tough to do here.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of today's 100-lap race could bring back some bad
memories for Team Kool Green drivers Tracy and Franchitti. Because
the race starts on the Austin backstretch, the Kool Green drivers
will be side by side at the green flag as they head for the turn
where they collided last year.
</P>
<P>
   It ended the day for Tracy, but Franchitti went on to win the
rain-shortened event. Montoya thinks that same turn at the end of
the backstretch will be the place to watch today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a couple of crashes on the
backstretch,'' Montoya said. ``If you are not completely beside a
guy, he's not going to give you room on that turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy believes the driver who makes the right braking decisions
today will win the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brakes always are going to be an issue here,'' Tracy said.
``There aren't a lot of places to cool the brakes. You have a lot
of tricky braking zones and it's very easy to slide off into a
runoff area if you're not careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the braking zones are fairly bumpy. You are braking right
at the limit of adhesion. Passing depends on how deep you can brake
going into the corner. Five feet too much and you're not going to
make the corner. You will slide into the barrier or get turned
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya made enough good decisions on the track Saturday to
shatter the course record, but he didn't slow once he regained the
pole over Herta. Montoya's ninth of 11 laps made it clear no other
driver was going to catch him.
</P>
<P>
   His speed was more than six/tenths of a mph better than Herta,
and had a lap time of 58.699 seconds to Herta's 59.086. That's a
huge amount in a sport where hundredths of a second can change your
starting position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could go pretty quick,'' Montoya said. ``We started
out just trying to beat Fernandez's time, then everybody else went
quicker. So I wasn't being conservative. I was close to the wall a
couple of times and I went, `Uh oh.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You never really know if you are on a quick lap on a street
course. You just have to push it. You can't be conservative or you
will start losing time.''
</P>
<P>
   With three races remaining on the 1999 CART schedule, Franchitti
is running out of time in his quest to catch Montoya for the
championship. Tracy was asked if he would try to help his teammate
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing as much as I can to help Dario, but there's not that
much I can do,'' Tracy said. ``Ultimately, Dario has to do it
himself. He has to beat that little guy (Montoya).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
