<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6392 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF--RYDERCUP-HNS &LR;      09-26 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF--RYDER </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Europeans set to sip from Cup
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Ben Crenshaw's American team saved pride
Saturday, but it will take more than competitive juices today to
save the Ryder Cup from another Concorde ride back across the pond.
</P>
<P>
   It will take destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans face a 10-6 deficit going into today's 12 singles
matches. Nobody has ever overcome more than a two-point margin to
win the Ryder Cup on the final day.
</P>
<P>
   Only a dreamer, somebody smitten with passion and patriotism,
and overdosing on reds, whites and blues, would believe anything
other than a third depressing Ryder Cup loss in a row is going to
befall the Americans today. In other words, Crenshaw thinks destiny
might ride shotgun with his team today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to leave you with one thought,'' Crenshaw said at the
end of his postmatch interview Saturday night. ``I'm a big believer
in fate. And I have a good feeling about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, break out the tarot cards and crank up the instant karma.
Call the Psychic Hotline and see if Madam Mystic is available. The
Americans are going to need all the help they can get.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw hasn't given up hope for his team, but just about
everybody else has after the Americans played better Saturday than
they had the previous day, yet couldn't make up any ground on the
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   What we have today in the 33rd Ryder Cup Matches is an
exhibition in the truest sense. The Americans and Europeans will
perform at The Country Club for fun and entertainment in 12 singles
matches.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is at stake, of course. The Cup is lost, unless
three-quarters of a century of history can be rewritten. As the
Americans split four points in the alternate-shot and best-ball
action right down the middle, they found the Europeans' four-point
lead unchanged after a dozen hours of play Saturday. A rowdy crowd
and a few better efforts from the Americans weren't enough to
derail the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Americans) need pumping up, because they're
losing,'' said Colin Montgomerie, who teamed with fellow Scot Paul
Lawrie for an important win Saturday afternoon over Tiger Woods and
Steve Pate. ``And they're losing heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval suggested in the lead-up to the Cup that this was
merely an exhibition because they don't hand out winner's checks.
During the first two days of play, it has been proved in the
Americans' camp that you get what you pay for. Even some disgusted
American fans in the gallery have uttered those very words.
</P>
<P>
   To win the Cup today, the Americans will have to win 8{ singles
points in the 12 matches. Mathematically, it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   But if you believe it will happen, you also believe your next
par-3 will yield a hole-in-one. A collapse today by Europe would
make Choke City look like a minor throat-clearing.
</P>
<P>
   As defending champion, Europe needs only 14 points to retain the
trophy. The Americans must earn 14{ points to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too high a hill,'' said Hal Sutton, who was
responsible for 1{ points Saturday and has been Crenshaw's best
player so far. ``We've shown a lot of fight this week. And I think
we can show some more. I think we've all got some more left in
us.''
</P>
<P>
   European captain Mark James stopped short of saying his team is
in the driver's seat, although it clearly is. But he said his
players have put themselves precisely where they had hoped to be
after two days of team play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a disappointment if we don't (win the Cup) because a
four-point lead is a reasonable lead,'' James said. ``But we're
under no illusions. We know the USA is going to fight back hard. We
have a huge amount of work to do yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But not nearly as much as the Americans if they are to fulfill
their captain's predictions that good things will happen today.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what has Crenshaw so optimistic is he and his team know
how close they are to being much closer to the Europeans. The
Americans had their chances Saturday to make this match tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia and Jesper Parnevik again decked the Americans. In
the morning's alternate-shot play, they beat Payne Stewart and
Justin Leonard 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the most pressure-packed match of the afternoon
best-ball action, they won the 18th hole to square their match with
David Duval and Davis Love III, giving Europe a somewhat unexpected
half-point. It was the difference between a three-point lead and a
four-point lead going into the final day.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia and Parnevik combined to go 3-0-1 in the first two days.
Only Lanny Wadkins and Larry Nelson in 1979 have accumulated a
better score in pairs, winning all four of their matches.
</P>
<P>
   When it wasn't the dyanmic duo, it was Colin Montgomerie
spoiling things for the United States. Though Jeff Maggert and
Sutton beat Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie in the morning match, the
pair of Scots won the 15th and 16th holes to take a 2-up lead on
Tiger Woods and Steve Pate. They closed it out when Woods missed a
six-foot putt down the hill on the 17th that would have sent the
match to the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Phil Mickelson's hot putter had led him and Tom Lehman
to a 2 and 1 win over Darren Clarke and Lee Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning matches, it was similarly sweet-and-sour for the
Americans. They did enough good things to keep pace, but not enough
to make up much-needed ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been part of a team like this before,'' Montgomerie
said. ``We all want to win so, so badly for our tour. This is
fantastic and I really do want to win this thing, I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the fates are in cahoots with Crenshaw, Monty won't be
disappointed today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
