<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6397 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ARENA-AZR &LR;      09-26 3147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARENA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARENA ADS A BONANZA FOR AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NENA BAKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The advertising agent for America West Arena earned at
least $5.2 million in commissions from 1992 to 1998, or about
three-quarters of a million more than Phoenix, which owns the
arena, received for the same period, city records show.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the agent, Terry Pugh of Paradise Valley, and Suns
President Jerry Colangelo formed a side deal, in violation of the
arena advertising agreement, that lasted for 28 months. City
officials were unaware of the joint venture until asked about it by
The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   After a review conducted by city auditors and outside legal
counsel, the city concluded the joint venture _ between JDMK LLC,
in which Colangelo is a principal, and Premier Sports Marketing
Inc., which was owned by Pugh _ had no impact on revenue to the
city. Officials do not plan to seek sanctions, said Jerry Geiger,
deputy director of the Community &AMP; Economic Development Department.
</P>
<P>
   But the business alliance between Pugh and Colangelo, which
began in April 1996 and ended in August 1998, according to Arizona
Corporation Commission records, raises more questions about the
city's stewardship of its $102 million downtown arena.
</P>
<P>
   The city owns the arena and functions as landlord for the Suns,
the primary tenant. The Suns run the day-to-day arena operations
and the city gets a small share of revenue after expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Phoenix Coyotes notified the city that the hockey
franchise would leave the arena unless disputes with the Suns over
financial matters, including advertising revenues that Pugh plays a
role in determining, could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Coyotes, who bring about three-quarters of a million
fans a season to downtown Phoenix, intend to leave America West
Arena by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Previous reports in The Republic have documented how a big chunk
of the $152.5 million the Suns have promised the city in shared
profits is slated to be paid out in the last 10 years of the Suns'
40-year lease. But this raises doubts the city will ever see the
big bucks promised by the Suns because of an escape clause that
allows the team to vacate the arena after 30 years _ if the
facility is deemed obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo and Pugh, whose contract with the arena extends to
2002, said they formed their venture to give Pugh more contacts and
capital to woo new clients. They said the company was kept separate
from Premier, which had the agreement for services at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine the conflict if we had done it any other
way?'' Colangelo said. &QL; 
THE `WIN-WIN' SITUATION
</P>
<P>
   The Suns and the city created a public-private partnership in
1989 in order to build a new arena for the NBA franchise. &QL; 
In his 1999 book, How You Play the Game, Colangelo describes it as
a ``prototype for how a municipality and a sports franchise could
put a deal together that would provide a win-win situation for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Suns and Pugh have emerged as bigger winners than
the city, which contributed $48 million toward the cost of the
arena while the Suns pitched in $54 million.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the city has received a total of $4.4 million in rent
plus its share of cash flow as an advance against future profits
from such operations as parking, signs, concessions, suite licenses
and event rental, according to city records. That's 3.5 percent of
what the city hopes to realize over the life of the Suns' lease.
</P>
<P>
   The city, which has twice audited arena operations, does not
have an employee devoted to full-time oversight of its arena
interests. Geiger said he doesn't believe one is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we put the deals together 10 years ago, we took a lot of
time to enumerate the basic ongoing responsibilities of contract
compliance and information exchange,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With those guidelines in hand, Geiger said ``to have somebody
doesn't make a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But the city's oversight has been lax. For example, questions
raised in June 1998 by city auditors about arena operations were
overlooked until earlier this month, prompted by inquiries by The
Republic.PROVISIONS STAND OUT
</P>
<P>
   Arena documents are about as thick as the Phoenix White Pages
and make about as interesting reading. But the provisions dealing
with advertising revenues stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the 1989 deal with the city, the Suns
organization is allowed to sell all commercial advertising for the
arena, provided the Suns retain an independent advertising agent
who can look after the city's financial interests in sign revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement outlines a compensation schedule for the
independent advertising agent, Pugh's company, that industry
observers describe as a sweetheart deal.
</P>
<P>
   It also allows the Suns and Pugh to determine dollar allocations
within sponsorship packages that affect revenue to the city and the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the advertising agreement gives the Suns and
Pugh the ability to carve up sponsorship packages in whatever way
they choose. They set the dollar allocations for TV, radio, cable,
public address announcements and signs within each package.
</P>
<P>
   A complex formula the parties agreed to in 1989 spells out how
arena revenues are distributed. But a key point is that sign
revenues are the only sponsorship money in which the city and the
Coyotes, who became a secondary arena tenant in 1996, are entitled
to share.
</P>
<P>
   All other advertising sponsorship revenues go directly to the
Suns affiliate that operates the arena. In turn, the operator is
obligated to pay the Suns 60 percent of advertising revenues in
consideration for services performed by the team.
</P>
<P>
   Under this arrangement, the Suns organization pays the agent _
and itself _ for selling sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Meyer, an attorney who represented the city in the original
arena negotiations, said the city insisted on having a watchdog
over sign revenues. An independent agent could make sure the Suns
did not bundle advertising sponsorships in a way that diluted the
value of the ad-sign component to the city, said Meyer, who is now
president of Eller Media Co., an outdoor sign company.
</P>
<P>
   Another protection for the city, Meyer said, was a provision
stating that the agent would be paid solely on the amount of sign
revenues within sponsorship packages. That way, the agent's
financial interests become identical to the city's.
</P>
<P>
   When Pugh and the Suns sell a sponsorship package that includes
radio, TV, cable and signs, ``I don't get paid on anything but the
signage,'' Pugh said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pugh's deal with the Suns, negotiated directly between the
two parties with no city input, pays him commissions that escalate
to 25 percent of gross sign revenues in excess of $1.6 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   That's well above arrangements in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten to 18 percent commissions are dead in the heart of the
typical range,'' said Dean Bonham, president of a sports-business
consulting company called the Bonham Group and a former president
of the Denver Nuggets. ``Twenty-five percent is rarely paid, and if
you get to that range, you've got to think it would be considerably
less expensive to take it in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the dollar mark at which Pugh's commissions top out
should serve as an incentive to the agent to maximize sales. Pugh
said his original projections indicated the Suns would be lucky to
achieve $1 million a year in sign revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the team has done much better than that ever since
the arena opened. Last year, the arena grossed $4.7 million in sign
revenues, and Pugh's agency received about $981,000 in commissions,
according to calculations based on city records.
</P>
<P>
   And because Pugh's commissions are based on gross sign revenues,
his agency gets paid before any other arena operator obligations,
including payments for operating expenses, debt service and the
arena renewal and replacement fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a million dollars a year that's taken out of the
stream,'' said Shawn Hunter, Coyotes president.
</P>
<P>
   Although this arrangement has raised some eyebrows in the world
of sports marketing, city auditors last year questioned another
aspect of the arena advertising agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors could see no guidelines for how the Suns and Pugh
determined sign revenue allocations within advertising sponsorship
packages.
</P>
<P>
   They asked for more information from the operator and the
advertising agent to help them determine the accuracy and fairness
of allocations.
</P>
<P>
   After inquiries by The Republic about the status of the
auditors' requests, Suns representatives met earlier this month
with the city and provided auditors with more information.
</P>
<P>
   City auditors then reviewed 114 advertising contracts and wrote
a report on Sept. 17. In it, they concluded ``that advertising
allocations have been reasonable and consistent.'' &QL; 
INNOVATIONS WORTH MILLIONS &QL; 
All those familiar with Pugh's work say that Pugh has conceived of
ways to make money out of sponsorship packages that had never
before been tried in sports facilities. His innovation ultimately
brought him millions and piqued Colangelo's business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Corporation Commission records show that Colangelo's
investment company and Pugh's agency organized a joint venture in
April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The venture was dissolved in August 1998, records show. But Pugh
and Colangelo said their alliance ended in April 1998. At that
time, said Jay Ruffner, a lawyer for Colangelo, the parties agreed
that Pugh would buy out Colangelo's company for $1.5 million,
approximately the amount that Colangelo and his partners had
originally invested.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Pugh sold Premier to Outdoor Systems Inc., a
Phoenix-based billboard giant, for $26.4 million. Premier is now
known as Outdoor Systems Sports Marketing Inc. Pugh is a consultant
for that business.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffner acknowledged that Colangelo did not inform the city of
his partnership with Pugh. But he said Colangelo and Pugh weren't
trying to hide their partnership from the city. He called the
situation a ``technical violation'' of the advertising agreement
that occurred because of an oversight by his law firm, Fennemore
Craig.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was absolutely no impropriety,'' he said, adding that he
was ``100 percent certain'' that city officials would have OK'd the
partnership had it been brought to their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Modifications to the advertising agreements made when the
Coyotes became an arena tenant diminished Pugh's watchdog role,
Ruffner said. Under such circumstances, Ruffner said, he could
think of no reason why the city would have objected to the joint
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said he is comfortable with the joint venture, even in
light of his watchdog role for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is: `Was there a conflict for any reason?' '' Pugh
said. His answer: ``That had all been thought about and everything
was saying (no).'' &QL; 
COYOTES CONCESSSION
</P>
<P>
   When the Coyotes signed on to play at America West Arena, the
team struck its own advertising agreement with the Suns and Pugh.
</P>
<P>
   The original 1989 agreement, which spells out Pugh's watchdog
role, still remains in place. But as a concession to the Coyotes, a
franchise that was coming into a facility where all the revenues
were spoken for by the Suns, the parties agreed to give the hockey
franchise any increases in existing sign revenues over the base
year of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few caveats:
</P>
<P>
   Advertising contracts that had escalator clauses built in were
excluded from the arrangement so that the Suns could retain the
benefit of deals they negotiated before hockey arrived. This
limited the number of contracts that would provide revenue to the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   And to establish a baseline accounting of existing sign
revenues, the parties retained an independent accounting firm,
Arthur Andersen LLC, which relied on the sponsorship allocations
made earlier by the Suns and Pugh to come up with a figure.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter, the Coyotes president, maintains that since then,
sign revenue increases within sponsorship packages have not
reflected the value of the 700,000 to 800,000 sign-viewing fans
that hockey brings to the arena each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A realistic amount for the advertising increase should be at
least $1.5 million'' over the base year, Hunter wrote in a letter
to city officials last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have received less than $200,000 in signage
increases for their first year at the arena and nothing since
because of unresolved disputes over the amount of the payments,
Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Work done by city auditors seems to bear out the Coyotes
concerns that the value of sign allocations has not changed with
the presence of the hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   City auditors calculated a net increase in sign allocations that
amounted to $195,646 from 1996 to 1997, and $29,710 from 1997 to
1998, according to audit files. Out of 139 signs, there were 18
changes in 1997, and 14 changes in 1998 that resulted in new
allocations, the auditors found.
</P>
<P>
   From 1996 to 1998, the percentage of sign revenue included in
sponsorship packages remained nearly constant at 23 percent to 24
percent, auditors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, we saw a slight upward slope in sign
revenues,'' said Randy Spenla, the city auditor who conducted the
recent review. ``We did not see anything to indicate that sign
revenues were significantly higher with the Coyotes in the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo maintains that the Coyotes have benefited from a
sweetheart lease and other concessions. One such example: The
hockey team keeps all the revenues from signs it sells around the
second level of the arena bowl. He said complaints by the Coyotes
are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   But Colangelo was less than pleased when the hockey team turned
down an offer from Premier Sports Marketing LLC, Pugh and
Colangelo's joint venture, to represent the Coyotes as the team's
agent for signs at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   For the Coyotes, another sticking point at the arena is the
increase in the number of exclusive advertising-rights categories
sold by the Suns. One way to enhance the value of sponsorships is
to have only one soft-drink company or bank, for example, allowed
to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter told the city that the granting of exclusives
significantly limits the number and types of advertisers available
to the Coyotes and led to $2 million in lost revenue in the 1997-98
season alone.
</P>
<P>
   But Colangelo said the Suns aren't trying to hurt the Coyotes by
adding exclusive categories of advertisers. Instead, he said, the
arena operator relies on that revenue to help meet the demands of
operating expenses, debt service payments, refurbishment and other
calls on net cash flow that the Coyotes, as a secondary tenant,
don't have.
</P>
<P>
   With the two sides at an impasse, the Coyotes intend to pack
their pucks and move to Scottsdale, pending financing and voter
support for a proposed new arena that would anchor a redeveloped
Los Arcos Mall.
</P>
<P>
   And if they go to Scottsdale at the end of the 2000 season, the
Coyotes are obligated to pay the Suns $2.5 million as a termination
fee.
</P>
<P>
   The money, according to the city, would be treated as arena
revenue in which the city shares.
</P>
<P>
   City records include copies of two letters from Sheryl Sculley,
assistant city manager, to the Coyotes. In November 1998, Sculley
assured the Coyotes that ``the city of Phoenix wants the Phoenix
Coyotes to continue to play hockey in America West Arena.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're anxious to work with you and the arena management to
ensure that you continue to play hockey in downtown Phoenix,''
Sculley said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter said the city can only take things so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be the owner,'' Hunter said, ``but they're not the
operator, and at some point it's out of their hands.'' &QL; 
NO RESTRUCTURING SOUGHT &QL; 
In hindsight, it appears city officials weren't holding the
sharpest of pencils when it came to signing up for a deal that
wasn't more precise about how advertising sponsorship allocations
would be determined.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials said they have not asked the Suns and Pugh to
restructure the advertising agreement, which might bring Pugh's
commissions in line with current market rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact the independent agent has been successful is a
positive for the city, not a negative,'' Geiger said. ``The agent
has contributed significantly to the fact that gross advertising
revenues from the arena have far exceeded all projections.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo, who agreed to revise the arena operating agreement in
1994 to increase the city's share of cash flow, said he is not
inclined to restructure the agreement with Premier.
</P>
<P>
   ``To change the deal because we pay out a lot of commissions,
that's unfair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, he does not expect the arena operator to renew
its contract with Premier, now Outdoor Systems Sports Marketing
Inc., when it expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, however, remains troubled by the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either the stupidest business deal in the world,'' he
said, ``or something funny is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Pugh disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   The way he sees it, Premier's work at America West ``set a lot
of firsts'' in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   He said he contributed designs, carved out sponsorship packages
and ``floated the whole thing'' for three years before Premier
received its first commission payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a bad deal for somebody to do,'' he said. ``I'm not
ashamed of that or I don't feel bad about it. If you look at the
dollar figures, it makes sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffner, Colangelo's lawyer, said Pugh's commissions now seem
outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we any inkling how profitable it would be, I don't think
we would have given Terry the deal we did,'' Ruffner said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Pugh's joint venture with Colangelo, Ruffner said no
conflict existed that would have been detrimental to the city or
the Coyotes. Ruffner said the modifications to the advertising
agreement that took place when the Coyotes arrived at the arena
made the hockey team the beneficiary of all new sign revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think you might get some great big scandal because
there was money being funneled off into somebody's pocket, all that
money belonged to hockey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said the issue for the Coyotes is that the franchise is
getting ``squeezed on both ends,'' which, he added, may have
something to do with the partnership between Colangelo and Pugh.
</P>
<P>
   On one end, ``we're not seeing as much of an increase over
baseline (sign) revenues as common sense says we would,'' Hunter
said. On the other end, the Suns are selling more exclusive
advertising categories all the time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're not very smart and signed up for a bad deal,''
Hunter said. ``Or maybe it's an odd partnership.'' &QL; 
Nena Baker can be reached at (602) 444-8256 or at
nena.baker(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
