<HEADLINE>
PARKING SPACE WARS PIT BIG VS. LITTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In these acres of asphalt in this central Phoenix
parking lot, Karen Owens circles the rows of cars, searching for
the perfect spot wide enough to fit her Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   She sandwiches the Explorer between two other sport-utility
vehicles and gingerly edges out, carefully holding the door to
avoid dings and to keep from brushing her tiger-print blouse on the
dirty Blazer just 18 inches from her.
</P>
<P>
   This is about big cars in small spots.
</P>
<P>
   As vehicles continue to expand _ Ford's newest, the Excursion,
could be used as a small bus _ and parking spots have shrunk to
compact sizes (more cars per row equal more shoppers in the store),
the battle between the SUV and the car has developed into its own
asphalt class warfare. Big Vehicle drivers circle and circle,
enviously eyeing the munchkin spot at the end. Little Car drivers
prowl around, seeking those nooks and crannies, hoping they won't
be squashed like bugs when they try to climb out of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, an advertising executive from Phoenix, knows to say no to
compact spots. To avoid spaces next to the other mammoth cars that
encroach on her space. And how to find that special spot where she
can exit without holding her breath.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years she's developed these skills, as have the
hundreds of thousands of Americans who own pickups and SUVs. The
nation's desire to haul its children, dogs and home-improvement
projects clearly outstrips its need to use less gas and pave less
ground. And the nation's retailers, which over the years have
shrunk parking spaces by 6 to 12 inches, have only made the squeeze
tighter.
</P>
<P>
   So, it would seem that Phoenix's move this year to increase the
size of its average parking spot would solve everything. You'd
think that adding a half-foot of space would land us in parking
space paradise. Turns out, however, that this is about more than
door dings.
</P>
<P>
   It's about what we value in society and about what the car means
to us. It's the reality that, although we've pursued what we want _
the bigger, the perceived safer and better and more insular _ we've
run out of room. We've moved too close to the white line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always looking for the big parking space,'' says Linda
Lopez, who as a senior engineering technician for Phoenix reviews
and approves new parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't like those little ones, you try to get in them
and they're so small,'' says Lopez, who drives a very big Mercury
Grand Marquis. ``You can't get in. Then if you do, you can't get
out of your car.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix upped the parking spot by 6 inches, increasing the
standard spot at busy, commercial businesses to 9 feet by 18 feet,
which may not seem like much until you find yourself wedged between
two Suburbans.
</P>
<P>
   The compact spot, at a tight 7{ feet by 18, may all but
disappear in new Phoenix parking lots, added only after malls and
stores meet the required number of regular-size spots. The compact
spot was one of the remaining legacies of the energy crisis, a time
when America was taught to feel greedy and irresponsible if it got
anything less than 30 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the new spots to 9 feet lets Phoenix catch up to the
other freeway-dependent city of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, it leaves it behind Glendale, the city that never left
those gas-guzzling '60s and never adopted the mini, compact spot.
Glendale's monster spaces still reign, at 10 by 20 feet. Phoenix is
now more similarly sized to Chandler, Scottsdale and Mesa, and even
a little bigger than Tempe, which at 8{ feet is now the stingiest.
</P>
<P>
   The differences are not lost on Molly Hood, a planner for
Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my apartment complex in Phoenix the spots are so tiny, my
doors are constantly getting bumped,'' says Hood, who drives a
little Plymouth Laser. ``But in Glendale, in Glendale the spots are
huge. You can tell when you pull in.''
</P>
<P>
   Although parking spot size may be a big concern, mall managers
don't see it as priority, especially after seeing would-be shoppers
circling their lots at Christmastime and realizing that shaving a
few inches off each spot translates into a few more spots for
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always are talking about how there's not enough
parking,'' says Paul Sauer, vice president and general manager of
Arizona Mills mall. ``No one ever complains that the spot isn't big
enough. They're just happy they find one.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is true to a point. But drivers of Big Cars and Small
still often will skip spots where a Big Vehicle is too close to the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any spot where I have to squeeze to get out,''
Owens says.
</P>
<P>
   And Katrina Murray often finds herself parking her minivan
off-center, simply to accommodate a Big Vehicle next to her,
forcing her to become an enabler to the Big Vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the spot is too narrow and a car is too close, you have to
scoot over,'' says Murray, 35, from Chandler. ``You don't want to
hit any doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Kohler tries her best to always park her Suburban
exactly in the middle, leaving as much room as she can to
accommodate smaller cars. She feels she has no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get into the spot, you can fit in, but then, you can't
really get out,'' says Kohler, noticing the slim foot of space left
after carefully parking the Suburban (two tries). ``It's bad. Bad
for me and bad for the little cars, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohler turns sideways as she climbs out of her Big Vehicle, the
silhouette of her five-months pregnant belly barely visible.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to one other, pressing issue. Cars keep getting
bigger, but so are we. No, we aren't all five months pregnant, but
studies say Americans are bigger than we've ever been; movie
theaters and sports stadiums are increasing their seat width and
restaurants are enlarging their booths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wondering what it will be like in a few months. Will I
fit?'' she wonders. ``Will it just add to the challenge?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laura Trujillo can be reached at (602) 444-8891 or at
laura.trujillo(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
