<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FALL TELEVISION SEASON IS UPON US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The story of how David E. Kelley named the private
detective agency in his new show, Snoops, tells you something about
how his mind works.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Glenn Hall agency. Hall was a hockey player. So, one
might assume, this is an homage to him.
</P>
<P>
   No. This is why Kelley, creator of the Emmy-winning Ally McBeal
and The Practice, is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn Hall is the one who let Bobby Orr score to win the
Stanley Cup for the Bruins,'' Kelley, a big hockey fan, said this
summer. ``Bobby Orr was my favorite hockey player. I always like to
give credit to the one who helped out.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that anecdote is a lot more interesting than
Snoops is.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley is television's golden boy. Ally McBeal and The Practice
won Emmys for best comedy and best drama this year _ the only time
one producer has been so honored for his work. He famously writes
nearly every word of both shows (a rarity in TV writing), longhand,
on a legal pad. (He's a former lawyer; old habits are hard to
break.)
</P>
<P>
   And he knocks off by 6 p.m. ev ery day so as to spend time with
his wife and children. His wife is Mi chelle Pfeiffer. Excellent
placement of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Snoops won't tarnish Kelley's reputation _ it would take a
Robert Downey Jr.-type meltdown to do that. But it won't add any
polish to his sheen, either.
</P>
<P>
   It stars Gina Gershon and Paula Marshall as unconventional
private detectives. They're a couple of red-hot babes.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the phone before you brand me a sexist pig. Their
attractiveness is a big part of the story. In fact, when Marshall's
character, a (rela tively) straight-laced police officer looking
for a job, shows up at Ger shon's door, Gershon sounds disap
pointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize,'' she says, ``but over the phone you sounded less
at tractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gershon and Marshall and their cronies use all sorts of
high-tech gizmos in their work. How, one might ask, can Gershon's
character afford such expensive toys? By once promising to have sex
with a man who kidnapped a billionaire's kid, we're told.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, I got the kid back when the police couldn't,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   I don't recall Sgt. Friday using that particular technique.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Snoops snoops use all manner of unconventional
ploys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bug people,'' Gershon ex plains to a skeptical Marshall.
``We break into their houses. We steal their Social Security
numbers. We're not police. We have more in com mon with the
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   They also have more in common with Charlie's Angels than Ally
McBeal or The Practice.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of leering and flirting in Snoops. It's the only
show I've ever seen that makes use of, and I'm quoting Gershon
here, a ``nipplecam.''
</P>
<P>
   The best chance Snoops has for survival is as a guilty pleasure.
With the emphasis on guilt, not pleasure. Kelley's association and
leading into The Practice will only attract view ers for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Snoops is a nice companion piece with The
Practice because it is so different,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   It is different. The Practice is ac tually good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new Sunday night shows:
</P>
<P>
   Third Watch: Although there is plenty of action, plenty of plots
and plenty of actors in this ensemble, the much-hyped drama from
John Wells, of ER fame, doesn't measure up to his previous hit. The
charac ters just don't mesh. This is actually a bad sign for ER _
it makes you realize how much that show de pends on chemistry to
work. With George Clooney gone and Julianna Margulies and Gloria
Reuben going after this season, the prognosis is grave.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm in the Middle: By far the best new Sunday night show.
Frankie Muniz is great as the title character, a sort-of normal kid
who is discovered to be a genius. So why haven't you heard more
about it? Because Fox isn't debuting its best new show till
January, after football. Guess there's no danger of the net work
bigwigs being revealed as ge niuses anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Jack and Jill: Young adults struggle to grow up. This is the WB,
so young beautiful adults, nat urally. But you could have guessed
that. The twist: Jack's a woman, Jill's a man. Act surprised. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
