<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6400 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      09-26 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMILY, LOVING THE ZZZZ-
 BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - They're the Osmond Brothers of the National League. In
the rock and roll world of profes sional sports, they're Lawrence
Welk. If the Arizona Diamondbacks were a television show, it'd be
Father Knows Best. If they were a book, it'd be the Boy Scout
manual.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As individuals, on and off the field, they're all very good, all
very nice. And because they won their division and may go all the
way this year, sports writers and TV commentators across America
want to know why they're not hearing frenzied shouts of joy from
Diamondbacks faithful.
</P>
<P>
   To which I'd respond, ``Shhhhhh. You'll wake them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe we lack fervor because the team is new.
They say folks in Phoenix haven't had enough time to build a
relationship with the Diamondbacks and, therefore, have no sense of
emotional attachment.
</P>
<P>
   That's not true.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe the team, as well as the city, hasn't
``suffered'' enough. They say by becoming a contender in only its
second year of operation, the Diamondbacks have spoiled us, al
lowed us to become apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't it, either.
</P>
<P>
   Still more theorists hold that base ball isn't what it used to
be, or that it's difficult for regular folks to relate to teams
nowadays because players come and go, or even that the more
contested division races are getting all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   No. No. And no.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it'd be best for all concerned if this needless
conjecture simply stopped. But I'm afraid it won't.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, they won't let sleeping fans lie. &QL; 
DESTINED TO BE SNOOZER &QL; 
So, we might as well admit it. This absolutely fabulous baseball
team, this (yawn) record-setting champion ship contender, this . .
. (I'm sorry, where was I?) . . . (Oh, yeah) . . . this All-Star
filled lineup whose success has made major league history is a
little . . . zzzzzzzzzzzzzzzz . . .
</P>
<P>
   Dull.
</P>
<P>
   It was destined to be so. From the very beginning, Diamondbacks'
Managing General Partner Jerry Co langelo said he wanted players
with ``character.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Diamondbacks analyst Bob Brenly said, ``(Critics) were
thinking the Diamondbacks were way off base. But you can have both,
good players with good character.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure you can. But why?
</P>
<P>
   Guys in the real world not only tolerate a little bad behavior
from professional athletes, we COUNT on it. How can we live
vicariously through a bunch of millionaire jocks who behave like _
us?
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking, for example, of players like former pitching great
Tug McGraw, who, when asked if he preferred AstroTurf or grass,
report edly replied, ``I don't know. I never smoked AstroTurf.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson scowls, but only at batters. Brian Anderson
appears mis chievous, but in an innocent, boyish way.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have real charac ter, but no real characters.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the team features a bunch of kind, hard-working, really
swell fellas intent on rewriting the book of inspirational cliches:
</P>
<P>
   ``The meek shall inherit the pen nant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The early bird catches the line drive in the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All work and no play makes Jack a professional prospect in
Arizona.'' &QL; 
REMEMBER SUNS FEVER?
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, 300,000 screaming fans swarmed downtown
Phoenix in the blazing heat to celebrate the Suns basketball team.
They did so for three reasons.
</P>
<P>
   1. The team almost won a champion ship. 2. Charles. 3. Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying we want guys like that on our baseball team, only
that the press shouldn't panic because Arizonans who suffered
initially from ``baseball fever'' appear to have slipped into a
coma.
</P>
<P>
   We're happy with the Diamond backs. We shelled out over 200
million bucks for the team's stadium, for which we were promised a
winner. Now, we have no reason to complain.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the cliche says: You made your ballpark, now sleep in
it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
