<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLASIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROQUES' ROCKY DAY IS HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ How does it feel to get beaten on the longest
pass play in Pacific-10 history?
</P>
<P>
   UCLA safety Ryan Roques wants a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Roques, who spent much of Saturday's 42-32 loss to Stanford at
his former position, cornerback, desperately tried to contain
Cardinal receiver Troy Walters. He failed.
</P>
<P>
   Walters caught nine passes for 278 yards and three touchdowns.
Of course, they weren't all against Roques _ just the one everyone
will remember.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA was in zone coverage on the play, so Roques started toward
the tight end. Then he saw Walters break free, moving right to
left, but he arrived too late to defend the pass. Walters caught it
and outran Roques to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Walters also beat Roques on an 18-yard touchdown pass late in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself making big plays, but I didn't get it done like I
think I should have,'' he said. ``It was a little tough at
cornerback, but I have no excuses. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Walters made a lot of big plays. A lot were against me and a
lot were against other cornerbacks. I wish I could play him again,
because I think I would have a better game than had today at
cornerback.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems each season the Bruins' secondary is in disarray.
Junior cornerback Marques Anderson has been suspended for the fall
quarter, and senior cornerback Jason Bell is out with a heel
injury.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, two freshmen, Joe Hunter and Ricky Manning, were
left to combat Stanford's potent passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   After Hunter was beaten repeatedly by Walters, Roques moved over
and reserve Eric Whitfield took Roques' safety spot.
</P>
<P>
   The changes did little good, but until Bell returns, the Bruins
have few options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason could help us,'' Roques said. ``But once again, I'm a
fifth-year senior, and I should be able to make the plays wherever
they need to be made. I've got to have a better game than this at
whatever position I play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
