<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL IS WELL WITH NEBRASKA _ AT LEAST FOR A WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ Considering that the streak stretched to 21
consecutive Nebraska victories over Missouri, the snapshot reaction
is ``Big deal. Doesn't Nebraska always beat Missouri?''
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't your father's _ or even your older sibling's _
Nebraska. Sure, the Cornhuskers slapped down a hopeful Mizzou team
that really, really, really, ``really'' believed it could pull off
the upset. Nebraska 40, Missouri 10 continued the Huskers'
dominance in this series. The Tigers' last victory came in 1978 in
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   After two woulda-coulda-shoulda losses to Nebraska the past two
seasons, Missouri was jazzed and geeked for this game. Fans were in
position three hours before kickoff. Traffic construction signs on
I-70 flashed ``Expect Delays. Go Mizzou.'' The Tigers' ``We
Believe'' attitude was buttressed by the belief that these
Cornhuskers were vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   And that's because Team Turmoil had totaled 486 yards in offense
in its past two games. In the season's first month, a quarterback
controversy evolved into a quarterback change and a go-to running
back became a left-the-team running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since two-a-days started, it's been one thing after
another,'' junior wide receiver Matt Davison said. ``This is the
first week we really haven't had any controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   And last night, they didn't get a game from the Tigers (2-1).
The Huskers' first 16 points arrived in Black and Gold packaging.
Consecutive high snaps on punts and an interception staked Nebraska
to a 16-0 lead in the first quarter. And, with Missouri alternating
two inexperienced quarterbacks, the Tigers were incapable of
mounting a serious rally. Missouri entered the game second
nationally in rushing with 310 yards per game; it finished with 25
rushing yards and 174 total yards.
</P>
<P>
   In his second season, Frank Solich has the Huskers 4-0 and
ranked No. 6. National championship hopes are still intact. The
defense, which is ranked ninth nationally, is capable of shutting
down any opponent.
</P>
<P>
   And give Solich credit for admitting a mistake that had hobbled
his offense. Choosing Bobby Newcombe over Eric Crouch at
quarterback was wrong. After two games, Solich reversed his field
better than Johnny Rodgers on a punt return. With Crouch at
quarterback, the Huskers have someone who understands the sleight
of hand needed to run the option.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no guarantee that Nebraska's traditional
grind-out-the-yards running game is present and accounted for. The
Huskers finished with 333 yards rushing and 446 yards in total
offense, but they had to pass to set up the run; five of their
first 11 plays were passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed the kind of offense we can be tonight,'' Davison
said. ``We're not one dimensional. In the past, we could run the
ball and it didn't matter what the other team did. We can't block
nine defenders with six. We realized we needed to mix it up a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this season, the Huskers got 100 yards from a
back. Junior Correll Buckhalter, a career backup, gained 132 _ and
57 yards came late in the third quarter against the run-down
Tigers. Crouch is the team's leading rusher with 245 yards. Can the
Huskers' challenge for a national title _ or even the Big 12
Conference crown _ without a quality I-back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, you want a very good line and very good running
backs,'' Solich said. ``If you don't have one of those, you're in
trouble. We've got good linemen, good backs and good receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelo Evans was expected to be this season's I-back star, but
he spit the bit and quit the team in a huff. He left complaining of
conspiracies and being neglected. Heaped on top of the quarterback
switch, Evans' inelegant exit created quite a stir among the
Children of the Corn. Slapping down the Tigers by 30 points helped
restore order. For one game, at least.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
