<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-ARKANSAS-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU RIDES TOMLINSON'S CAREER-HIGH 269 YARDS TO NARROW VICTORY ON
ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ark. _ TCU football coach Dennis Franchione walked up
the locker room steps last night and looked straight in the eyes of
running back LaDainian Tomlinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I give you the ball enough tonight?'' Franchione asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sure did,'' Tomlinson said. ``I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs are thankful for Tomlinson today, because the
5-foot-11 junior running back carried them to their first victory
of the season, 24-21, against Arkansas State at Indian Field with
his finest night as a Frogs player. Tomlinson finished with a
career-high 269 yards on a TCU all-time high of 40 carries. He also
scored two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson's 79-yard touchdown run on the first play from
scrimmage was the longest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they handed to me the first five plays of the game, I
knew what the game was going to be like,'' Tomlinson said. ``I knew
the game plan. It was to run me. I knew I had to have a big game.
It was fun, then the defense stepped up for us late.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked as if TCU (1-2) would pull away from the
winless Indians (0-4) after taking a 21-7 lead in the first
quarter, the Frogs needed defense and Tomlinson again in the fourth
quarter to get the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas State, which got 155 yards from sophomore running back
Jonathan Adams, scored two touchdowns in the second quarter to get
within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 24-14, the Indians recovered a LaVar Veale fumble on a
punt to take possession at the TCU 15-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   A pass interference call against TCU turned an incomplete pass
on third-and-12 into a first-and-goal at the 2. After a rushing
play for a loss, ASU quarterback Cleo Lemon hit Jacquis Walker in
the left side of the end zone for the touchdown to cut the lead to
24-21 with 2:46 left in half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm especially proud of the way we played defense in the
second half,'' Arkansas State coach Joe Hollis said. ``I've seen
14-point spreads turn to 28-point spreads and that didn't happen
with this football team. I'm sorry we're 0-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team, including the 18-point favorites from TCU, moved
the ball effectively in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Frogs needed two defensive stands in the fourth
quarter, they got both. TCU stopped Arkansas State at midfield
early in the quarter with an interception by Terrance Maiden. The
Indians' next drive was stopped by sacks from Aaron Schobel and
Maiden.
</P>
<P>
   TCU got the ball within the final two minutes with a chance to
run out the clock deep in their own territory.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-eight from their own 19, the Frogs handed to
Tomlinson. He picked up 9 yards for the first down. By the time TCU
did have to punt, only 19 seconds remained. Arkansas State tried
three sideline passes, but all were defended and incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   A final pass deep down the field with two seconds left was
batted down by the Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that 21-7 was not comfortable,'' Franchione said. ``We
knew we needed to score more points. When we didn't score the first
time or two in the third quarter, I was a little worried because we
hadn't slowed them down much either.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RLaDainian\S played very well. The last first down we got was
a great effort by him. He had a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson had three rushes of more than 30 yards nullified by
penalties. Overall, TCU had 14 penalties for 135 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penalties have hurt us some this year,'' Franchione said. ``We
rip off a big gain, then all of a sudden it's coming back. It's
something we've got to address.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
