<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS A WIN AWAY FROM AL WEST TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The defending American League West champions
sent their overachieving challengers from Oakland face-first into
the canvas for the second time in as many evenings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics should be reminded that the three-knockdown rule
is in effect. Only an A's.MDRV/[ .MDNM/-whoopin'.MDRV/]
victory.MDNM/ this afternoon separates the Rangers from clinching
their third AL West title since 1996. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers reduced their magic number to one with last night's
10-4 victory at The Ballpark in Arlington, and their eight-run
second inning _ consummated by Todd Zeile's grand slam off
right-hander Kevin Appier (15-14) _ forced the A's to return to
their corner for yet another standing-eight count. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to come in and play better than we did,'' said
left fielder Rusty Greer, who alluded to the Rangers' four losses
in five games to the sub-.500 Tampa Bay Devil Rays and Baltimore
Orioles earlier during this homestand. ``We knew this was a big
series, and we wanted to play our brand of baseball.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have, and it should come as no surprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the real test of this team has been how we play
against the tough teams that are winning,'' said Zeile, whose slam
gave the Rangers and right-hander John Burkett an insurmountable
six-run lead. ``When it comes time to strap it on, we seem to rise
to the occasion.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did it.MDRV/[.MDNM/ during.MDRV/] in.MDNM/ September
1998 with five consecutive victories against the Anaheim Angels and
earlier this.MDRV/[.MDNM/ August.MDRV/] season.MDNM/ with 10
victories during a 13-game stretch against Cleveland, Boston, New
York and Toronto. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burkett (8-8) responded, too, after surrendering three runs (two
earned) before escaping the first inning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't looking good early, but I always have confidence
that I'm going to get the job done,'' Burkett said. ``I also had a
lot of help tonight. You can't underestimate the effect of the play
Mark McLemore made. That was the huge play in the game.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McLemore robbed center fielder Rich Becker of a one-out,
second-inning single with a diving stop and started a 4-6-3,
inning-ending double play. From there, Burkett coasted before
departing with a 10-3 lead after seven innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It responds to urgency,'' closer John Wetteland said. ``The
problem is if you rely on that, it will let you down _ most
assuredly. So, I'll take consistency over something like that. Now,
defending ourselves, we've .MDRV/\R.MDNM/been
consistent.MDRV/\S.MDNM/ all year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we needed this series. Yes, it's a case of us rising
to the occasion, but you can't rely on that only. You have to have
that we're-going-to-bash-your-brains-in-tonight attitude, too.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The A's can attest to the Rangers' proficiency in that area
after 12-4 and 10-4 losses the past two.MDRV/[.MDNM/
evenings.MDRV/] nights.MDNM/. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won anything yet, but when we do,'' Wetteland said,
``we should have anyway. We should be where we are right now. I can
understand getting all excited about it and everything, but what
lies ahead is long and arduous.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland alluded to the postseason, of course, where the
Rangers need to reach the next level. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have visions of the playoffs last year,'' Wetteland
said. ``I don't like it. I don't like it one bit. I prefer to
remember last year's playoffs and how humiliating that was.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers can turn their attention toward rectifying that with
a victory this afternoon. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
