<SLUG> BC-GLF--BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Europe's Junior, Jesper dance to a different beat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ If you came upon them someplace other than
the snooty, manicured grounds of The Country Club, you might expect
them both to be riding skateboards.
</P>
<P>
   But as Europe seems to roll inexorably toward another convincing
Ryder Cup victory, Sergio Garcia and Jesper Parnevik are instead
the ones driving the steamroller. Junior and Jesper.
</P>
<P>
   Based on appearances, they are about as intimidating a pair as
Laverne and Shirley. One doesn't have his high school diploma and
the other wears the goofy hat that makes him look like he took a
wrong turn during the Tour de France. But together they're deadlier
than Smith &AMP; Wesson. The Kid and The Lid.
</P>
<P>
   They have teed it up twice each day in the team competition and
have come away with 3{ points out of a possible four in Europe's
10-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   They have been irrepressible and irresistible, with more magical
chemistry than Siegfried &AMP; Roy and, they too, know how to make a
Tiger disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to play with each other,'' said European captain
Mark James, the great stoneface. ``And the least I can do, really,
is to give them a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Few gave Garcia and Parnevik much chance to be the lead horses
pulling Europe's wagon. But for all the efforts of veteran Colin
Montgomerie and the notable Lee Westwood, it is Europe's version of
the Backstreet Boys who have given the team its bounce, its rhythm,
not to mention more than a few dance steps in the fairways.
</P>
<P>
   This time Parnevik and Garcia put down Justin Leonard and Payne
Stewart with a routine 3 and 2 thumping in the morning to run their
Ryder Cup records to a pair of perfect matching 3-0s. Then in the
afternoon they battled to a gritty square match with Davis Love III
and David Duval by using their usual bolts from the blue.
</P>
<P>
   The Kid and The Lid had fought back from an early two-hole
deficit and got to No. 12 looking like the wheels were ready to
come off. Neither managed to hit the fairway with his tee shot,
then Parnevik went into a bunker and fluffed his shot out, still 85
yards away. So he pulled out his sand wedge and struck another
arcing rainbow that found the pot of gold, rolling in for a 4 that
kept the match even.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had made a mess of that hole,'' Parnevik said. ``Then I saw
Sergio had a really tough chip shot himself to get up and down, so
I told my caddie, `It seems like we have to hole this one.' To see
it go in was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   It touched off another one of their spontaneous celebrations as
they danced like a pair of self-winding watches on the wrist of St.
Vitus.
</P>
<P>
   With these two, every hole is another potential disco. But that
is not to overlook they also play spectacular golf and are the
perfect complements to each other's personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their best team,'' Love said. ``Every time they both
get on the green, one of them makes it. That's what we've been
saying about Ryder Cups the last three years, somebody like Sergio
that never had played before, holes a lot of putts or hits a lot of
great shots. There is not much luck involved on their side, it's
just great shots. I'm just glad we don't have to play them again.''
</P>
<P>
   When it wasn't Parnevik chipping or making a key putt, it was
Garcia sliding the sharp sword into el toro. And it was The Kid who
struck last. With Duval and Love 1-up on the 18th hole and
threatening to take a full point for the U.S. team, Garcia hit a
beauty of an 8-iron that settled in eight feet from the cup. Then
he nailed his birdie putt to win the hole and square the match. At
a time when every partial point was going to make an American
comeback today more possible, it was a critical turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia eats apples during a match; Parnevik, the son of a
comedian, gobbles volcanic dust, and they've erupted on the United
States like Vesuvius. At the 17th tee, Garcia hugged U.S. captain
Ben Crenshaw and kissed his wife, Julie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have fun, I play good golf,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergio's been virtually a replacement for the young Seve
(Ballesteros),'' James said. ``When we were in the team room and
they showed him on a monitor, he said, `Look at this, the next
hole. Watch this.' And they didn't show the next hole. So he's
throwing things at the television. He's a live wire and I think
Jesper's looked after him fantastically because Jesper's been a
great check on him. But Sergio's personality is very charismatic
like Seve and he's definitely a force that this team has felt
positively.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kid and The Lid have put an overlapping grip on the Ryder
Cup. Go figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
