<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6412 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-BAYLOR-TEX     09-26 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CHASES BAYLOR, GHOSTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO _ All week Texas coach Mack Brown was regaled with tales of
weird things that had happened to past Longhorn teams in what
former UT coach David McWilliams once called the
Waco-Bruceville-Eddy Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Brown merely snorted at the idea that Floyd Casey Stadium was
somehow haunted for Texas, which had lost nine of its past 12 games
in the city by the Brazos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is haunted,'' Brown said. ``I don't believe in that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Bury that theory for the time being. Baylor didn't have a ghost
of a chance last night against the No. 22 Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Texas (4-1) won its Big 12 opener convincingly by scoring on six
of its first nine possessions on the way to a 62-0 victory that
left the Bears (0-4, 0-2) reeling after last week's 41-10 loss to
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Major Applewhite completed 26 of 37 passes for 333
yards and three touchdowns _ in three quarters. It was his third
300-yard game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive line did a phenomenal job,'' Applewhite said.
``I have one grass stain on my knee. And that was from taking a
knee watching Chris \RSimms\S play.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Hodges Mitchell followed his 188-yard performance
against Rice by gaining 131 yards on 22 carries _ including
first-half touchdown runs of three and 13 yards _ and also scored
on a 10-yard reception in the third quarter. Mitchell also did not
play in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably some things we'll see on film we need to
work on,'' Mitchell said. ``But it seemed like everything was
working pretty well tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas finished with 586 yards of total offense and its first
shutout in eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most complete game we've played in the last two
years,'' UT coach Mack Brown said. ``We got our first shutout since
'91 and that's a great selling point, especially when you're
playing your twos and threes in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Baylor is that bad,'' said cornerback Ervis
Hill, who had two interceptions. ``Coach Brown just did a really
good job of getting us pumped up. Before we got on the bus, he
showed us film of them tearing down the goalposts here two years
ago \Rafter a 23-21 victory\S. We didn't want them to do that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite completed 17 of 23 passes in the first half for 231
yards. He threw scoring strikes of 14 yards to tight end Chris
Smith and 8 yards to Ryan Nunez _ ending drives of 80 and 58 yards
_ during a 28-point second quarter that buried the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas defense set up the first two second-quarter touchdowns
that broke open a 14-0 game after first-quarter marches of 80 and
53 yards that ended in short scoring runs by fullback Chris
Robertson and Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker De'Andre Lewis picked an Odell James pass out
of his gut at the Baylor 13-yard line on the first play of the
second quarter. Mitchell scored his second touchdown of the half on
the next play by cutting outside and breaking two tackles down the
right sideline.
</P>
<P>
   End Aaron Humphrey's jarring tackle separated Jermaine Alfred
from the ball midway of the quarter and linebacker Anthony Hicks
recovered at the Bears' 17. After Applewhite drilled Ryan Nunez for
a 10-yard gain on third and four from the 11, Robertson scored his
second touchdown for a 28-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Texas then drove 80, capped by Smith's scoring catch, and took
it 58 yards after Hill's second interception at the Texas 42,
leading to Nunez's touchdown reception three plays later. Kwame
Cavil (8 catches, 97 yards) took an Applewhite pass 37 yards to the
Baylor 8 for the big play in the drive.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite threw his final touchdown of the night to Mitchell
with 2:31 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have a snyopsis for this, other than the fact
that we are only 20 quarters into this process,'' Bears coach Kevin
Steele said.
</P>
</TEXT>
