<HEADER>
A6413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-BAYLOR-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      09-26 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Longhorns dominate all facets in 62-0 rout
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ This time there would be no miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of misery for sure, but no miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after being the victim in the most celebrated
victory in the 100-year history of Baylor football, Texas found
redemption in giving the Bears one of their most embarrassing
losses ever.
</P>
<P>
   In a dominant performance, the Longhorns controlled every facet
of the game from the start and finished as strong as they started,
rolling to a 62-0 rout before 41,784 at Floyd Casey Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And just like after the Bears' 34-24 comeback victory over Texas
in 1974, subsequently dubbed the ``Miracle on the Brazos,'' those
who saw this year's game went away not believing what they had
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have a big synopsis for this other than we are
only (16) quarters into this process,'' Baylor first-year coach
Kevin Steele said. ``Looking through the small window, people might
think we are never going to get it done. We will get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The margin of defeat was the third-largest for Baylor, and the
worst in 86 years. LSU topped the Bears 89-0 in 1908 and the
Longhorns scorched them 89-0 in 1913. Saturday also was the first
time Texas has shut out an opponent since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we asked (our defense) to do was dominate the
ballgame, and we felt like the game would be dominated in the
running game for us and in stopping the running game for them,''
Texas coach Mack Brown said. ``If we stopped their running game,
they would become one-dimensional, and we knew they like to be
balanced offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (0-4, 0-2 Big 12) gained only 12 yards on 20 carries,
while Texas (4-1, 1-0) picked up 233 yards on the ground. Backup
quarterback Odell James led the Bears with a less-then-grand
rushing total of 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But the running game was only part of the dominance for the
Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Total yards: 586-159. First downs: 34-8. Passing yards 353-147.
And most importantly, touchdowns: 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   Texas quarterback Major Applewhite was superb, completing 26 of
37 passes for 333 yards and three touchdowns, and Hodges Mitchell
came through with his second consecutive 100-yard rushing game,
picking up 131 yards on 22 carries with a pair of first-half
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite and backup Chris Simms, who saw action in the fourth
quarter (3-of-4 for 20 yards and one touchdown), stood unmolested
in the pocket and picked the Bears apart. Baylor did not have a
sack, and Brown said it was the first time he had ever seen a game
where the quarterbacks for one team never hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was maybe one or two times where a throw was hurried,
but for the most part, maybe 99.9 percent of the time, they weren't
even close,'' Applewhite said. ``They have some good defensive
backs, but our offensive line protected really well. I just think
that they really got discouraged early in the game, Baylor did. We
kind of took their will (to win) away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns took it away with a masterful first half.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite completed 17 of 23 pass attempts for 231 yards and
Mitchell rushed for 99 yards on 14 carries as Texas raced to a 42-0
lead at the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   At the half, Texas had 348 yards of total offense and 18 first
downs, compared to Baylor's 127 yards and six first downs. And the
Baylor numbers were inflated by four plays of 19 or more yards that
didn't amount to anything as far as a threat to the Texas defense.
</P>
<P>
   The second half was just as impressive as the Longhorns held
Baylor to 32 totals yards and two first downs.
</P>
<P>
   After opening a 14-0 lead after the first quarter, the Longhorns
tallied 28 second-quarter points and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   A Chris Robertson dive into the end zone capped an 11-play,
53-yard march on UT's first possession for the game's first points.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the opening quarter, Texas went 80 yards in eight
plays, taking just 3:01 to do it, with Mitchell ending the drive by
following fullback Ricky Brown off the right side for a three-yard
touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the second quarter, UT linebacker De'Andre
Lewis picked off a pass from backup quarterback James to set Texas
up at the Baylor 13.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell wasted no time finding the end zone, juking Tommie
Black and running over Rodney Smith for the Longhorns' third
touchdown of the game. Kris Stockton added the extra point for a
21-0 Texas lead.
</P>
<P>
   James connected with Darrell Bush on a 29-yard screen play for
the Bears' first first down of the game more than 16 minutes into
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   However, the drive stalled after a costly holding penalty,
setting up a punting situation on fourth-and-13 from the Bears' 45.
Baylor chose to try a fake punt, but punter Kyle Atteberry's pass
was picked off by Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns finished the half in style, with their pass
offense continuing to click on all cylinders after Hill's second
interception and a four-yard return gave Texas the ball at its 42
with 1:35 to play in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite hit Kwame Cavil for 13 yards and then found him again
for a 37-yard pickup to the eight. On the next play, the sophomore
quarterback gunned a pass to a sliding Ryan Nunez in the end zone.
The drive took only 48 seconds and gave Texas an insurmountable
42-0 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
