<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6414 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-RICE-NAVY-HNS &LR;      09-26 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RICE-NAVY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rice gets a taste of victory
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It's sort of like getting that ice-cold soda after a long, hot day
_ and the drink is flat. Yes, your thirst is addressed. But you
want more.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the Rice offense was for a large part of
Saturday's game _ bland enough to do the job but hardly satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls suffered a turnover, tossed an illegal forward pass,
were stopped twice inside the 20, and committed numerous mistakes.
But they finally put together a long drive in fourth-quarter crunch
time to set up a 31-yard Derek Crabtree field goal that gave them a
20-17 victory over Navy before a crowd of 44,217 at Rice Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Rice outgained Navy, 322 yards to 281, but the multiple miscues
created an uneasy feeling on the offensive side of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were frustrated, because we were moving the ball like crazy
but not getting any points,'' said Rice quarterback Chad
Richardson. ``But I think it shows a lot about this team that we
stuck in there and kept moving the ball. We stopped making the
little mistakes and finally put some points on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first victory of the season gave the Owls some much-needed
momentum as they prepare to travel to Tulsa next week for their
Western Athletic Conference opener.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Owls' problem Saturday lay in a number of injuries
on offense. Tackle Rod Beavan (multiple injuries), fullback Jamie
Tyler (series of bruises), and quarterback Jeremy Bates (stress
fracture in foot) all missed the game. Backup quarterback Corey
Evans suffered a twisted knee in the second half and will have an
MRI to determine the scope of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corey had gone down the series before (the game-winning
drive), and Chad was cramping, so we decided on the sidelines that
we were just going to do our basic things,'' said Rice guard Neal
Gray. ``We were going to try to save Chad's legs and be a typical
option offense _ go four yards at a time. Before you knew it, we
were down in field-goal range. It gives you a lot of confidence
that in weeks to come we can do that in crunch time.''
</P>
<P>
   Owls coach Ken Hatfield said part of the problem was Navy's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kept us from being as effective as we wanted to be, but
we're not perfect,'' Hatfield said. ``We made some things happen
and earned things the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   With only Richardson available to quarterback in the fourth
quarter, former quarterback Ben Wulf _ who has been working out at
running back _ was taking snaps on the sideline in case he was
needed. Also though Bates had not suited up, he went to the locker
room to dress out and returned with less than four minutes
remaining in the game, ready to be inserted if Richardson were to
go down.
</P>
<P>
   Navy (1-3) marched 80 yards in eight plays on its first
possession _ including a 41-yard run by quarterback Brian
Broadwater off the initial snap _ to take a 7-0 lead. Rice (1-3)
countered with three plays and minus-three yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were worried after our first series,'' Gray said. ``But the
way our team is, we have been through a lot of tough times this
season. We knew it was important to overcome it and keep working
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Things looked better on Rice's next possession when the Owls
took a punt from their 46 and drove to the Navy six. However, a
pitch from Richardson to halfback Leroy Bradley fell off of
Bradley's shoulder pads and was recovered at the seven by Navy's
Ryan Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   On its next possession, Rice drove again, this time from the
Navy 44 to the Middies' 12, before the offense broke down. On
fourth-and-one, Richardson was stopped by Chris Lepore for a
two-yard loss, and the Midshipmen took over at their 14.
</P>
<P>
   Two possessions later, Navy used another big play to take a 14-0
lead. On first down at his 21, Navy fullback Raheem Lambert took
the ball up the middle, broke two tackles and sprinted 79 yards to
silence the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the Owls came right back, covering 80 yards in seven plays
to draw within 14-7. Evans scored on a five-yard run on
third-and-goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Rice defense flexed it muscle, holding the Middies on
three straight plays to set up fourth-and-10 at the Navy 12. After
a punt, Rice set up shop at the Navy 47 with 1:58 left on the
first-half clock and drove all the way in only five plays. The
game-tying score came on a 15-yard pass from Richardson to receiver
Raphael Tillman on the right side of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Midshipmen refused to bend, however. They took their first
possession of the second half and drove from midfield to the Rice
32. Tim Shubzda then booted a 49-yard field goal _ matching the
third-longest in school history _ to give the Middies a 17-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls then found their stride on offense and did what they do
best _ devouring the clock with a 15-play drive. Rice started from
its 20 and got to the Navy 24. On third down, Richardson overthrew
a wide-open Tillman at the goal line, and the Owls had to settle
for a game-tying 41-yard field goal by Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams struggled to get anything going offensively until
Rice had another time-eating drive late in the contest. After 16
plays and 7:59, the Owls couldn't advance past the Navy 14.
Crabtree kicked a 31-yard field goal with 2:27 remaining, sending
the Rice players into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   A key play came when Richardson appeared to be stopped on
third-and-two at the Navy 18. He jumped the line and dived for a
first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a critical play and was a tough game,'' Hatfield
said. ``No one on either side was giving up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
