u s BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-SOUTHERNMISS-     09-26 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-SOUTHERNMISS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas A&AMP;M defense carries day
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
COLLEGE STATION _ All those accolades for the Texas A&AMP;M offense?
Better put them on hold for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' offense scored no touchdowns against Southern
Mississippi on Saturday afternoon at Kyle Field and had only one
drive that went farther than 35 yards. Quarterback Randy McCown was
12-of-29 for 134 yards, while running back Dante' Hall managed 23
yards on 16 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The best offense was the Wrecking Crew defense, which
intercepted four passes and returned two for touchdowns in a 23-6
win. Kicker Terence Kitchens added three field goals, including a
62-yarder at the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game, we want to get our turnovers,'' said cornerback
Jay Brooks, who returned an interception 41 yards midway in the
third quarter for the Aggies' first touchdown of the game. ``We
want picks (interceptions), and we want to score on defense. The
guys up front put a lot of pressure on their quarterbacks, and the
defensive backs played together.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kitchens hit three field goals in the first half, Brooks
and Michael Jameson both returned interceptions for touchdowns in
the second half. The Aggies held Southern Mississippi to 129 total
yards (111 passing, 18 rushing) and had six sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was vintage Wrecking Crew today,'' said Aggies coach R.C.
Slocum. ``It was fun to watch. We knew they had an outstanding
defense, and it was going to be a challenge moving the ball. To
have a chance to win the game, our defense was going to have play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense went way beyond that. Because of it, the Aggies won
a game in which the offense did not score a touchdown for the first
time since 1985, when they had four field goals and an interception
return for a touchdown in a 19-7 win over Houston. The last time an
Aggies offense did not score a touchdown in a game was in a 16-6
loss (two field goals) to Texas in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing you can say about this game was that we got a
win,'' said Hall. ``The (offensive) numbers are ugly, but the win
was pretty. That was a great defense we played, but our defense was
the story today. But our defense is the story every week.''
</P>
<P>
   And how. In three games, the Aggies have allowed 68 rushing
yards on 75 carries. Overall, they have given up 691 yards of total
offense. The Golden Eagles' only touchdown of the game came on a
54-yard pass from backup quarterback Cable Davis to Todd Pinkston
early in the fourth quarter. Take that away, and the Aggies held
Southern Miss to 75 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play particularly well on offense,'' said Southern
Miss coach Jeff Bower in the understatement of the day. ``We
couldn't move the ball, and we never got into a rhythm. That's a
really good defensive team if you're not doing things well on
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the Aggies. On the opening drive of
the game, it looked as if they were going to go three-and-out. But
punter Shane Lechler dropped the snap, picked the ball up and raced
22 yards to the Texas A&AMP;M 46 for the first down.
</P>
<P>
   On their best drive of the day, the Aggies moved to the Southern
Miss four-yard line behind 3-of-3 passing by McCown for 25 yards
and 15 rushing yards by the quarterback. The drive stalled, and
Kitchens kicked a 20-yard field goal to make it 3-0 with 8:05 left
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' defense allowed a total of three yards on eight
plays in the first quarter, setting the tone for what kind of day
it was going to be for the Golden Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, a short punt set up the Aggies at
the Southern Miss 46. McCown hit Bethel Johnson for 21 yards on
first down. Later in the drive, McCown ran for 10 yards, but things
stalled at the 11-yard line. Kitchens nailed a 28-yard field goal
to make it 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   With time running down in the first half, an interception by
Jason Webster gave the Aggies the ball at their 36 with only 33
seconds left. McCown hit Chris Cole for 22 yards, and a pass
interference call on Southern Miss put the ball at the 27, in good
field-goal range for Kitchens with 14 seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies were called for holding on the next play, pushing
it back to the 44-yard line. Kitchens, a walk-on who was told he
had been awarded a scholarship by Slocum two days before Saturday's
game, banged a low line-drive kick through from 62 yards to make it
9-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come over to Kyle Field every day and kick about 75 to 100
field goals,'' said Kitchens. ``But the longest I think I'd ever
tried was 60 or 61 yards. It was the end of the half, so there was
nothing to lose. I just tried to hit it good but not overkick it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies continued their defensive domination in the third
quarter. After two series of going nowhere, USM starting
quarterback Jeff Kelly was replaced by Davis. The second pass Davis
tried was picked off by Brooks, who returned it 41 yards to make it
16-0 with 7:20 left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't improve for Davis, who was intercepted three times
and sacked three times. His lone bright spot was finding Pinkston
for the touchdown to make it 16-6. The Golden Eagles went for two
points and didn't convert.
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Eagles got the ball, Sedrick Curry intercepted
a pass by Davis. In the series after that one, Jameson intercepted
a pass and went 26 yards into the end zone to make it 23-6 with
8:32 left in the game. Davis was 2-of-12 with three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to put pressure on their quarterbacks to force them
into mistakes,'' said Aggies linebacker Jason Glenn. ``We're never
satisfied with just good defense. We want great defense. We want it
like the old Wrecking Crews that were dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's brother, Aaron, was a cornerback on the 1992 and '93 A&AMP;M
teams that won Southwest Conference championships and held teams to
10 points or fewer in 13 of the 25 games they played. Is this
year's Wrecking Crew starting to measure up to those teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we're getting there,'' said Glenn. ``With more work
and more practice, I think we can live up to that tradition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
