<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
RANGERS PASSED A's TEST; SO, LET THE PARTY BEGIN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Reared on caution and the bitter milk of
Septembers past, Rangers fans had every reason to look to the
eastern sky last night.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd had come for a party. But the inky,
threatening clouds just beyond The Ballpark walls threatened to
postpone it all.
</P>
<P>
   An omen?
</P>
<P>
   Not this year. Not this season.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's quick 3-0 lead vanished _ like the threatening rain _
in one, eight-run blink.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, it seems, stops the party this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most interesting and exciting thing to me has been the way
we've played these last two nights,'' manager Johnny Oates said
after the Rangers' 10-4 victory had chiseled their magic number to
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the way the guys have responded. The way the pitchers
have pitched. The way the hitters have hit. And the fans have been
_ that's the way it's supposed to be going into October.''
</P>
<P>
   The test, in other words, is over. The Rangers have passed.
</P>
<P>
   They've passed the Oakland test. They've passed the TAAS test.
They've passed the SAT. They've passed the litmus test, the
Rorschach test, the crash test, the breath test and the stress
test.
</P>
<P>
   In what was supposed to be their ultimate test of the season,
against the precocious, onrushing Athletics, the Rangers have been
the ones with all the A's.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for a party.
</P>
<P>
   As Rangers fans know, both of the club's two previous division
titles have been clinched on the out-of-town scoreboard, not on the
field. The Rangers have yet to wrap up the American League West
with a victory, on their home field, in front of their home fans.
</P>
<P>
   That could all change today. The Rangers will have 15 cases of
something bubbly and chilled, waiting to celebrate a division title
that some thought was slipping from their grasps.
</P>
<P>
   But they've passed the test.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they did one year ago, when they went out to Anaheim and
laid waste to the Angels' hopes, the Rangers have done the same to
the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Before last night's game, Oates said he had been joking with
Oakland manager Art Howe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Art, `I like you guys, but would you please go away?'
'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics didn't have to. Rather, just as they did Friday
night, the Rangers exploded past the A's in one furious,
single-inning haze. John Burkett simply took it from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an answer for you,'' Oates admitted. ``But we've
done it four times in the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come out of Detroit and it looks like we have our backs to
the wall, and \REsteban\S Loaiza beats Cleveland. Then we go into
Kansas City and we look terrible _ just terrible. It looked like we
weren't even having fun. Rusty \RGreer\S and Luis \RAlicea\S get
hurt, and we looked like we were down again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we come back. The same scenario four times. Why? I don't
know. I'm just glad they do.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, this is a veteran-laden team that, while some Rangers
fans were wincing and worrying, has become a consistent winner _
and, soon, a division winner for the third time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   They have avoided the long, telling droughts that used to define
seasons past. The heroes have come from a multitude of directions.
It was Burkett again last night, along with, among others, third
baseman Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a young ballclub,'' Oates said. ``Because of the
veterans we have, I think it's easier to stay away from those ups
and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   These Rangers have played with heart. The games like these
against Oakland and against the Indians have shown that vividly.
</P>
<P>
   And the poster kid for the team's heart may be Burkett, who won
again last night when the Rangers needed it most.
</P>
<P>
   When times were tough earlier this season, when Burkett's
earned-run average looked like a long cab fare and he was yanked
from the starting rotation, he handled his demotion with class.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the scourge of this season, John Burkett now may be
one of its best symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his perseverance, the Rangers have a party coming.
</P>
<P>
   This test is done.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
