<SLUG> BC-BOX-MOSLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY HAS WELTERWEIGHT WALLOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMECULA, Calif. _ Meet Shane Mosley. Welterweight.
</P>
<P>
   The former IBF lightweight champion, who abdicated his throne
and moved up two weight classes in search of more fame and fortune,
proved he belongs by doing something no one else has been able to
do: knock out Wilfredo Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it in a most dramatic way, with two rights and
follow-up left that ended a close, entertaining brawl at 2:38 of
the final round Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   How does Mosley (33-0, with 31 knockouts) compare to the
welterweights he moved up to face one day?
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, who lost to Oscar De La Hoya in eight rounds because of
a bad cut, said Mosley is a legitimate 147-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's any better than Oscar or (Felix)
Trinidad,'' said Rivera (30-4-1, 19 KOs). ``All I know is he's a
harder puncher. He's the only one who was able to stop me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a great champ.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley had a tough time.
</P>
<P>
   He started quickly, using his superior speed and all-around
ability to control the early rounds. However, Rivera, as tough and
crafty as they come, piled up points in the middle rounds by
holding and leaning and punching as Mosley began to tire.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when it counted most, Mosley took complete charge. He
ended the ninth round with a painful flurry and dominated the 10th,
landing several solid blows before finally putting Rivera down for
the first time in his career. The Puerto Rican was too hurt to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   The judges had Mosley leading 88-83, 86-85 and 86-86 after nine
rounds. The Daily News had it 87-84 Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the De La Hoya fight (against Trinidad), I thought I was
ahead on points,'' said Mosley. ``But I didn't want to leave it in
the hands of the judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lightweights are faster than welterweights, but Rivera takes a
great punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top welterweights are Oscar, Trinidad and Sugar Shane
Mosley. I proved I have welterweight power tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's move from 135 pounds to 147 raised some eyebrows, even
in light of his ability. Now his ambitions seem to make perfect
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready. I want to fight for a championship in my next
fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary bout, South African Lehlohonolo Ledwaba stopped
Edison Valencia of Colombia at 2:31 of the fifth round to retain
his IBF junior featherweight title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
