<HEADER>
A6422 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-1980S-CENTURY-SLUG-TE     09-26 2200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1980S-CENTURY-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWC PAYS HEAVY PRICE FOR SCANDALS OF THE 1980S 
WITH THE CENTURY IN SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once he took office as commissioner of the Southwest Conference
in November 1982, it wasn't long before Fred Jacoby got an accurate
read on the future of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't in the office two weeks,'' Jacoby said, ``and I could
tell we had problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby couldn't find an assistant coach in the conference who
had a copy of the NCAA enforcement guidelines. When Jacoby asked
one of his aides if he knew where to find one, the aide went back
to his desk and rummaged through the drawers and uncovered a copy.
</P>
<P>
   SWC assistant coaches not only didn't have a copy of the NCAA
guidelines, it was almost as if boosters of some of the SWC schools
didn't have a care about what the rules were. Slush funds were
created. Personnel within the athletics departments at some schools
were in charge of distributing payments to players in violation of
NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   David Berst, the NCAA director of enforcement whose appearance
on SWC campuses was as popular as a mound of fire ants, remembers
the attitude of some of the school administrators he investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was `Catch me if you can,''' Berst said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, most were caught.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1980s ended, six of the nine SWC schools were placed
on probation for recruiting infractions. Only Arkansas, Baylor and
Rice were untouched. And by the close of the decade, Arkansas was
poised to bolt from the SWC in favor of the Southeastern
Conference. The end of the SWC was on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a building crescendo,'' Jacoby said, ``and I got caught
right in the vortex.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Teaff, former coach at Baylor, said the recruiting
scandals were a major contributing factor to the league's demise
after the 1995-96 school year. For Teaff, who grew up in West Texas
listening to SWC football on the radio, it was the end of a
life-long passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conference had a storied history,'' Teaff said. ``It was,
in so many people's minds, the premier college football conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the '80s for me was an extremely disappointing time. It
was our tragedy, and it played out nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaff remembers the tension in meeting rooms when SWC coaches
attended special conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just glared at each other,'' Teaff said. ``I looked around
the room and knew what \Rother coaches\S were doing, and they knew
that I knew what they were doing. Previously, I had such respect
and good relationships with other coaches like Darrell Royal \Rat
Texas\S and Frank Broyles \Rat Arkansas\S. But with these coaches,
there was agitation. There were hard feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference where coaches used to pat each other on the back
had become a league where coaches seemingly wanted to stab each
other in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby believes the forces that led to the league's unraveling
began building as far back as the 1950s when practically all SWC
schools were fielding teams capable of winning a conference
championship. But the '60s were dominated by the state schools _
mostly Texas. That continued into the '70s, by which time unrest
built among alums wanting their schools to get back in the title
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people that went to school after World War II were in
their 40s and 50s and making good money when we moved the clock up
to the '80s,'' Jacoby said. ``I know I could go to lunch with a
group of lawyers or other professionals, and one of them went to
law school at Texas, another one to SMU or Baylor or Tech. They'd
needle each other if their alma mater had a bad football team. It
was bragging rights _ very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, they were tired of losing. I think that's when
the payments started.'' `A payroll to meet' ``Mustang Mania'' was
created in the early 1980s when SMU began to challenge for its
first trip to the Cotton Bowl since 1965, and only its second since
Doak Walker played in 1949. It gave birth to the ``Pony Express''
when Eric Dickerson and Craig James became college football's most
prolific pair of running backs playing on the same team.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, after NCAA probation kept them from advancing to any
bowl games despite a 10-win season in 1981, the Mustangs played in
_ and won _ their Cotton Bowl after the '82 season. There was a
10-2 record in '83, but the true Mania soon started creeping out.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, SMU recruited Muse, Pa., offensive lineman Sean
Stopperich. The NCAA contended Stopperich was given a monthly
salary to attend SMU, and his father _ laid off from a steel mill _
was given an apartment in the Dallas area. Stopperich never played
at SMU because of a knee injury, but the NCAA, in May 1985, handed
SMU a two-year probation that included the loss of 45 scholarships.
It was deemed the most severe penalty in NCAA history.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the second time in the '80s the NCAA visited ``The
Hilltop.'' The NCAA left by imposing sanctions on SMU for major
recruiting violations. Seeing that a school like SMU seemed unfazed
by things like TV and bowl bans and the loss of scholarships, the
NCAA instituted Section 7-(f)-(1) into its enforcement code in June
1985.
</P>
<P>
   That rule stated that any school caught cheating twice within
five years could lose the right to compete for up to two years. It
became known as the ``Death Penalty.'' SMU was one of six schools
that voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't long before SMU walked into trouble again, due
to a decision made even before the harsh sanctions were handed down
in May 1985.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, SMU officials called a meeting to ban nine
boosters involved in some level of NCAA rules violations. But one
booster, Dallas real estate executive Sherwood Blount, pointed out
something to SMU board of governors chairman Bill Clements. Soon to
be elected to his second term as Texas governor, Clements was about
to make a decision that would put national embarrassment on his
political career. Blount told Clements there were still players on
the SMU roster promised money to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a payroll to meet,'' Blount is quoted as saying in
David Whitford's 1989 book, ``A Payroll to Meet.'' ``Maybe you
should consider a line item to the university budget.''
</P>
<P>
   So, according to Whitford's book, and an investigation conducted
by a group of Methodist bishops, Clements told SMU athletic
director Bob Hitch to keep the cash rolling and honor the previous
financial commitments. Though SMU had fired recruiting coordinator
Bootsie Larsen because he dished out the money in the previous
scandal, Hitch assigned associate AD Henry Lee Parker to collect
the money from boosters and pay it out to those players expecting
the cash.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was David Stanley, a linebacker who wanted to
transfer out of SMU after the probation in 1985. After no teams
would offer him a scholarship, Stanley wanted back in at SMU. Coach
Bobby Collins refused.
</P>
<P>
   So Stanley started talking _ to the NCAA and, maybe more
damaging to SMU, to a Dallas television station. On a Nov. 12, 1986
telecast, Stanley said he had been promised $25,000 to play
football at SMU. An envelope with the initials HLP (Henry Lee
Parker), in which Stanley said he received his monthly cash, also
appeared on the telecast.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Committee on Infractions applied the ``Death Penalty''
on Feb. 25, 1987. It suspended SMU's football program for the '87
season and limited the school to seven games away from home in '88.
After forcing the resignations of Hitch and Collins, SMU decided
not to play again until 1989. The Mustangs haven't been to a bowl
game since.
</P>
<P>
   The gravity of the moment showed on Berst. Shortly into the news
conference announcing the ``Death Penalty,'' Berst tried to walk
away from the dais. He collapsed and was carried into a side room.
He apparently was suffering from the flu and stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember everything,'' Berst said, ``until my eyes closed.''
Hu$h, it's Jackie While Baylor, SMU and Texas were making all the
trips to the Cotton Bowl in the early '80s, Texas A&AMP;M was suffering
from an inferiority complex. Dallas businessman H.R. ``Bum'' Bright
changed that when it came time to make a decision on the status of
coach Tom Wilson after the 1981 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got five of what, to me, were the big-name coaches at the
time,'' Bright said. ``I got Bud Wilkinson, Bear Bryant and I can't
remember who else, and I told them to give me the names of five
coaches _ 1-2-3-4-5 in their order of preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took all the names and the one mentioned most was Bo
Schembechler \Rof Michigan\S. No. 2 was Bobby Bowden \Rof Florida
State\S. Three was Jackie Sherrill \Rof Pittsburgh\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright talked contract with Schembechler and his wife when they
visited the Bright household in Dallas. Schembechler had previous
history of heart trouble. So when Schembechler said he wanted a
10-year contract _ ``live or die'' _ Bright scratched Schembechler
off the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a delightful man,'' Bright said. ``Just as charming as
he could be. His price was very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Money was an issue with Bowden, whose program at Florida State
was poised for a run at national prominence. Bright said Bowden
told him that FSU had an athletic budget twice the size of A&AMP;M's.
</P>
<P>
   So Bright called Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me `Bum, by God, I told you to hire this boy Jackie
Sherrill,''' Bright said. ``Sherrill was there in the hotel room,
so I talked with Jackie. Jackie was a high-class guy as far as I
was concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   But his aloofness, and his contract, didn't ingratiate him with
other SWC coaches and media. His contract called for a salary of
$260,000 per year _ more than the university president _ and he
didn't have much to show for it when A&AMP;M went 16-16-1 his first
three seasons .
</P>
<P>
   But in '84, A&AMP;M started a five-year winning streak over UT. And
the '85 season produced the first of three consecutive Cotton
Bowls, winning one against Heisman Trophy winner Bo Jackson and
Auburn and another over high-profile Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   But trouble was on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies were placed on NCAA probation in '88, keeping them
from the Cotton Bowl. They were headed back to the Cotton Bowl in
'89 when a mysterious overnight delivery service package containing
money showed up addressed to a former recruit. The speculation ran
wild. Before the game with Texas, students at UT went to work in
the upper deck of Memorial Stadium. Using the flip-back seating
that is visible to anyone driving on Interstate 35 in Austin, they
spelled out a message:
</P>
<P>
   HU$H.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M escaped a serious NCAA probe. But Sherrill resigned to make
way for the promotion of assistant coach R.C. Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   To Bright, hiring Sherrill was the right move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we had to go out and get a good coach, and that's what
we got. I thought everything turned out real well. Nobody did as
good a job at A&AMP;M as Jackie did, unless you go back and look at
Dana Bible.'' SEC's in them thar hills By the end of the decade,
who would want to keep company with the Southwest Conference?
Arkansas, remote in the Ozark Mountains and untouched by the NCAA,
began to pack up the truck and was ready to move to the SEC. The
Southeastern Conference, that is. Full stadiums, nice TV contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The recruiting scandals weren't the last straw that got Arkansas
looking outside the SWC.
</P>
<P>
   ``That period of time contributed not to us moving, but it
contributed to there being less confidence in our programs by the
fans,'' Arkansas athletic director and former football coach Frank
Broyles said. ``We were damaged by this to a degree. We couldn't
sell our TV package for what we thought it was worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Like in all sports, TV was becoming the major revenue stream for
college athletics. With slow growth on the tube for the SWC,
Broyles looked at the other revenue producer. But the live gate at
league stadiums had fallen off, particularly among the smaller
schools.
</P>
<P>
   While the Razorbacks are just about the only major sporting
interest in Arkansas, the same wasn't the case in Texas. Broyles
counted it up. By the '80s, there were three major-league teams in
the Fort Worth-Dallas area (the Cowboys, the Rangers and the
Mavericks), three more in Houston (the Oilers, the Astros and the
Rockets) and another in San Antonio (the Spurs).
</P>
<P>
   There were days in the '50s when Arkansas and A&AMP;M would move
their game to Houston and play in front of 70,000 people at Rice
Stadium. But in the '80s, Rice Stadium looked like an empty seat
factory on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the SEC was filling stadiums and getting big TV
contracts like another southern phenomenon _ NASCAR. Broyles was
ready to put the pedal to the medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pie was split many, many times by the pros coming into
Texas,'' Broyles said. ``The newspapers had more to write about.
The discretionary dollar was scaled over to other venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1988, after seriously considering what Arkansas' future
could be in the Southwest Conference and hearing what was available
in the SEC, I asked \Rthe SEC\S if we could join.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, it happened. The SWC wouldn't last much
longer.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
