<HEADLINE>
1980S TIMELINE 
WITH THE CENTURY IN SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
1980
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan. 20: President Carter says that the United States will not
compete in the Summer Olympics in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 22: PGA Senior Tour is formed.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 22: The U.S. Olympic hockey team stuns the U.S.S.R., 4-3,
in the semifinals and wins the gold medal two days later, defeating
Finland, 4-2, in the Lake Placid Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 23: Speed skater Eric Heiden sets five world records en
route to five gold medals in the Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   April 6: Gordie Howe plays the final game of his 32-year career.
</P>
<P>
   April 24: An attempt by U.S forces to rescue 52 diplomatic
hostages held by Islamic revolutionaries fails.
</P>
<P>
   July 30: Houston Astros pitcher J.R. Richard collapses during a
workout at the Astrodome after having a stroke. Richard, 30, struck
out 300 batters in both 1978 and 1979 and had an ERA of 1.89 at the
time of his career-ending tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 20: Los Angeles Dodgers rookie left-hander Fernando
Valenzuela becomes the first rookie to win the Cy Young award.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 25: Roberto Duran says, `No mas, no mas' in the eighth
round of his welterweight rematch against Sugar Ray Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 13: The NCAA votes to sponsor Division I women's
championships in 12 sports after the 1981-82 season.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 20: On the day of President Reagan's inauguration, the 52
American hostages are released after 444 days.
</P>
<P>
   March 30: President Reagan is shot. Later that evening,
Indiana's Isiah Thomas leads the Hoosiers past North Carolina,
63-50, for the NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   June 12: The first midseason baseball strike begins. Players
leave in disagreement over compensation for free agents; an
agreement is reached on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   July 29: Prince Charles, 32, of Great Britain weds Lady Diana
Spencer, 20.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 26: Houston's Nolan Ryan throws his fifth no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 6: In Cairo, Egyptian president Anwar Sadat is assassinated
by Islamic extremists. 1982
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 10: ``The Catch.'' San Francisco's Joe Montana hits Dwight
Clark on a 6-yard pass in the back of the end zone with 51 seconds
remaining in the NFC title game as the 49ers defeat Dallas, 28-27.
</P>
<P>
   March 28: With the AIAW absorbed by the NCAA, the first women's
basketball Final Four is held with Louisiana Tech defeating Cheyney
State, 76-62, in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   March 29: North Carolina freshman Michael Jordan makes a 16-foot
jumper to give the Tar Heels' a 63-62 win over Georgetown in the
NCAA finals.
</P>
<P>
   May 12: The 12-team United States Football League is formed.
</P>
<P>
   April 1: Panama takes over control of policing the Panama Canal
Zone.
</P>
<P>
   June 9: Baltimore's Cal Ripken begins his consecutive game
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 21: The NFL players strike for the first time during a
season. Play resumes on Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 20: Thanks to five laterals during a kickoff return on the
game's final play, California defeats Stanford, 20-19.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 4: Georgia running back Herschel Walker wins the Heisman
Trophy. 1983
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 23: Herschel Walker stuns the football world by turning pro
early and signing a contract with the New Jersey Generals of the
USFL.
</P>
<P>
   April 4: North Carolina State's Lorenzo Charles dunks in Derek
Whittenberg's 30-foot shot as time runs out to give the Wolfpack a
stunning, 54-52 win over Houston in the NCAA title game.
</P>
<P>
   April 26: The Baltimore Colts select Stanford quarterback John
Elway with the first pick in the NFL draft; Elway resists playing
for Baltimore owner Robert Irsay and he is eventually traded to
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   May 20: Colts quarterback Art Schlichter is suspended
indefinitely by the NFL for betting on games.
</P>
<P>
   July 24: George Brett's home run at Yankee Stadium is disallowed
because he has too much pine tar on his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 26: The United States loses the America's Cup for the
first time in the event's 132-year history as Australia II defeats
Liberty, 4 races to 3.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 23: Terrorists in Lebanon kill 241 U.S. Marines and 58
French paratroopers in army barracks.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 25: 3,000 U.S. marines invade Grenada.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31: Chicago Bears founder George Halas dies. 1984
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 1: No. 1-ranked Nebraska loses to Miami and freshman
quarterback Bernie Kosar in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   March 28: The Colts move from Baltimore in the middle of the
night to their new home of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   April 5: On a sky-hook in Utah, Kareem Abdul-Jabar becomes the
NBA's all-time leading scorer, breaking Wilt Chamberlain's career
mark of 31,419 points.
</P>
<P>
   June 19: North Carolina guard Michael Jordan goes third in the
draft to Chicago, behind Houston (Hakeem Olajuwan) and Portland
(Sam Bowie).
</P>
<P>
   July 22: Kathy Whitworth wins her 85th career LPGA event to
surpass Sam Snead's 84 PGA tour wins and become the all-time
winningest professional golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 7: Walter Payton passes Jim Brown as the NFL's all-time
leading rusher. Payton finishes his career with 14,860 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 23: With six seconds remaining, Boston College's Doug
Flutie completes a 64-yard Hail Mary pass to defeat Miami, 47-45;
one week later he wins the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 9: The Rams' Eric Dickerson breaks O.J. Simpson's
single-season rushing mark with 2,105 yards. 1985
</P>
<P>
   March 6: Boxer Mike Tyson makes his pro debut by knocking out
Hector Mercedes in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   April 4: A New Orleans grand jury indicts three members of the
Tulane men's basketball team as well as five other people connected
to point-shaving the season before.
</P>
<P>
   May 3: Willie Shoemaker surpasses $100 million in purse
winnings. He retires the next month having won 8,475 races.
</P>
<P>
   April 1: Villanova shoots 79 percent to defeat heavily favored
Georgetown, 66-64, for the NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 11: Pete Rose singles on a 2-1 pitch from San Diego's Eric
Show to surpass Ty Cobb as baseball's all-time hits king with
4,192.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 21: Light-heavyweight champion Michael Spinks hands Larry
Holmes his first defeat in a unanimous 15-round decision.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 5: Grambling coach Eddie Robinson wins his 324th game to
become college football all-time winningest coach.
1986
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 25: Mike Tyson knocks out his 17th consecutive opponent to
break Rocky Marciano's heavyweight record.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 28: The space shuttle Challenger explodes 73 seconds after
liftoff from Cape Canaveral, Fla., killing all seven astronauts
aboard, including school teacher Christa McAuliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 8: Spud Webb of the Atlanta Hawks, a 5-foot-7 guard, wins
the NBA's Slam Dunk title.
</P>
<P>
   March 30: By defeating Southern California, 97-81, the
University of Texas women's basketball team completes a perfect
34-0 season.
</P>
<P>
   April 13: At 46, Jack Nicklaus becomes the oldest golfer to win
the Masters, capturing his sixth green jacket at Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   July 27: Greg LeMond becomes the first American to win cycling's
Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 25: With the Boston Red Sox ahead three games to two in the
World Series, first baseman Bill Buckner's fielding error on a slow
roller in the 10th inning allows the New York Mets to rally for a
6-5 victory in Game 6. Two nights later, the Mets win Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 14: The Cowboys' streak of 20 consecutive winning seasons,
the third longest in pro sports history, comes to an end with a
23-21 loss to the Philadelphia Eagles. 1987
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 4: Stars &AMP; Stripes, captained by Dennis Conner, reclaims
the America's Cup yachting trophy from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 25: SMU's football program receives the ``death penalty''
from the NCAA, which cancels the Mustangs' 1987 season. Later, the
school also elects to cancel the 1988 season.
</P>
<P>
   March 30: Cowboys founder Clint Murchison Jr. dies at age 63
after a long illness.
</P>
<P>
   April 6: In one of the richest bouts in boxing history _ it
reportedly grossed more than $100 million _ Sugar Ray Leonard
defeats Marvin Hagler for the middleweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   April 6: Appearing on ABC's ``Nightline,'' Los Angeles Dodgers
vice president Al Campanis makes remarks many consider racist and
insensitive. Campanis is fired two days later.
</P>
<P>
   June 4: Edwin Moses loses a 400-meter hurdles race for the first
time in almost 10 years, ending a record 122-race victory streak.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 29: Don Mattingly of the New York Yankees sets a
major-league record by hitting his sixth grand slam of the season.
1988
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 16: CBS broadcaster and oddsmaker Jimmy ``The Greek''
Snyder is fired for making racist remarks.
</P>
<P>
   May 26: Led by Wayne Gretzky, the Edmonton Oilers win the
Stanley Cup for the fourth time in five years.
</P>
<P>
   July 2: Martina Navratilova's streak of six consecutive women's
singles titles at Wimbledon comes to an end with her loss to Steffi
Graf.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 9: The Edmonton Oilers trade Gretzky to the Los Angeles
Kings in a multi-player, multi-million dollar deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 12: Tom Landry of the Cowboys ties Curly Lambeau's NFL
record by coaching his 29th consecutive season with the same team.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 23: Jose Canseco of the Oakland A's becomes the first
major-league baseball player to hit 40 homers and steal 40 bases in
the same season.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 29: At the Summer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea, Florence
Griffith-Joyner sets a world record in the 200 meters with a time
of 21.34. She had set a world record in the 100 at the Olympic
trials in Indianapolis two months earlier with a time of 10.49.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 7: Pitcher Nolan Ryan, 41, signs with the Rangers as a free
agent. 1989
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 11: The NCAA passes Proposition 42, which disallows
athletic scholarships to students who fail to meet academic
standards set by Proposition 48. Three days later, Georgetown coach
John Thompson walks off the court before a basketball game against
Boston College in protest. Thompson says that the two propositions
are discriminatory to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 3: Bill White becomes the first African-American man to
head a major U.S. pro sports league when he is chosen National
League president.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 25: Jerry Jones reaches an agreement with Bum Bright to
purchase the Cowboys and announces that University of Miami coach
Jimmy Johnson will replace Tom Landry.
</P>
<P>
   March 22: Pete Rozelle resigns as commissioner of the NFL after
29 years.
</P>
<P>
   April 18: The sale of the Cowboys to Jerry Jones is approved by
the NFL. Tex Schramm resigns after 29 years as the team's general
manager to take charge of the World League of American Football.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 22: Nolan Ryan of the Rangers becomes the first pitcher in
major-league history with 5,000 strikeouts by fanning Rickey
Henderson of the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 24: Pete Rose, baseball's all-time hits leader, is banned
from the sport ``for life.'' Baseball commissioner A. Bartlett
Giamatti issued the ruling after an investigation of ``serious
allegations'' against Rose involving gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 17: An earthquake measuring 7.1 on the Richter Scale
devastates San Francisco, killing more than 60 people. The quake
occurs only minutes before the start of Game 3 of the World Series
between Oakland and San Francisco at Candlestick Park. The Series
is postponed for 10 days. ] nn
</P>
</TEXT>
