<SLUG> BC-McCARTHY-FOOTBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE-AMERICAN FAMILY TO GET LETTERMAN'S JACKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The kid was as tough as they come, his teammates
remember - took his hits on the line of scrimmage from guys much
bigger and never quit.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Larry Kobayashi was a gamer all right. A real scrapper at
right guard on the second string at Manual Arts High as a sophomore
in 1940 and a junior in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   He would have been a starter on the 1942 varsity in his senior
year, they all agree. A lock, the coaches said.
</P>
<P>
   But no one saw Dec. 7, 1941, coming.
</P>
<P>
   When football practice began in '42, Larry Kobayashi,
Japanese-American, was nowhere around. He, his parents and three
sisters were living in a small town called Northe Cache on the
Utah-Idaho border by then.
</P>
<P>
   They had been given two choices by our government when war broke
out with Japan - move inland, away from the Western Defense Zone,
or be relocated to a camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a distant cousin who arranged housing for us, so we
packed up and went,'' Kobayashi, 73, said last week from his
Camarillo home. ``My dad had to close his grocery store and become
a field worker to support us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left Manual Arts with a heavy heart. I only had a semester
and a half to go before graduating.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be almost four years before the Kobayashis were allowed
to come home to Southern California. By that time, Larry was just
finishing up a stint in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   The government that didn't trust him in 1942 drafted him in
1943.
</P>
<P>
   Larry taught Japanese to Army officers in the Counter
Intelligence Corps in Baltimore, Md. After being discharged, he
came home to enter the school of pharmacy at the University of
Southern California, graduating in 1951 and opening his own
pharmacy, which he ran until retiring in 1985, and moving to
Camarillo with his wife, Yukimi.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where he was last month when the phone rang and the
voice on the other end of the line asked, ``Is this the Larry
Kobayashi who played football at Manual Arts High in 1941?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, everyone on the team knew it wasn't right, Ralph Ahn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the authorities were telling us it was right, so we were
confused,'' said Ahn, a Korean-American and one of Kobayashi's
closest teammates on the Manual Arts football team in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we knew was that the '42 season was starting and Larry
wasn't going to be with us, only because he was Japanese,'' said
Ahn, 72. ``Heck, I was Korean. I thought I was next.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't next. Ahn graduated from Manual Arts, joined the
service and later became a football coach. From 1964 to 1969, he
was head coach at Alemany High School before devoting himself full
time to the family business, the Moongate Restaurant in suburban
Panorama City.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kobayashi, Ahn had moved on with life. But unlike his old
pal, he had also kept an eye on the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once or twice a year, I'd get together socially with the guys,
mostly the football players, and Larry's name would come up,'' Ahn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never got his varsity letter, and he deserved it. Larry was
as much a part of that team as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be great, the guys agreed, if they could find him
now, almost 60 years later, and give him that football letter?
</P>
<P>
   ``But nobody knew where he was,'' Ahn said. ``Then I got lucky
and ran into someone at the Japanese-American Community Center in
Arleta who knew his sister. That's how we finally got a hold of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   So come Oct. 7, at the 5th annual Manual Arts Athletes of the
Ages reunion, one of the guests of honor will be the second-string
right guard who never got the chance to be a starter because he was
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   The captain of this year's football team, along with school
principal Wendell Greer, will present Kobayashi with a special
letterman's jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor, but I don't think I earned it,'' Larry said
Friday, offering no hint of bitterness at what happened to his
family 57 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never looked back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahn said his old pal was wrong, that he certainly did earn that
letterman's jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sure could have used you in '42 because we weren't a very
good team that year,'' Ahn said Friday, seeing his old friend for
the first time in 57 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kobayashi smiled but didn't have the heart to tell him the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   He had a great football year in 1942. He made the varsity and
started at right guard for tiny Northe Cache High School, which
went all the way to the Utah state championship.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
