<HEADLINE>
UNITED BEATS GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Knowing that Colorado blew a chance to take
the Western Conference lead earlier in the day _ and with D.C.
United practically taking the night off _ the Los Angeles Galaxy
did nothing to take advantage of these generous gifts.
</P>
<P>
   United, resting the bulk of its starters for bigger matches next
week, extended its winning streak to 11 with a 2-0 victory over the
Galaxy in front of 29,161 Saturday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Wood and Clint Peay scored for United, handing Los Angeles
its second straight loss during a crucial stretch of matches with
the Western Conference title and playoff positioning yet to be
decided.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy (18-11, 48 points) lead over Colorado (19-9, 47
points) was trimmed to one heading into Wednesday's meeting between
the two clubs at the Rose Bowl. And within striking distance are
Dallas (17-13, 45 points) and Chicago (16-33, 44 points).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not our best game that's for sure,'' said Galaxy coach
Sigi Schmid. ``It's been a while since we lost two straight. We
lost a little of the momentum we have been building up. But if it's
going to happen, it's better that it happens now than in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Eastern Conference regular season title in the bank,
United rested seven of its starters to prepare for next week's
CONCACAF Champions Cup in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Striker Roy Lassister and defender Jeff Agoos came on in the
second half to bolster United's lineup, but the league's best squad
had the look of a reserve team. United is hoping to defend the
CONCACAF title it won last year by beating CD Toluca of Mexico to
become the first U.S. club to win the lA5A% &QC; nship.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-team competition for North and Central America as well
as the Caribbean region has added significance this season. The
winner will earn a berth to January's first-ever FIFA World club
championship to be held in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid says facing a depleted cast is sometimes just as tough as
facing the starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the guys are out there that you know, they are a lot more
predictable,'' said Schmid. ``These guys that they played out there
tonight are confident because this is there chance to make a mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Lassister came in he played 45 minutes and he was no
problem for us. But A.J. Wood and Albright up front were a much
bigger problem for us because of their size. I mean, it really
didn't matter who they put on the field, they were just better than
us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing concern for Los Angeles is the play of Mexican striker
Carlos Hermosillo. He has gone scoreless in his last four games
after returning from back stiffness. And he's rarely getting
chances in front of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had chances against Colorado (last week), but he
didn't have many tonight,'' said Schmid. ``Sometimes he drops to
deep. I also didn't think he had a good game, but I don't think we
provided enough service for him from the midfield.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the depleted cast didn't seem to bother United at
all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6433 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-STANFORD-LAD     09-26 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-STANFORD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD BEATS UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD _ The Bruins attributed this loss to three plays, but
what really beat them was one down _ third down.
</P>
<P>
   If it looked familiar, it was. UCLA's defense was as porous
Saturday against Stanford as it was last season against Miami and
Wisconsin. Ineptitude simply wore a different face; 10 months ago,
the Bruins couldn't stop the run. Saturday, they couldn't stop the
pass, especially on third down.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 42-32 loss before 47,432 at Stanford Stadium
that gave the Cardinal (3-1, 3-0) early-season control of the Rose
Bowl race and put the Bruins (2-2, 0-1) in a familiar position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to treat it like the (season-opening loss to)
Washington State (in 1997), when we came back to win every game
after that,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``There were some good
things to build on (Saturday), and obviously some things to work
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford gained 672 total yards _ just 17 fewer than Miami _ but
that's just the beginning of UCLA's ignominy.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal passed for 465 yards (a record for UCLA opponents)
and averaged an astounding 17 yards per pass attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve quarterback Joe Borchard, of Camarillo, inflicted most
of the damage. He replaced injured starter Todd Husak in the second
quarter and passed for five touchdowns. He also ran for a team-high
74 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford receiver Troy Walters caught nine passes for 278 yards
_ including a Pacific-10-record, 98-yard touchdown catch early in
the third quarter. His yardage total is the third-highest in Pac-10
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to attack them,'' Walters said. ``Our
game plan is to attack no matter who is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing hurt the Bruins more than their ``third-down
defense.'' In the first half, Stanford had six third-down attempts
and needed an average of 8.3 yards to convert. It completed all six
chances and averaged 11 yards in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of the game was their big plays and third downs,''
Bruins defensive tackle Pete Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (2-2, 0-1) actually did a few things right. They
contained Stanford's running game, and they moved the ball
effectively in the second half. They pressured the Cardinal
quarterbacks and got a special-teams touchdown (Lovell Houston's
95-yard kickoff return).
</P>
<P>
   They ran the ball effectively. They did not commit a turnover,
and they showed impressive resiliency for a young team _ 40 of the
60 players were freshmen or sophomores _ by rallying from a 28-3
third-quarter deficit to close within 35-32 late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins could not overcome three obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   First, quarterback Drew Bennett did not execute the downfield
passing game to Toledo's satisfaction. (All-American receiver Danny
Farmer didn't catch a pass, and receiver Freddie Mitchell had no
catches in the second half.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bennett needs to get rid of the ball a little quicker,''
Toledo said. ``We missed balls when guys are open that we need to
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Bruins scored just three points in the first
half despite four possessions in Stanford territory. Meanwhile, the
Cardinal executed like UCLA's offense of recent years and built a
21-3 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Second, UCLA's defense looked dazed and confused on third down,
especially on Stanford's final possession of the first half. The
Cardinal converted four successive third-down plays and scored with
50 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Bruins could not overcome Stanford's three big
plays in the second half: Walters' 98-yard touchdown catch, which
gave Stanford a 28-3 lead; a 32-yard fourth-down run by Stanford
punter Sean Tolpinrud that kept a touchdown drive alive; and
Borchard's 56-yard run on third down, which set up the clinching
touchdown late in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran out of gas at the end,'' Borchard said. ``I needed a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   So did UCLA's defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
