r s BC-FBC-CSUN-EASTERNWASHI     09-26 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-EASTERNWASHINGTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE FALLS TO EASTERN WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ They couldn't be stopped. They couldn't stop
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the way the 1999 season will unfold for the Cal State
Northridge football team? Great offense, terrible defense?
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Washington ran all over the mistake-prone Matadors and
beat CSUN 48-41 in a Big Sky Conference game Saturday night in
front of 3,556 chilled fans at Woodward Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore quarterback Marcus Brady completed 36 of 49 passes for
484 yards and five touchdowns, but it wasn't enough. CSUN lost four
fumbles and the Eagles had not one but two running backs rush for
more than 200 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a misprint. Jovan Griffith had 262 yards and a
school-record six touchdowns, and his backup, Jesse Chatman, had
211 despite missing a large chunk of the game with a twisted ankle
suffered on the last play of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stopping the run is a concern,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff
Kearin said. ``We didn't get it done. We've got to look at what
we're doing on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles (2-2, 1-1) had 456 yards rushing, breaking a
19-year-old school record. Amazingly, CSUN (1-2, 0-1) was still in
the game in the final minute. Brady completed a 26-yard touchdown
pass to Ryan Beckwith with 50 seconds left to make it 48-40. Derek
Brown's extra point cut the lead to a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN tried an onsides kick, which was bobbled for a moment by an
Eagles player but recovered by EWU's Chatman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have four turnovers in a game, you shouldn't
expect to win,'' said Brady, who was also sacked four times.
``We've got to cut down on the turnovers and the mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN was already without one emotional leader before the game
started. Jaumal Bradley, the Matadors' leading rusher and a senior
co-captain, suited but couldn't play because of tonsillitis.
Without Bradley, the Matadors had 73 rushing yards and, more
important, couldn't sustain drives long enough to keep the defense
rested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaumal brings a certain something to the offense,'' Kearin
said. ``That's tough, the emotional loss of him not being on the
field. Everybody felt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two players scored in a first half that featured a combined
56 points and 606 yards of offense _ Griffith and CSUN wide
receiver Terrence Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith's first-half line _ 19 carries for 179 yards and five
touchdowns _ was typical of how bad the Matadors were blown off the
ball in the game's first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, a sophomore from Lompoc and one of only three Eastern
Washington players from California, tied the school's single-game
record for rushing touchdowns in less than a half. His touchdowns
covered 4, 1, 44, 36, 1 and 8 yards.``(Eastern Washington) was
getting it done,'' said CSUN linebacker Cos Abercrombie, who had a
season-high 11 tackles. ``The big play killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN stayed close in the first half thanks to Jones, a senior
transfer from Fresno State who had two touchdown catches, from 59
and 47 yards, and an 86-yard kickoff return to open the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' first touchdown _ on the opening kickoff _ gave the
Matadors a 6-0 lead with the game only 17 seconds old. Jones gave
CSUN its first kickoff return for a touchdown in eight years. As a
receiver, he finished with six catches for 138 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Brady completed passes to nine different receivers. Aaron Arnold
had a team-leading 10 for 130 yards; Arnold broke the school career
record for receiving yards on a 33-yard reception that set up a
touchdown in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Anrold wasn't about to let the defense take the fall for the
loss, even though the Matadors had 557 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put (the defense) in a bad spot sometimes,'' he said. ``We
left them in some bad positions.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither Arnold's record, or Brady's 73 percent completion
rate, or Jones' three touchdowns, could overcome Eastern
Washington's rushing attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you see a team running all over like that... this is
depressing,'' Abercrombie said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
