<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It can be interesting to debate what it means to
pitch well in meaningless September games. It's better than getting
pounded, but just what does it prove about what a pitcher can do in
a meaningful situation? That's what the Los Angeles Dodgers'
decision makers must decide during the offseason when they
contemplate whether to move one of their experienced starters.
</P>
<P>
   When evaluating Eric Gagne, they have four starts to go on.
Three of those, including the Dodgers' 3-2 loss to the San Diego
Padres at Dodger Stadium on Saturday, are impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne yielded two hits and one run in seven innings, but in
typical fashion, he didn't figure in the decision though he left
with a lead. The first two batters reliever Matt Herges (0-2) faced
hit homers. Gagne lost a chance for the win when Wally Joyner's fly
to the right-field wall bounced off Raul Mondesi's glove and over
the fence. Wiki Gonzalez then homered to left to give the Padres a
3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a month of looking for anything to help the future,
Gagne might be what the Dodgers want. The 23-year-old rookie
right-hander has allowed five hits in his last 12 innings and has
25 strikeouts in 24 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him, I like his style,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``He goes at you. The only thing that worries me is his
glasses keep fogging up. Maybe we'll send him to one of those scuba
stores to get that stuff to put on them so they don't fog up
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with the way Gagne's pitching, why change anything?
The French-Canadian struck out seven, one short of the eight
Florida Marlins he fanned in his debut.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne walked one and didn't allow a base runner until Phil Nevin
led off the fifth inning with a single to right. An inning later
Ruben Rivera smashed Gagne's first pitch deep into the left-center
field bleachers to cut the Dodgers' lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm giving up too many homers,'' said Gagne, who's allowed
three homers. ``I need to keep the ball down a little more. I need
to work on all of my stuff. My offspeed, my curveball. I have to
throw it for more strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Dodgers like Gagne's ability to throw strikes with
his fastball or offspeed pitches, but they are equally enamored
with his go-get-`em attitude and his willingness to challenge
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   In Gagne's only loss, the Mets scored five runs in six innings.
But after a two-run homer in the first inning, Gagne retired 17 of
19. In his other three starts, Gagne has allowed two earned runs
and seven hits in 18 innings. To show for it, Gagne's 0-1 with a
2.63 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
