<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6440 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN     09-26 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FALL FOR FAKE PUNT THAT WASN'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Stanford punter Sean Tolpinrud's play was so
good, the Bruins thought it was a fake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to ask them, but it looked like one to me,''
Bruins coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Tolpinrud's 32-yard fourth-down run was not a called play.
</P>
<P>
   It was pure improvisation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The snap took me to the right, so I started to the right to
get it,'' he said. ``I knew it would be hard to get a punt off, and
I saw nothing but grass. Rather than try to punt, I thought I
better take off and run.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a split-second decision _ one made so naturally that the
Bruins thought it was a fake punt called from the sideline.
Tolpinrud raced 32 yards to UCLA's 18, and on the next play
Stanford scored to take a 35-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a basketball play where a guy shoots a 30-footer and
the coach is saying, `No, no, no, yes,''' Cardinal coach Tyrone
Willingham said. ``The only thing I told Sean to do was get out of
bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   First touch, first touchdown: One of UCLA's biggest plays came
from an unexpected source: freshman Lovell Houston, who returned a
kickoff 95 yards for a touchdown early in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Houston, an oft-injured cornerback, has
touched the ball at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the sideline, and at that point we were (trailing
28-3),'' Houston said. ``I heard coach Toledo call, `Houston.' He
said, `Here's your chance, baby. I'm going to put you in and see
what you get.'''
</P>
<P>
   What Toledo got was UCLA's first kickoff-return touchdown since
JoJo Townsell in 1980. The play re-energized UCLA seconds after
Stanford receiver Troy Walters' 98-yard touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the one good call I made the whole day,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   QB review: Quarterback Drew Bennett's numbers were impressive _
19 of 31 for 207 yards _ but the passes he missed were more
important than the ones he completed.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett had open receivers all day, but he either didn't see
them or threw the ball too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-five percent of quarterbacking is knowing what you
see,'' he said. ``I had trouble doing that. You can't be a Division
I quarterback and do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' quarterback situation has not changed. If freshman
Cory Paus (bruised ribs) is healthy, he will start Saturday at
Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Tailback DeShaun Foster gained 100 yards for the
first time this season....
</P>
<P>
   Bruins kicker Chris Griffith missed his first field goal of the
season when the Cardinal blocked a 49-yard attempt in the first
quarter....
</P>
<P>
   Safety Joey Strycula led the Bruins with 11 tackles....
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Tony White's father, Anthony, died of a heart attack
Friday. He was 42. White played against Stanford and made five
tackles....
</P>
<P>
   UCLA reported no significant injuries....
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Walters needs 56 yards and 24 catches to set the
Pac-10 career record in both categories.....
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins lost despite two penalties and no turnovers....
</P>
<P>
   UCLA lost a conference game for the first time since the
season-opening defeat against Washington State in 1997, a string of
15 wins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
