</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE INJURY DOESN'T FAZE MATADORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ It happened again. This time, though, the tactic
wasn't as devious.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge coaches didn't know until Saturday
morning that Eastern Washington quarterback Fred Salanoa had a
serious knee injury and wasn't going to play against the visiting
Matadors. Salanoa, who started the Eagles' first three games and
had not practiced since Wednesday, found out Friday afternoon he
had a torn medial meniscus and is out for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Salanoa's replacement, sophomore Chris Samms, was 9 of 18 for
132 yards and no touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kearin, CSUN's interim head coach, said Salanoa's absence
didn't have any effect on the Matadors' defensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to run the ball,'' Kearin said.
``(Head coach Mike) Kramer said he didn't know anything about
(Salanoa) until he walked off the practice field Friday, after I
had already talked to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation involving Salanoa is similar to last year's
hidden-injury fiasco against Montana, when the Grizzles chose not
to report a back injury to All-American quarterback Brian Ah Yat,
who didn't suit up in CSUN's 21-7 win.
</P>
<P>
   Missing man:!off When Samms got hurt in the third quarter,
almost forcing the Eagles to use third-string Lance Hattemer, a
junior college transfer with no Division I-AA experience, thoughts
drifted to Griffin Garske.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Garske? He started 10 games for the Eagles last year,
and threw for 404 yards against CSUN. But he quit the team after
the season when he was told by Kramer that he wasn't going to be
the starter this season.
</P>
<P>
   There's no place like it: It took four years, but Patrick Cwik
finally got a chance to play in front of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Cwik, a senior backup linebacker at CSUN, is from nearby
Spokane. He transferred to Northridge from Hancock College in 1997
and the Matadors hosted Eastern Washington last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chazz Moore, a senior cornerback from Portland, also had family
attend the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sparkling effort: Senior safety Rahman Sparks saved a touchdown
in the first quarter when he knocked the ball out of tight end Dan
Curley's hands in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Curley was getting ready to cradle the ball when Sparks' big hit
jarred it loose.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks later left the game with what the CSUN trainers called
rib contusions. He is doubftul for next week's home game against
Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
   Two firsts: Senior linebacker Jack Heaslet got his first
interception as a Matador when he picked off Samms near the CSUN
goal line in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Moore got his first interception of the season, and third of his
career, in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Embarassing! Once again, CSUN hurt itself with penalties. The
Matadors committed 10 Saturday for 82 yards, and the worst penalty
could have been a personal foul on backup quarterback Josh Fiske.
Fiske was called for a late hit on a kickoff return in the first
half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 0237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
