<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6442 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-FBC-UCLASIDE2-LADN     09-26 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLASIDE2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL OFFENSE EXPLOITS UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAMONA SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Stanford had the playmakers. UCLA didn't.
</P>
<P>
   True to Pacific 10 Conference form, neither team looked
especially good on defense and that was the difference as the
Cardinal exploited UCLA's defensive weaknesses in a 42-32 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford totalled 672 yards of total offense, an onslaught that
attacked the Bruins from every possible angle.
</P>
<P>
   Preseason All-America Troy Walters had 278 yards receiving and
three touchdowns. Backup quarterback and former Camarillo star Joe
Borchard came off the bench to throw for 324 yards and five
touchdowns, including a 14-yarder to DeRonnie Pitts in the fourth
quarter that put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game plan is to get the ball to our playmakers. Troy is
one, DeRonnie is one, and David Davis is one,'' Stanford coach
Tyrone Willingham said. ``We're going to get the ball to them in a
position where they can make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That plan was apparent from the start. On Stanford's fourth
play, starting quarterback Todd Husak hooked up with Walters on a
flea-flicker good for a 42-yard gain. The play, and subsequent
scoring drive capped off Kerry Carter's 5-yard touchdown run
epitomized an offense that executed one big strike after another.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Husak left the game in the second quarter with injured
ribs, the Cardinal cruised along, lighting up an inexperienced
Bruins secondary for 465 yards passing, the most UCLA had ever
surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford had six plays for more than 20 yards _ including
Borchard's Pac-10 record-breaking 98-yard touchdown pass to
Walters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a lot of true freshmen out there and that kind of
things shows in a game like this,'' said Pitts, who finished with
two touchdowns and 119 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Borchard, a two-sport star who is more accustomed to making big
plays on the Cardinal's baseball team, performed brilliantly.
Besides the 324 yards passing _ achieved in only three quarters _
he also broke loose on a 56-yard run on third-and-5 midway though
the fourth quarter, extending a drive that eventually resulted in a
Pitts touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it was a case of a playmaker making a play. Pitts caught
the ball at the Bruins' 5-yard line, then hurled himself over the
goal line from about 3 yards out for the touchdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 0239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 04:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6448 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-REWRITE-LADN     09-26 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC LOSES IN TRIPLE OT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ USC lost Carson Palmer on Saturday night, but
even that staggering blow could not overshadow an emotional 33-30,
triple-overtime loss to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans went back and forth with the Ducks before finally
succumbing in the third overtime, despite playing the second half
without Palmer, who might have broken his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   USC's David Newbury shanked a 37-yard field goal in the third
overtime, and Oregon won it when third-string kicker Josh Frankel
kicked a 27-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon lost starting kicker Nathan Villegas to a knee injury and
backup kicker Dan Katz missed a field goal in the first extra
period.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams missed field goals in the first overtime and scored
touchdowns in the second.
</P>
<P>
   As memorable as the game was, USC coach Paul Hackett was mostly
upset over the Trojans' performance.
</P>
<P>
   USC set a Pacific-10 Conference game record with 21 penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not about Oregon, it's about us,'' Hackett said. ``We
had mistakes all over the place. We had a holding penalty on a
touchdown. It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans nearly won without Palmer, their talented sophomore
quarterback around whom they built so much of their offense, when
he injured his right shoulder in the first half and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   He would be eligible for a redshirt year if he is forced to miss
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But at least inside Autzen Stadium, Palmer's injury was
forgotten as the Trojans fought hard without their star
quarterback, and got a wonderful effort from Mike Van Raaphorst
(20-36, 227 yards, one touchdown).
</P>
<P>
   After trailing 20-10, USC scored 13 straight points. But just
when USC seemed to win it, Oregon tied the score 23-23 when
Villegas kicked a 26-yard field goal with 30 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst directed USC on two touchdown drives, including
the go-ahead touchdown with 3:08 left when Chad Morton scored on a
1-yard run. That gave the Trojans a 23-20 lead, but a bad snap
botched the extra point, which would prove crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's hope for a comeback seemed finished when Jason Cooper
fumbled the ensuing kickoff and USC linebacker Aaron Graham
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   But David Newbury missed a critical 30-yard field goal with 2:16
left. It turned out to be a costly miss, because Oregon marched
down the field and tied the game with 30 seconds remaining in the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was forced to watch the game in street clothes in the
second half with his right shoulder in a sling. Oregon lost its two
top tailbacks, Reuben Droughns and Herman Ho-Ching, to injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's injury occurred two plays before the first half ended,
when he scrambled to the sideline and was hit hard by Oregon rover
Michael Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   USC didn't lose its offense without Palmer, as the Trojans moved
the ball consistently with Van Raaphorst. One of Van Raaphorst's
best passes was a 26-yard completion to R. Jay Soward (12 catches,
148 yards) in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But after Soward caught the pass at the Oregon 26, he was hit by
Tamoni Joinder and fumbled. Linebacker Matt Smith recovered the
fumble, and three plays later, Feeley hit Tony Hartley on a 43-yard
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Feeley, who was brilliant most of the game, found Ho-Ching on a
swing pass for a 9-yard touchdown pass that put the Ducks ahead
20-10.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst continued to play admirably, hitting true freshman
Steve Stevenson on a 28-yard pass in the fourth quarter. Tailback
Chad Morton scored on a 2-yard run to cut the deficit to 20-17.
Stevenson injured his left ankle on the reception and did not
return.
</P>
<P>
   The game, between two of the conference's top teams, lived up to
its billing and the Trojans were touting the ramifications even
before the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to determine where we are in the Pac-10 and the
whole season,'' Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   But that analysis became muddled after Palmer's injury. Oregon
suffered its own catastrophe, when tailback Droughns separated his
ribs and tore cartilage and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks found other ways to move the ball without Droughns.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon caught the Trojans off guard on its opening possession of
the second half. With a fourth-and-1 situation at the Oregon 39,
the Ducks lined up to punt. But the snap went to up back Justin
Wilcox, who pitched the ball to punter Kurtis Doerr on an option.
Doerr ended up gaining 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The drive eventually stalled at the USC 2-yard line, and Oregon
kicker Nathan Villegas put the Ducks ahead 13-10 with a 19-yard
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   With Palmer, the two teams played a dead even game. That was
reflected in more than the 10-10 halftime score. USC had 17 yards
rushing, Oregon 20. USC had 135 yards passing, Oregon 130. The
Trojans had 152 yards in offense, while the Ducks had 150.
</P>
<P>
   Things could not have started any better for the Trojans.
Droughns fumbled on the first play of the game, and free safety Ife
Ohalete recovered at the Ducks' 24.
</P>
<P>
   USC's first play was a 23-yard pass from Palmer to Stevenson.
The Trojans then proved they can score in their goal-line offense
as Morton ran it in from the 1. Offensive guard Faasea Mailo lined
up at fullback on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon responded later in the quarter by going 65 yards before
its drive stalled at the USC 29. Villegas kicked a 46-yard field
goal to cut the lead to 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Then it got worse for the Trojans. Palmer was intercepted by
free safety McLemore and the Ducks took over at the USC 39.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Enyi Nwamuo had the big play, a 22-yard reception, and
then had a 1-yard touchdown reception just over linebacker Zeke
Moreno's outstretched hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans tied the game 10-10 on the ensuing drive when David
Newbury kicked a 29-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite bringing out loudspeakers in practice, the Trojans
offensive line had five false starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 0402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-GORE-0927-COX     09-26 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON'S HELP FOR GORE CAMPAIGN COULD ALSO HURT VICE
PRESIDENT'S BID
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Standing in the sun-dappled splendor of the Rose
Garden last week, President Clinton ceremoniously killed the
centerpiece of the Republican legislative agenda _ a $792 billion
tax cut _ with the stroke of a pen.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vetoed the package, he said, to protect the country from
a return to the ravages of Republican policies he blamed for
quadrupling the federal debt, raising interest rates and stifling
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore and I came into office determined to
change all that, with a new economic strategy focused on fiscal
discipline, expanded trade, investment in our people,'' said
Clinton. ``This strategy has worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks, it turns out, are part of yet another
strategy, this one intended to help Al Gore succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   With Gore trailing Republican frontrunner George W. Bush by
nearly 20 points in national polls, and former Sen. Bill Bradley
mounting a surprisingly strong challenge as a Democratic
alternative to the vice president, Clinton is looking for ways to
help his second-in-command.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the formula is to use every opportunity _ a presidential
veto power with a White House backdrop, for example _ to associate
Gore with the successes of the Clinton administration, beginning
with an economy that has grown nearly 40 percent since Clinton took
office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done more with the job he's had the last six and a half
years than any person in history,'' Clinton told two dozen wealthy
Democratic donors attending a Gore fund raising dinner last week in
a dark-paneled room at the Hay-Adams Hotel, across from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, though, helping Gore's campaign is a far more
complicated proposition than simply sharing the presidential
spotlight and proffering accolades and toasts.
</P>
<P>
   His own presidency is indelibly stained by scandal. There are
signs that the public is weary of Clinton and his political and
personal entourage. And when he plays to his rhetorical strengths
it often only highlights Gore's own limitations in connecting with
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's role in helping Gore, in other words, is heavily
circumscribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton can help him only in a very careful sort of
way,'' said Brown University political science professor Darrell
West. ``He can't be heavy-handed about helping him.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents have a natural tendency to be cautious in promoting
their number-twos, whether because of petty jealousy, professional
egotism or reservations borne of working closely with them for four
or more years.
</P>
<P>
   Few vice presidents have won election to replace their bosses.
In 1988, George Bush became the first sitting vice president to be
elected to the top job since Martin Van Buren's win 152 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The White House insists that Clinton very much wants Gore to be
the next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you with 100 percent certainty that he's not
ambivalent,'' said Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Lockhart, Clinton views Gore's campaign as
something of a mission, one key to the Clinton legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He honestly believes that we've changed the way we do business
in this town,'' said Lockhart. ``It's very important to him that we
build on this success, rather than undo many of the steps we've
taken to move forward, and he thinks that the vice president's the
best person to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the best way to help Gore, though, is dicey.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things any vice president seeking the
presidency must do is convince the public that, after years of
playing a supporting role, he's suddenly ready to lead.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton to take an aggressive approach in the selling of Al
Gore might only underscore Clinton's leadership abilities, not
Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem for a vice president always is to establish
themselves as their own person without repudiating their boss,''
said Jonathan Siegel, director of the Harris Interactive Election
2000, a project of the Rochester, N.Y.,-based Harris polling
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to Al Gore to both have the message and the ability to
communicate it,'' said Siegel. ``Bill Clinton can't do it for him,
his handlers can't do it and his advisers can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore appears to suffer, moreover, in areas where Clinton is
strong.
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken Sept. 10-14 among 1,698 Americans by the Gallup
Organization shows Gore trailing George W. Bush by 19 points in
people's perceptions of Gore's effectiveness as a manager; by 16
points in his ability to affect change; and by 20 points in his
ability to inspire others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the same things that Clinton has done well on
historically,'' said Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup
Polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Bill Clinton transfers those kinds of characteristics onto
Gore is a real challenge,'' said Newport. ``I don't think that you
can do that by osmosis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore-Clinton equation is further complicated by Clinton's
impeachment-marred conduct in office. Enough Americans from both
parties still regard Clinton's behavior as sufficiently
reprehensible, and his impact on the office as sufficiently
corrosive, that Gore stands to suffer, in some quarters at least,
by association.
</P>
<P>
   At best, Clinton polarized much of the nation, splitting the
electorate into Clinton supporters and Clinton despisers. That's
left precious little of the ideological middle ground over which
presidential campaigns are fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Al Gore, would I really want Bill Clinton going
around and campaigning for me,'' wondered Roger Hartley, who
teaches government at Roanoke College in Salem, Va. ``The president
is kind of a lightning rod.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from those who feel strongly one way or the other about
Clinton, there appears to be a substantial portion of the American
public that has simply overdosed on the rich media diet of Clinton
fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this phenomenon out there, Clinton fatigue, that
makes it hard for Clinton to go out there and help Gore,'' said Dan
Thomas, professor of political science at Warburg College in
Waverly, Iowa. ``It could amount to the kiss of death.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One group that is anything but fatigued, however, consists of
the long-term Democratic Party stalwarts who recall with a shudder
the party's pre-Clinton malaise. They credit the president, despite
his faults, for having reinvented and reinvigorated the entire
party.
</P>
<P>
   These backers turn out en masse at fund-raisers and rallies,
where Clinton invariably receives a rock star's reception. He
remains able to electrify a crowd like no other politician of his
generation. To the extent that's useful to Gore, Clinton is
prepared to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If going out and raising money is helpful he's going to do
that. If going and making appearances is helpful he's going to do
that,'' said Lockhart. ``If staying here and concentrating on
getting things done is helpful he's going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As a backdrop for appearing presidential, it's hard to beat the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   West said he would expect to see Clinton do everything possible
in the months ahead to portray Gore as a co-partner in the
administration's achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do it by sharing credit, making sure the vice president
gets a lot of press, giving him positive announcements to make and
sending him to foreign funerals, where he can look presidential and
meet with foreign leaders,'' said West.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Clinton and Gore will both face the limits on what
one man can do for another. Public perceptions aren't always easily
swayed and no amount of praise from a figure of boundless charisma
can create the same persona in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's hurting Gore currently,'' said Newport, ``is Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   What's clear, though, is that those who thought Clinton had
waged his last campaign were wrong. He's embarked on at least one
more _ this time, for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been going through this campaign all my
life,'' Clinton said Friday in a speech to members of the
Democratic National Committee, ``and I'm not even running.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 0921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CLINTON-GORE-0927-COX     09-26 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON'S HELP FOR GORE CAMPAIGN COULD ALSO HURT VICE
PRESIDENT'S BID
