<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JESSEJAMES27-COX     09-26 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSEJAMES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge refuses to allow Jesse James' body to be exhumed
 &HT;    By Brad Reagan
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARLIN, Texas _ From the third row of a Falls County courtroom,
Byron Courtney Jr. strained to hear the words of the attorneys
arguing up front.
</P>
<P>
   At 83, Courtney couldn't make out the details of the dialogue,
but he knew they were jousting over whether his grandfather, the
man who practically raised him, was really the outlaw Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   To Courtney, his grandfather was ``a man of honor and a man of
his word,'' not a murderer and bank robber.
</P>
<P>
   Or was he? Courtney's family is bitterly divided over the
identity of its patriarch. It is an emotional dispute that was
heard in court recently, but it may never be resolved to everyone's
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney, of Waco, is one of a faction at odds with Liberty Hill
resident Betty Dorsett Duke over her 1998 book, ``Jesse James Lived
and Died in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke says James L. Courtney, her great-great-grandfather, was
actually the notorious gunman who most historians believe was shot
in the back of the head in 1882 by Bob Ford. Duke says she believes
James pulled ``one of the biggest bluffs in American history'' by
faking his death and living out the rest of his days as a farmer
near Blevins in Falls County.
</P>
<P>
   Tales that James faked his death and moved to Texas are nothing
new.
</P>
<P>
   According to one story, he moved to Granbury, near Fort Worth,
and lived under the name J. Frank Dalton until he died in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1992, two brothers claiming to be James'
great-grandsons showed up in Waco to look for $14 million in gold
they said he buried there. They never found it.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Duke produced photos showing similarities between
James and Courtney and between their mothers, and she noted that
census records revealed no listing for James L. Courtney before
James' death. She also produced a diary entry by Courtney that
appears to be signed ``J. James.''
</P>
<P>
   Although not totally convinced, some historians and Western lore
enthusiasts refused to dismiss Duke's claim. And after the first
edition of the book was released, Willie Ford, a descendant of
James' alleged shooter, Bob Ford, wrote Duke to weigh in that his
family long believed James' death was faked, Duke said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the book came out, the family split into two factions. One
believes there is a good chance James L. Courtney was Jesse James.
The other, the larger of the two, thinks the mere thought is a
disgrace to the man's memory.
</P>
<P>
   To settle the matter once and for all, Duke asked Falls County
Judge Michael Meyer to exhume Courtney's body in order to compare
DNA samples from the body with samples from known descendants of
Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   The same procedure was done in 1995 on remains buried near
Kearney, Mo. Tests showed that body was that of James, but Duke
says she believes those tests were flawed. As historian James E.
Starrs, who oversaw the 1995 exhumation, once observed, ``Legends
die hard, and Jesse James legends die hardest of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Courtney Jr. fought the exhumation with the support of
most of the rest of the family during a five-hour hearing Friday,
Sept. 17, in Marlin. Max Courtney, a forensic scientist in Fort
Worth and a great-grandson of James L. Courtney, testified that
some of Duke's photographs appear to have been doctored.
</P>
<P>
   The photos purport to show that James L. Courtney's mother and
Jesse James' mother were both missing their right arm, but Max
Courtney produced an original photograph that he said showed that
Duke's photo had been reversed and otherwise altered to make it
appear that Courtney's mother was missing an arm.
</P>
<P>
   Duke said two photograph experts told her the photos showed a
match between the two women. She said she had no knowledge of the
photo being reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Duke and her daughter, Teresa, both broke down on the stand
while testifying, but they received little sympathy from the other
family members. At one point, as Teresa Duke testified that a
Courtney elder once confessed that he believed Courtney was Jesse
James, a prim elderly woman in a pink pantsuit leaned over to her
husband and whispered loudly, ``That's crap.''
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Teresa Duke asked Meyer to approve the exhumation on
the grounds that ``maybe the families will unite and stop all this
fighting and bickering.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in his ruling Meyer cited the ``sanctity of the grave''
and ruled that Duke's evidence was not persuasive enough to require
exhumation.
</P>
<P>
   The Courtney family was elated. ``We knew all along it was a
hoax,'' said Byron Courtney Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it's over,'' added Max Courtney.
``That's proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's attorney, Jim Rodman of Austin, said there is little
chance she will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Betty Duke vowed to continue her fight.
She said she is not angry with her family, just disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're ashamed. They think of Jesse James as a
cold-blooded killer. They don't take into account that it was
because of the Civil War and his beliefs,'' Duke said. ``I won't
quit. I still believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
