<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-REDFILES-REVIEW-NY     09-26 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REDFILES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RED FILES': THE ROSENBERGS AND OTHER SPIES, EXPOSED BY RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Program notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Count it as an unanticipated bonus of the end of the Cold War:
Secret KGB files have been opened for the inspection of Western
scholars, and former Soviet spymasters have been boasting to
reporters of their achievements in purloining America's
technological know-how. The information provided and the deductions
they invite have at least (and, one hopes, at last) put an end to
the cottage industries that for decades proclaimed the innocence of
Julius and Ethel Rosenberg and others of any spying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Files: Secret Victories of the KGB,'' the opening hour of
a four-part PBS series (the subsequent three weekly reports go
behind the scenes of Soviet sports, the Soviet moon mission and
Soviet propaganda), focuses on the careers of Morris and Lona
Cohen, an American couple of Communist persuasion whose names long
ago surfaced in studies of espionage at Los Alamos when the atomic
bomb was being developed. Now, with the help of former Soviet and
Western agents, the Cohens' story is told in more detail, revealing
the impulses that drew scores of Westerners into the service of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Cohen, a New Yorker, was recruited by Soviet intelligence
in Spain where he fought and was wounded with the Communist-led
Abraham Lincoln Brigade in the 1930s. Like other spies _ one source
says there were at least 125 in the United States _ he served not
for money but for ideology.
</P>
<P>
   George Blake, an important British agent who would wind up, like
the Cohens, being arrested and freed in a prisoner swap, is seen
saying he still believes he was helping to build a new society,
and, ``It is never wrong to give your life to a noble ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, when Cohen was in the Army, his wife passed
industrial secrets to her Soviet handlers. Her biggest assignment
was to pick up material from a Los Alamos physicist, Ted Hall. She
hid the secrets in an uninspected Kleenex box, which a security
guard gallantly returned to her after he had searched her other
belongings. The narrator credits Mrs. Cohen and Americans of like
opinions with helping to give the Soviets the information they
needed to detonate a bomb of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The names of Klaus Fuchs, Kim Philby, Gordon Londsdale and other
notorious Soviet agents also figure in ``Red Files.'' As for the
Rosenbergs, a former Soviet agent says that Rosenberg provided
``invaluable intelligence about radar and sonar,'' but not about
the atom bomb, and he contends that the couple's execution was
unjustified: ``America wanted to kill somebody for the fact that
the Soviet Union so quickly built an atom bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Rosenbergs' arrest in 1950 the Cohens were
spirited out of the United States and then worked for Soviet
intelligence in Moscow and in London, where they were finally
arrested in 1961. They were sentenced to 20 years in prison, but in
1969 they were exchanged, presumably for Western spies, and settled
in the Soviet Union, where they were awarded medals.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end they seemed to have some misgivings. Mrs. Cohen
emphasized to a KGB interrogator at a debriefing that ``no American
soldier died because of what I have done,'' and her husband spoke,
somewhat delicately, about ``mistakes'' that fell upon the Soviet
Union during the Stalin period.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cohen confided to a Russian friend that she would like to
die in the United States, but she and her husband are buried in a
Moscow cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RED FILES: SECRET VICTORIES OF THE KGB'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday night at 9 (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   A production of Invision with Abamedia in association with PBS
and Devillier Donegan Enterprises. J. Mitchell Johnson, series
producer for Abamedia; Ron Devillier and Brian Donegan, executive
producers for Devillier Donegan Enterprises; William Cran and Kate
Leonard-Morgan, series producers for Invision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
