<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-US-MAG-MEDIA-ART-2TAK     09-26 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MAG-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WENNER MEDIA TAKES ON TIME INC. IN TRANSFORMING US INTO A MONTHLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Two graphics and a photo are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jann Wenner walked into the private dining room that
joins his office at the Wenner Media headquarters on the Avenue of
the Americas, strode to the window and looked up at the Time and
Life Building, towering in the afternoon sun, two blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There it is,'' Wenner said, running a hand over his wavy,
just-graying hair. ``The evil empire. The colossus.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the forbidding Time and Life monolith made Wenner's
media empire _ all one floor of it _ look, well, puny.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, two weeks ago Wenner announced that he would
challenge Time Inc.'s two major entertainment weekly magazines,
People and Entertainment Weekly, by changing the frequency of Us
magazine _ Wenner Media's barely profitable entertainment magazine
_ from monthly to weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The kickoff of Us Weekly, scheduled for March, sets up what will
be one of the most intriguing magazine publishing battles of 2000.
It also raises this question, to use the lingo that gave birth to
Rolling Stone: What is this guy smoking to think he can take on the
reigning kings of journalism lite?
</P>
<P>
   And there's another issue: Is there room, or a need, for even
more celebrity coverage _ coverage that Wenner and his chief
managers freely admit will be friendly and sycophantic?
</P>
<P>
   This David-versus-Goliath gamble will cost Wenner dearly. The
54-year-old publishing magnate, who since founding Rolling Stone
magazine 32 years ago with a loan of $3,000 has been a living
symbol of the boomer generation, said he would spend at least $50
million of his money to transform the moribund Us _ with its
sinking advertising revenue and stalled circulation _ into a
scorching weekly success.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, you think, gee, that's risky,'' Wenner said
over a lunch of sashimi and ginger ale in the private dining room.
He wore a Charvet shirt, gold cuff links and custom-made trousers.
``And you think, wow, that's a lot of money,'' he said. ``My money.
But the payoff of a weekly magazine is enormous. We have a
well-known national brand name and a loyal readership. We have
loyal advertisers. When you look at it as a publishing proposition,
and think about the advertising possibilities, and look at how the
distribution system works, then the whole thing reaches a kind of
critical mass you just can't ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   But the big question is: Why does he need to take such an
enormous risk? After all, he does not need to prove himself: He may
not own the biggest media conglomerate in the world but Wenner
Media _ which publishes Us, Rolling Stone and Men's Journal _ is
generally respected in the industry. Every so often, he said, he is
offered a large sum of money for Rolling Stone, a magazine that
regularly wins National Magazine Awards and serializes the work of
authors like Tom Wolfe. He said the most recent offer was for $500
million, which he turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking Us weekly is important to me, not as a mission, but
because it is fun,'' he said. ``And I think that a certain amount
of power and influence comes out of a weekly frequency because you
have the power of the news. And, of course,'' he said, dropping his
voice to what could almost be described as a seductive growl, ``I
also think it will be very, very profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Wenner's life has changed dramatically since he was a
22-year-old with a loan from his girlfriend's father and a penchant
for rock music. Once branded ``Boy Wonder'' by the press, Wenner
has become a repository of sorts for an entire generation's hopes
and foibles: As boomers have gone mainstream, so has Wenner, and
even he recognizes that his transformation is starkly evident. When
asked if as a young man he ever thought that he would spend entire
weeks thinking about supermarket racks and distribution systems, he
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started out, I had no master plan,'' Wenner said. ``The
times were laissez-faire. What was hip was to have a hassle-free
life.'' He arched an eyebrow dramatically, and said: ``But we all
know that little fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   When discussing Men's Journal, which has become more of a
lifestyle magazine than the adventure journal of its original
conception, Wenner departed on a reverie about physical mortality
worthy of Hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to an age where your body is starting to creak and you
start paying attention to yourself,'' he said. ``Your appearance
matters. Fashion and all that stuff. What defines quality of life
is radically different from what it was 30 or 40 years ago.'' He
added: ``You're trying to get the most out of what's left of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And the ``Boy Wonder'' title, he added, has got to go.
</P>
<P>
   ```Boy Wonder' was amazing. It stuck until I was 45,'' he said.
What would Wenner like to be called now? ``How fast can you leap to
`eminence grise'?'' he asked. (He settled on ``Junior Tycoon.'')
</P>
<P>
   Wenner's life has changed more markedly than most boomers. In
1995, his marriage to Jane Wenner _ the co-founder of Straight
Arrow Publishing, the forebear to Wenner Media _ unraveled when he
began to see a young staff member at Calvin Klein, Matt Nye.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wenners are not divorced, nor are they separated. They
own Wenner Media together, so her financial cooperation is vital to
the success of Us Weekly. Wenner does not deny his relationship
with Nye, but said he chooses not to discuss it or its impact on
his company.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to the extent that Us is involved, she is fully on
board,'' he said of his wife. ``And that's what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   To Time Warner's Time Inc. what matters is the potential for
competition. It has not ignored Wenner. Over the last year, the
company has designated People editors to closely monitor Us
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Time editors admit in private conversation that they are nervous
about the possibility of another weekly celebrity-oriented magazine
competing for space in supermarket checkout lines across the
country, although they add that Time spent $175 million on
Entertainment Weekly before it became profitable.
</P>
<P>
   On the record, editors at People will admit nothing but world
domination. Carol Wallace, the managing editor of People, said: ``A
lot of things keep me up at night but any monthly going weekly sure
isn't one of them. I am so far more concerned about what goes into
our issue than what goes into theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wenner and his general manager, Kent Brownridge, became
convinced of the profitability of taking Us weekly when they first
discussed the notion with an executive at DSI, a magazine
distribution service whose main competitor is _ who else? _ a
Time-Warner subsidiary, Time Distribution Services, the company
that fills supermarket shelves with People and Entertainment Weekly
every week. DSI is owned by American Media, the company that
publishes The National Enquirer. Brownridge admits that he became
fixated on the idea of Us dominating supermarket shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game is getting retailers to allow you to put
your rack on every single checkout line _ not every other one, not
every third, but every single line,'' Brownridge said. ``So no one
can possibly escape from the store without seeing Us. We're going
to be out there with the carrots and the Campbell's Soup and the
bottles of milk. And a supermarket looks at it like this: How much
profit per square foot can I make? After all, how much do they make
on vegetables? It's a lot of work keeping them fresh. It's a
drag.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing Brownridge's confidence that magazines sell better than
vegetables, Wenner also said the early Entertainment Weekly
investment is not a good comparison _ that because his magazine is
an existing brand, and has a million readers, he does not need to
spend $175 million. And he does not want to mimic People. Indeed,
there is an almost palpable disdain for People's middlebrow
sensibility at Wenner Media. Terry McDonell, the editor of Men's
Journal, who will be the editor in chief of Us Weekly, said: ``We
will not be showing pictures of surgeons in Houston throwing
frisbees to cocker spaniels, if you get what I mean.'' (His No. 2,
Charles Leerhsen, was previously the deputy managing editor of
People.)
</P>
<P>
   Us Weekly will be more style-oriented (one tentative feature is
titled ``Ten Ways a Celebrity Can Wear a Sarong'') and, as Wenner
said, ``we will be nice to celebrities. A lot of my friends are in
the entertainment business, and People has a terrible relationship
with those people. Famous people hate being in People.'' Wenner's
close friends, he said, include pop singer Robbie Robertson, USA
Networks chief Barry Diller and the actor Michael Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Brownridge said Us would more closely resemble a weekly, young
version of Vanity Fair than it would People.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to focus on young celebrities,'' Brownridge said.
``We're not going to do the little girl who fell down the well or
the three women who got eaten by bears in Yosemite. And we are not
going to look for negative stuff or write nasty sleaze. I don't
think we're going to hire helicopters to fly over Jennifer Aniston
and Brad Pitt's wedding so it sounds like `China Beach' or
`Apocalypse Now' with the choppers overhead. Celebrities are going
to like Us Weekly. It is going to be their friend.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But do readers want celebrity-friendly coverage _ a formula that
has worked so well for Time's In Style _ in a weekly magazine? Some
in the advertising industry are skeptical. Roberta Garfinkle, the
director of print media at the advertising agency McCann-Erickson,
said her general prognosis was unsure. ``Will they be able to hold
their circulation?'' she asked. ``Will they be able to
consistently, week after week, deliver a relevant newsworthy
celebrity magazine? I think that's really tough, and I am not sure
if he knows what he has gotten himself into.''
</P>
<P>
   E. Daniel Capell, an expert in magazine circulation and the
editor of Capell's Circulation Report, said the critical issue is
that Us is barely meeting its rate base _ the circulation
guaranteed to advertisers _ as it is. ``So what happens to the
newsstand sale which they are not getting in 30 days if you go
weekly?'' he said. ``It seems to me to be awfully difficult to
maintain, let alone increase, circulation if you go to a weekly
frequency. That's an awful lot of sales to get in seven days you're
not even getting in 30 days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gene DeWitt, the president of DeWitt Media, which places ads
for clients like BMW, said Wenner is ``crazy like a fox. The
advertising demand is there for it, because marketing has
accelerated and we need more weekly venues.'' He said that with a
weekly schedule, advertisers will be better able to time their ads
to their promotional needs, a necessity for car manufacturers whose
rebate schedules and sale dates can change at the last minute, and
for entertainment companies whose movie release dates and
promotional plans change frequently.
</P>
<P>
   If half of creating a profitable magazine is healthy
advertising, then the other half must surely be plain mojo. And
Wenner's got plenty of it. In discussing his friend and semi-rival,
Art Cooper, the editor in chief of the men's magazine GQ, Wenner
said: ``Art is funny, you know. He loves to go around saying that
he is the best magazine editor in America.'' Wenner paused, let his
eyebrows wriggle for dramatic effect, then added: ``But of course,
that's me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
