<SLUG> BC-YACHT-RACE-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEADLY REGATTA SPURS RACE TO BE FIRST IN BOOKSTORES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Mont., Australia)   (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crowded race to publish books about the disastrous
Sydney-Hobart yacht competition of 1998 has all the critical
elements of calamity adventure _except, of course, multiple deaths.
</P>
<P>
   There are the four fiercely competitive authors: an
underfinanced Montana fly fisherman with a scrappy
David-vs.-Goliath attitude; a seasoned Australian journalist and
former weatherman with ocean racing experience; a secretive
reporter for The Wall Street Journal on leave to write a book, and
a rugged Southern Californian with a zest for kayaking and climbing
on the international endurance-sport circuit.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the nail-gnawing race: writing a riveting and
commercially successful tale of the malevolent storm that took the
lives of six sailors in the tragic December 1998 ocean-sailing
competition from Sydney, Australia, to Hobart, Tasmania.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the Australian sailing event itself, which is often
labeled the Everest of open-ocean racing, the crowded writing
competition has evolved into a contest of speed, creativity,
surprise maneuvers, high-technology, jockeying for sources and,
naturally, sniping about adventure resumes.
</P>
<P>
   The basic question, of course, is whether there is room for four
books trolling the same watery catastrophe. But the four publishers
in this case are anxiously betting that there is plenty of hunger
for calamity among couch adventurers.
</P>
<P>
   The books are following a new wave of adventure books in the
1990s that began its latest arc with the popularity of Jon
Krakauer's best-selling account of surviving the Everest disaster
of 1996, ``Into Thin Air,'' and Sebastian Junger's tale of doomed
fishermen, ``The Perfect Storm.'' And a subset among calamity books
is extreme adventure that results in disaster and death. The
Sydney-Hobart race may have a crowded field of writers, but in the
works are new manuscripts about old tragedies featuring avalanches
and multiple deaths or volcano eruptions and multiple deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first book was about adventure racing, which was strictly
adventure, but no one has ever died of that kind of racing,'' said
Martin Dugard, the Southern Californian who has just published his
account of the sailing disaster, ``Knockdown.'' ``I wanted to do a
sequel, but I actually had a publisher say that they weren't
interested unless someone dies during the race.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the developing genre of disaster writing, Dugard, himself a
regular participant in the Raid Gauloises adventure competition,
concedes that there is a thin line between the roles of ambulance
chaser and author. ``There's not much of a difference if you really
want to be brutal about it,'' he said, noting that his goal was to
be able to explain the motivations of adventurers in a thoughtful
way that might elude, for example, ``business writers.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the various writers are sporting in their praise
of each other, although there are inevitable tensions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dugard sought to interview Rob Mundle, an
Australian journalist who participated himself in the ocean race
three times and has covered the event for 30 years. Mundle was not
particularly receptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was researching my book when I got a call from a guy, who
said I've got a call from someone in America who would like to talk
to you about working with him,'' Mundle recalled. ``And I said,
`That's very nice because I'm well down that track already.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dugard said he remembered a blunter response. ``I was talking to
someone who said he would call Mundle. And then he told me, `Mundle
says he won't talk with you and he's already halfway done with his
book.' That really got my competitive juices flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rejection came again for Dugard when he tried to resume
interviews with the skipper and crew of one boat, the Sword of
Orion. ``Rob Kothe, of Orion, was very forthcoming and then the
Little, Brown guy came along,'' Dugard said. ``All of a sudden Rob
said, `I can't talk to you. Bruce has got my story.'''
</P>
<P>
   That would be G. Bruce Knecht, who covered the book publishing
industry for The Wall Street Journal before moving to its Hong Kong
bureau. He politely refuses to talk about his project because he is
still writing his book for Little, Brown &AMP; Co. He also declined to
answer questions about whether he had maneuvered sources away from
other authors.
</P>
<P>
   In the field of competitors, Little, Brown paid the highest
price for its book, reportedly spending as much as $500,000 on an
advance for Knecht. There is no scheduled date for its publication
and Little, Brown, a unit of Time Warner Inc., is content to let
Knecht come in last in the race on the assumption that he will
write a definitive book, which will draw readers with new insights
about rich business moguls risking life and expensive yachts on the
open seas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce is a very, very good writer,'' said Sarah Burnes, a
senior editor at Little, Brown. ``He's really risen and gone beyond
his journalistic writing. It seems to me that the books that are
coming out really fast are just descriptions of the story and
what's happening is that Bruce is taking the time to write a bigger
book and something that's more thoughtful.''
</P>
<P>
   But the other three publishers placed their bets on speed,
including Willow Creek Press, a small independent publisher in
Minocqua, Wis., which figured that its book, ``A Hard Chance,''
could pick up some momentum from publicity for books by larger
publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware this is a David and Goliath scenario,'' said Kim
Leighton, the author of ``A Hard Chance'' and a fly fishing
outfitter in Montana. ``But like Ed Psaltis, who won the race with
his seasoned crew of Midnight Rambler, I'm confident that I can win
my division.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dugard made a valiant effort to get ``Knockdown'' out first,
writing 2,000 words a day, but he was unexpectedly edged out by
Mundle's ``Fatal Storm,'' which was published in early July.
</P>
<P>
   It was sweet justice for McGraw-Hill Cos., which published
``Fatal Storm'' after failing to persuade Dugard to write its book,
said Philip Ruppel, a group publisher for McGraw-Hill, who added
that a company editor had worked with Dugard on an outline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made an offer to Marty,'' Ruppel said. ``And he got a
better offer from someone else. This is our business. It wasn't to
be.'' He said McGraw-Hill quickly started searching for a
replacement with the strategy that it could win only with crushing
speed and an early-July publication date. ``My edict was that you
have to be first or don't bother publishing,'' Ruppel said. ``I
really believe that in many ways. We wouldn't make the investment
if we were second or third because by then your book has to stand
out in every way and then your risks are much higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruppel said he decided to keep the McGraw-Hill book secret so
that other publishers would remain complacent. ``Fatal Storm'' was
first published in Australia and then McGraw-Hill bought the rights
to publish it in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But when Pocket Books learned that McGraw-Hill had the lead, the
publisher, part of Pearson PLC's Simon &AMP; Schuster unit,
counterattacked with the announcement in July that its entry,
``Knockdown,'' would be available for readers to download into
hand-held electronic books. It meant little in terms of sales,
since that market is still in its infancy, but it gave Pocket Books
a wash of publicity, including a feature in the McGraw-Hill
magazine Business Week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   From Australia, the actual winner of the 1998 Sydney-Hobart race
is avidly following the literary competition. Psaltis is a featured
character in most of the books along with the battered crew of the
Midnight Rambler, a small yacht that eventually won the race with a
handicap for size.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised at the attention that our local race is
receiving all over the world,'' he wrote in an e-mail message. ``I
suppose the tragic events have made it a news item outside of
Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, he is not doing his own book. However _
attention all publishers _ he has jotted down notes on the race so
he won't forget the details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
