<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPUTER TUTOR FOR CHILDREN LEARNING TO READ 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to eye-popping graphics, professor Jack Mostow
acknowledges, ``commercial software has our pants beat.''
</P>
<P>
   So why does he think that his recently patented software, which
is about as visually exciting as the ingredients panel on a
soup-can label, will appeal to the 60 elementary students at
Centennial Elementary in McKeesport, Pa., who are to begin using it
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It listens,'' Mostow said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the computer tutor does listen. The students, who will
be wearing headsets with microphones attached, will read aloud
short stories as the computer flashes them, sentence by sentence,
on its screen.
</P>
<P>
   If the computer hears the child stumble over a word or
mispronounce it, the computer _ which talks as well as listens _
offers a clue, such as a rhyming word that has a similar spelling.
For example, if the word is ``sight'' the computer will say and
display words like ``right'' or ``fight,'' but not dissimilar
rhymes like ``height'' or ``kite.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer tutor relies on a speech recognition system called
Sphinx II, which makes it possible for a computer to hear
continuous speech, as opposed to isolated words. Sphinx II was
developed at Carnegie Mellon University, where Mostow is a
principal research scientist and director of the university's
computer-tutor effort, Project Listen.
</P>
<P>
   The computer ``listens'' only to stories that have been recorded
into its system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project is feasible because the computer knows what the
child is attempting to read,'' Mostow said. ``That's why it's much
easier than taking voice dictation in that sense. It's harder in
the sense that there are an infinite number of ways to misread a
word.''
</P>
<P>
   The students at Centennial are participating in a study paid for
in part by the National Science Foundation that will compare
reading progress in three sets of children: those following the
standard curriculum, those helped by the computer tutor and those
receiving supplemental tutoring from human teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The computer tutor is also being used at Fort Pitt Elementary
School in Pittsburgh, where a prototype was introduced in 1996.
After eight months, six third-grade Fort Pitt students who were
problem readers _ children who in some cases, according to the
principal, could not even spell their names _ averaged more than
two years' growth in their reading skills.
</P>
<P>
   Mostow contends that the computer tutor may have advantages over
human tutors. For one, the computer tutor does not lose patience.
``The computer is quite happy to read a sentence to students as
many times as they want to hear it,'' he said. Moreover, students
who might otherwise be embarrassed by reading aloud are not
intimidated by reading to a computer. And it has dozens of rhymes
on the tip of its digital tongue.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the computer tutor catches only about half
the mistakes children make. And it is not inherently sensitive to
different manners of speech. For example, at Fort Pitt, Project
Listen had to adjust the computer tutor so that it was more
tolerant of dropped final consonants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a blurry line between reading tutoring and
pronunciation tutoring,'' Mostow said. ``When somebody is learning
how to read, what you care about is comprehension. If they
pronounce a word the same way they do in their spoken language _
that's not a reading error. It might be a dialect difference, it
might be a speech problem, but it's not a reading error.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer tutor also has multiple personalities. Its stories
and rhyming clues have been recorded in about a dozen different
voices.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, one minute a student might hear Martin Luther King Jr.'s
voice rereading a misread word. The next minute the student might
hear the computer offering words of praise in the voice of another
child.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Mellon hopes the technology will eventually be the
basis for commercial reading software. ``In a classroom we don't
have to compete with Nintendo,'' Mostow said, ``but the home
version will probably have to have flashy graphics.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostow and Gregory Aist, a graduate student, received patent
5,920,838. More information about the program can be found on the
World Wide Web at www.cs.cmu.edu/listen.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
