<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-RETAILING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG CHALLENGE FOR MANY INTERNET COMPANIES IS FULFILLING ORDERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies involved in e-commerce have achieved most-envied
status in the late 1990s business world with their riches from
initial public offerings, gaudy marketing budgets and news
clippings that laud them as pioneers of an industrial
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the glamour, then, it is not a little ironic that the
most important issue facing the industry is the retail function
with the least boardroom cachet: order fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Picking, packing and shipping products was difficult enough in
recent years for Internet retailers who had no experience in such
matters. But with consumers' expectations rising and e-commerce
companies preparing to ship a wider array of merchandise to
customers this holiday season, distribution issues now loom even
larger than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is emerging as a huge issue,'' said John Hagel, who leads
the e-commerce practice for McKinsey &AMP; Co., a consulting firm.
``And it's a real bottleneck to growth. Too many companies started
with the assumption that the challenge was getting people to buy
things, when, in fact, the real challenge is getting it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Forrester Research, an Internet consulting firm,
Web retailers will ship roughly 230 million packages this year _
mostly during the holiday season. Large companies like PlanetRx and
Etoys ship more than 1,000 packages daily, while the industry
behemoth, Amazon.com, ships more than 10,000 a day. And last week,
the research firm of Jupiter Communications predicted that the
busiest sites, including Amazon, CDNow and Barnesandnoble.com, may
each reach 58,000 transactions a day in November and December.
</P>
<P>
   That process is rife with potential pitfalls and inefficiencies.
In their infancy, most merchants simply took customers' orders, had
those orders delivered by a distributor and hoped that the items
were in stock and shipped on time to the right people. In those
days, which, in some cases, extend to today, customers could all
but count on e-mail telling them the items they had ordered were
out of stock or would be shipped late.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is starting to halt such practices. To gain customer
allegiance, Internet merchants are seeking more control over the
shipping process. In many instances, most notably in the case of
Amazon, they are building huge warehouses of their own near major
shipping hubs. But because a high-technology distribution center
can take two to three years to complete, Internet merchants are
scrambling to find third parties to handle distribution for them.
Two leaders in this category are Federated's Fingerhut Business
Services Inc. and Hanover Direct's Keystone Fulfillment Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Keystone handles fulfillment for Mercata, KBkids and Dress Barn,
while Fingerhut does the same for Wal-Mart, Levi Strauss and Etoys,
among others. Fingerhut's 1.2-million-square-foot distribution
center in Provo, Utah, will employ up to 1,200 workers during the
holiday peak, processing orders, shipping items and handling
returns.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of many e-commerce executives, such arrangements
entail far more than simply writing a check and getting back to the
business of planning the company's initial public offering. Because
consumers are increasingly demanding so-called real time inventory,
which includes access to information about product availability and
shipping status, distribution warehouses must be closely wired to
the merchant's Web operations. Third-party distributors, however,
typically have their own electronic tracking and ordering systems,
which require painstaking efforts to link with the retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every order, we have to pass information to their
system,'' said Louis Zambello, senior vice president of Etoys,
which recently began shipping products from Fingerhut's Utah
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warehouse then has to pass it back to us for
confirmation,'' Zambello said. ``When the item ships, that
information goes to us for confirmation. When they get inventory in
stock, that also has to go to our system, and if you do anything
special for the customer, it has to flow from you to the
outsourcer, back to you for confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   Integrating the retailer's computer system with the
distributor's, he said, ``takes dozens of people on both sides
working long hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambello added, ``The misconception is that outsourcing is
easier, but it's just different.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Etoys and Fingerhut would not disclose the costs
associated with building warehouses or maintaining outsourcing
relationships, Rakesh Kaul, president and chief executive of
Hanover Direct, said the costs for both options could be steep.
</P>
<P>
   Companies can expect to pay between $60 million and $80 million
to build a one-million-square-foot warehouse, Kaul said, while they
would pay a third-party distributor roughly 10 percent of each sale
to fulfill their orders. In building distribution centers of their
own, e-commerce companies ``have to bear in mind fixed costs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like owning a 747,'' Kaul said. ``You have to be big, or
fortunate enough to fill it, because if you don't fill it and
operate all the time, you're guaranteed to lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel of McKinsey agreed. ``Unless you do high volume, it
doesn't make sense to build this capacity in the long run. There
are significant economies of skill and scale in these businesses,''
he said, referring to third-party distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining assistance from fulfillment experts will be even more
critical, Hagel said, as e-commerce companies evolve. Not only will
Web retailers increasingly seek to sell products abroad _ an
exercise that presents logistical nightmares _ but they will also
be pushed by consumers to even greater levels of service, including
customized products.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, though, Hagel said, Internet retailers are
complicating matters by broadening their product selection in an
effort to increase the amount spent by each customer. That means
potentially shipping multiple items from multiple points, using
different shippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, I understand the importance of that as a way to
derive more revenue from customers,'' Hagel said. ``But on the
other hand, if these companies think they've been challenged by
fulfillment issues to date, it's nothing compared to what's
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the sudden ascendancy of fulfillment is
vindicating a segment of the business world that has long since
suffered from a lack of respect. ``We used to be those guys in the
dirty suits out there,'' said John Buck, president of Fingerhut
Business Services. ``Would you believe that fulfillment is the
darling of the day? It's actually stunning to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
