<SLUG> BC-DANCE-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BESSIES' ARE AWARDED FOR DANCE AND PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A playful spirit prevailed on Friday night as Dance
Theater Workshop and the Danspace Project presented the 15th annual
New York Dance and Performance Awards at the Joyce Theater. The
awards, called the Bessies in tribute to Bessie Schoenberg, the
teacher of dance composition, celebrate achievements in dance and
performance art.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of that playful spirit was the way Ann Carlson and John
Kelly, the masters of ceremonies, kept reappearing in guises
ranging from nudity to solemn robes and Wild West gear.
</P>
<P>
   But in welcoming remarks, David White, executive director and
producer of Dance Theater Workshop, chided Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
for ``hurling dung at the Brooklyn Museum,'' a reference to the
mayor's opposition to ``Sensation,'' the museum's show of
controversial British art, which includes a Madonna adorned with
elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   The Bessies, selected by a committee, honored both specific
works of the 1998-99 season and sustained achievements over the
years. Choreographer and creator awards of $1,000 each,
underwritten by The Village Voice, went to Ping Chong and Muna
Tseng (working in collaboration), Anne Teresa de Keersmaeker,
William Forsythe and Ballett Frankfurt's Design Team (Stephen
Galloway and Naoki Takizawa), Joe Goode, Headlong Dance Theater
(David Brick, Andrew Simonet and Amy Smith), Dean Moss, Tere
O'Connor, Mary Overlie and Steve Paxton. Ms. Overlie's ``Locations
of Love'' and excerpts from Goode's ``Deeply There'' were danced.
</P>
<P>
   Performer awards of $500 each, also underwritten by The Voice,
went to Roxanne Butterfly (Samedini), Dana Caspersen, Rachel
Lynch-John, Paige Martin, Jim May and Sharon Skepple.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time an Installation and New Media Award was given
to recognize a site-specific or not easily classifiable production.
The recipient was a group called Red Dive, for a production at the
Lower East Side Tenement Museum.
</P>
<P>
   A special citation went to Point Community Development Corp. in
the Bronx for developing an art center in the Hunts Point area.
</P>
<P>
   These were other honors:
</P>
<P>
   Composer awards:
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Johnston, David Lang, James Lo and Hannibal Lokumbe.
</P>
<P>
   Lighting and visual design awards:
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wierzel, Caspar Stracke and Benton Bainbridge (in
collaboration) and the Wooster Group Design Team (James Johnson,
John Collins, Jim Findlay, Philip Bussman, Jennifer Tipton and
Elizabeth Jenyon).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
