<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENNEY-AD-COL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.C. PENNEY LEADS NEW FASHION SEASON WITH A SWEEPING CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Texas, Mass., Pa., Ill.) (Eds: In grafs 11 and 12, Another clothing ..., the `2' in Todd
Oldman TO2 and `Enjoy To2 Day' should be represented by the number
2 squared.) 
(nk) 
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the fall fashion season just starting, several retailers
and designers are introducing campaigns for their lines.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest campaigns comes from the J.C. Penney Co.,
which is seeking to reposition itself as a fashion leader. Though
spending on the campaign was not disclosed, trade publications
estimated it at $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new branding effort, which began last month, will include 23
commercials that were created by Temerlin McClain in Irving, Texas,
a unit of True North Communications. The spots focus on a specific
fashion or look and rely on a creative effort to illustrate it.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one 15-second commercial begins by announcing a
look _ white button-down shirts and a variety of black stretch
pants _ and the commercial is filmed in black and white. The look
for the second spot _ for women's faux suede shirts in earthy tones
_ was filmed outdoors, emphasizing the many colors of fall.
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Williams, the singer and actress, narrates both spots,
which are accompanied by distinctive music, and each commercial
ends with ``Look who.'' Another round of the ``Look'' commercials
presents four 15- and 30-second spots for items like fabric shoes,
hooded tops and the company's Worthington and Jacqueline Ferrar
private labels. Print, radio, Internet and direct mail campaigns,
as well as ads aimed at black and Spanish-speaking consumers, will
accompany the television blitz.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy, aimed at women ages 35 to 54, replaces a
two-year campaign with the theme ``J.C. Penney. I love your
style.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the branding effort, Penney is introducing a
separate campaign for its St. John's Bay casual clothing line aimed
at younger consumers. Though those billings were not disclosed,
trade publications estimated spending at more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   That campaign, also by Temerlin McClain, portrays the St. John's
clothing as fitting a relaxed state of mind. Television commercials
carry the theme ``Every day's the weekend in St. John's Bay.'' The
effort will also include direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   Mossimo Inc. in Irvine, Calif., which sells clothing through
department and specialty stores, is introducing a campaign for its
casual collection geared toward a younger generation. Billings were
not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign, which was created in collaboration between
Mossimo and Toth Brand Imaging in Concord, Mass., two-page ads have
photographs of models standing in carefree poses on open roads,
accompanied by a big signature Mossimo logo. The ads appear in
September issues of magazines including Bikini, Details, Esquire,
GQ, Spin and Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Another clothing marketer, Sun Apparel Inc. in New York, is
introducing its first campaign for its Todd Oldham TO2 line of
jeans, sportswear and accessories. Billings were estimated at more
than $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The eye-catching campaign, created by RDA International in New
York, does not resemble traditional fashion ads. A print ad uses a
busy collage of photographs, including snapshots of the designer
and models whom Oldham photographed himself, combined with a bevy
of illustrations and graphics set against a red, orange and yellow
backdrop. The ad includes the designer's signature crown logo,
along with the headline, ``Enjoy To2 day.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad appears in September issues of Seventeen, Teen People,
Interview and Mademoiselle magazines. Other components of the
campaign, which began in June with teaser ads, include posters,
postcards and a Web site at which people can design and e-mail
greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Spade, an accessory company best known for pricey handbags,
is also introducing its first campaign. Print ads, which were
created in-house, were photographed by a London-based photographer,
Tim Walker. Each photograph was meant to capture a moment that the
viewer can interpret. In one ad two brown coats _ one a man's, one
a woman's _ hang on a coat rack embracing. A red herringbone
handbag hangs over the shoulder of the woman's coat. Another ad
shows just the torso of a woman dressed conservatively in a wool
skirt, sweater and overcoat carrying a hot pink handbag. The ads
appear in the September issues of Harper's Bazaar, Vanity Fair and
Vogue. Billings were estimated just under $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth retailer, Aeropostale in New York, a unit of
MSS-Delaware Inc. that sells clothing for teen-agers, takes a
different tack for its first campaign with a 35-second cinema spot.
Billings were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The spot, created by the Chicago office of the Bozell unit of
True North, begins with a countdown leader similar to the beginning
of a movie and then opens with loud funky music and fast-paced
camera techniques that seem to bring various stills of teen-agers
clad in Aeropostale clothing to life. Male and female voice-overs
express the teen-agers' thoughts _ ``I hope I pass French'' or ``I
hope I pass calculus'' or ``I hope we pass a taco stand.'' The tag
line: ``Life can be serious. Your clothes should be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The cinema spot is running in 16 markets including Chicago, New
Jersey, New York, Philadelphia and Washington. Three print ads were
created using visuals from the cinema spot. One reads: ``I think a
lot about world hunger. I think a lot about environmental issues. I
think a lot about hair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
