<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PARIS-REVIEW-ARCHIVES     09-26 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-REVIEW-ARCHIVES-ART-(TRIMS)(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MORGAN ACQUIRES TREASURES FROM THE PARIS REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Malcolm Cowley once said that the motto of The Paris
Review could be ``enterprise in the service of art.'' Other
literary journals have been founded and then have foundered, but
the Left Bank quarterly created by several hopeful young American
writers has remained a vital part of the literary scene after more
than 45 years of operation. In the case of The Paris Review,
persistence and intellectual acumen (and an instinct for survival)
have paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Peter Matthiessen, Harold L. Humes,
George Plimpton (its longtime editor) and others, The Review has
discovered new writers, publishing early stories of Philip Roth as
well as fiction by Terry Southern, Nadine Gordimer, V.S. Naipaul
and Richard Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally the editors made mistakes. John Irving's story
``The Pension Grillparzer'' was rejected by one of Plimpton's
colleagues with a curt note saying the author ``fails to do
anything with language or form.'' The story became a pivotal part
of Irving's novel ``The World According to Garp.'' As Plimpton
recalled: ``We posted that reply on the bulletin board. It sat
there for years as a warning, because that's a perfect short
story.''
</P>
<P>
   In probably its most significant claim to a legacy, The Review
has persuaded major authors to sit for portraits in extensive
interviews in the ``Writers at Work'' series, whose subjects
include figures like Eliot and Pound, Cocteau and Celine, Faulkner
and Hemingway, Mauriac, Moravia, Simenon, Saul Bellow, Paul Bowles,
Norman Mailer, Eudora Welty and Marianne Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a step into posterity, the archives of The Review have
been acquired by the Pierpont Morgan Library. This vast collection
includes letters to and from authors (one of them is the note
rejecting ``The Pension Grillparzer''), manuscripts, original
versions of interviews, editorial and business records, photographs
and ``common books'' with memos and musings from various editors.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, which is to be announced this week by Charles
E. Pierce Jr., the director of the Morgan, was made with the
financial help of an unnamed ``mutual friend'' of the library and
The Review. The price was estimated to be in excess of $500,000.
Plimpton said the money would go to a foundation to help the
magazine continue publication.
</P>
<P>
   In the collection are 100 boxes with more than 200,000 pages of
text.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before being moved to the Morgan, the papers filled the basement
of Plimpton's Manhattan brownstone. During the next year the
archives will be cataloged and then made available to scholars and
will be a primary source for anyone attempting to write a history
of The Paris Review.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the archives, Pierce said: ``To have such a
treasure trove from the end of this century is really an
extraordinary opportunity. It extends the range of our 20th-century
collection,'' which also includes the voluminous collection of
contemporary books from the estate of Carter Burden, the
businessman and philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Paris Review was created in 1953, partly in reaction to
other literary magazines. The goal was to de-emphasize criticism
and to focus on original works of fiction and poetry and on writers
talking about the craft of writing. In the early 1970s the magazine
moved its offices to Manhattan, with Plimpton continuing as the
quarterly's editor and primary promoter. Over the years he has
enlisted backers from Sadruddin Aga Khan (the first publisher) to
Hugh Hefner. Often he has helped sustain The Review by sponsoring
benefit social events.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary exploration of the archives reveals the intricate
inner workings of the magazine, the difficulties of dealing with
artistic temperaments and financial crises, and the quest above all
to make a distinctive cultural contribution. The Review seems to
have improvised its way into longevity. Running through the papers
is the motif of money. Repeatedly writers ask: When am I going to
be paid? When will that story or interview appear? Will it ever
appear?
</P>
<P>
   In correspondence Roth revealed his impatience with the slow
pace of editorial decisions. In one letter he said, ``By the way,
what finally did you people decide about `Goodbye Columbus'?'' Then
when that story was accepted, he wrote, ``I understand the price is
either two or three hundred: I vote for three.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The interviews began in 1952 with E.M. Forster, whom Plimpton
knew from his days as a graduate student at Cambridge University.
After Forster appeared in the first issue, the conversations came
to be considered a certification of an author's importance. There
have been more than 250 of them, many reprinted in a series of
books.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some authors made special demands. Nabokov supposedly was the
only one who was paid for his participation. The editorial
explanation of that payment ($500) was that, in his case, the
interview was conducted entirely by mail, with Nabokov writing his
answers. Because the interviews began before the general use of
tape recorders, an author would often be visited by two people, who
would alternate between asking questions and transcribing answers.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning the talks were intended to be collaborations
rather than inquisitions, Plimpton said. The authors were
encouraged to edit the transcripts and rewrite their answers. Then
editors would make additional suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Faulkner requesting an interview, Humes said that
one purpose was for the ``Old China Hands'' of literature to
explain their conjuring tricks to younger writers. He added that if
Faulkner agreed, he would have the ``final authority to pass on
every word of the finished interview before publication.''
</P>
<P>
   After reading his interview, Mailer penciled in several pages of
questions and answers. Graham Greene was the only one to refuse to
have the conversation reprinted in a book. In a neatly typed letter
signed ``Yours Jack,'' Kerouac said he had edited out ``all the
vulgarities and racial name-callings, after all when you're yakking
in private with friends it's not necessarily what you would say in
public print, in such heated boozy terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the authorized quality of the interviews, many writers
were quite outspoken, and several of the colloquies have become
classic: Hemingway in conversation with Plimpton, Robert Penn
Warren's interview by another eminent writer, Ralph Ellison (along
with Eugene Walter). In a candid talk with Jean Stein, Faulkner
said: ``The writer's only responsibility is to his art. ...
Everything goes by the board: honor, pride, decency, security,
happiness, all, to get the book written. If a writer has to rob his
mother, he will not hesitate; the `Ode on a Grecian Urn' is worth
any number of old ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   At first Hemingway expressed a hesitation because, he said, he
could not speak about his writing as Forster, Greene and Irwin Shaw
did. He wrote in longhand to Plimpton: ``My experience has been
that when a writer talks about himself and his work except with his
girl or other writers or to try to straighten kids out with what
you know that can help them he is usually ... a poseur or a more or
less pompous ass.''
</P>
<P>
   An answer in one interview might provoke a question in another,
as in this one to Nabokov: ``E.M. Forster says his characters
sometimes take over and dictate the course of his novels. Has this
ever been a problem for you, or are you in complete command?''
Nabokov said haughtily, ``My knowledge of Forster's work is limited
to one novel which I dislike,'' and in contrast, ``My characters
are galley slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all authors have been eager to be questioned. Naturally,
both J.D. Salinger and Thomas Pynchon, the mystery men of American
letters, refused. Salinger replied with a note striking a
Bartleby-like stance of ``I prefer not to.'' Eventually The Review
ran a piece about a journalist's aborted attempt to talk to
Salinger.
</P>
<P>
   Plimpton has always hoped that Pynchon would relent, banking on
the author's goodwill because Plimpton reviewed his novel ``V''
favorably in The New York Times Book Review. Also eluding The Paris
Review are Harper Lee and Anne Tyler, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Hall, who was the first poetry editor of The Review,
interviewed Eliot and Pound and often came up with new ideas for
subjects. Apparently he was one of several in pursuit of Salinger.
When Hall was living in New Hampshire, he wrote to Plimpton: ``For
the next 10 weeks, I will spend two afternoons each week in
Hanover, where old Jerry reputedly comes shopping from time to
time. I will try to catch him shoplifting, or whatever it takes, in
order to blackmail him into an interview.''
</P>
<P>
   One literary battle occurred after Stephen Spender wrote a piece
recounting episodes involving Hemingway and Laura Riding. In a
heated essay, Martha Gellhorn, Hemingway's former wife, challenged
Spender's memory and then upbraided Lillian Hellman for passing off
fiction as fact. In one of many letters to Plimpton, Gellhorn said
that her marriage to Hemingway broke up on the ``jagged rock'' of
``apocryphism,'' adding, ``Miss Hellman has his worst
characteristics without his talent or his charm, when he happened
to be charming.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Browsing through the archives at the Morgan on a recent morning,
Plimpton grew nostalgic for Paris in the '50s. He remembered his
first sighting of Hemingway, buying a copy of the second issue of
The Paris Review in a bookstall at the Ritz Hotel. He recalled that
when he and his associates were searching for material, they
canvassed cafes for sketches left by artists as payment for meals.
They found drawings by Picasso, Braque, Matisse, Lautrec and also
Chaplin and Jacques Tati, and reprinted them in The Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very rich time over there,'' he said. ``Paris was a
ripe place _ and the right place _ to start a magazine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
