r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     09-26 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NOTHING BUT SURREAL TRUTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer,'' says the latest issue of Elle, ``may be as
simple as half a bagel rather than no bagel at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the question,  &UR; Mike Foley &LR;  was driving in San Francisco
recently when he noticed a sign advertising Joanne's Psychic
Readings, ``Mention this ad and receive 50 percent off.'' Wouldn't
the psychic just know if the discount was applicable? he asks.
</P>
<P>
   And People magazine reports that  &UR; President Clinton &LR;  dined with
 &UR; Lucy Lawless  &LR; (``Xena, Warrior Princess''),  &UR; Chelsea, &LR;  and actor
 &UR; Temeura Morrison &LR;  in New Zealand this month. Morrison said that
Clinton is ``a big fan of Lucy's,'' and Lucy said she found Clinton
``incredibly engaging.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - In Toronto, the Disney Channel is shooting ``The Color of
Friendship,'' a TV movie about former Oakland Rep.  &UR; Ron Dellums &LR; 
and a white South African exchange student who came to stay with
his family. The movie includes several members of the Dellums
family in cameos, &LR;  and actor  &UR; Carl Lumbly &LR;  as Dellums. It will be
shown during Black History Month, February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   - Stay an hour, pay through the nose; stay all day and it's
free.  &UR; Daniell Revenaugh cq &LR;  of Berkekey plans to mark the 203rd
birthday of  &UR; Franz Schubert  &LR; by playing all 20 of his sonatas,
beginning at 10 a.m. January 31 at the Julia Morgan Theater in
Berkeley. Entrance will be free, but listeners will pay on the way
out, on a reverse sliding scale in which staying power will be
rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Mark Allen Levinson &LR;  of Alain Pinel Realtors is asking $18
million, the highest asking price for any residence ever in San
Francisco, for the Captain's House at 300 Sea Cliff Avenue in San
Francisco. The house, on 0.43 acres overlooking the ocean and
Golden Gate Bridge, was built in the 1930s and was last owned by a
neurologist who bought it in 1975 and recently died.
</P>
<P>
   - A BBC poll of Oxford University students said that 16 percent
wanted more people to have sex with and 60 percent wanted more
money.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FACILITIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michael Rosa  &LR; says that he and his fellow cabbies are getting
even with that ritzy new hotel that won't allow them to use the
restroom by telling tourists of vermin in the food and bell boys
stealing luggage.
</P>
<P>
   But another cab-driver correspondent says that he would never
think of using hotel bathrooms, which he considers as ``private and
for guests.'' His practical options: ``coffee bars and service
stations.'' And a third offers his own solution: a bicycle water
bottle, after which the liquid is dumped into the street (and the
stench is blamed on the homeless).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the New York Observer reports on an experimental
police program in which public urinators in midtown Manhattan are
required to take part in meetings of a ``quality of life group,''
in which the consequences and meaning of the act are discussed.
According to the Observer, ``Each urinator was asked to explain
what led them to do what they did _ too much beer, too little
discipline was the short answer _ and then to probe the real root
cause of their offense.'' They all agreed it was a bad habit picked
up in childhood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING EVEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michael Anketell &LR; , producer of an annual Friends of People With
AIDS gala in Los Angeles for 11 years, tells all about people who
gave him trouble in his forthcoming book, ``Heavenly Bodies''
(Taylor; $30.95).
</P>
<P>
   According to a preview in Los Angeles magazine, Anketell says
that supermodel  &UR; Naomi Campbell &LR;  threatened one year that she
wouldn't walk the runway in a fashion show if her entire entourage
was not admitted free. And the head of a European fashion firm
asked if Anketell could set him up with movie chief
 &UR; Sherry Lansing &LR;  for the event. When Anketell told the fashion man's
public relations representative that Lansing is married and happy,
she inquired, ``Can you get  &UR; Cher &LR; ? Or  &UR; Goldie &LR; ?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate people from Ohio, so a couple years ago in Columbus, I
decided to jump the crowd. There's only one of me, but I had the
height advantage. I jumped them, but I landed on a concrete bunker
and dislocated my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Iggy Pop &LR;  describes a highlight of a career in rock &LR;   &LR; 'n'
roll, in Gear magazine.
</P>
