 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Monday, Sept. 27. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   G7-MEETING (Washington) _ Developments from the meeting of the
top economic officials of the world's wealthiest nations. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FIGHTING (Moscow) _ Developments: the Russian military
warned Sunday that it may launch ground operations against Islamic
militants in Chechnya, while warplanes bombed the Chechen capital
for a fourth day. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-GUIDES (Washington) _ The federal government is
mailing out 36 million guides this month aimed at educating the
nation's elderly on the increasingly complicated world of health
care. The guides are the result of months of market testing, focus
groups, expert reviews and survey research, much of which
discovered that the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries have only a
sketchy understanding of the basic Medicare program, let alone the
managed care alternatives. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-RECRUIT (Washington) _ The Army and Air Force face
significant shortfalls in recruiting numbers in what the Pentagon
fears is a worsening trend that is chipping away at national
security. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PATAKI-TRAVEL (Undated) _ A look at how Gov. George Pataki
finances his travel abroad.
</P>
<P>
   NY-VIRUS-DEATHS (New York) _ Researchers say three deaths, maybe
five, in New York were from the West Nile virus, not encephalitis.
By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-RECORDBREAKER (New York) _ Placido Domingo breaks Caruso's
record for opening nights at the Met. By Anthony Tommasini. (With a
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-CUP (Brookline, Mass.) _ Justin Leonard capped the
greatest Ryder Cup comeback in history on Sunday by winning five of
six holes to overtake Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal and
clinch victory for the United States over Europe. By Clifton Brown.
(With photos.)
</P>
