u f BC-LUCENT-AT&AMP;T-CONSULTIN     09-26 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-AT&AMP;T-CONSULTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T FACES ITS SPINOFF AS A RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago, AT&AMP;T Corp. spun off its communications
equipment operation as Lucent Technologies Inc. in an attempt to
remove the crippling conflict among the equipment business and
AT&AMP;T's communications units.
</P>
<P>
   The move was a big success, almost certainly the most trenchant
that Robert E. Allen made as AT&AMP;T's chairman. Lucent, as an
independent equipment company, has gotten new business from
customers, including the Bell local phone operations, that had
grown wary of helping subsidize AT&AMP;T's telephone operation.
</P>
<P>
   But now, for the first time since the spinoff, AT&AMP;T and Lucent
may find themselves in conflict again, this time in the hot market
for communications consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the companies, who still sometimes speak of one
another as if they were in the same corporate family, could still
make a deal to keep everyone happy. But with Lucent and AT&AMP;T each
building consulting operations geared toward corporate clients and
with contracts potentially worth billions on the table, such an
accord could require exquisite diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The looming conflict was precipitated by Lucent's $3.7 billion
deal in August to acquire International Network Services Inc., a
sort of temp agency for high-powered network engineers. Since being
spun off from AT&AMP;T, Lucent has worked closely with its former
parent in a variety of ways. But Lucent intends to use the
International Network deal to bolster its Netcare consulting
operation. John L. Drew, chief executive of International Network,
is to lead the Netcare unit.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years AT&AMP;T has built its own AT&AMP;T Solutions
consulting and outsourcing operation into a multibillion-dollar
business. Moreover, AT&AMP;T has long relied on International Network
to supply engineers and networking experts for many of the big AT&AMP;T
corporate clients that may now become targets for Lucent Netcare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very substantial relationship with INS as a supplier
to us, a key supplier to us, in working with us on a number of
engagements for major clients,'' said Jim Byrnes, an AT&AMP;T Solutions
spokesman, declining to comment further on the potential conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T Solutions and Lucent Netcare operations do not appear
to overlap completely, but the companies' public statements alone
make it clear that the two units are approaching the same market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designing, building and managing global networks,'' reads the
headline on AT&AMP;T Solutions' Web site. ``That's what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the news release announcing Lucent's deal for International
Network, Drew said, ``Our combined companies will offer customers a
level of service in designing, integrating and managing
next-generation networks that is simply unmatched.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the companies said that AT&AMP;T and Lucent
would probably strike a deal to give AT&AMP;T continued access to
International Network personnel. In exchange, it seems likely that
Lucent would want to become some sort of preferential equipment
supplier to AT&AMP;T Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always partnered with AT&AMP;T Solutions, and when we
acquire INS, that will continue,'' said Kathy Fitzgerald, a Lucent
spokeswoman, declining to comment specifically on how such an
arrangement could be structured.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card, however, is Cisco Systems Inc., the data
communications equipment giant that is Lucent's rival. AT&AMP;T does a
lot of business with both Lucent and Cisco, which could make it
tricky for AT&AMP;T to make a side deal with Lucent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
