<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Sept. 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Tropical moisture will stream northward from the eastern Gulf of
Mexico to the central Appalachians at the perimeter of an expansive
high-pressure system over the western Atlantic. Clouds will
increase as far north as New York as onshore winds along the East
Coast direct more humid air inland. Rainfall in excess of 2 inches
is possible from Florida to the Carolinas. During the weekend,
Melbourne, Fla., received nearly 8 inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Northeast will stay bright and warm as a result of
high pressure centered just east of New England. Readings may reach
80 degrees in the valleys of northern Vermont. Clouds will arrive
later in the day, but rain is not expected before Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A chilly rain will follow the passage of a cold front from the
central Great Lakes to the Texas panhandle. Temperatures will be as
much as 30 degrees lower behind the front. Colder breezes from the
north will drive the very cool weather down along the east slopes
of the Rockies. Showers will be mixed with snow in the higher
foothills of Colorado and in some valley locations of central
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure crested near Vancouver will control the weather
over the western third of the nation. The clockwise circulation
around the fair weather system will take the very cool, dry air
from the interior and carry it to the northwest coast. Increasing
offshore winds in California will promote sunny, very warm
conditions in the northern sections. Weaker winds in southern
California will allow coastal clouds to linger for a few hours in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Dry Bayou
</P>
<P>
   Except for the edges of the Gulf Coast _ that is, south Texas
and the Everglades _ it has been a very quiet season for tropical
storms in this region. The effect is being noticed most in
Louisiana where yearly precipitation deficits have mounted to more
than 10 inches from New Orleans to Lake Charles. In fact, this
month has brought Lake Charles only 1.38 inches or slightly more
than 25 percent of normal September rainfall. Much of the late
summer and autumn rainfall is attributed to tropical moisture, but
a robust Bermuda high has steered this year's storms toward the
Atlantic seaboard instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
