<HEADER>
A6628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-TAIWAN-AFTERSHOCK-A     09-26 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TAIWAN-AFTERSHOCK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTERSHOCK IN TAIWAN KILLS 3, TOPPLES WEAKENED BUILDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Refiling to include map advisory. No other changes.)  
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (nk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Taiwan suffered a major aftershock on Sunday that killed
at least three people and injured 58 others, destroyed buildings
and roads already weakened from last week's devastating earthquake,
and sent thousands of horrified residents scurrying for safety.
</P>
<P>
   The aftershock, which measured 6.8, hit at 7:52 a.m. and was
centered about 6 miles east of Sun Moon Lake in Nantou county. This
mountainous region in the middle of the island was the epicenter of
last week's 7.6-magnitude quake, which killed more than 2,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   Local radio and television reports from Taiwan said the
10-second aftershock set off numerous landslides across the
country. At least three motorists died when their cars were buried
on a road in central Yulin county. There were unconfirmed reports
that two children riding with their parents had died on the same
road.
</P>
<P>
   The news reports said people across the island fled buildings in
a panic Sunday morning, many wearing motorcycle helmets and some
only their underwear.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-story apartment complex, already damaged, collapsed on a
busy road in the city of Nantou, and a nearby office building
exploded and burst into flames, the reports said. The 40 apartments
of the complex were evacuated after the quake on Sept. 21, but many
residents had returned recently to gather possessions. It could not
be learned if anyone was hurt in the two buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the injured were rescue workers who were struck by
falling debris in Nantou and Taichung counties, near the epicenter.
Eleven people were hurt by flying glass and other debris in a rice
wine distillery in the town of Puli.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the death and destruction, there were tales of heroic
rescues, even as many Taiwanese had given up hope of finding
survivors beneath the tons of steel and concrete rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Two brothers were rescued on Sunday after being trapped for five
days in a collapsed high-rise building in Taipei. Sun Chiu-kuang,
20, and Sun Chui-feng, 25, survived by eating rotten apples from a
refrigerator buried with them and drinking their own urine and
water sprayed on the rubble by rescue workers, Taipei city
officials said. The officials said the brothers' father had told
them that he had ``been waiting for this moment and that he hadn't
slept since the initial earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, President Lee Teng-hui declared a six-month state
of emergency, giving the military increased powers to maintain
order and imposing severe sentences for overcharging consumers for
basic necessities that have become scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's government has come under sharp criticism for being slow
to respond to the earthquake, which destroyed vital highways and
bridges. Many towns and villages could not be reached by rescuers,
who were also hampered by inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 people remain homeless, and many cities,
including parts of the capital, are without electricity, as the
earthquake and its aftershocks caused severe damage to power
generating plants and substations.
</P>
<P>
   In Taiwan's third largest city, Taichung, thousands of residents
have been sleeping outdoors, fearing aftershocks. In a telephone
interview, one resident, Khu Mu-hsiang, said Sunday that his family
and neighbors were afraid to return to their high-rise apartment
complex and that they planned to continue sleeping in tents in the
elementary school playground across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that we are literally petrified and on edge all
the time,'' he said. ``Each time the ground moves, we keep
wondering when it will stop and if this is finally `the big one.'''
</P>
<P>
   More than 7,300 aftershocks have hit Taiwan since last Tuesday's
earthquake, an average of almost one a minute. Eight of the jolts
measured six or above and have been classified as major quakes in
their own right.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Taiwan's Seismology Center said they expected
aftershocks to continue for several months and that further quakes
of 6.8 magnitude are possible. Taiwan straddles a major fault line
on the western edge of the Pacific ``rim of fire'' and has dozens
of tremors each year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than 1,000 buildings, mainly high-rise apartment complexes,
have collapsed since the quake last week, and about 5,400 buildings
have been damaged severely, raising concerns that many were not
built according to government codes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government announced a nationwide investigation,
with the help of hundreds of prosecutors, engineers and architects,
to determine if contractors had violated building codes.
</P>
<P>
   Two building contractors have already been arrested, and 16 more
have been prevented from leaving the island. In one case,
investigators found that the support pillars of several collapsed
buildings had been made of concrete that was poured around empty
oil cans, creating huge air bubbles inside that caused the concrete
to collapse in the quake.
</P>
<P>
   American rescue workers who came to Taiwan to assist in the
recovery effort told The Associated Press that they saw similar
corner-cutting just last month in cheap Turkish buildings that used
salty sea sand in concrete. Many of those structures collapsed
during the quake on Aug. 17 that killed more than 15,000 people in
Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6629 &Cx1f; taf-z
