<SLUG> BC-R-MUD-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUD', `DROWNING': AN ADVENTURE IN FOLLOWING ONE WRITER'S WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo note)  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ART ADV 13 : 2 photos, one from each play, are being sent to
NYT 14  photo clients. Non-subscribers 15  can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are at once eerie and gorgeous, the gelatinous
mounds of flesh that feel the pain of rejection so deeply in the
lovely, enigmatic ``Drowning,'' a playlet by Maria Irene Fornes
that is over in the intake of a long, plaintive sigh. These exotic
creatures, animated with Wonderland-ish panache by the costume
designer Teresa Snider-Stein, look like tuskless walruses that have
evolved into bipeds.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, the childlike Pea, touchingly played by Marc Damon
Johnson, has fallen in love with the photograph of a woman in a
newspaper. The picture is a blessing, and then a curse, because the
woman is utterly repulsed when she meets Pea. His innocence
stripped away, he gets his first, corrosive lesson in how to see
himself through others' eyes, a lesson in how to detest himself.
``Is this why we have come to life?'' he asks. ``To love like this?
And hurt like this?''
</P>
<P>
   It is a simple, direct question that Ms. Fornes, a career
avant-gardist, poses in one extreme form or another in many of the
plays she has written over the last four decades, and it will be
one of the concerns explored again and again this year by the
Signature Theater Company, which is devoting its ninth season to
the works of this 69-year-old Cuban-born playwright. It will be a
true adventure for many fans of Signature's one-writer-a-season
concept, because unlike the last three honorees _ John Guare,
Arthur Miller and Sam Shepard _ Ms. Fornes has never found a
mainstream following. On an avenue of department stores, she is
forever a boutique.
</P>
<P>
   That is why she seems even more deserving of the Signature
treatment than some of her more famous colleagues: New York is,
after all, more and more a city of boutiques. And what is Signature
to do if not amplify the voices of those like Ms. Fornes, a
contemporary of trademark playwrights of the '60s and '70s like
Megan Terry and Ntozake Shange, who have a tough time getting
heard? (In earlier seasons the troupe was instrumental in
reinvigorating the reputations of Edward Albee, Horton Foote and
Adrienne Kennedy.)
</P>
<P>
   On the evidence of the first evening of her works, ``Mud'' and
``Drowning,'' both written in the 1980s, Ms. Fornes' inventive
voice, with its embrace of the surreal, will remain a marginal one.
Still, it's worth a listen, if one is willing to listen patiently.
Her plays have the meticulous composition of still lifes, which
means at times they are strikingly balanced and at others opaque,
impassive. The dialogue can be so flat, so lacking in the perfume
of real conversation, that the play could have been grown in a
hothouse, under artificial light. Anaerobic is a word that comes to
mind.
</P>
<P>
   She is perhaps best when writing in short strokes, which reveal
her clever employment of dramatic structures without lapsing into
turgidity. In the fascinating 1982 work ``The Danube,'' for
instance, she wrote a tragedy that she set in Budapest to the
rhythms and conventions of foreign-language instruction tapes. And
in her best-known play (of which you may never have heard), the
1977 ``Fefu and Her Friends,'' Ms. Fornes devised a tragicomedy
about a women's party, a kind of absurdist ``First Wives Club,'' in
which the audience picked up and moved from room to room in Fefu's
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mud'' and ``Drowning,'' which opened Sunday night in
Signature's Peter Norton Space, are given incisive productions by
the director, David Esbjornson, with meaningful assists from the
set designer, Christine Jones, and the lighting designer, Scott
Zielinski. In ``Mud,'' the longer and less interesting of the
pieces, Ms. Fornes explores the joyless existence of a small-town
woman named Mae (Deirdre O'Connell, in a performance of splendid
composure) and the brain-dead men who love, need and destroy her.
</P>
<P>
   The crumbling world in which she slaves _ the rooms of the house
may be as dank and decrepit as prison cells, but there's always a
Beckettesque pair of pants waiting for her to press _ is the
nightmare domain of martyred women everywhere. To make matters
worse, Mae suffers the attentions of Lloyd (Paul Lazar), a fetid,
dimwitted slug whom she tosses out of bed in favor of Henry (John
Seitz), whose sexual and intellectual promise dissolves as a stroke
leaves him just another useless lump for Mae to feed and clean.
Lazar's manchild and Seitz's paralytic interloper are fine
creations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mud'' is arranged in 17 scenes, each ending in a freeze, as if
they were to be posed and added to a photo album of Mae's wasted
life. ``I feel I am hollow and offensive,'' she says, invoking the
language of the victim. We know in Ms. O'Connell's moving
countenance that Mae gets exactly what she doesn't deserve.
</P>
<P>
   The male grotesques of ``Drowning'' are even less well equipped
than Mae to weather everyday brutality; their nerves are as exposed
as their oily, splotchy skin, which undulates in massive folds
around their jaws and shoulders. Johnson's Pea and Philip Goodwin's
gently avuncular Roe share a table at a European cafe, as Pea
relates in three short takes the before-and-after of his
infatuation with the woman in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The playlet is almost over by the time you recover from the
weird effect of the actors' swollen appearances, but Johnson is
nonetheless disconcertingly affecting in the instant of Pea's
discovery of heartache. One leaves the theater wondering where and
when Ms. Fornes might next supply such a disturbing moment of
emotional clarity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: `MUD' and `DROWNING'
</P>
<P>
   Two plays by Maria Irene Fornes; directed by David Esbjornson;
sets by Christine Jones; costumes by Teresa Snider-Stein; lighting
by Scott Zielinski; sound by John Kilgore; production stage
manager, Fran Rubenstein; production manager, Brian R. Duea.
Presented by the Signature Theater Company, James Houghton,
founding artistic director; Bruce E. Whiteacre, managing director;
Elliot Fox, general manager. At the Peter Norton Space, 555 W. 42nd
St.
</P>
<P>
   `MUD'
</P>
<P>
   With: Deirdre O'Connell (Mae), Paul Lazar (Lloyd) and John Seitz
(Henry).
</P>
<P>
   `DROWNING'
</P>
<P>
   With: Marc Damon Johnson (Pea), Philip Goodwin (Roe) and Jed
Diamond (Stephen).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
