<HEADLINE>
HASTERT ADMITS BUDGET DEADLINE WILL BE MISSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The speaker of the House acknowledged Sunday that
Congress and the White House will not finish the budget for the
next fiscal year by 12:01 a.m. Friday, when the year begins, and
said that Congress would pass a stopgap bill by then to keep the
federal government going for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., appearing on Face the
Nation on CBS, said, ``It's not our intent to have a government
shutdown.'' But he said that such a shutdown was always ``a
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1995, a budget impasse led to the shutdown of parts
of the federal government, for which Republicans in Congress were
widely blamed.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the same program, Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the
House minority leader, said, ``I think we're going to miss the
deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they were merely acknowledging what has been obvious
for weeks as spending bills became bogged down in the fight over
tax cuts and other fiscal issues, missing the budget deadline is
still a disappointment to the Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans said from the first of the year they were
going to get everything done on time,'' said Gephardt. ``They
haven't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said that Clinton would prefer
a continuing resolution for two weeks rather than three, because
``we think they ought to be able to get their work done sooner.''
He said Clinton would sign a continuing resolution if it simply
continued spending authority at 1999 levels for any federal
agencies whose 2000 budgets have not been passed by Congress and
signed by the president; if Congress attaches other provisions to
the resolution that the president does not like, then he would veto
it, he said. The result would be a partial shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The federal budget is divided into 13 spending bills, of which
Congress has sent four to the White House. Clinton is threatening
to veto seven of the 13, and has already done so with one, an
appropriation for the District of Columbia budget, because it puts
limits on certain actions by the District government. Of the three
others that have passed, he has signed one, a bill on military
construction, and has not said what action he will take on the two
others, the budgets of the Treasury and the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the Republicans is that they have repeatedly
promised not to dip into the surplus accumulated this year by the
Social Security system to pay for other areas of government, but
the individual committees with budget authority are working on
spending plans that would do just that, to the tune of billions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said Sunday, ``Congress has spent the Social Security
trust funds for the last 40 years, almost 40 years, ever since
L.B.J. in 1967 passed the Great Society and funded the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying not to do that now,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hastert also declined to distance himself from a Republican
presidential candidate, Pat Buchanan, who has threatened to leave
the party and seek the nomination of the Reform Party. Sen. John
McCain, of Arizona, another Republican presidential candidate, has
called on Republicans to repudiate Buchanan because of his writings
and statements on the American involvement in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should be able to accept people with a lot of
divergent views, and I think that's good for the debate within the
party,'' Hastert said. ``So I would urge Pat Buchanan to stay,
carry out the debate within the party, and let the people make the
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan continued to defend his recent book in an appearance
Sunday on CNN's Late Edition, calling it ``a boring, scholarly work
on foreign policy'' and saying that he considered the war ``a noble
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Mr. McCain did not read the book,'' he said. ``I
don't want to continue to quarrel with him. I do believe he was
misled in saying that I did not think it was a noble cause, and I
think I said so all week long, and there's no need, I think, on my
part to continue the quarrel.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Buchanan called for a noninterventionist
foreign policy. He called the Kosovo intervention ``an
unconstitutional, undeclared war. The smashing of Serbia, which had
nothing to do with us, I thought was an outrage, I was ashamed of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was a leading voice for intervening in Kosovo earlier
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
