<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF THE DECADE 
WITH THE CENTURY IN SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big names and big moments helped make 1988 the most memorable
year in an incredible decade of sports.
</P>
<P>
   The year marked Tom Landry's 29th and final season with the
Cowboys, though he didn't know it at the time. New owner Jerry
Jones fired Landry during the off-season and hired Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   News from the NHL was just as stunning, with The Great One,
Wayne Gretzky, traded by the Edmonton Oilers to the Los Angeles
Kings, along with two other players for two players, three
first-round draft picks and $15 million. Gretzky had led Edmonton
to four Stanley Cup titles in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer dramatics, nothing topped Kirk Gibson's home run in
Game 1 of the World Series against Oakland. Thought to be out of
the Series because of a leg injury, Gibson was sent to the plate as
a pinch-hitter with two out in the ninth against A's All-Star
reliever Dennis Eckersley. His blast into the right-field seats
gave the Los Angeles Dodgers a 5-4 victory, propelling the Dodgers
to the Series title. It was Gibson's only Series at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Also back on top was another familiar name, Notre Dame, led by
coach Lou Holtz. The Irish won their first national title in 11
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In tennis, one legend lost and another was on the rise as Steffi
Graf's remarkable career took full flight. The young German ended
Martina Navratilova's six-year reign at Wimbledon and became the
new standard-bearer of women's tennis, winning the Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Florence Griffith Joyner stole the show at a memorable Olympics
in Seoul with golds in the 100 (a world record), 200 and 4X100
relay. Soiling the games was the sad saga of Ben Johnson. Two days
after winning the 100-meter dash in a world-record 9.79 seconds,
Johnson tested positive for steroids and was stripped of his gold
medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
