<HEADLINE>
INNOVATIONS FOR THE 1980S 
WITH THE CENTURY IN SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PGA Senior Tour: In 1978, a tournament called The Legends of
Golf in Austin introduced America to the concept of competition
among older players who were no longer competing on the PGA Tour.
It was supposed to be a one-time event, but response from
spectators and television viewers went through the roof. That
prompted organizers to hold the tournament again in '79. By 1980,
interest in the over-50 set was so high that the PGA Tour decided
to cash in by creating the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Instant replay: The use of replay as an officiating aid was
approved by the NFL for the first time in 1986, but there were
practical problems from the beginning, notably the extended delays
while the official studied the replays. Even so, the NFL owners
voted to keep replay for six consecutive seasons before finally
overturning it in 1992. Replay returned to the league this season
with a new system that allows coaches to challenge calls.
</P>
<P>
   Salary cap: With payrolls skyrocketing faster than profits, NBA
owners and players made an unprecedented agreement in 1984, putting
a limit, or cap, on the salaries a team could pay its players. A
year later, the NBA moved to the concept of a ``soft'' cap by
implementing the so-called Larry Bird exception, allowing teams to
exceed the cap in order to sign free agents already on their roster
(which allowed the Celtics to keep Bird).
</P>
<P>
   West Coast offense: The offense, based on controlling the ball
with short passes rather than the run, was devised by Bill Walsh in
his days at Stanford and as an assistant with the Cincinnati
Bengals. But it was Walsh's Super Bowl champions in San Francisco
that popularized it and spawned countless imitators in the college
and pro football ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Shot clock and 3-pointer: In 1982, four of college basketball's
greatest players _ North Carolina's Michael Jordan, James Worthy
and Sam Perkins and Virginia's Ralph Sampson _ played in the
Atlantic Coast Conference championship game, and the best they
could do was a 47-45 snoozer (the Tar Heels won). To get scoring
back in the game, the ACC experimented with a 30-second clock and a
short 17-foot, 9-inch arc for the 3-point shot the following year.
Fans loved the higher-scoring, more entertaining games. The NCAA
adopted a 45-second clock for the 1985-86 season and a year later
put in a 3-point line at 19 feet, 9 inches.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
