<HEADLINE>
TEAM OF THE DECADE 
WITH THE CENTURY IN SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Feb. 22, 1980, in Lake Placid, N.Y., a group of amateur
hockey players made being American fun again.
</P>
<P>
   Team USA's remember-where-you-were-when-it-happened 4-3 victory
against the heavily favored Soviets, for a while, made people
forget about a gloomy economy and growing world tensions
exacerbated by the Soviets' invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
President Carter had pledged the week before to boycott the Moscow
summer games. The ongoing Iranian hostage crisis would not end
until January 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets, who defeated a team of NHL All-Stars the previous
year, had won the gold medal every Olympics since 1960 and were
prohibitive favorites to do so again.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, seeded seventh in the 12-team field, finished
the preliminary round with a 4-0-1 record punctuated with a 7-3
victory against a talented Czechoslovakian team and advanced to the
semifinals of the medal round against the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they played us 10 more times, they'd probably beat us every
time,'' said Neal Broten, a center on the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets took 1-0 and 2-1 leads before Mark Johnson scored
with one second remaining in the first period, prompting Soviet
coach Viktor Tikhonev to pull legendary goalie Vladislav Tretiak in
favor of Vladimir Myshkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even realize he \RTretiak\S was out of there until
the middle of the next period,'' Broten said. ``But after that
first period we knew we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets led 3-2 in the second period before Johnson again
tied the score with a power-play goal. With 10 minutes remaining,
captain Mike Eruzione fired a wrister through a screen that beat
Myshkin for a 4-3 lead. Goalie Jim Craig made the lead hold up for
a victory that sent fans in the arena into bedlam and a nation into
euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the things I did in my career, that was numero uno,''
said Broten, whose jersey was retired by the Stars after 20-NHL
seasons. ``We weren't expected to win a medal, let alone a gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the United States did win gold when it defeated
Finland, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   But, the real medal was won when, for a few hours, people who
didn't even care about hockey or sports again loved being
Americans. \Nsubheds:Runners-up
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Lakers: .721 winning percentage, five NBA titles San
Francisco 49ers: .688 winning percentage, four Super Bowls Miami
Hurricanes football: .831 winning percentage, three national titles
Edmonton Oilers: .623 winning percentage, four Stanley Cups
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
