<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6636 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-1980S-CENTURY-TEX     09-26 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1980S-CENTURY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSY OF THE DECADE 
WITH THE CENTURY IN SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If drug abuse among athletes was common before the 1980s, the
public knew little about it. That all changed in a decade when
suspensions of high-profile athletes evolved from stunning news to
become almost commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA led the movement toward more aggressive testing and
rehabiliation. New commissioner David Stern was charged with
regaining credibility for a league plagued by poor attendance and
TV ratings in the 1970s in part because of the perception its
players used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Even stiff penalties and rehabilitation programs couldn't save
everyone. In 1986, four of the NBA's top seven draft picks were
linked to drugs. Len Bias, taken No. 2 overall by the Boston
Celtics, died of a cocaine overdose two days after the draft. Chris
Washburn, chosen third, was eventually thrown out of the NBA after
two drug-plagued seasons. William Bedford, taken sixth, was
suspended twice. Roy Tarpley, taken seventh by the Mavericks
despite their knowledge of his drug use at the University of
Michigan, was banned, reinstated and banned again for substance
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Random testing for steroids and illegal drugs made its way to
the NFL. Among those suspended were big names such as Hall of Fame
linebacker Lawrence Taylor. Most puzzling was the bizarre case of
Bengals running back Stanley Wilson. Caught high on cocaine the
night before Super Bowl XXIII in 1989, Wilson was banned for life
by the NFL and is now serving 22 years in prison for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Major League Baseball is sports' most lenient body
on substance abuse. New York Yankees pitcher Steve Howe, suspended
seven times, became the poster boy for baseball's tolerance. Howe
was thrown out of baseball permanently in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Olympics officials began policing more heavily for
peformance-enhancing substances in the 1980s but often fought a
losing battle against athletes who masked their use of drugs. In
1988, however, Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson's positive test for
steriods resulted in him being stripped of a gold medal in the 100
meters.
</P>
<P>
   Few fans, by the late '80s, were shocked by the news.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6637 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-T     09-26 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELVIN, OATES SAFE FROM CORPORATE RAIDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Hicks showed some foresight when he gave an extra year to
general manager Doug Melvin and manager Johnny Oates on their
latest contract extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has noticed corporate raiding is becoming common among
major-league teams as they scurry to fill general manager and
manager positions.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland general manager Billy Beane is among the most coveted
executives around. The Seattle Mariners are interested, and there
is speculation Beane could end up with the Anaheim Angels,
replacing Bill Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   Beane deserves the praise for turning the Athletics around, but
the players deserve some credit. They publicly stood strong behind
manager Art Howe during the lean years when it appeared Beane and
Sandy Alderson were ready to fire him. My vote _ which is an
official one _ goes to Howe as manager of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies wanted Cleveland general manager John Hart,
who is expected to move on when the Indians are sold. But they were
told he was unavailable, so they settled for his long-time
assistant, Dan O'Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   Indians hitting coach Charlie Manuel is a strong candidate to
replace Rockies manager Jim Leyland, but Buddy Bell, who worked
under O'Dowd in Cleveland before going to Detroit, is another good
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner, another hot name, could surface there or a dozen
other places. Baltimore is a possibility. Even though the Orioles
are the hottest team in baseball, it won't do manager Ray Miller
much good. He's still expected to be gone at the end of the season,
but the Orioles are expected to stay with Frank Wren as general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Garner could also end up with the Cubs, although Triple-A Iowa
manager Terry Kennedy is the likely candidate to replace Jim
Riggleman. However, with former Minnesota Twins general manager
Andy MacPhail now the Cubs' president, don't be surprised if they
take a run at Tom Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are also thinking big in their general manager
search. They've talked to Bob Watson, who won a World Series with
the Yankees in 1996, and Pat Gillick, who built the Blue Jays'
dynasty and did well in Baltimore before growing tired of owner
Peter Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners also considered Dean Taylor, who was the Braves'
assistant when he got the job in Milwaukee. Taylor's next move is
to hire a manager, and Don Baylor, the former Rockies manager who
is now the Braves hitting coach, is the top candidate there.
Another strong candidate is Yankees hitting coach Chris Chambliss.
</P>
<P>
   Garner, Baylor, Chambliss and Oakland coach Ken Macha are among
the names being mentioned in Anaheim to replace Terry Collins, and
it would be a shock if Baylor isn't managing somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look like there will be an opening in Detroit.
Detroit president John McHale and general manager Randy Smith are
publicly supporting manager Larry Parrish, although owner Mike
Ilitch will have the final say. Ilitch was smitten with Parrish
last fall, but some of that admiration has cooled during the
Tigers' disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres have also had a rough year, but owner John
Moores said last week he stands behind general manager Kevin Towers
and manager Bruce Bochy and hopes they are with the franchise
``forever.''
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT on Sammy Sosa
 &LR; pcredit:Chicago Tribune/Milbert Orlando Brown via AP The Chicago
Cubs pay Sammy Sosa an average of $10 million per year, but after
consecutive seasons of 60 or more home runs, the Cubs think he
might want more money.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs expecting Sosa to ask for more money
Word out of Chicago is Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa wants to
renegoiate his contract. Sosa's four-year, $42.5 million extension
that he received in 1997 seemed excessive at the time; he and Gary
Sheffield were the first two players to average $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently it's now inadequate, what with Sosa hitting 60
homers for the second consecutive year and Dodgers pitcher Kevin
Brown making $15 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa will make $10 million in 2000, $11 million in 2001 and
there's a mutual option for 2002 at $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Sammy has concerns or thoughts, we have to try and do what
we can,'' Cubs general manager Ed Lynch said in the Chicago
Sun-Times. ``Sammy obviously is one of the great players in
baseball. When Sammy talks, we listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Also there has been some insinuation that Sosa is getting
slighted this year as far as people paying attention to his home
run exploits.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire took up this theme when he said, ``I personally
thought when he hit 60 he should have been the lead story on every
sports network. He wasn't, which is a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just that the focus is back on the pennant races,
which is still the most important thing about September.
\Nsubheds:Quick hits
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have a third-base controversy brewing as they
approach the playoffs. John Valentin, who missed three weeks
because of a bad knee, was activated off the disabled list Thursday
and says he's ready. But the Red Sox were 15-5 with rookie Wilton
Veras at third during Valentin's absence. Veras, younger and
stronger, is hitting .295 this year, while Valentin is at .251 and
still bothered by the knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are also taking a hard look at rookie left fielder
Daryle Ward, who is hitting .271 with seven home runs and 25 runs
batted in. He might force Derek Bell, slumping and hurt, out of the
lineup in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Giants outfielder Ellis Burks had 91 RBI in 375 at-bats coming
into the weekend. That's the third highest RBI total in his career
and gave him a chance to be the first National Leaguer in history
to get 100 RBI in less than 400 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa might treat us to a slam-bang finish
when the Cardinals and the Cubs meet for three games next weekend
in St. Louis. But neither one should even come close to winning the
National League MVP Award. Jeff Bagwell, Chipper Jones and Matt
Williams are far more deserving.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers, 5-0 with the Mets, suddenly loves New York and
wants to stay: ``If they want me back, I'd love to stay. I'd be
crazy not to. With the kind of defense this team plays, with the
guys who can hit, and an ownership that looks like it wants to do
things, I love this place.''
</P>
<P>
   With their attendance down from 2.4 milion to 1.6 million, the
Devil Rays are talking with veterans Roberto Hernandez, Fred
McGriff and John Flaherty about deferring some of the money in
their contracts so the club can be active in the free-agent market
this off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays pitcher David Wells, on speculation he might be traded
so the club can sign Carlos Delgado and Shawn Green, ``Let me tell
you something, you don't win without pitching. You can have all the
guys you want hitting 50 homers, but you're not going to win. You
got to have pitching, good defense and they go hand in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' 11-3 victory against Colorado Wednesday gave
them a 157-157 record over the past two years. That's the quickest
an expansion team has reached the .500 mark. The Kansas City Royals
were the previous quickest, reaching the .500 mark in their eighth
season.
</P>
<P>
   Braves pitcher John Smoltz has been fooling around with a
knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   Further erosion of the Dodgers occurred when Triple-A manager
Mike Scioscia announced he was leaving the organization to pursue a
job with another team. Scioscia, a future major-league managerial
candidate, wasn't happy with his future with the club.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies prospect Pat Burrell, the first overall pick in the
1998 draft, hit .333 with 28 home runs and 90 RBI in 117 games at
Double-A Reading, and could force Ron Gant out of left field next
year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
