<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6639 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-MODANO-TEX     09-26 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MODANO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS STARS' MODANO HOPES TO MIX OFFENSIVE GLORY WITH TEAM
SUCCESS 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The feeling was like no other as Mike Modano
hoisted hockey's ultimate prize.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup was the reward for enduring those long, hard
practices. For squelching the desire to rebel when coach Ken
Hitchcock relentlessly demanded more, more of a team that already
had the best record in the NHL. For checking his ego at the door
and sacrificing his considerable individual skills for the sake of
the Stars' defense-first style.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup symbolizes teamwork, and Mike Modano was a team
player.
</P>
<P>
   That was three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars begin defense of the Cup on Friday, when they play the
Pittsburgh Penguins in the regular-season opener at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With his name safely engraved on the precious trophy, Modano
thinks about the next step, the next level, of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Almost wistfully, he dreams of individual glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to finally get to the 100-point plateau,'' he said.
``MVPs and all that stuff, it would be nice to have a piece of that
before it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   He also would like to hoist the Cup again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that we accomplished what we did last year, but it
would be even greater to sustain that level,'' Modano said. ``It
was a great year and we enjoyed it a lot, but we all feel that we
have another good year or two in us that we can be effective and
maybe take another run at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano has proved he's a wizard with a hockey stick, but it
would take a remarkable magic trick to do both, to score 100 points
while playing Hitchcock's Cup-winning, team-oriented style that
stresses using defense to generate the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does, he's pretty good,'' linemate Brett Hull said. ``I
would say he can, but I think Mike's got responsibilities in other
places that doesn't allow it. If they just turned him loose like
Jagr, he could do what Jagr does. But he's got other
responsibilities that the team considers more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull is talking about Jaromir Jagr, the Penguins' forward who
led the league with 127 points last season and won the Hart
Memorial Trophy, the MVP award Modano dreams of.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, though, plays on a team with a wide-open style. The
Penguins scored 242 goals, fourth in the NHL, but gave up 225. The
Stars scored 236 goals, eighth in the league, while allowing a mere
168, fewest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, whose career high is 93 points, had 81 last year, 13th
in the NHL. But, as Hull pointed out, Jagr doesn't have the other
responsibilities that Modano has, the commitment to playing a
two-way game.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock has no problem with Modano aiming for 100 points, but
doesn't want it to interfere with helping the team win in other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's capable of reaching it, but I don't think you want to do
that at the risk of undermining his game,'' Hitchcock said. ``His
game is a winning game. He really is a productive player in a lot
of areas other than just points. What I would rather be looking for
is how many of the points he's scoring are important points, how
many are important goals, where his plus/minus is at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are challenges. To me, if he was the top plus/minus
player in the league, if he led our team in winning goals and
winning points, that would be a big challenge for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano isn't a selfish player. He's not going to push team goals
aside while he pursues a scoring title. He's prepared to once again
work hard in the gritty part of the game, to forecheck, to
backcheck, to kill penalties.
</P>
<P>
   But he sees no conflict between playing Hitchcock's style and
scoring 100 points. The reason: his talented line mates, Hull and
Jere Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very conservative system, but what you do with the puck
is what sets good players apart from other players, your ability to
make plays and create plays,'' Modano said. ``All three of us have
good shots we can get off, and we see the ice pretty well. We check
and shut down good teams and that allows us to have more time with
the puck. If we have more time with the puck, points will come and
good things will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars signed Hull, who has topped the 100-point plateau
four times and scored 50-plus goals five times, before last season,
conventional wisdom said the Stars' No. 1 line would be one of the
best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The line indeed had moments of brilliance, but injuries kept it
from reaching its full potential. Hull played in just 60 of the
team's 82 games, Lehtinen 74 and Modano 77.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that line's played together enough,'' Hitchcock
said. ``I'd like to see that line be at least able to stay together
for 70 games. If Brett can adapt to that style and stay healthy,
then the line has a real good chance to be one of the strongest in
the league if not the strongest.''
</P>
<P>
   It also would help if Lehtinen, a two-time Selke Award winner as
the best defensive forward in the league, adds more offense to his
game. Hitchcock thinks that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Visions of an improving Lehtinen and a healthy Hull fuel
Modano's dreams of taking the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the three of us stay healthy we can all accomplish
things,'' he said. ``Brett can get 50 goals, I think Jeri can get a
point a game, and I can get 100 points. We can have one of the more
dominating lines in the league. That would be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And scoring 100 points while winning the Stanley Cup again? That
would double the fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
