r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAILEY-TE     09-26 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAILEY-TEX </SLUG>
 
CHAN GAILEY'S OffENSE AND CHAN GAILEY MAINTAIN SEPARATE IDENTITIES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week, they win on haymakers, gadget plays and Rocket
launches. The next week, they sort of schmooze their way to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Teams frequently take on the personality of their coach. The
Cowboys have taken on the multiple personality of the Chan Gailey
Offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 2-0 with a bye today, which basically means that
the Gailey Offense is idle and Gailey is home thinking up gadget
plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Gailey Offense is not the West Coast offense, which is to
say that it's not the trendy horizontal passing offense developed
by Bill Walsh in San Francisco and thoroughly mimicked this past
decade by an NFL coaching fraternity unafraid to copy off somebody
else's paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're anything but the West Coast offense,'' said Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman, who threw 49 times against Washington and
22 times against Atlanta. ``I think Chan's system is a little bit
more of a throwback system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much about getting five guys out into routes, or
about flooding zones, as it is about Chan wanting to establish the
running game with Emmitt \RSmith\S, then doing some things in the
passing game off of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey and the Chan Gailey Offense should never be confused
with one another. They hail from separate planets, operate on
dichotomous wave engths, maintain their separate identities and are
entitled to their own idiosyncrasies.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's Georgia-grown personality is a lot like his golf game,
straight down the middle. Gailey's run-oriented, vertical-passing
offense is, at times, a lot like Mr. Toad's Wild Ride.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is khaki pants and a button-down oxford shirt. Gailey's
game plan is a mix of old world and new millennium. It's a blend of
no-nonsense running game between the tackles and a read-and-react
pass offense designed to exploit a defense's weaknesses as the play
is still unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Chandler Gailey, age 47, is pretty much ``what you see is
what you get.'' The Gailey offensive game plan, in its second
season with the Cowboys, is more along the lines of ``what you get,
you can only wonder if you're going to see it again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching is a guessing game, but there are two sets of
cat-and-mouse ... preparation and game-day adjustments,'' said
Gailey, who seems to enjoy the mental gymnastics required in doing
the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You evaluate what you do as an offense and what the opposing
defense will be trying to do to stop you,'' Gailey said. ``Watching
film ... the whole preparation part, that's really enjoyable to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other part is the game-day adjustments, and I enjoy that,
too. It involves figuring out what did they change, how do we
adjust to it, and how quickly?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is his own offensive coordinator, which was an absolute
prerequisite for anyone trying to convince Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones that he could be Barry Switzer's successor two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was looking for ``someone creative yet fundamental,'' who
would not sacrifice the basic fundamental approach to winning in
the NFL by running the football and never letting them see you
flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very unpredictable,'' said Cowboys defensive coordinator
Dave Campo, who is happy to be on the same team as Gailey. ``You're
not sure if you're going to get five wide receivers or an empty
backfield, or maybe a no-huddle \Roffense\S right in the middle of
the whole deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a coaching staff getting ready to play a Chan
Gailey-coached offense, you'd better make sure that you can handle
every single different personnel group that he might show you ...
and he has a good `feel' for what is going to work. So it's very
difficult to get a bead on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said there is one myth about his offense. It's the Gailey
playbook. It's not as thick as the Manhattan phone book or as
difficult to digest as Sanskrit.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to set the record straight this week. It's
``normal-size'' and ``just a normal playbook,'' said Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Gailey would script the first eight to 10 plays of
a game. This season, he has decided to ``group'' plays according to
down-and-distance, then meet with Aikman on Saturday night and go
over which ones Aikman feels most comfortable in using.
</P>
<P>
   The past two seasons, Gailey has put Aikman in the shotgun to
maximize his view of the field in obvious passing situations.
Gailey said he wants Aikman to feel that he has the freedom to
audible out of a bad play into a good one, which is exactly what he
did on the second David LaFleur touchdown pass against Washington
in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   The call was an off-tackle run. Aikman audibled into a quick-out
to his tight end. Gailey loved the adjustment that was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan's offense is different and there's something to that,''
said Campo. ``It's a little like it was with the wishbone in
college football where you would face the same basic `look' week
after week, then all of a sudden you were facing something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   So what makes Chan Gailey's offense ``different''?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the multiple formations and varied schemes with a
myriad of players rotating in and out of the game, Gailey attacks
downfield with the pass, yet uses a power running game to control
down-and-distance, clock, field-position, all those facets of the
game that, ironically, make the Chan Gailey offense both sound and
exotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an innovative offense,'' said Campo. ``Chan is not a
one-dimensional guy. You have to defend the whole field with him,
and you have to be ready to handle unusual things at unusual
times.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
