<SLUG> BC-AUTO-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM AND UAW HOPE TO REACH PACT THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 9th and 10th grafs noting strike deadline set
by Canadian union and adding quote from Canadian union's
president.)  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors and the United Automobile Workers union
hope to reach a new, four-year labor contract within the next
several days, as the relationship between the world's largest
company and its main union appears to have improved considerably
since last year's 54-day strike in Flint, Mich., auto industry and
union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for the two sides worked through the weekend to mold
an agreement similar to that concluded by the union with
DaimlerChrysler AG on Sept. 16. DaimlerChrysler workers voted on
that agreement on Saturday. While the vote count is not scheduled
for release until Monday, local union officials predicted that the
pact would be easily ratified.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW's previous, three-year agreement with GM,
DaimlerChrysler and Ford Motor Co. expired on Sept. 14, but the
union has agreed to keep workers on the job while it negotiates
with each company. A GM official close to the talks said Sunday,
``They're making progress, they met until very late last night.''
</P>
<P>
   The UAW agreement with DaimlerChrysler and a pact by the
Canadian Auto Workers union with Ford last Tuesday both call for
wage increases that exceed the inflation rate by nearly 3 percent,
plus a wide range of benefits. The UAW contract also limits how
quickly DaimlerChrysler can shrink its work force through
attrition, a provision that might cause some difficulties for GM.
</P>
<P>
   If GM accepts an identical provision, it could continue
downsizing but with some limits on how quickly it does so. Another
issue in the talks involves the extent to which workers at GM's
former auto parts division, which it spun off in May, will be able
to return to job openings at GM.
</P>
<P>
   Labor relations between GM and the UAW have improved since last
year's strike for several reasons. GM appears to have suffered a
small but permanent loss of market share because of the strike,
making neither the company nor the union eager to repeat the
experience. The American auto market is booming, leaving every
automaker straining to keep up with production and autoworkers
reluctant to risk their profit-sharing checks on another walkout.
And GM has completely revamped its approach to labor negotiations
since last year.
</P>
<P>
   GM strongly criticized union leaders during last year's strike,
in an unsuccessful bid to persuade employees that the work stoppage
was a mistake. After the strike, GM brought home a quiet-spoken
American executive, Gary Cowger, who had been running GM's German
subsidiary, and gave him unusually broad authority as group vice
president for labor relations. His predecessor, Gerald Knechtel,
had been only a vice president, and had less authority.
</P>
<P>
   Cowger, who likes to talk about his grandchildren and who spent
the first 13 years of his career working his way up through
supervisory positions at a GM assembly plant in Kansas City, Kan.,
has gotten along very well with UAW leaders, said a union official
who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A deal with the UAW would not guarantee a strike-free autumn for
GM. It must still reach an agreement with the Canadian Auto Workers
union. The Canadian union wants GM and DaimlerChrysler to sign
contracts in Canada similar to Ford's; the union announced Sunday
afternoon that workers had ratified the Ford contract. The union
said it would seek a new labor contract with DaimlerChrysler next,
setting a strike deadline of Oct. 5 for a pact.
</P>
<P>
   Basil Hargrove, the Canadian union's president, said that he was
leaving GM for last partly because it posed the toughest issues.
``We have an incredible amount of problems at GM,'' mainly
involving job security, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scott Sprinzen, the managing director for auto industry credit
ratings at Standard &AMP; Poor's, said that a peaceful labor settlement
between GM and the UAW would be welcome on Wall Street. Standard &AMP;
Poor's currently assigns a single-A rating to GM's long-term
credit, but because of the potential for labor unrest, the rating
comes with a ``negative outlook,'' which means that it may be
downgraded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they reach an agreement in the U.S. and Canada, we could
well take a look at that negative outlook,'' Sprinzen said. Any
improvement in GM's credit rating would save the company money by
allowing it to borrow money at lower interest rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
