u p BC-GOP-FLA27-COX     09-26 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FLA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush to be lone GOP candidate at Florida convention
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Cokie Roberts is out and so is God.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the media deity nor that higher authority were enough to
convince all of the GOP's presidential candidates to come to
Florida next month.
</P>
<P>
   Only Texas Gov. George W. Bush is showing up at the state
Republican convention in Orlando. And even he won't be attending
the Christian Coalition of Florida's ``God and Country Rally.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Sunshine State, the presidential campaign next month is
largely a no-show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed that the candidates have refused to commit to our
event,'' said Max Karrer, chairman of the state Christian
Coalition, which canceled a rally planned for the same time as the
GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's state conventions have, in the past, been popular and
significant political events. President Clinton credits success at
the 1991 state Democratic convention with giving his campaign the
credibility he needed.
</P>
<P>
   George W.'s dad fought hard to win the state's straw poll in
1979. George Herbert Walker Bush finished third that year, but
eight years later, as vice president, he won.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Gov. Jeb Bush was chairman of the convention and
he worked hard to make sure the straw poll, won by Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole, was a national event. CNN's Larry King hosted a spirited
candidate forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised that none of the other candidates are showing
up,'' Bush said. ``I think they are making a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, 3,300 delegates will hear from a variety of state and
national leaders during the Oct. 8-9, convention in Orlando. ``I
think it will be a very interesting and important convention but I
can certainly understand why some of the delegates might be
disappointed,'' said GOP Chairman Al Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush agreed to come to Florida, where he has raised more than
$3.3 million for his campaign, for about 90 minutes. During that
time he'll give a brief speech, shake a few hands and meet
privately with key supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But the last thing Bush wants is to do that day is be on the
same stage with his political rivals. As a result, plans for Cokie
Roberts to host a candidate forum to be broadcast on ABC were
nixed.
</P>
<P>
   Without a forum, all the other candidates said they would rather
spend their money in Iowa and New Hampshire where real votes will
be cast early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
