<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TALBOTT-PROFILE-ART-N     09-26 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALBOTT-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA IS FAR FROM LOST, TALBOTT INSISTS, URGING PATIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a longtime news magazine hack and chronicler of
government at the highest levels, Strobe Talbott was trained to
look for the telling detail, the pivot point that shaped great
lives or great events. In his own life, it was the Cuban missile
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   He was 16, a sophomore at the elite Hotchkiss School in
Connecticut, already a very, very serious young man hurtling toward
a very, very serious adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the headmaster summoned us all into the school
chapel,'' Talbott said in an interview late last week. ``We got
down on our knees and prayed that the world wouldn't blow up.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when his contemporaries were thinking more about dates
and dances and Dairy Queens, Nelson Strobridge Talbott III was
obsessed with the prospect of nuclear annihilation. It became his
occupation and his preoccupation for the next 37 years, as a
student of Russian language and history, then as a Time
correspondent and author of a half dozen books on the dismal
science of nuclear arms control. Since 1993, he has been the
Clinton administration's chief policy maker on Russia, a country
that is today more threatened by corruption and dissolution than by
the prospect of nuclear holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, because of his expertise on the Soviet Union and its
newly independent fragments, has become the focus of the current
who-lost-Russia debate in Washington and beyond. He has become the
target of critics of President Clinton's policy of financial and
political engagement with Russia as revelations pour forth of
massive money-laundering schemes, the looting of industries
formerly controlled by the state and organized corruption in and
around the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who lost Russia?'' Talbott said, is a bad headline over a very
important story.
</P>
<P>
   The question, he said dismissively, is ``worse than shallow,
worse than simplistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott went on, speaking in rounded paragraphs occasionally
punctuated by the tenting of his fingers or the arching of his
patrician eyebrows: ``I think it is healthy and necessary that we
have an ongoing discussion or debate on the challenges posed not
just by the transformation of Russia, but the transformation of
large parts of the world. One theme of this administration is
dealing with the transition from closed societies to open
societies, not just in Russia, but in Latin America, the Middle
East and much of Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Be patient, he advises, nobody said it was going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott's critics _ and they span the political spectrum _
accuse him of a romanticized view of Russia born of his love of
Russian literature and a misplaced faith in America's ability to
shape events in a country that has never known true democracy or
law-based capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   He has an answer that would fill a thick volume but which he
consented to distill to sound-bite length for a poor practitioner
of his former trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Cold War ended a decade ago, we went from a period of
excessive certainty to a much more dynamic, more volatile period.
That has had both positive and negative implications,'' he said,
sitting beneath a blown-up image of two hands hovering above a
chessboard that served as a Time magazine cover for one of his long
essays on arms control negotiations in the 1980s. ``The VCR of
history is on fast forward. That illusion of progress led a lot of
people to expect that the transformation of Russia would take a lot
less time than it in fact will.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my modest suggestions to the world is strategic
patience,'' Talbott continued. ``We have to be calm and steady and
have a clear sense of purpose when that dynamic is discouraging, as
it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott's platinum-plated resume is familiar to those to whom
such things matter _ son of a banker in Shaker Heights, Ohio;
Hotchkiss; Yale; a Rhodes Scholarship at Oxford University;
translator of Nikita Khrushchev's memoirs; a distinguished 21-year
career at Time, and, importantly, Friend of Bill. Clinton was
Talbott's housemate during part of their time at Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott has served at the State Department since the first day
of Clinton's presidency, first as special adviser on the former
Soviet States and since 1994 as deputy secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   He is _ what's the polite term? _ supremely self-assured in his
role, partly because of his breeding, partly because of his record,
partly because of his long relationship with the president. His
wife, Brooke Shearer, is a senior official at the Interior
Department and a longtime friend of the Clintons in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   His interests include classical guitar _ he keeps a handmade
Venezuelan guitar in his private office which he plays only
occasionally and ``badly, alas.'' He runs to work from his home in
Northwest Washington and rides his bicycle on weekends. He plays
squash and entertains official visitors constantly. He said there
was precious little time for quiet reflection and the kind of
writing he used to do. Now it is all speeches and congressional
testimony and memos to his ``bosses'' (like very few officials in
government, he has only two _ the secretary of state and the
president).
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said he intended to remain in government, God and
president willing, until the end of Clinton's term. He said he had
given virtually no thought to what might become of him afterward.
But he is not at all worried about what the future might hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into this job serendipitously,'' he said, not referring
explicitly to his friendship with the president because he doesn't
have to. ``The best thing I can do to prepare for the next phase of
my life is to do this job as well as I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
