<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY27-COX     09-26 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley focuses on health care for uninsured
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The battle for the Democratic presidential
nomination between Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley enters a new phase Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will unveil in Los Angeles a plan to provide health
insurance to the nation's 44 million uninsured, the first of three
domestic policy initiatives designed to give more substance to
Bradley's low-key campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which Bradley says will provide coverage to ``as
many people as possible,'' will sharpen the distinctions between
the two candidates on an issue that is a major theme of both and a
potent issue among Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's health care proposal will also likely bring closer
scrutiny to his record as a senator. With the exception of gun
control and campaign finance reform, Bradley has avoided specifics,
focusing instead on the broad themes of his campaign and
introducing himself to voters as ``the boy from Crystal City,
Missouri, and the senator from New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore announced his own health care plan in Los Angeles earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of providing health care to the uninsured is
particularly problematic for Bradley. In the Senate, Bradley was
not a player in the health care debate in 1994 over President
Clinton's failed plan to provide coverage to all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley served on the Senate Finance Committee, one of two that
wrestled with Clinton's initiative. Bradley sided with Republican
critics on several key aspects of Clinton's plan, opposing a
provision that would have required employers to provide coverage to
employees if the employers didn't develop affordable plans by a
certain date.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, Bradley remained on the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1993 and 1994, Bradley was clearly not a leading player
even though he was situated on a committee that could have played a
leading role,'' said Ron Pollack, executive director of Families
USA, who promoted the idea of universal coverage during the 1994
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley had intense interests on the committee but they
were mostly financial tax and international fiscal matters,'' said
Sen. John Chafee (R-R.I.), who served with Bradley on the Finance
Committee. ``I don't remember Bill having much to do with health
care matters.''
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, however, Bradley has made affordable
health care a central component of his appeal to working families.
Bradley has portrayed the plight of the nation's 44 million
uninsured as a major failing of a surging economy and, by
implication, a major failing of Clinton administration policies.
</P>
<P>
   He has argued for a phased-in approach that will get as close as
possible to universal coverage. He has promised that his plan will
include some prescription drug benefit and that it will restore the
primacy of physicians _ not ``bureaucrats'' _ in making health care
decisions for patients.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has also promised to attach a cost estimate to his
proposal, something Gore did not do when he unveiled his own,
phased-in approach earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for anybody who's actually going to do
health care to tell the people what it's going to cost,'' Bradley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's proposal will also likely focus most on children and
problems of affordable health insurance for the nation's low-wage,
working families.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Bradley repeatedly advocated and voted to expand
Medicaid coverage to include pregnant women and infants, and
children under 18 who lived at or below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the Senate sponsor of legislation requiring insurers
to offer 48 hours of hospital treatment for mothers having babies,
curtailing the practice of ``drive-thru deliveries.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
