<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-NYT &LR;      09-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS COOL TO COLOMBIA'S U.S.-BACKED PEACE OVERTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ During President Andres Pastrana's first year
in office, critics often described his method of dealing with the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, the country's largest
guerrilla group, as all carrot and no stick. Now, with American
prodding and support, he is adopting a tougher stance _ but finding
the rebel leadership as intractable as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The government's shift in attitude, made evident during
Pastrana's visit to the United States this week, has brought
efforts to end three decades of civil conflict here to a critical
juncture. Though his ultimate objective remains a negotiated
settlement, increased American aid to the Colombian military, which
accounts for the bulk of a 3-year 1.5 billion proposal before
Congress, would significantly strengthen Pastrana's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``For negotiations to succeed,'' Gen. Charles Wilhelm, the chief
of American military forces in Latin America, told a congressional
committee on Sept. 21, ``I'm convinced that the government must
strengthen its negotiating position, and I believe that increased
leverage at the negotiating table can only be gained on Colombia's
battlefields.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana needs such bolstering because last November, shortly
after he took office, he made a Switzerland-sized area of Colombia
a demilitarized zone and handed it over to the rebels, known here
by the Spanish-language acronym FARC. It was a good-faith gesture
meant to bring the insurgents to the negotiating table, and no
concessions were demanded in return, not a cease-fire or even a
mechanism to monitor human rights abuses and other violations.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have been quick to exploit that vagueness and lack of
safeguards. By all accounts except their own, they have abused the
spirit of the government's inducement by stockpiling weapons,
recruiting and training new fighters, killing perceived enemies and
protecting the lucrative drug operations that have moved into the
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by such activities and the public outrage they have
generated, the government announced early in May that it had
reached an agreement with the rebels on a formal agenda for
negotiations. But the start of such talks has been indefinitely
postponed because Pastrana insisted, belatedly, that an
``international verification commission'' be allowed into the
guerrilla zone.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 16, however, the government backed down from that
demand, saying that it would accept an ``accompaniment
commission.'' But the rebels issued a statement calling even that
offer ``unacceptable'' and criticized the Pastrana administration
in unusually harsh language for what was called its ``warlike
attitude'' in seeking aid from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recognized alliance of Pastrana with the United States to
augment the war in Colombia against the FARC, with the distractive
sophism of jointly combatting drug trafficking, puts in doubt the
government's peace intentions,'' the communique stated. The
document also warned that an alliance with the United States
``could overflow into a civil war with unforeseen circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial, El Espectador, a leading daily newspaper here,
described the guerrilla statement as ``a bucket of cold water'' on
a population waiting for the ``unfreezing'' of peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an old FARC tactic,'' said Armando Borrero, a former
head of the government's national security council. ``Every time
they get something, they ask for more, which makes it hard to have
real negotiations with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Pastrana said this week that Manuel Marulanda, the
main leader of the rebels, had ``signed with his own pen and hand''
a verification agreement in May, but later went back on his word
after the group's National Secretariat refused to support him. The
episode had not been disclosed publicly before, presumably out of
concern for Marulanda's sensibilities and public reaction to
evidence of double-dealing by the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   During a television interview Saturday, however, a rebel
spokesman, Raul Reyes, said the group wanted to resume dialogue
with the government ``as soon as possible,'' adding that ``it is
absolutely clear that the problem with the commission has been
solved.'' He provided no further details, though, saying only that
``we should proceed to negotiations and will not talk any further
about the creation of a commission the FARC does not accept.''
</P>
<P>
   In an essay written just days before his assassination on Sept.
15, Jesus Bejarano, a former government ``peace commissioner'' who
in 1991 helped negotiate an agreement with another rebel group,
said that peace could be achieved only when there was ``a critical
mass of positive facts that make negotiations possible.'' As
examples, he cited the cases of El Salvador and Guatemala, where
fighting between government and rebels dragged on for years.
</P>
<P>
   For such a ``critical mass'' to be achieved here, though, the
government may have to transform a weakness into a strength. The
absence of a cease-fire has worked primarily to the advantage of
the rebels so far. But as Alfredo Rangel, another prominent
political analyst here, noted, it also offers the government an
opportunity ``to strengthen the dissuasive capacity of the armed
forces, so as to convince the guerrillas that a military victory is
impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6658 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CALIF-GOP-HNS &LR;      09-26 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BUSH SNUBS GOP'S ORGANIZATIONAL ARM IN CALIFORNIA TO RUN CAMPAIGN
HIS WAY IN DELEGATE_RICH STATE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ In an echo of internecine Republican
skirmishing back home in Texas, Gov. George W. Bush has overcome
the archconservative leadership of the GOP in California, a
potentially decisive state in his campaign for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a midsummer fight over rules for next March's
primary in the nation's most populous state, Bush and his top
strategists in Austin and the Golden State have decided to largely
ignore the conservative diehards who control the struggling, broke
California party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has run up a strong lead in polling, fund-raising and
endorsements in California, stiffed the state Republican convention
here this weekend. It was the second time this year he had refused
to appear at the gathering of rightwing activists. He instead
attended a home-schoolers event and a GOP Hispanic dinner in
Washington on Friday and spent the weekend at the Ryder Cup golf
competition in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Seeming to make his snub of the convention more obvious, Bush
will campaign in California later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking forward to coming out here and building upon his
grass-roots support,'' said the Bush campaign's California
spokeswoman, Margita Thompson. ``He's going to go meet with them in
their own towns around the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's absence was criticized by nomination rival Steve
Forbes, the multimillionaire magazine publisher seeking to become
the more conservative alternative to the front-runner, moderates
defended the governor's decision to skip the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he really had any alternative,'' said Bob
Larkin, a Simi Valley insurance agent who chairs the centrist
California Congress of Republicans. The congress held a rump
session across the street from the official convention. ``Why
should he show up to support folks who tried to slap at him?''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin referred to the move last June by California Republican
Chairman John McGraw and the state party's executive committee to
ditch the statewide winner-take-all presidential nominating primary
in favor of a system that would have considered a candidate's
showing in each of the state's 52 U.S. House districts. The move
was seen by Bush strategists as an attempt to weaken the
front-runner's hand and provide an opportunity for more
conservative candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters, citing legal requirements, forced McGraw to
seek legislative approval of the change, which was not obtained
before the national party's July 1 deadline for submitting final
rules for 2000 delegate-selection plans.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bush backers hoped the governor and his campaign operatives
in California would step up the fight against McGraw, an
anti-abortion ideologue who has declared that ``killing our babies
(is the) issue of the century. Cutting taxes or any other issue
pales in comparison.'' Some participants in the rump convention
wore stickers reading ``Abort McGraw.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the fight about primary rules complete, the Bush forces
have decided that the party organization is largely irrelevant to
its California campaign, which already has more important assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the winner-take-all primary. We've got the vast support
of Republicans in the (California) legislature. We've got the vast
support of Republicans in the congressional delegation. We've got
the enthusiastic support of Republican fund-raisers in the state.
We get a wild response whenever the governor is out there,'' said a
top Bush adviser. ``We don't need to worry about taming anything.
We're in control of our destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush strategist's view is shared by independent analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming more and more apparent that as irrelevant as the
(Republican) party has become in the state, the hard-right element
is becoming even more irrelevant,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a
political scientist at the Claremont Graduate University.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fights with the California party's hard-right hierarchy
is reminiscent of his tussles with a similar element in the Texas
GOP, including criticism of the governor by former state Chairman
Tom Pauken and Bush's open feud with conservative Republicans on
the state Board of Education. Bush also spoke out for more
tolerance in a dispute between the state party officials and the
gay Log Cabin Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw attempted in several sessions with reporters during the
weekend to gloss over any past disagreements with the Bush
campaign, a sentiment also voiced by some Bush campaign leaders in
California, including state co-chairman Mike Schroeder, immediate
past chief of the state GOP.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw said that despite continued agitation from his
conservative allies he considered the winner-take-all issue closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do nothing to jeopardize our delegation'' to the
Republican National Convention next summer in Philadelphia, McGraw
said.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw acknowledged that Bush ``seems to be playing very well''
in California and said he planned to see the governor this week
when Bush campaigns in Redwood City, near McGraw's home in the
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's bulging campaign treasury will allow him to fund a major
television advertising campaign leading up the California primary,
``and that speaks louder than the squeals of the hard right,''
Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   The state party may also find itself soon financially beholden
to Bush, who reportedly has agreed to star at two fund-raising
events for the California GOP, which is currently in the hole. In
June 30 filings, the party had debts of $311,000 and only $131,500
in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   An insider said the party, which lost the governorship last
November to a Democrat for the first time in 16 years, has failed
to attract its usual financial support from key donors _ many of
whom are aligned with Bush and were irritated by McGraw's move
against the winner-take-all primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys may loosen up if Bush is the main attraction at a
party fund-raiser,'' a key Republican official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a message or is that a message?'' said Jeffe. She also
predicted that ``a Bush person will be sitting on top of the money
bag'' when it arrives at the state party headquarters. In fact,
former state GOP chairman Schroeder is expected to be the
go-between on how the money should be allocated.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bush is conservative and opposes abortion, it is not
the focus of his campaign and he has attracted support of more
moderate California Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to make us a united party, and our state
leadership isn't interested in that,'' said Victoria Bull of
Pasadena, Calif., a Republicans for Choice leader who attended the
rump convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory A. Zlotnick of Mountain View, chairman of the moderate
California Republican League, said the state party currently is run
by ``people more dedicated to ideological purity than they are to
winning elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent statewide survey by the nonpartisan Public
Policy Institute of California found that on an open primary
ballot, like the one that will face voters March 7, Bush was tied
with Vice President Al Gore, the leader for the Democratic
nomination, at 27 percent. The next Republican contender was former
Cabinet official Elizabeth Dole at 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If that were the primary result, Bush could claim the entire
giant California delegation to the Republican National Convention _
about one-fifth of the votes needed to secure the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential contenders Forbes, Dole and former
diplomat Alan Keyes addressed the state convention over the
weekend, with Keyes making the most direct assault on Bush, whom he
labeled an ``unprincipled equivocator.''
</P>
<P>
   The Public Policy Institute survey earlier this month found that
in the general election, Bush topped Gore 49-44 percent and that
the governor ran ahead of the other Democratic contender, former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, 51-38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, a Democrat, carried California in the last
two national elections, and his party rarely has won the presidency
without being victorious in the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-DESPAIR-ART-2TAK     09-26 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-DESPAIR-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS RALLY, WEARILY LOOKING FOR SOMEONE ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Jelena Kovacevic, 25, wants change so
badly she is nearly in tears. She's afraid of the winter, afraid of
her grandparents dying from lack of medicine, afraid of the future,
afraid that she will never live in a Serbia in which she will want
to bear a child.
</P>
<P>
   A painter and graphic artist, she goes nightly to the opposition
demonstrations in Novi Sad seeking the ouster of President Slobodan
Milosevic, but she does not believe that they will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to the rallies because I want something good to happen in
this country, so I can't stay at home. But I don't go because I
support the opposition, either,'' she said, twisting her fingers
around her three earrings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so tired, tired of everything,'' she said.
``Normally, I'm a person with a lot of energy, but I don't feel it
now. I don't see the person in the opposition who can lead the
Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kovacevic's despair is widely shared among the tens of
thousands, young and old, who have turned out for Serbia's first
week of rallies to try to oust the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   It is a despair shared, privately, by opposition officials and
organizers, who are trying to swallow down their disappointment in
their own people.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 80,000 people across Serbia turned out last Tuesday,
but since then the numbers have, if anything, been shrinking. The
enthusiasm is palpable in Novi Sad, 90 minutes north of Belgrade,
and numbers are back up to 30,000 in the capital now that
demonstrators have been asked to march instead of simply listen to
speeches, but they are down in other Serbian cities.
</P>
<P>
   In a country of nearly 11 million people, the turnout is not
even close to a politically definitive figure, let alone to the 2
million demonstrators that the Democratic Party leader, Zoran
Djindjic, believes will be necessary to get the Milosevic
government to crack. And the behavior of the demonstrators is
extraordinarily _ and undramatically _ polite.
</P>
<P>
   The indisputable fact about the opposition is its division:
Djindjic and the Alliance for Change, a coalition of smaller
parties, have taken a path of daily rallies opposed by the largest,
notionally opposition party, the Serbian Renewal Movement of Vuk
Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Don Quixote against the windmills,'' said Vesna, who
asked that her last name not be used because she works for an
international organization. ``However much we'd like to see
Milosevic fall, to see him hanging with his wife from a lamppost in
Terazije Square, like Mussolini, on the other hand'' _ she paused,
lifting up her arms, turning her palms toward her face _ ``the
power is still in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   People are tired and afraid of losing what little is left to
them, including their jobs, Vesna said. ``From the end of the war
until now, energy has been dissipated by the war, the bombing, the
shortages of everything. And the opposition dissipates energy, too,
with empty rallies, with their squabbling and their fight for
supremacy.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic and Djindjic, former allies in the Zajedno, or
Together, coalition that led 88 days of opposition demonstrations
in the winter of 1996-97, not so casually despise each other.
Draskovic, who now controls Belgrade and its television station,
Studio B, says that the Alliance strategy is all wrong, that street
pressure will not bring down Milosevic but should be used to demand
fair and early elections, even if Milosevic keeps his post.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic Party officials and many rally goers believe that
Draskovic simply wants to destroy Djindjic and become the sole
leader of the opposition, and that his position is part of a deal
with Milosevic to keep each other in power.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Vesna believes that Draskovic is hopelessly compromised by his
desire to keep Belgrade, its money and privilege, and that he
cannot be considered a member of the opposition at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is true that the revolution eats its own children,''
she said. ``Draskovic chooses not to join these rallies, and he is
doing all he can to kill them.'' Studio B has taken a dismissive
line toward the rallies, reporting them but underestimating
turnout, much like state television.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Vuk is a red bandit now,'' said Jovan Bandin, using a
description commonly attached to Milosevic and his allies. Bandin,
a portly, bearded businessman who says he will attend rallies until
the end, said he liked Draskovic three years ago, ``but he's
Slobo's man now. He's doing everything he can to stop real
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Bandin, who imports Timex watches and Herbalife, a nutritional
supplement, says: ``I have a house and cars. I don't need anything.
But what I need I don't have, and that's freedom _ the freedom to
live and travel.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Bandin is also highly critical of the West's effort to drive
Milosevic into a corner by indicting him for war crimes, giving him
no option but to turn and fight for his position. `` Without an
exit, he won't go, not without a real battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Mina, 21, an economics student, has come to the rallies without
much real hope. Asked why, she said bitterly: ``Milosevic has
smashed my hopes. But the largest blame for that belongs to the
opposition parties. They have no clear line, they just wait to see
what Milosevic will give them, and everyone knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   But she conceded that the opposition has real problems of
finances and lack of media access, too. For instance, cardboard
masks of Milosevic's face with a red line through it, so popular at
the first rally, had disappeared by the second day. The Alliance
had money to print only 12,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With Draskovic's Studio B essentially unsympathetic to the
rallies, it is difficult for Djindjic to answer the carefully honed
criticisms of the state television that has been the mainstay of
Milosevic's 12-year rule of Yugoslavia. Like all good propaganda,
reports over the state news media play on real issues: there was a
war here, NATO did bomb and take over Kosovo, and ordinary
civilians died.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the start of the bombing, in March, Djindjic told
The New York Times that the democratic opposition would be the
first victim of NATO's war against Milosevic. And it remains very
awkward for the political opposition to push for Western reforms
and the ouster of Milosevic with the visible support _ moral and
financial _ of those who bombed for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, opposition officials say, NATO not only failed
to finish off Milosevic, but it also has failed to protect the
multiethnic character of Kosovo. By letting even innocent Serbs be
driven from a province that remains a sovereign part of Yugoslavia,
NATO has allowed Milosevic to justify fighting the war, however
unwinnable, by pointing to its consequences for the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kovacevic, the Novi Sad artist, sees the opposition as part
of the ``collateral damage'' of the NATO bombing war, caught
between patriotism and its desire to push for Western-style
democratic change. She has done a series of ``collateral art'' and
distributed it on her web page (http://www.surf.to/jelena),
including a graphic of Sisyphus, eternally trying to climb his
mountain with a huge red Communist star still embedded in his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition had its chance to do something and failed
everyone,'' she said. ``And now, when it's the last chance to do
something, when Milosevic is weaker, they're quarreling among
themselves. You know people are afraid when they start to
quarrel,'' she said. ``People lose their faith and trust in them,
and that's why the demonstrations have lost strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kovacevic is trying without much success to pull money
together to attend art school in America, but she also feels guilty
about wanting to leave her family and friends before a winter that
everyone knows will be difficult, with shortages of electricity and
heat. But she doubts that winter will be a great ally to the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just adds to this collective depression,'' she said.
``Imagine people in New York without enough electricity and heat,
without confidence in the future, without knowing what will happen
tomorrow to basic parts of life. Will there be medicine? Will my
computer be dead without electricity? This uncertainty translates
into apathy, not action.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kovacevic was 6 when Tito died in May 1980 after 35 years as
the unquestioned leader of the old Communist Yugoslavia. ``Everyone
cried and I couldn't understand it,'' she said. ``But since then
I've lived in so many states, in so many Yugoslavias, each one
smaller than the last, but for 10 years with the same leader _
that's the worst thing of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of her friends have joined the great exodus of young people
from Yugoslavia, to live and work abroad. ``They call or e-mail me
and ask how am I. I can't answer _ things just get worse and worse.
And when they talk about visiting, I tell them not to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kovacevic toyed with her earrings again, finished a coffee
and prepared to wander out to another rally. ``After the war, I
really thought Milosevic would be gone in a few days,'' she said.
``But now he seems stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
