<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bidding War Opens for British Bank
</P>
<P>
   Royal Bank of Scotland Group is said to be preparing a
counteroffer for National Westminster Bank. The takeover offer,
expected as soon as Monday, would be about 25 billion pounds, or
about $41 billion, according to executives briefed on the plan.
That would be 3 billion pounds more than a rival, the Bank of
Scotland, offered in a hostile bid for National Westminster on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Year 2000 Organizer Resigns
</P>
<P>
   Paloma O'Riley, co-founder of the Cassandra Project, an
Internet-based clearinghouse for potential Year 2000 computer
threats, has resigned as the service's research director, saying
that people are losing interest in efforts to organize
neighborhoods and communities. Her activism brought invitations to
testify before Congress and made her a leader in the pursuit of
grass-roots solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Digital Music Effort
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, trying to gain a stronger foothold in the burgeoning
digital music market, plans to announce Monday that the newest line
of Internet audio chips from Cirrus Logic will support Microsoft's
Windows Media Audio format.
</P>
<P>
   Penney Begins Fall Fashion Push
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest campaigns of the fall fashion season comes
from J.C. Penney Co., which is seeking to reposition itself as a
fashion leader. Trade publications estimated spending for the
campaign at $35 million. The new branding effort, which began last
month, will include 23 commercials that were created by Temerlin
McClain in Irving, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Contender Emerges at Miami Herald
</P>
<P>
   The four-month search for a new executive editor at The Miami
Herald is almost over, and Robert Rivard, editor and senior vice
president of The San Antonio Express News, is the leading candidate
for the job, according to one Knight Ridder executive, who asked
not to be identified. The Herald's publisher said other candidates
were still under consideration. The new editor will inherit a
newsroom bolstered by a 1999 Pulitzer Prize for investigative
reporting but bruised by circulation declines.
</P>
<P>
   Online Sales, Real-World Shipping
</P>
<P>
   Order fulfillment remains the most important issue facing the
e-commerce industry. Picking, packing and shipping products was
difficult enough in recent years for Internet retailers who had no
experience in such matters. But with consumers' expectations rising
and e-commerce companies preparing to ship a wider array of
merchandise to customers this holiday season, distribution issues
now loom even larger than before.
</P>
</TEXT>
