<SLUG> BC-WORLDBANK-NOMINEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BANK CHIEF TO BE RENOMINATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has decided to renominate James
D. Wolfensohn as president of the World Bank, administration
officials said Sunday, _ a political victory for the former
investment banker who openly split with the administration over its
early handling of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers informed finance ministers
of the other major industrial nations of the decision on Saturday,
telling them that ``Jim Wolfensohn has done an extraordinary job of
bringing energy and passion to the bank's crucial development
mission.'' Wolfensohn is in the midst of restructuring the bank,
whose mission is to combat poverty around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997 and early 1998, Wolfensohn openly criticized both
the Treasury and the World Bank's sister institution, the
International Monetary Fund, for designing national bailouts in
Asia that paid too little attention to hardships that would result
for the poorest residents of Indonesia, Thailand, South Korea and
other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue packages, he contended, were too skewed toward aiding
banks and international lenders. But in recent months he has
smoothed over relations with the administration, and officials say
there was no real debate about his reappointment, which is likely
to be announced formally on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, speaking at the annual meetings of the World Bank and
the IMF, Wolfensohn said that while Asia is recovering, ``the
economic situation is especially difficult in Latin America,'' and
that ``we will still be going backward rather than forward in the
fight to reduce global poverty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
