<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-TV-SPORTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGING AMERICANS PRODUCE HIGHEST RYDER   TV RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The 33d Ryder Cup produced not only the
greatest comeback in its history, but also its highest ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's final-day numbers are expected to be even higher than
those achieved Saturday, when the Europeans finished with a 4-point
lead. The second day of action earned a 4.9 rating and 14 share in
the overnight survey of 43 markets.
</P>
<P>
   Boston viewers gave NBC's Channel 7 a 7.2 rating and 21 share.
Those numbers are particularly significant because the network
began its 10 1/2-hour day at 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The highest rating achieved in a single market occurred in West
Palm Beach, with a 9.2 rating. Hartford, Conn. pulled a 6.3 and
Providence, R.I. had a 7.3.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's production was wonderful Sunday, balancing informative
profiles and graphics with the action. And, of course, there was
Johnny Miller, the best analyst of any sport. He is so frank,
honest, and knowledgeable that he is one of the rare analysts who
commands attention from the most sensitive of listeners _
professional golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Miller so dogged Justin Leonard's woeful performance on Saturday
that Davis Love told Jim Gray, ``He didn't believe in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was just calling it as he saw it. With Sergio Garcia on a
roll, Miller said that Jim Furyk was an underdog in Sunday's match.
Furyk beat Garcia, 4 and 3, and said, ``I didn't feel like I was an
underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Leonard took a shot at Miller. ``It's a good thing I didn't
go home,'' Leonard said. Miller had suggested on Saturday that
Leonard ``find a shovel, dig a hole, and get in it.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol rolled the dice with his
purchase of the Ryder Cup rights back in 1991. NBC lost money that
year but stuck with it, and recently spent more than $10 million to
secure the television rights the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol defended his decision not to have a permanent scoreboard
on screen and said that viewers heard the total score every three
or four minutes. He was correct. Ebersol also pointed out that
showing the total score would have required a large graphic, which
would prevented viewers from seeing live action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we live in a time of instant gratification,'' Ebersol
said. ``But I'd like to think of television as settling people
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol also defended Miller, saying the analyst is loyal to his
viewers first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Azinger made the same criticisms against Miller after the
1991 Ryder Cup,'' Ebersol said. ``Miller has developed a thick skin
ever since then. But like Johnny has said countless times before,
he gives his loyalty to the viewer at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even Ebersol could have predicted the succces of the Ryder
Cup. ``This event gives the PGA what it has been looking for _ a
fifth major,'' Ebersol said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-MEETING-BOS     09-26 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MEETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTIVATIONAL MEEETING PULLED AMERICANS TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Jim Furyk, after absorbing a 3-and-2 loss
with partner Mark O'Meara to Darren Clarke and Lee Westwood
Saturday morning, never took his clubs out of the bag for the
four-ball competition.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard at the end of the day said it all: Europe 10, USA
6. Neither development did much for Furyk's mood. ``I was a little
down when I left the golf course,'' recalled Furyk after Sunday's
stunning Ryder Cup victory at The Country Club. ``I stayed here
extra long. But when I heard the guys in our talk Saturday night, I
knew we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``talk,'' orchestrated by captain Ben Crenshaw, included a
video of well-wishes and highlights of the players' achievements
before the team left the clubhouse for their hotel. It was a
never-say-die exhortation that was soon echoed by every team member
and by Governor George W. Bush of Texas, who even made reference to
the Alamo and the willingness to fight to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben kept saying, `We can do this. I've got a good feeling
about it.' '' said Davis Love. ``Today, we came out and did what he
asked us to do. The mood was great. Everybody spoke. It was hard to
believe. Every time anybody said whether we win or lose, somebody
would stop them and say, `Wait a minute, we're going to win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, at the meeting, wanted to put something else to
rest: The perception that he was approaching the Ryder Cup
selfishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I was happy to be here,'' said Duval, who set the tone
early by wiping out Jesper Parnevik (5 and 4), a thorn in the US
side until Sunday. ``I was sick and tired of everyone saying we
weren't a team. I was upset with what I had interpreted as a
misrepresentation at times. I said I think we're better (than the
European team) and let's go show it and let's go kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, added Steve Pate, the meeting was a needed
reminder to the Americans that they hadn't played poorly. ``It was
just that the European team had played unbelievably well,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't a players-only meeting, said Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all played a part in it,'' said Woods. ``All the players,
wives, girlfriends, assistant captains. It was a great meeting. It
was a great night. We shared what we thought. It was a very
beautiful evening.''
</P>
<P>
   One that left Hal Sutton with ``no doubt in my mind leaving it
that we all felt we could go out and make a real run at this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the Bush reference about the man at the Alamo who
knew he wasn't going to make it, this time the Americans survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not be soldiers who fight in wars,'' said Phil
Mickelson, ``but this was somthing of its own and we needed to
fight as if we were.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fight talk helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all went around the room and all 12 players spoke,'' said
Love. ``I can't believe how together these 12 players were.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the flashpoint, Crenshaw said at Sunday night's press
conference, ``for a friendship and a bond that was unbreakable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
