<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-FAMILIES-NYT &LR;      09-26 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY'S TALE OF POLITICAL TERROR TURNED PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIMOR-ALBRIGHT) 
(js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ For Domingos Goncalves, the day of terror
began two hours before dawn, as she crouched on the floor of her
bedroom, praying that she would survive the attack that she knew
was coming.
</P>
<P>
   For the armed men who were shouting in the alleyways, outside
her house, the day began with a call for more gasoline as they
moved methodically through the neighborhood, burning one house
after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard one commander say, `OK, some elements go to buy
gasoline,'' said Miss Goncalves, 30, a lay worker in a Roman
Catholic Church. ``Then everybody gather in front of the police
station.'''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all her neighbors had already fled the campaign of terror
and destruction that began after the news on Sept. 4 that the
people of East Timor had voted for independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Goncalves said people had told her to run. ``But because my
mother is crippled from rheumatism, my brother and I stayed with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   What the family witnessed _ the destruction of their home and
the killing of Miss Goncalves' brother _ provides a look inside an
extraordinary three-week surge of violence in which irregular
militias supported by the Indonesian military appeared to try to
annihilate the people of an entire territory.
</P>
<P>
   In a land where almost everybody seems to know everybody else,
the violence as witnessed by the Goncalves family was as personal
as it was political.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Goncalves' brother, Afonso, for instance, seems to have
died not only because of his pro-independence views but also
because of his mental retardation and a family feud in which a
niece had eloped with a member of a militia group.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, his death involved vengeance, as the Indonesian
army, defeated in its attempt to subdue the territory it invaded in
1975, set out to ensure that a free East Timor would have to build
a new country from nothing.
</P>
<P>
   For two days the Goncalves family hid in their house, listening
to the shouts, the shooting, the screams of fear, the busy sounds
of motorcycles and trucks, the roar of fires as the destruction
drew nearer.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all their neighbors were gone. The houses around them
were empty. In their own home, Miss Goncalves said, the only sound
was their own breathing and their whispered prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very frightened,'' she said. ``I prepared myself to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   On the third day, her family's turn came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the leader shouting, `Burn that house, burn this
house,''' Miss Goncalves said. ```This house' meant our house. They
came on motorcycles, hitting at things with rifle butts and sticks,
hitting houses and fences, breaking windows, shooting their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Goncalves fled to a thicket of mango and papaya trees
behind the house. She watched through the bushes as a man wearing
the black T-shirt of a militia group called Aitarak and carrying a
military-issue automatic rifle kicked down the door.
</P>
<P>
   What she heard was more terrifying than what she could see, Miss
Goncalves said. ``I heard a woman screaming,'' she said. ``I tried
to tell if it was the screaming of my mother. I was sure that she
and my brother were being killed.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, her mother, Martinha Goncalves, 70, picks up the
story as she sits in a shack in a dry river bed that serves as a
camp ground for many of Dili's homeless people. Her mind has faded
with age, and a second daughter, Filomena Soares, 41, helps her.
</P>
<P>
   When the armed men burst into the house, Mrs. Goncalves said,
she sat staring at them, immobile on her bed. Her son, who was 37,
hid behind a door. The armed men, busy with their looting and
vandalism, paid no attention to them.
</P>
<P>
   Was she afraid?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel anything,'' Mrs. Goncalves said. ``But Afonso
was afraid because he worried about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Were there many men in her house?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot. But I have trouble with my memory. The person who can
tell you the whole story is Afonso. But Afonso is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, before the men returned to burn the house, her son found
a transport tricycle and he and his mother moved to the home of
friends on the other side of Dili, Mrs. Soares said.
</P>
<P>
   It was five days before three armed men, one wearing an army
uniform, found Afonso there and killed him.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mrs. Soares' husband they were looking for, she said,
because of his reputation as a strong supporter of independence.
When word came that they were on their way, he ran.
</P>
<P>
   But Afonso, always slow to react and determined not to leave his
mother, was at the house when they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   They saw him and said, ``People like Afonso we have to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   What this meant, Mrs. Soares said, was that the armed men were
determined to kill a member of a family that had strongly supported
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came filled with fury and they were ready to kill
anybody,'' she said. ``If Afonso had run, they would have killed
our mother.''
</P>
<P>
   It was noon, said a neighbor, Simeao da Cruz Ribeiro, 59, when
the three men walked up to the house. Everybody knew who they were:
two brothers and an uncle who belonged to a militia group and who
hated the Goncalves family.
</P>
<P>
   The family feud dated back to last year, when Mrs. Soares'
foster daughter, Octaviana, 22, fell in love and ran off with
another member of the family who had arrived now to kill her
brother. The Goncalves family had objected to the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started to beat Afonso with their rifle butts,'' Ribeiro
said. ``He put his hands over his head and began to scream. Then
they shot Afonso between the legs and he fell onto his face. He
crawled on the ground to a tree and he lay on his back at the foot
of the tree, looking at the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribeiro said his 19-year-old daughter, Siria Brigida, ran over
to him. ``Uncle Afonso, Uncle Afonso,'' she called.
</P>
<P>
   He lifted his head and repeated the same phrase twice before he
died: ``Look after my mother. Look after my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors buried him in front of their house in a grave
marked with small stones and strewn with red and purple flowers.
They wrote his name on a piece of wood because they could not find,
anywhere in this ravaged city, a hammer and nails to build a cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
