<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6685 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-OPERA-RECORDBREAKER-A     09-26 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-RECORDBREAKER-ART-835(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINGO TO BREAK CARUSO'S RECORD FOR OPENING NIGHTS AT THE MET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Baseball fans may be caught up with the home-run race
between Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire, but if all goes according to
plan, opera buffs will be cheering Monday night as the tireless
tenor Placido Domingo hits a few high notes into the top balcony of
the Metropolitan Opera House and breaks an operatic record that has
stood longer than Babe Ruth's 60-homer season did.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Opera opens its season Monday night with a
popular double bill: Mascagni's ``Cavalleria Rusticana'' and
Leoncavallo's ``Pagliacci.'' And for the 18th time in his career
Domingo will star in a Met opening-night performance, surpassing
Enrico Caruso's tally of 17. To drive home the point, it would
seem, Domingo is setting the record by singing Canio in
``Pagliacci,'' Caruso's signature role.
</P>
<P>
   Caruso sang his 17 opening nights during just 18 seasons, from
his Met debut as the Duke in Verdi's ``Rigoletto'' in 1903 through
1920 with his portrayal of Eleazar in an opera he championed, ``La
Juive'' by Halevy. This near-consecutive streak indicates how
Caruso dominated his era. Had he not died of pleurisy at 48 in 1921
he would have no doubt added to his total.
</P>
<P>
   Domingo's 18th opening night comes as he begins his 31st season
with the Met. His first opening night was in 1971 with the title
role in Verdi's ``Don Carlo.'' As he relaxed recently in his
dressing room at the Met after a rehearsal for ``Pagliacci,''
looking comfortable in a long silk bathrobe, Domingo, 58, seemed as
energetic and ambitious as ever.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had always assumed that Caruso's record would never
be topped. ``But when I was in my 11th or 12th opening night
somebody asked me, `Do you realize how close you are to the number
of times Caruso opened the Met season?' What can I tell you? I
started to think maybe I can do it.'' For now he has no plans to
stop at 18, provided the Met continues to offer the dates, and his
voice holds out.
</P>
<P>
   Vocal excellence and popularity are hardly the only factors that
go into a singer's being so honored. Forced to choose, some artists
might prefer other Met plums, like being cast in a new production
or a television broadcast. Opening nights have long been ritzy
social events for patrons and indispensable fund-raisers for the
company. On Monday night some 600 guests in formal finery who have
paid $2,000 or $2,500 a seat are to attend the opera, which will be
followed by a dinner in the Met's Grand Tier. Remaining tickets
sold for between $75 and $850. The 3,700-seat house is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, opening night is not the night we would normally
make a major artistic statement,'' the Met's general manager,
Joseph Volpe, said recently. ``If we can make some statement, have
the public on board and also honor a great singer, that is the
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prestige of opening night at the Met is something
almost every singer wants, probably more so than opening at La
Scala, the Paris Opera or Covent Garden. It is not just Domingo's
celebrated voice that has enabled him to sing so many first nights.
Stamina, loyalty to the company and wide-ranging repertory have
been just as important.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's performance will be his 565th at the Met
(including his appearances as a conductor). This represents a
significant share of his total performances, now approaching 2,900.
But Caruso's career was even more focused on the Met. In 18 Met
seasons he sang 607 performances _ at a time when a season
typically lasted less than five months.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with these two vocal sluggers, Luciano Pavarotti's
opening-night tally of seven seems modest. He has been central to
the Met's planning and enduringly popular for 30 years. But he has
less stamina and a narrower repertory than Domingo, whose roles on
opening nights alone range stylistically through Verdi's Otello,
Wagner's Lohengrin and Siegfried, Offenbach's Hoffmann and
Saint-Saens' Samson.
</P>
<P>
   The suave, velvet-voiced Italian baritone Ezio Pinza is in third
place with nine opening-night performances during a career that
went from 1926 to 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The female record holder? The incomparable Rosa Ponselle? No,
only five. Hers was a short career. The beloved Lucrezia Bori? Only
four. Surely Renata Tebaldi is up there? Surprisingly, no. She had
only two: a 1958 ``Tosca'' and a 1968 ``Adriana Lecouvreur.''
</P>
<P>
   The top female of opening nights is Margarete Matzenauer, the
Romanian-born soprano, later a contralto. During a loyal 19-year
Met career through the 1920s she performed in eight opening nights
as Verdi's Amneris and Ulrica, Saint-Saens' Dalila and other roles.
</P>
<P>
   During the '20s and '30s, Antonio Scotti, the impassioned
Italian baritone, and Giovanni Martinelli, the heroic Italian
tenor, each racked up eight opening nights, as did Robert Merrill,
the robust American baritone, in later decades.
</P>
<P>
   With six each, the next closest female artists on the list, also
from that storied era, are the soprano Emma Eames and the contralto
Louise Homer, both beloved American artists.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, especially in earlier decades, the Met did make
important statements with its choice of works and singers for
opening nights. And the decisions were often influenced by social
movements and historical events.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1891, the Met's ninth season, a new team of
managers rescued the company from German control. The direction was
set in the company's second season in 1884 by Leopold Damrosch, the
German-born conductor, who believed unabashedly in the superiority
of Germanic music and urged the Met to court the growing population
of German immigrants in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's operas were repertory staples, and even the occasional
French or Italian work was performed in German. If some critics
today think that James Levine, the artistic director of the Met,
monopolizes the podium, they should consider the case of Damrosch,
who announced at the beginning of 1884 that he would conduct every
single Met performance and did so until his death in February 1885.
</P>
<P>
   The new team signaled a shift back to varied repertory on
opening night in 1891 with a performance of Gounod's ``Romeo et
Juliette,'' featuring the elegant Polish tenor Jean de Reszke and
Eames in the title roles.
</P>
<P>
   Opening night on Oct. 28, 1929, provided a powerful but
unintentional statement. A contented and no doubt well-heeled Met
audience heard Bori and Beniamino Gigli, Caruso's successor, in
Puccini's ``Manon Lescaut,'' about the ruinous effect of
materialism on young love and the good life. The next day the stock
market crashed.
</P>
<P>
   After France fell to the Nazis during World War II, the
sweet-toned, light-as-air French coloratura soprano Lily Pons
became an ardent spokeswoman for her home country. In 1942 her
patriotism burst into an opening-night performance of Donizetti's
French-language ``Fille du Regiment.'' Pons, singing the title
role, interpolated ``La Marseillaise'' into an aria as she waved a
French flag while the stirred audience joined in.
</P>
<P>
   When Sir Rudolf Bing took over the company as general manager in
1950, he made a major artistic statement on his opening night with
a performance of Verdi's longest, most difficult, arguably greatest
but then seldom-heard opera, ``Don Carlo.'' The incomparable cast
featured the bass Cesare Siepi and the mezzo-soprano Fedora
Barbieri in their Met debuts, Merrill, and Jussi Bjorling in the
title role.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961 Leontyne Price became the first black singer to star in
a Met opening night. She portrayed the title character in Puccini's
``Fanciulla del West'' opposite the Brooklyn-born tenor Richard
Tucker. This was a scant seven years after Marian Anderson broke
the color barrier at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Price was also at the center of the opera world when she
sang in the 1966 premiere of Samuel Barber's ``Antony and
Cleopatra.'' With this work the Met inaugurated its Lincoln Center
house. Most critics felt that whatever the merits of the score, the
opera was smothered by the gaudy, empty extravagance of Franco
Zeffirelli's production. But there was no mistaking the importance
of Ms. Price's selection.
</P>
<P>
   To bestow such an honor on a black American artist in the middle
of the civil rights movement was a powerful statement. The opera
was broadcast live on radio, and in an affecting press conference
shortly before the premiere Ms. Price beamed with teary pride as
she told reporters that a radio station near Laurel, Miss., her
hometown, had raised funds and boosted its wattage so that it could
hook into the Met's broadcast for the big day of Laurel's
celebrated native daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, for the Met's centennial opening night, the opera of
choice was Berlioz's ``Troyens,'' an inspired but daunting work.
This was a five-hour evening, not typical opening-night fare and no
crowd pleaser. Why was it done? ``I wanted it, I asked for it and
they agreed with me,'' Levine said recently. ``The more I thought
about it, `Les Troyens' represented exactly what we want: an epic
work, a one-evening work, a work that you can only do with large
flexible resources like the Met's.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I said to everyone that this time I think artistic
considerations should come first because of the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, ``We had the cast.'' Indeed they did, with
Tatiana Troyanos as Didon, Jessye Norman in her Met debut as
Cassandre and Domingo as the hero Enee, who was already performing
in his sixth opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's opening offers another promising Met artist in
his company debut, the 36-year-old Argentine tenor Jose Cura as the
young peasant Turiddu in ``Cavalleria Rusticana.'' In 1994 Cura won
the international vocal competition sponsored by Domingo. This
season, at the company Domingo directs, the Washington Opera, he
will conduct Cura in Verdi's ``Otello.'' Domingo said he was proud
to have been a mentor to the young tenor and happy to share the
evening with him. But does he not feel at all competitive with this
hunky, highly touted Argentine, who looks great onstage and is
tackling many of the older tenor's signature roles, including
Otello?
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition does not really exist,'' Domingo said. ``It's
friendly competition. Everyone wants to do well. No one wants the
other to be bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good. But it is hard to imagine that such an attitude got
Domingo to this record-setting opening night. He does not seem
worried, though. Even if this turns out to be his last Met opening
night, his record of 18 should be almost impossible to beat. Of
course, that's what they said about Caruso's 17. Not to mention the
Babe's 60. And McGwire's 70.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
