<HEADLINE>
RIVALS SEEK TO CAPITALIZE ON BUSH'S ABSENCE FROM PARTY MEETING IN
CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With $52 million backing his campaign for the
Republican Party's nomination for president in 2000, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas sat out the California GOP convention here, attending
the Ryder Cup golf tournament in Massachusetts this weekend
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's absence at the state party's twice-yearly gathering left
him open to familiar attack, this time from his rival for the
nomination, Steve Forbes, a multimillionaire publisher who placed a
distant second behind Bush in the Iowa straw poll last month.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's absence also opened the way for another
candidate, Elizabeth Dole, who has been struggling for support in
the face of Bush's overwhelming financial advantage, to deliver the
keynote address at the convention's dinner on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spoke at lunch and at a press conference on Saturday. On
Friday night, the Forbes campaign threw a lavish party featuring an
open bar, dessert and a swing band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's George?'' Ken Blackwell, the national finance chairman
for Forbes' campaign, asked shortly before Forbes addressed the
lunch crowd. ``That's the operative question.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Bush's failure to appear, Forbes said, ``The more he
does it, the more he helps us.'' He also challenged Bush to five
debates before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   With the first primaries still months away, the Bush campaign
has had to fight a perception of complacency, given the governor's
war chest and his strong first-place showing in the Iowa straw poll
and in national surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bush canceled an appearance at an elementary
school in Central Falls, R.I., because of poor weather, but managed
to attend a fund-raiser in nearby Providence the same night. Vice
President Al Gore, the Democratic front-runner for president,
altered his travel plans two days later to make an appearance at
the same school, where his spokesman told reporters, ``We'll take
kids over cash any day.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, it was Forbes who swooped in. Casting himself as
an outsider defying a party whose leadership had all but officially
thrown its support behind Bush, he said the governor's absence
``underscores the difference between the GOP establishment, which
just likes to trim around the corners and duck, and those of us who
want to engage in real issues that help real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Forbes' speeches, literature and pictures seek to portray
him as the ideological heir of Ronald Reagan, his attack violated
Reagan's often-stated 11th commandment: ``Though shalt not speak
ill of another Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the edict fell to Mrs. Dole, who refrained from
attacking Bush for not showing up. ``He runs his campaign and I'll
run mine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, state party officials said Bush did not attend
the convention here because he had gone to the Republican National
Hispanic Assembly dinner in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday Scott McClennan, a spokesman for the Bush
campaign, acknowledged that the dinner had taken place on Friday
night, and that on Saturday Bush was ``fulfilling a prior
commitment'' to ``watch his good friend Ben Crenshaw,'' coach of
the American golf team, at the Ryder Cup in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign released a statement dismissing the criticism
voiced by Forbes, whose platform calls for a flat income tax.
``Other candidates can talk about things but what's important is
that Governor Bush has acted on Republican principles and gotten
proven results, such as by signing the two largest state tax cuts
in Texas,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   McClennan noted that Bush had agreed to one primary debate on
Jan. 15. ``There will be plenty of time for debates when voters are
paying attention closer to the primaries and causes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Bush had come to California twice since he began
his campaign for the party's nomination, and would return on
Tuesday to campaign in Bakersfield, Riverside, Silicon Valley and
Santa Barbara. ``He is campaigning hard in California and across
America to earn the Republican nomination, and reach out to people
with his message of prosperity with a purpose,'' McClennan said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though Forbes sought to make an issue of Bush's absence, in
truth few of the people attending the convention _ all of them
members of the 1,400-person state party apparatus _ appeared
disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel snubbed,'' said Carl Olson. ``I don't need to see
him in person to know what he's up to. He's in the papers every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Schockency, who was on hand for Mrs. Dole's speech, was
also not annoyed that Bush was not there. ``It doesn't bother me,''
she said. ``It's a long way to the election.''
</P>
<P>
   And Joan F. Stevens seemed almost envious that Bush was at the
Ryder Cup. Noting the longstanding friendship between Bush and
Crenshaw, a fellow Texan, she said: ``I can understand that. I hope
he's having a good time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
