<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-JAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE IS ENOUGH, JAMES SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Americans won't have Mark James to boo when
the Ryder Cup moves to The Belfry at Sutton Coldfield, England, in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``One captaincy is enough,'' said the 49-year-old native of
Manchester, England. ``If I come back, it will be as a player, but
after seeing these golfers, I'm going to need an extra 20 or 30
yards off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   The European captain, who has played on seven Ryder Cup teams,
said he is resigning. ``I'm stepping down,'' said James. ``It's a
once-in-a-lifetime job. There are plenty of other deserving
candidates to become captain and they should get their chance. It's
such a terrific honor. But, there is no chance of me
reconsidering.''
</P>
<P>
   James enjoyed the role and spent much of Sunday shuttling from
one player to another, offering encouragement and trying to rally
his forces. He wasn't a Bill Parcells coach. He was more like Pete
Carroll _ and he lost.
</P>
<P>
   Giving American captain Ben Crenshaw the credit, James said he
could see the momentum changing. But he wasn't prepared from the
Americans' blitzkrieg Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't think that Crenshaw out-maneuvered him with the
pairings or the use _ or non-use _ of players. James said it was a
``team decision'' to keep three of his players on the sidelines for
the first four matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me before the final round that I could use seven
players in my first four matches and have a 10-6 lead going into
the singles matches on Sunday, there is no question I would have
done just that.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Sunday's Brookline Massacre, James said it would
be disappointing to see the Europeans lose the Cup needing just
four points. ``To say I'm disappointed would be an
understatement,'' said James.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't select any heroes or goats on his squad. ``I haven't
looked at the scoreboard,'' he said. ``I don't know who played
well. But I don't think any one player is responsible. We came as a
team and we will lose as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't like what he saw when so many Americans rushed out on
to the green when Justin Leonard sank his history-making putt on
17. He doesn't blame Crenshaw either. ``It wasn't the right thing
to do. Jose still had to putt. '' Olazabel's distraction wasn't the
reason Europe lost. ``I don't hold Ben Crenshaw responsible for the
action. The Americans won. They got out to a quick start and the
rest of the team rode it to victory. We tried to stop it, but
sometimes you just can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
