<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN'S WIFE DEFENDS HIM IN RARE TV APPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With G7-MEETING) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Trying to dispel mounting allegations of corruption,
the wife of President Boris Yeltsin delivered an emotional defense
of her family in a rare television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast by the state-owned television network ORT on Saturday
night, the interview was the first time that a member of the
Yeltsin family had addressed the nation on charges that the
president and his youngest daughter, Tatyana Dyachenko, received
kickbacks from the Mabetex construction firm.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Naina Yeltsin nor an indulgent interviewer dealt with
the accusations in any detail. Instead, Mrs. Yeltsin portrayed her
family as people of modest means who were the victim of a
sensationalist and politically biased press and jealous rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even my granddaughter says, `Granny, what shall I say in
school, after what they wrote about us?,''' Mrs. Yeltsin recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `Masha, people are losing their honor and their
scruples,''' she added. ```But you know we do not have any villas
abroad or castles or yachts. We do not have them. So why should you
get upset about all this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Yeltsin is the most popular member of a generally unpopular
family. With her husband's approval ratings at a low and her
daughter, Tatyana, the subject of numerous corruption rumors, she
may be the family's best hope to influence public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians think of her approvingly as a homemaker who stays
aloof from political intrigue and does quiet charity work.
Certainly ORT, a government network largely controlled by the
tycoon Boris Berezovsky, did its best to present Mrs. Yeltsin in a
sympathetic light.
</P>
<P>
   The interview, which was conducted by Pavel Sheremet, an ORT
journalist known for his crusading reports about political abuses
in Belarus, followed moving coverage of the funeral of Raisa
Gorbachev, the wife of the last Soviet leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society has often been cruel to these wise woman,'' Sheremet
said, referring to the criticism of Mrs. Gorbachev for her refusal
to stay in the background and for her sense of style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now history repeats itself,'' he added. ``We are witnessing an
unprecedented attack on the family of the first Russian president.
Does it not occur to anyone that the family suffers from this?''
</P>
<P>
   During her 10-minute interview, which appeared to have been
taped in a Yeltsin country residence, Mrs. Yeltsin was dressed in a
tasteful two-piece dark gray suit and light blue scarf. Two
steaming cups of tea sat on the table, as befits a gracious Russian
hostess.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Yeltsin was not accompanied by any family members. And she
spoke more in sorrow than in anger. She insisted that the rumors of
failing health that have dogged her husband are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read the papers I sometimes find rubbish like he cannot
lift a pen or move his tongue to speak,'' she said. ``I take it all
quite hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And she presented Tatyana Dyachenko as a dutiful daughter who
has been unjustifiably tarred because of her foray into politics.
</P>
<P>
   As Yeltsin's image adviser, Mrs. Dyachenko has become an
increasingly influential member of the Kremlin inner circle. She
has been accused of receiving a credit card from the Mabetex
construction firm, and the Russian press has reported that she has
a lavish foreign villa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts when all these fables are told about her,'' Mrs.
Yeltsin said. ``When I read that she was a drug addict, I thought
well, one can really get carried away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes wonder what prayer I should say to relieve her of
all this,'' Mrs. Yeltsin added. ``When I try to comfort her, she
says, `Mom, I hope you can endure all this.' I am a mother. I can
endure even more because I have already lived my life, and she has
it all ahead of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the former supporters who have now turned against
them, she said that was not the result of mistakes on her husband's
part, but the self-interested machinations of ambitious
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, power spoils many people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports that Yeltsin is so concerned that his
enemies might seek to punish his family if he leaves office,
perhaps by launching corruption investigations, that he might look
for ways to prolong his control.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Yeltsin was never asked about this speculation. But she
used the interview to reassure the nation that her husband plans to
turn over the reins of power, as scheduled, in July. All the family
wants, she insisted, was to live quietly after that and perhaps do
a little tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all live under God,'' she said. ``If we are in good health
and have the opportunity we might go someplace to see something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
