<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT     09-26 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' NIGHTMARE CONTINUES WITH 3-2 LOSS TO PHILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ They have tried players' meetings and a manager's
meeting, blasting music and a clubhouse so quiet it could have
existed in a vacuum. On Saturday the manager suggested he should be
fired if the team does not make the playoffs, and on Sunday he
pulled the ultimate desperate managerial move: He changed his
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is working for the Mets right now _ not the subtle
details nor the dramatic strokes, not all the positive talk, not
Bobby Valentine's insistence that he felt great after leaving the
park Saturday. Not even plunging Edgardo Alfonzo from the second
spot in the lineup to the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost again Sunday, 3-2, to the Phillies, completing an
apocalyptic, wearying six-loss road trip in which they were swept
by the two extremes of baseball: a very hot team and a team that
had been reeling toward oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the Mets' luck, which Valentine has been convinced
for the last few days was about to change, got even worse when the
game was over. The Reds won on a three-run homer in the bottom of
the 12th inning to take a one-game lead in the wild-card race. In
the space of six days, the Mets have gone from being one game out
of the division lead to scrambling to stay in the wild-card race
with six games left.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the Braves, who come to town on Tuesday for a
three-game series that now looms about as ominously as Mount
Everest, clinched the division Sunday. After the Mets had another
drab performance, after a day of assurances by general manager
Steve Phillips that this predicament might actually make things
easier for the Mets, they slink home to an off day, unable to
explain just what has happened to their season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss for words,'' Mike Piazza said. ``I don't want to
say it, but it can't get much worse. I think everyone is stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets left Veterans Stadium on Saturday, they did so to
the beat of salsa music and with their stomachs full of crabs from
their postgame meal. It was an oddly convivial scene, and Phillips
said the players might have been relieved that they no longer had
to look over their shoulders at the Reds gaining on them, that
having them side by side would be a good thing. Now, the Reds are
passing at full speed, while the Mets have pulled off into the
breakdown lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey has got nothing to say about this crazy stuff now,''
said Rickey Henderson, and that was before he knew about the Reds'
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have tried everything to break out of their funk.
Sunday, Valentine pulled another trick out of the same pocket that
no doubt holds the sword he nearly threw himself upon a day
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had gone out for dinner Saturday night, he said, and
began thinking that the Mets needed to present a different
challenge to opposing teams, by breaking up their string of
left-handed hitters in the five, six and seven spots of the lineup.
Valentine said he was on the exercise bike Sunday morning when
Alfonzo, the right-handed hitter who had been batting second for
most of the season, wandered in and suggested the same thing: Put
the left-hander Roger Cedeno, who bats seventh, in the two spot and
insert Alfonzo at sixth, between the lefties Robin Ventura and
Darryl Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it works,'' Valentine said. ``I've never done
shake-it-up changes. I think we've had really good lineups and now
this is a better lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   But this one did not get it done any better. Rick Reed pitched
well enough to keep the Mets in the game, giving up three runs, two
of them on a two-run homer by Rico Brogna with two outs in the
fourth. But the Phillies had the former Met Paul Byrd starting the
game, the same pitcher on whom the Mets pasted seven runs in four
and a third innings one week ago. Byrd's fastball had been clocked
in the low-80s in recent weeks, indicating that his arm was all but
dead, and the Phillies had lost his last five starts, in which his
earned run average was 9.39.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The Mets managed just five hits and two runs in seven
innings against Byrd, and the two runs were a terrible
disappointment when so much more finally seemed possible.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning, Piazza led off with a single, but was
taken out at second when Ventura hit into a fielder's choice. After
Alfonzo flied out, Hamilton walked, moving Ventura to second base.
Rey Ordonez belted a 1-1 fastball to right field that scored both
Hamilton and Ventura. Matt Franco, pinch-hitting for Reed, walked
on four straight pitches but Byrd, obviously facing his last
batter, got Henderson to strike out with an 87 mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the ninth inning _ along with that improbable eighth
inning in Wednesday's game against the Braves _ that may go down as
one of the signs that the Mets are not going to pull out of this
tailspin. Alfonzo grounded out to lead off the inning, but then
reliever Wayne Gomes delivered 11 straight balls en route to
walking Hamilton, Ordonez and pinch-hitter Bobby Bonilla. With
Shane Halter running for Bonilla and Steve Montgomery in to pitch,
the game came down to Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we could at least push one across,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't. On a 1-2 count, Henderson made contact and the
ball took one bounce on the AstroTurf headed toward right field.
The ball bounced so low that the second base umpire, Rich Rieker,
had to dive to get out of its way. But Dave Doster, who had been a
defensive replacement _ the same guy who snagged Benny Agbayani's
liner to end the Mets' best threat Saturday _ grabbed the ball on
the short hop. He flipped to shortstop Desi Relaford to start the
game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to change,'' Valentine said for what seemed like
at least the fourth day in a row. ``It always happens and we're too
good for it not to happen. When it comes, it will come in bunches.
It was real close to changing today and I think the guys felt it.''
</P>
<P>
   If they aren't already numb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
