<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BRITISH COURT BEGINNING HEARINGS, PINOCHET WILL LEARN HIS FATE
SOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who has called himself ``the
only political prisoner in England'' since his arrest here nearly a
year ago, will begin finding out this week whether he must go to
Spain to face charges of crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Weeklong hearings starting Monday at Bow Street Magistrates
Court are the first action in the case since May. Then, the last of
many legal maneuvers ended with the failure of his High Court
appeal of Britain's decision to let the Spanish extradition request
go forward. Pinochet, the 83-year-old former Chilean dictator, will
not have to be present in these new hearings until the day the
ruling is issued.
</P>
<P>
   The case has transformed international law and galvanized human
rights and exile groups. It also has stirred passionate old
antagonisms in Chile and other countries that have emerged from
dictatorial regimes to face demands for justice from relatives and
representatives of the victims of abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its eventual outcome, the Pinochet case has already
secured a valuable legal precedent for the rights movement: the
finding that former heads of state do not enjoy immunity from
prosecution for systematic atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bridgehead has been established: the concept of crimes
against humanity as the arrow that pierces the Achilles' heel of
state sovereignty,'' said Geoffrey Robertson, a well-known London
lawyer and an authority on war crime prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Pinochet case has caused diplomatic problems for Britain
even though the government has been at pains to say that the
general's detention has, from the start, been a police and judicial
matter, not a political one.
</P>
<P>
   The strain in relations between Spain and Chile intensified this
month when Chile recalled its ambassador to Madrid for the second
time in protest over the treatment of Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative government of Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar
has had to give formal backing to the extradition request by the
high-profile maverick investigating magistrate, Baltasar Garzon,
but has made it clear it does not support the undertaking and has
no desire to see the former Chilean president in the dock in
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   In a rebuff to Spanish prosecutors seeking to short-circuit the
case before it ever gets to Madrid, a three-judge panel from
Spain's National Court ruled Friday that Garzon does have
jurisdiction to prosecute Pinochet on human rights charges.
</P>
<P>
   He has been living with his wife, Lucia, under house arrest in a
rented mansion in an exclusive suburb in Surrey, south of London.
Military, business and Senate leaders from Santiago have been
flying in periodically to back his case for being freed. In the
most recent instance, a group of them gathered on Sept. 11 to
celebrate the 26th anniversary of the coup that brought Pinochet to
power.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet himself has remained out of the public eye, appearing
only on several occasions during the summer when he was taken in a
wheelchair to a nearby hospital for checkups. His supporters say he
suffers from dizzy spells, diabetes and heart, kidney and prostate
problems, and they contend that he ought to be released immediately
on humanitarian grounds because of his deteriorating health.
</P>
<P>
   The state of his health will play no role in the coming
hearings, which are expected to last five days and produce a
verdict in three weeks. The presiding judge, Ronald Bartle, the
deputy chief metropolitan magistrate, will be ruling only on
whether the extradition application is in order and whether the
crimes it lists are extraditable offenses. The European Convention
on Extradition does not require Spain to produce evidence of its
charges.
</P>
<P>
   If the decision goes against Pinochet, he will be able to appeal
it, and that would prolong the year-old case many more months. If
he did not appeal, the final decision would rest with Jack Straw,
the home secretary, who is Britain's top law-enforcement official.
</P>
<P>
   For Straw, Pinochet's age and health would be a significant
determining factor. Straw could decide that the general is not fit
enough to comply with the extradition order and free him on
compassionate grounds to return home.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The general's backers have publicized his hospital visits during
the summer and emphasized the fact that continued detention is
damaging his health. He has told friends that he is depressed and
is becoming resigned to dying in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Sunday Telegraph in July, he complained
that he had been ``kidnapped,'' and he denied any direct
responsibility for any atrocities in Chile. ``I didn't have time to
control what others were doing,'' he said. ``At this very precise
moment, let's say, the only political prisoner in England is me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the one court appearance he has had to make, he said at a
bail hearing in December that he does not recognize the right of
any court outside of Chile to try him ``against all the lies of
Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was arrested in London on Oct. 16, 1998 at the request
of Garzon, who had assembled a case against him in the course of
studying atrocities committed during the so-called dirty wars in
Latin America in the 1970s. Garzon took the bold step of asking the
British police to arrest the general after learning that he was in
a London hospital recovering from minor back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The case wound its way through Britain's courts, and in March
the country's highest tribunal, the Law Lords of the House of
Lords, upheld his arrest but drastically reduced the scope of the
case. It threw out all but charges of torture and conspiracy to
torture and said he could not be extradited for any offenses before
Dec. 8, 1988, when the United Nations torture convention took
effect in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The original 285-page Spanish indictment had accused him of
genocide, murder, torture and kidnapping in connection with the
deaths and disappearances of more than 3,000 people dating back to
1973, the year he seized power and began his 17-year-long rule of
Chile. Since the March ruling, Garzon has added other charges to
the indictment, bringing the new total to 108, all dating from
after 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
