<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PUBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS DECRY LACK OF US SPORTSMANSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When Justin Leonard's outrageously long putt dropped in
the hole, Tony O'Sullivan was prepared to applaud the American,
especially given that Leonard's stroke had won not only the Ryder
Cup but had secured O'Sullivan a tidy sum in a bet.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as Americans raced onto the green even before Spain's
Jose Maria Olazabel got a chance to launch a last desperation putt
to put off the inevitable, O'Sullivan watched it on television and
reacted as all of Europe reacted: with disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical Yanks,'' O'Sullivan said, shaking his head, standing
at the bar in the Duke's Head, a pub in Highgate, North London.
``You can win this like a gentleman, or you can win it like that.
I'd be embarrassed to win it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Duke's Head, and across Europe, the Americans won respect
for their golf game, but not for their decorum. The Americans may
have won, but they won badly, according to Europeans. Across Europe
Sunday night the newscasts told that Europe lost the cup but won on
style points. Newspapers Monday will repeat that theme.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crushing defeat for the Europeans, who had outplayed
the Americans in team play over the first two days and needed only
4 points from the 12 singles matches Sunday to retain the Ryder Cup
they won two years ago in Spain. But the Americans put together the
greatest comeback in the 33 Ryder Cup matches ever played, closing
it out with a putt that, like Leonard, was Texan in length and
brazenness.
</P>
<P>
   They were so confident at the Duke's Head Sunday that they put
the ``footie'' on the telly. Football, or soccer, is normally king
in pubs in London, in all of England, and in all of Europe on
weekends in September, but it takes a backseat when the Ryder Cup
is on.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, however, had a commanding 10-6 lead in the Ryder Cup, so
the Duke's Head regulars treated themselves to the
Wimbledon-Tottenham soccer match. By the time the Ryder Cup
coverage was switched on, Mark Kingston had a bad feeling. The TV
graphic showed the Americans ahead in the first six matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're effed,'' Kingston said, taking up a pint of Guinness for
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston sat at the end of the bar in the Duke's Head, a narrow
pub, 40 feet long and 10 feet wide. The Duke's Head is one of those
places in London where there is a mix of English, Scots and Irish,
with the occasional continental thrown in. They constantly insult
each other, good naturedly.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Englishmen like Kingston were cheering on Scots like
Colin Montgomerie and Irishmen like Padraig Harrington. In fact,
the Englishmen at the Duke's Head were cheering on Harrington, a
Protestant from Dublin, and Darren Clarke, a Catholic from Northern
Ireland. When Harrington won his match on the final hole, he was
toasted lustily at the King's Head.
</P>
<P>
   But even as American golfers put on a dominating display of
skill, Europeans were preoccupied by the lack of etiquette shown by
the gallery at The Country Club. The heckling of Montgomerie, in
particular, bothered the regulars at the Duke's Head.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston, 36, a writer, was appalled, but tried to be
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that emotions are high, on both sides,'' he said.
``But the Americans are taking this to the extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony James, a bartender, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really just ignorance,'' he said. ``The people in the
crowd there don't know how to behave on a golf course. That type of
behavior would never occur in Europe, and if it did, it wouldn't be
tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   On TV, the British announcers said that marshals at The Country
Club were egging the crowd on. At the Duke's Head, people exchanged
open-mouthed stares.
</P>
<P>
   With the Americans up, 13-10, John Murphy, the Duke's Head
owner, returned to his pub after a long day out. He had watched his
native Cork lose to Meath in the All-Ireland football final. He was
stunned to learn that the Americans had overtaken the Europeans in
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yanks come back great, don't they?'' Murphy enthused. His
customers shot him dirty looks.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was unapologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a good sportsman,'' he said. ``I don't care who wins as
long as it's well played.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the point, Murphy's regulars and a good portion
of Europe argued. The Americans showed superior skill, but an
appalling lack of grace in victory.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston was reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like sour grapes, but I really think there is a
cultural difference here,'' he said. ``When Americans want
something, they go and get it. They don't care what other people
think. They don't care how it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan, meanwhile, was regretting his windfall, which came
at 5-2 odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have rather lost my bet,'' he said. ``I won my bet,
but the Ryder Cup is gone. The whole idea of the Ryder Cup, great
golf and good sportsmanship, ended today. It's all over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
