<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-CROWD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEERS KEPT US TEAM PUMPED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The roars kept coming in waves, from
different sections of The Country Club course.
</P>
<P>
   And repeatedly European players who prepared to hit shots that
were becoming increasingly difficult had to step back as more
cheers erupted, signaling another step in the great American
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the cheers came as a sense of relief, as with Mark
O'Meara's 4-foot putt for a halve on 17 in his match with Padraig
Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   Other times they came from sheer joy, as when David Duval closed
out his match with Jesper Parnevik, 5 and 4, with a birdie on 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans staged the greatest comeback in Ryder Cup history
with their skill, but like athletes from team sports who need a
jump-start from the crowd, something rarely seen in golf, the US
players fed off the raucous fans.
</P>
<P>
   The European players later complained about the crowd's
behavior, particularly the heckling of Colin Montgomerie. ``Cheer
for your team all you want,'' said Jose Maria Olazabal, ``just show
respect for your opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the home-court _ or home-course _ advantage was
everywhere. One didn't need to look at the Jumbotron screens or the
scoreboards to learn how the matches were progressing. The crowd
said it all.
</P>
<P>
   A roar at four meant a Tom Lehman birdie, which put him 1 up and
on his way to a 3-and-2 victory over Lee Westwood; an explosion at
10 meant Phil Mickelson had gone 3 up in his match with Jarmo
Sandelin. And on and on it went.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly it built, and the players fed off the cheers, as
evidenced by Lehman doing his best Hale Irwin imitation circling
the 13th green and pumping his fist in triumph after a birdie put
him 4 up with five holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew every time I approached the green and pulled my hat off
it would turn the volume up,'' said Steve Pate, who beat Miguel
Angel Jimenez, 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   The outbursts hit their apex when Justin Leonard made his
45-foot birdie putt on 17 against Olazabal, which put the Americans
on the brink of victory. When Olazabal missed his 20-foot birdie
try, the comeback was complete.
</P>
<P>
   And then the celebrations really began, creating some remarkable
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, the favorite foil of American golf fans who played
so well all weekend, suffered the ultimate indignity of having to
walk up the 18th fairway through a gallery chanting ``USA, USA'' as
he finished his meaningless match with Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The American team streamed onto the 17th green to congratulate
Leonard after his miracle putt, angering Olazabal, who had to
regroup before his birdie try that would have kept the Europeans'
hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the staid courtyard in front of The Country Club
clubhouse had turned into a love fest. People streamed across the
once well-manicured grounds, waving American flags, chanting ``USA,
USA.'' The American team turned the side balcony into a frat house,
spraying each other and the crowd with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The record books will give the US team the victory, but Sunday's
crowd merits at least a footnote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
