<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-EXPOS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves still beast of the East
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ They hadn't even cleared the field, most of the
Braves still trundling up a tunnel to the clubhouse when the news
flashed in from Philadelphia. The Mets had lost again. A troubling
but resilient division race had reached a conclusion. Really?
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves won their eighth consecutive division title
Sunday. Just when the year was supposed to get interesting, the
team gave the NL East the back of its hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``In six days, we gained six games,'' said manager Bobby Cox.
``That's impossible, you think. But it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a minute of the conclusion of the Braves' 10-0 win over
Montreal, the Mets' 3-2 loss in Philadelphia clinched it. Eddie
Perez produced his second four-RBI game of the year and John
Smoltz, winless for the past 4 1/2 weeks, threw his most dominant
game of the season (eight scoreless innings on six hits). It didn't
seem possible but that's how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't think we could do it here,'' first baseman
Ryan Klesko said. ``They gotta lose three and we gotta win three to
clinch here. I thought we'd have to win one or two in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Not now. This week's three-game series with the Mets becomes a
non-issue, save for the New York cry for Mets manager Bobby
Valentine's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we couldn't shake the Mets all year,'' said second
baseman Bret Boone. ``Then we have that series with them (last
week's three-game sweep) and we come up as big as we can. I mean,
you couldn't write a better script.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos were gone before they knew it, the Braves twice
loading the bases in the first inning for a Brian Jordan two-run
single and Perez's base-clearing double that provided a 5-0 lead
seven at-bats into the day. Perez became the latest metaphor for
this year's club, a second-line player asked to produce in the
place of an injured star (Javy Lopez).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't paying too much attention to what was going on with
the division,'' Perez said. ``So before the game, Bobby (Cox) told
me I needed to get a big hit today so we can clinch. I mean, what
are you talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   With their seventh consecutive win, the Braves hold the year's
biggest divisional lead at seven games over New York. Long before
the 10 cases of champagne were exhausted, the club had to pause to
reconsider the loss of four front-line players and just what it had
gone through the previous seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means so much because of what we went through in the course
of the year,'' third baseman Chipper Jones said. ``I don't know of
any other team that could take the hits we took and be able to be
standing here in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
