<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-COLLINS-COL     09-26 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARNIVAL ON CLYDE STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ She will tell her grandchildren about the
rumble in a jungle called The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   So will a jubilant swarm of golfing bugs who surged across the
rumpled, sun-strewn acreage like locusts Sunday, partaking of the
moveable shotmaking feast.
</P>
<P>
   She is among them _ the more than 30,000 wanna-see's.
Resourceful Ruth Lyne, slim and chic with flowers in her straw hat,
towers tip-toe above the roped-in multitude on her portable
grandstand. She is clapping for a United States triumph that seemed
very remote 24 hours before. Her grandstand is a gray plastic milk
carton that she lugs from hole to hole, making her a face above the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gramma . . . what happened then?'' the tykes will someday
clamor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin Leonard . . . '' she will go on, ``Justin Leonard made
the damndest putt _ a 45-footer _ on the 17th, and for the
Americans it was, `Come back home, guys . . . all is forgiven.''
Comeback was the day's word, all right. A counter-punching comeback
as it had been in the original ``Rumble in the Jungle'' in Zaire a
quarter-century ago. Then Muhammad Ali, belting George Foreman as
though he had 1-irons in his gloves, regained his world.
</P>
<P>
   And Ruth Lyne, a local lady, was glad to be a Ryder Cup witness.
Doubly glad for her milk crate that may have been a designer model.
Instead of Ralph Lauren, however, it was labeled ``Guida's Dairy,
New Britain, Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our houseguest, Wally Schwind from Fairfield, Conn., brought
it as a present,'' Lyne says. Much more thoughtful than candy or
flowers. Definitely more useful as the golf-watcher's friend. It is
the dearest of gifts now _ even historic _ because of what it
enabled her to behold. She hasn't decided whether to hang it from
the living room ceiling as the Spirit of St. Louis is displayed at
the Smithsonian, or send it to the golfing Hall of Fame at St.
Augustine, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture experts say she should keep it in the family at least
until 2049 because milk crates are certified as valued antiques at
age 50.
</P>
<P>
   Where did the donor, Schwind, get the treasured pedestal?
</P>
<P>
   All he will say is that it fell off a truck.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to the Europeans. They fell off the truck
in blowing their 10-6 lead, something like Thomas Dewey squandered
his lead in the 1948 Presidential race to Harry Truman.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Lyne's crate was but one of many elevational props on a day
when never had so many spent so much time seeing so little.
</P>
<P>
   It seems dumb luck to happen onto a hole where something
wonderful is happening _ and you have a clear look at it. The
cheering, at a minimum Friday and Saturday, resounds across the
course like express trains, signifying the US recovery _ always
over there somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   As Sunday commenced it looked as if there could be a revival of
a book by sometimes-Bostonian Henry James called ``The Europeans.''
But, for the tourists, the day turned into the dead end of the
suspense novel by Brooklynite Stanley Ellen: ``House of Cards.''
</P>
<P>
   The first chapter of the horror story was written in the blood
of France's Jean Van de Velde. A bygone Frenchman, a pal of George
Washington, the Marquis of Lafayette, came to this country to help
Americans. Van de Velde did so, too, reluctantly, losing to Davis
Love, 6 and 5. The cards, bad ones, began falling for the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   It became to-halve or halve-not, and the holiest grail called
the Ryder Cup was won and lost by a half-point. By 4:19 of a
glorious last-taste-of-summer afternoon, the struggle is over.
</P>
<P>
   The Carnival on Clyde Street (become Carnage on Clyde for the
Cup defenders) has wound down, although celebration will continue
into the moonlit night. Prince Andrew, come to cheer Europe, was
whisked off in a Rolls-with- police-escort in the direction of his
dysfunctional family. His misfunctional team has vanished,
presumably wandering the dark and deserted greens to study putting.
</P>
<P>
   But an Englishwoman named June Gregory with small blue,
gold-starred flags of the European Community in her hair, sits on
the grass near the 18th hole, not anxious to leave. She is from
Sheffield. Smiling, she says, ``It was such a marvelous,
entertaining time.'' Amen to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
