<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSNOTES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN JOINS MATADORS STAFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Barbara Jordan had her heart broken two weeks ago
when she found out she didn't make the U.S. national softball team
that will play in the Olympics next summer in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan, from Agoura, realized a different goal last week
when she was hired as an assistant softball coach at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream was to make the Olympic team,'' Jordan said, ``and my
other dream was to coach softball at CSUN. It's always been
something I hoped to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years after they were classmates at Granada Hills High
and teammates on the Highlanders basketball team, Jordan has been
reunited with Matadors head coach Janet Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 33, went on to become an all-conference outfielder at
CSUN, and Sherman went to UCLA and was the Bruins' starting
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go way back,'' Sherman said of her friendship with Jordan.
``Her knowledge of the game is unbelievable. I know I have a lot to
learn from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan coached at Westlake last year, guiding the Warriors in
the Southern Section playoffs despite missing a portion of the
season for national-team tryouts. A national-team alternate for the
'96 Summer Games in Atlanta, Jordan was one of 38 finalists for the
final 15 spots this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had visualized playing in the Olympics,'' Jordan said. ``I
had a good tryout; I was pretty confident. I'm proud of myself for
giving it everything I had. It's just a bitter pill to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is the Matadors' outfield coach and recruiting
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   __ Swift kick: Even though she didn't think she could play
outside hitter in college, Hedder Illustre is doing everything she
can to prove the women's volleyball coaching staff right in playing
her there.
</P>
<P>
   Illustre, a 5-7 freshman from Carson, is leading the team in
digs and is third in kills. She had 30 digs at Northern Arizona on
Sept. 16, tying her for third on the school's all-time, single-game
chart for four-game matches. ``I didn't think I'd be strong enough
to play outside,'' said Illustre, who had a career-high 23 kills
against Idaho State on Sept. 18. ``In club (volleyball), I never
played front row.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though she's not as tall as her opponents, who rarely stand
under 6-feet, Illustre has imagination. She tried to preserve a
rally last week against Portland State by kicking the ball. She
didn't just stab at the ball, though; she took a full kick.
</P>
<P>
   The move is legal but rarely done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aggressive,'' Illustre said. ``I really hate losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Illustre is proving a worthy successor at outside hitter to
Kristen Sigal, a three-year starter who left the program after
leading the Matadors in digs last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought so highly of (Sigal),'' Illustre said. ``She
was good. (But my teammates) are really supportive of me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Big catch: The women's basketball team landed a top-notch
transfer in former Palmdale High standout Kristi Rose, a 6-4 center
and two-year starter at Utah who was selected to the All-Western
Athletic Conference's defensive team last year.
</P>
<P>
   As a Division I player transferring to another Division I
school, Rose must sit out this year. She will be eligible to play
for the Matadors as a senior for the 2000-01 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was fifth in the WAC in blocks in '98, averaging 1.3 per
game. She was second on the team in scoring (7.5 points per game)
and rebounding (4.8).
</P>
<P>
   Rose is the second former Daily News All-Star basketball player
to transfer to CSUN this year. John Burrell, who averaged 30 points
per game as a senior for Highland in 1995-96, came to CSUN from
Nevada in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   __ Comings and goings: The baseball team gained two commitments
last week: Jon Voita, a catcher-infielder at El Camino Real, and
Bill Wright, an all-league third baseman at Bakersfield's Garces
High.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who are in the third year of a rebuilding process
after the program was cut in the summer of '97, have new faces on
head coach Mike Batesole's staff. Steve Gossett, a former college
teammate of Batesole's at Oral Roberts, is the new pitching coach,
replacing Jamie Nelson, who resigned in July to pursue a
minor-league coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Another new coach is Kevin Patrick, who was the Matadors'
starting second baseman the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   __ Watch out: The cross country course at Fresno's Woodward Park
is known as one of the most challenging in the state. But some
members of the women's cross country team probably never thought of
it as dangerous _ until Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were running the course, preparing for the Fresno
State Invitational, when a mountain biker rode right into their
pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He struck Francis Santin head-on and four or five others were
diving into ditches,'' head coach Don Strametz said. ``The girls
were black and blue all over. He stopped and asked, `Are you OK?'
and then that's the last they saw of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors finished fourth the next day. Jennifer Smith was
fourth in the individual standings with a time of 18 minutes, 32
second over the 5,000 kilometer course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
