<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-YEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AN ABOUT-FACE, OFFICIAL HINTS THAT JAPAN WILL MOVE TO BOLSTER
YEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of the Bank of Japan strongly hinted
Sunday that he was prepared to reverse course and act to halt a
three-month-long rise in the value of the Japanese yen, before it
chokes off Japan's fragile economic recovery and triggers further
clashes with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In early trading in Australia and Asia, the vaguely worded
announcement from Masaru Hayami, governor of the Bank of Japan, and
a communique issued Saturday night by the finance ministers of the
Group of Seven largest industrialized nations proved enough to
strengthen the dollar and weaken the yen.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m. Sunday evening, the dollar was trading at 105.57-62
yen, up 104.09 at Friday's close in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although he denied he was changing course, Hayami's statement
appeared to mark a full retreat from the position the bank took
less than a week ago, when it defied Japanese politicians and
Washington by refusing to stop the 17 percent rise in the yen's
value.
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes struggle over Japan's monetary policy
dominated the opening this weekend of the annual meetings of the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, which are also
focusing on corruption in Russia. Sunday, a new arrangement was
also struck to revalue 14 million ounces of the IMF's gold reserves
to pay off some of the debts of the world's poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
   Hayami's comments Sunday are also important because Wall Street
reacted badly to last week's moves by the Bank of Japan. Investors
feared that more expensive Japanese goods could help trigger
inflation in the United States, as consumers pay more for Toyotas
and Sony electronics, among other goods. That, in turn, could
convince the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates, slowing the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the future of the American stock markets seemed
increasingly dependent on the decisions of Japan's central bank, an
institution that operates by its own rules and market rationale.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision announced late Sunday, the fund said that the 14
million ounces from its gold reserves would not be sold on the open
market as originally planned _ a move that drew strong objections
from lawmakers in gold-producing parts of the United States and
from countries like South Africa. Instead, through bookkeeping
sleight-of-hand, the World War II-era gold is being revalued at
current prices, and used by the poor countries to repay their
loans.
</P>
<P>
   The G-7 ministers, in a statement Sunday night, put the onus on
Japan to solve the problems being triggered by the surprising
strength of the yen. Only if Japan acted to loosen further what the
bank already considers a dangerously loose monetary policy _
interest rates are already at zero in Japan _ would the other
countries consider stepping in and intervening in the currency
markets to weaken the yen, the statement suggested.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday, as traders went to work in Australia and Tokyo, they
were watching every utterance of Hayami, a man whose delphic
comments can make his American counterpart, Alan Greenspan, seem
like a beacon of clarity.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Hayami, still reveling in the new independence of the
Bank of Japan, said he would not adjust the country's monetary
policy simply to control foreign exchange rates. That, he said, is
how Japan got into trouble in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since those statements by Hayami, the yen had continued to
strengthen, making Japanese exports like cars and electronics more
expensive, and thus less competitive, on world markets. At a press
conference here Sunday afternoon, Hayami, speaking in Japanese,
said that he had been ``misunderstood'' by the markets and by major
governments around the world. ``Our policy of appropriate and
timely response to developments in the economy and financial
markets was not understood by the Group of Seven,'' he said. ``Now
they understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officials at the meetings say that it is Hayami who now
understands _ that the yen's rise could choke off the country's
recovery and thus hurt both Tokyo and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been the only real engine of economic
growth in the world in recent years, and the price it has paid is a
huge trade deficit, as it sucks in the rest of what the world
manufactures. Unless Japan recovers, the thinking goes, that
deficit will not be reduced by much.
</P>
<P>
   A weaker dollar and a stronger yen would, in ordinary times, be
good news for American exporters. But in this case, there are
doubts that Japanese consumers will stop saving and start buying
again unless they fear the onset of modest inflation _ exactly what
pumping more money into the economy could create.
</P>
<P>
   So the finance ministers meeting here on Saturday hammered out
language to try to create doubt in the minds of currency traders
over whether the yen would be allowed to appreciate further. ``We
share Japan's concern about the potential impact of the yen's
appreciation for the Japanese economy and the world economy,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayami, who last week said that controlling foreign exchange
rates was ``not an aim of Bank of Japan monetary policy'' began to
suggest Sunday night that he was revising his view. He said the
central bank was ``very concerned about the effects of the strong
yen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, as Hayami seemed by turns to want to explain the bank's
new thinking and to insist nothing was changing, he issued a
statement saying that ``the bank is prepared to use the flexibility
it has in the context of the present monetary policy stance to
respond appropriately and timely to developments in the economy as
well as financial markets, including the foreign exchange market.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ``clarifying our position,'' adding that ``many
of us are rather old, like myself, so I simply used softer words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
