<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-KROLL-OGARA-TROUBLES-     09-26 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KROLL-OGARA-TROUBLES-ART-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLES AT KROLL-O'GARA ATTRIBUTED TO INFIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fast-growing company that posted record profits just two
months ago suddenly hits the skids, its share price tumbling by
almost half in a day. Rumors of intrigue abound. Shareholders want
to know what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a job for Kroll-O'Gara, the United States' leading
corporate gumshoe. Only in this case, the company in question is
Kroll-O'Gara. And the reason appears to be fighting in the
executive suite.
</P>
<P>
   With stealth befitting his reputation as America's No. 1 private
detective, Jules Kroll, Kroll-O'Gara's chairman and chief
executive, has lined up several potential ``white knight''
investors who he expects will help him remove Thomas O'Gara, the
vice chairman, from the company, according to people close to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Kroll said late last week that it had hired Bear, Stearns to
explore strategic options, including a possible sale. People close
to the company said that Kroll had found suitors who have offered
to buy the stake held by O'Gara, who has been frozen out of
management decisions since he and Kroll fought over control last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty has been bad for Kroll's once high-flying stock.
The price, which has been slipping all year from a January high of
$41.375, collapsed on Friday, falling $11.50, or 45 percent, to
close at $14.3125. The plunge followed an announcement that the
company would fall far short of third-quarter earnings estimates,
at least in part because it will delay new acquisitions while
weighing overtures from outside investors.
</P>
<P>
   The delay has temporarily derailed what had been a growth
strategy based on a steady stream of acquisitions as Kroll-O'Gara
bought a dozen security and investigative companies in recent
months. But some analysts also complained that the company had not
been forthcoming about its earnings shortfall or about the
continuing animosity between its two top executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an element of surprise here. People thought that this
was a company with a good acquisition strategy and strong growth,''
said Thomas O'Halloran, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read. ``Then
we find out that they will miss earnings by 40 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Halloran slashed his recommendation on the stock to ``hold''
from ``strong buy'' on Friday, which helped prompt the selloff. He
said he suspected that the company was having trouble integrating
some security businesses it had bought in recent months. And he
said the fact that the top bosses were not talking to each other
complicated matters.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to comment on the development while
negotiations are under way for a possible sale. But several people
close to the company said they felt that Kroll's core business was
healthy and that final resolution of the conflict between Kroll and
O'Gara was not far off.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The combination of Kroll and O'Gara seemed promising in the
early days _ less than two years ago. O'Gara Co., an Ohio-based
armored-car maker, bought Kroll Associates, a New York-based
private investigation company, in December 1997 for $101.3 million
in stock. Kroll and O'Gara struck up a close relationship, people
close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Though O'Gara, which was a public company, bought Kroll, which
had been closely held, O'Gara ceded the posts of chairman and chief
executive to Kroll. O'Gara's brother, Wilfred O'Gara, became the
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The combination got off to a fast start. An avid schmoozer who
cultivates relationships with corporate tycoons in the United
States, Europe and Asia, Kroll had long dreamed of making his
private-investigation practice into a global, one-stop center for
all kinds of corporate security. Kidnappings, terrorism and
assassinations abroad were good for business _ as was the wave of
mergers in Europe and the United States prompting companies to seek
information about a potential partner or rival.
</P>
<P>
   As a public company, Kroll-O'Gara now had stock as an
acquisition currency. The company branched out into employee drug
screening, the manufacture of surveillance cameras and accounting
services. It picked up affiliates in Hong Kong and Argentina.
Earnings grew fast and the stock soared through much of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, however, Thomas O'Gara and Kroll had a
falling out. People close to the company said they had disagreed on
the price and the timing of the company's biggest purchase to date,
of Securify Inc., a start-up specializing in Internet security that
is based in Mountain View, Calif. O'Gara pushed to get the deal
done immediately. Kroll wanted to delay the acquisition until
completion of another purchase that was less expensive and would
add to earnings sooner, people close to Kroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Kroll did buy Securify in early February for stock valued by the
company at $55.2 million. But the conflict between Kroll and O'Gara
only worsened. O'Gara and Kroll units had not integrated very well.
Half the company was run out of O'Gara's old headquarters in
Fairfield, Ohio, the other half from Kroll's offices in New York.
Kroll, who colleagues say is sometimes short-tempered and
suspicious, froze O'Gara out of decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, O'Gara pressed the company's board of directors
to dismiss Kroll. But the board voted to support Kroll instead.
Though the company subsequently sent signals that analysts
interpreted as meaning that the tension had eased, Kroll had
decided to rid the company of the O'Garas, people close to the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Kroll hired Bear, Stearns to help him find an investor
that would buy out the O'Gara stake and allow him to run the firm
himself, these people said. The decision to hire Bear, Stearns was
not disclosed publicly until last week, at the same time the
company said it would miss earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a buyer took longer than Kroll had hoped, these people
said. One person briefed on the effort said Kroll had tried to
persuade Securitas, the Swedish security company that owns
Pinkerton, a rival of Kroll, to make a bid. It was unclear if it
had done so.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential investors include large accounting firms that
are looking to bolster their investigative units. People close to
Kroll also held out the possibility that a large private investor
might step in, replacing the O'Garas and leaving Kroll to run the
firm with a fresh infusion of capital.
</P>
<P>
   But with the company seeking investors, Kroll delayed making new
acquisitions, including several that were close to completion and
would have added to earnings immediately, people close to the
company said. With the end of the third quarter approaching and no
instant remedy in sight, the company had no choice but to warn that
earnings would fall short.
</P>
<P>
   O'Halloran, the Warburg Dillon Read analyst, said that even with
the turmoil at the company, he expected that any purchaser of Kroll
would have to pay between $19 and $24 a share, well above Friday's
closing price. ``It was probably overdone,'' he said of the
selloff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
