<HEADER>
A6746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PRIMEDIA-MULTIMEDIA-A     09-26 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMEDIA-MULTIMEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMEDIA SET TO APPOINT NBC VETERAN AS ITS CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  and  photo  are being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Exclusive) 
(nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that signals the magazine industry's growing
recognition of the potential vitality of multimedia, Thomas Rogers,
the president of NBC cable who expanded the NBC network into the
cable and Internet markets, will be named chief executive of
Primedia Inc. on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time that one of the major magazine publishing
companies has hired a chief executive with an extensive Internet
resume.
</P>
<P>
   Primedia owns more than 200 publishing properties _ from New
York and Seventeen magazines to highly specialized publications
like National Hog Farmer and Fire Chief _ and video businesses,
including Channel One, the television news channel provided to 8
million students at 12,000 high schools in the United States. In
1998, the company had sales of $1.5 billion and earnings of $330
million. The leveraged buyout firm of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts _
headed by Henry R. Kravis, the founding partner _ controls just
under 80 percent of Primedia's stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, what is really needed for us is to become a
full-service media company,'' Kravis said. ``That means not just
print, not just television, not just the Internet, but we need to
take the assets that we have and really go into the new
technologies. Tom brings to Primedia the leadership capability that
is so important, and the respect of the media world that comes from
founding CNBC and MSNBC.''
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders in the magazine industry like Time Inc., Hearst
Magazines, Hachette Filipacchi and Conde Nast, have tried to figure
out the way to translate a magazine's assets onto the Internet;
none have done so with any great success.
</P>
<P>
   At NBC, Rogers became a strong advocate for new media, even
ruffling some feathers in the network's executive suites. He made
the company less dependent on income from the network alone.
Rogers, who began his career as legal counsel to the House of
Representatives subcommittee on telecommunications, headed NBC's
move into the cable television by founding CNBC and later MSNBC, in
cooperation with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   William F. Reilly, the former chairman and chief executive of
Primedia, announced his resignation in July and left earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, Rogers engineered several low-cost deals
in which NBC bought stakes in Internet start-ups. Last year, he
joined NBC with Cnet, acquiring a piece of Cnet's Snap navigation
hub with an option to expand ownership to 60 percent. Two weeks
ago, Rogers oversaw NBC's acquisition of 32 percent of Paxson
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   In his new post, Rogers said his goal was to transform Primedia
from a magazine concern with little Internet exposure into a
magazine company with a big Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   In Standard and Poor's annual publishing survey for 1998,
Primedia was ranked as the sixth-largest magazine company in terms
of magazine revenue, behind Time Inc., Hearst Magazines, Advance
Publications (owner of Conde Nast), Reed Elsevier and the Thomson
Corp. But despite its ranking, Rogers said, Primedia was ``not that
well-known a company.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``This is a collection of terrific assets, assets that
in their existing sectors perform very nicely. But they have an
enormous amount of untapped potential as new-media properties. If
we can figure out how they relate to the new-media businesses _ by
that I mean the Internet or video or digital convergence _ over
time we can create a highly integrated company which can, I think,
be a real leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said the natural appeal of Primedia's magazines to
Internet users was their highly focused nature. American Baby,
Modern Bride, Automobile and the Primedia guides like New Home
Guides and Apartment Guides, ``all address central turning points
in life: getting married, buying a car, having a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he plans to develop the company's
business-to-business Internet sites as well as its electronic
commerce division. ``E-commerce is the golden goose of the
Internet,'' he said. ``It's not just about advertising and
subscriber revenue. We need consumers to look to the Internet as a
place for goods and services and rely on it in a day-to-day way
that supplants all kinds of brick-and-mortar approaches.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mark Mooradian, senior analyst for Jupiter Communications, said:
``All of the major magazine companies seem to have taken a wrong
turn down the `we're going to establish a major portal site'
strategy. Time did it with Pathfinder. Hearst did it with Home
Arts.'' He added, ``Primedia hasn't done much of anything. The
great growth opportunity is to get the vertical category that is
your expertise and own that, create commerce on it and sell highly
targeted advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Wolf, a media analyst and senior partner at Booz,
Allen &AMP; Hamilton, said Primedia's highly focused nature made it a
natural for expansion into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look across the major magazine groups, they are still
really in their infancy in developing these Web businesses,'' Wolf
said, though he had praise for Time and Hearst, which has
affiliations with popular sites like Women.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primedia has a more natural audience for some of their Web
sites because many of their publications are enthusiast magazines,
which have a natural constituency. If you're hog farmer, you want
your latest hog news, and you're willing to pay for it,'' Wolf
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he had no immediate plans for changes at any of the
Primedia magazines. ``I am not an expert on New York magazine,'' he
said. ``But as a general matter, I want to see all the Primedia
properties grow. I think some of the consumer franchises _ and New
York magazine has a strong consumer franchise _ each have different
ways to tap into that. Seventeen magazine is well suited for the
hot teen demo, which everyone is clamoring for. Automobile
magazine, well, obviously buying cars on the Internet has become an
enormous industry at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Editors and creative people at magazines like New York need
and deserve an awful lot of latitude in terms of what's going on in
the market and how to respond to it,'' he continued. ``I hope to
say to them, ``Here are new ways to take your creativity and take
it out onto the marketplace and expand your franchise even more.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
