<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-SHOESALES-NY     09-26 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SHOESALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIKE, LONG WARY OF E-MARKETERS, LINKS UP WITH FOGDOG
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
(nk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nike Inc., which has consistently blocked Web-only stores from
selling its goods, has reversed its stand and will let Fogdog
Sports, an online sporting goods dealer, sell the full Nike product
line.
</P>
<P>
   But Nike extracted a high price for the right to buy its shoes:
Warrants to acquire 12 percent of Fogdog's shares.
</P>
<P>
   Nike is the first of the big athletic shoemakers to forge a pact
with a retailer that sells goods only on the Web. And its
imprimatur may cast a favorable light on Fogdog, a 3-year-old
company with less than $10 million in annual sales. Fogdog, based
in Redwood City, Calif., filed for a public stock offering on
Friday just as the Nike deal was closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nike is the 800-pound gorilla in the industry,'' said Timothy
Harrington, Fogdog's chief executive. He said that the company's
growth had been slowed because, until now, the only Nike goods it
had been able to offer had come from other retailer's overstocks
and other unofficial channels.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fogdog hopes it can recoup the cost of the deal from
consumers _ who will find a broader selection _ and more
importantly from investors, who may see the Nike swoosh logo as an
indicator of the potential of Fogdog's stock.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time an Internet start-up has given away
stock to a supplier in order to validate its business model. Before
going public early this year, Priceline.com, the
offer-your-own-price shopping site, gave warrants for about 10
percent of the company's shares to Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   The sporting goods category, which has been slow to develop on
the Internet, has seen a flurry of activity this year. Most notably
a small Philadelphia company called Global Sports arranged to
create online stores for a half-dozen large sporting goods
retailers, including Sports Authority, Athlete's Foot and Sports
Chalet.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rubin, the chief executive of Global Sports, said he
thought Fogdog's strategy was flawed and risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never in a million years give any stock in my company
to a manufacturer,'' he said. ``What will they say when Reebok and
New Balance come and say, `What percentage do we get?'''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said Nike was the only manufacturer that will get
such a deal. ``Nike is the only company with double-digit market
share,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now all of the big footwear brands declined to sell their
wares to Internet stores. Their position was similar to the
rationale of other manufacturers with high-end brands, including
Sony and Ralph Lauren, that had not wanted to risk diluting the
value of their brands by distributing them through inexperienced
entrepreneurs using untested technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a lot of online retailers who were not putting the
right emphasis on product presentation,'' said Mary Kate Buckley,
the Nike vice president who looks after its Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Nike thought that it would have to limit the
number of online retailers much more tightly than it did for local
stores. And so the company wanted to choose Web dealers carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bricks-and-mortar partners offer a convenient location
where customers can feel the product quality and try products on,''
she said. ``When you move to the Web, you present products in two
dimensions, take away the local convenience. So we were concerned
that over time if everyone is selling the same thing online, the
only difference would be price.''
</P>
<P>
   So Nike moved slowly, first by allowing some of the larger
chains of bricks-and-mortar sporting goods stores _ like Venator
Group's Foot Locker and Copeland Sports, a California chain _ to
sell Nike products on their Web sites. But even this was tentative.
Nike recently stopped selling to Copeland's Shopsports.Com.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not meeting our marketing standards,'' Ms. Buckley
said, declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Nike started selling about half of its various shoe
models and 20 percent of the rest of its products directly to
consumers through the Nike.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, when Fogdog came back to Nike with another of its
steady stream of requests to distribute the Nike line, Nike was
intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   Fogdog said it would maintain its policy of not discounting
products below the manufacturers' suggested minimums. Moreover,
Nike judged that Fogdog was becoming the leading online company in
the category.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were showing us business plans, but Fogdog was
out there executing for three years,'' Ms. Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   And Fogdog offered Nike a portion of its stock just before the
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Nike agreed to give Fogdog the support it gave to big
chains, including preferred prices, technical information, joint
marketing and other promotions. Nike will continue to expand its
own sales effort through Nike.com, but it agreed not to sell to any
other pure Internet company, including all of sites being developed
by Global Sports, for at least six months.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin of Global Sports said he believed that Nike would soon
choose to support his venture, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our six partners are all among Nike's top 20 accounts,'' he
said. ``Nike needs to support them, and they need to be on the
Internet in order to survive in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buckley acknowledged that this arrangement was sure to cause
some consternation among Nike's other retailers. But she predicted
that it would ultimately be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a big commitment to sporting goods
retailing,'' she said. ``The sporting goods industry has been slow
to adapt to the Web. This will be a jump-start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
