<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin cruises to victory at Dover
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ Mark Martin hasn't got time for the pain,
especially when he is winning a race.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is suffering from two degenerating disks and has
scheduled off-season back surgery, cruised to an easy victory in
Sunday's MBNA Gold 400 at Dover Downs International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   It was Martin's third consecutive victory in the fall Dover race
and second of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling no pain right now,'' Martin said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie sensation Tony Stewart continued his hot streak as the
runner-up, followed by Winston Cups points leader Dale Jarrett and
promising rookie Matt Kenseth. Stewart has reeled off back-to-back
finishes in second place after winning at Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   For Martin, Sunday's ride down victory lane allowed him to pass
Bobby Labonte for second in the point standings. Jarrett has built
a seemingly insurmountable 257-point advantage with seven races
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one more down, we're counting them off,'' Jarrett said.
``We just have to keep having these type of days. It'd be nice to
win, but if we don't and can get top fives we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's long-time back problem, which he recently termed as
``intolerable,'' has been only one of several miseries for the Ford
No. 6 driver this past summer. He lost an uncle and close friend in
recent months, and is still mourning over the death of his father
last year. Martin also broke several bones in a Daytona wreck
during practice on July 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a bad day, (all those things) bother me, like after
Richmond (35th finish) and New Hampshire (17th),'' Martin said.
``But on a good day, it's not so bad. Everybody has tests in their
life and my life has been awfully good. So just the last 12 months
have been a little more of test for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin plans to have surgery Nov. 22, the day after the
season-ending NAPA 500 in Atlanta. Martin canceled the operation at
the last minute during the previous off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scheduled, I might chicken out (again) but I sure need it
and I can't wait until I end my racing career to do it,'' Martin
said. ``It's unfortunate with the recovery time that it pushes me
right into Daytona (opening racing for 2000 season).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be tough, but it needs to be done for me to face
the great years I have left in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's other victory this year was also at Dover Downs,
capturing the MBNA Platinum 400 on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how bad I wanted to win (Sunday's race),''
Martin said. ``We have run well this summer, but we haven't been a
contender to win ... I haven't felt like I could take a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
