<HEADER>
A6760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-RAMS27-CO     09-26 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-RAMS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons face third loss in match against Rams
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Joe Namath returned to the NFL Sunday, wearing a
Rams uniform with the name of Kurt Warner on his back.
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time _ he had plenty _ the St. Louis quarterback
helped dig a deep hole for the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was Warner, doing his best Namath impersonation,
who led the Rams (2-0) to a 35-7 blowout of Atlanta. He passed for
three touchdowns, ran for one and bragged about it afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Warner wasn't the only imposter at the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are 0-3 and bear no resemblance to the team that
went 16-3 last year on the way to Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Already playing without running back Jamal Anderson, who is out
for the season with a torn right anterior cruciate knee ligament,
and wideout Tim Dwight, who pulled his hamstring during warm-ups,
the Falcons also lost quarterback Chris Chandler, who left with
3:13 left in the second quarter with a reinjured hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were behind 28-0 when Chandler exited, after the
Rams scored on their first four possessions and outgained Atlanta
311-67 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   That warm fuzzy team chemistry thing is taking a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we decide to come together as a team, the better we are
going to be,'' wide receiver Terance Mathis said. ``Once people
realize, again, it's us against the world like last year _ when we
didn't worry about anything or anybody but each other _ it's going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, it looked like 11 Falcons against the world, and the
world won.
</P>
<P>
   Warner wasn't sacked all day and rarely was pressured while
triggering an opening drive that went 80 yards in 17 plays that
took 10:13.
</P>
<P>
   Then the defense, the only salvation in opening losses to
Minnesota and Dallas, joined the caravan south. St. Louis had 442
yards and converted 10-of-14 third downs. Warner threw touchdown
passes of 38, 46, and 17 yards _ all in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graziani (14-of-22, 152 yards, first career touchdown pass,
no interceptions) played well in relief of Chandler, putting
together a 99.1 passer rating. It didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   This does: While getting ready for a home game against
Baltimore, the Falcons face long odds in trying to join the 1998
Bills, the '95 Lions, the '92 Chargers, the '82 Bucs, and the '81
Jets as teams that began the season 0-3 yet made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had all the answers, we wouldn't be 0-3,'' said coach Dan
Reeves, who was even-mannered in defeat. ``There's a lot of things
happening right now, and when you play poorly, that magnifies
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
