<HEADER>
A6761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER27-COX     09-26 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. retakes Ryder Cup with historic last-day rally
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ OK, pay them whatever they want. Put the
checks in the mail and don't spare the zeroes.
</P>
<P>
   And throw in a cash bonus for Justin Leonard, whose 45-foot putt
on the 17th hole at The Country Club on Sunday completed the
grandest comeback in Ryder Cup history. The United State defeated
Europe 14 1/2-13 1/2 with a performance that defied everything
logical about match play and its unyielding pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Accused of being fragmented by a play-for-pay issue last month,
the U.S. team came out Sunday and proved everyone wrong. Maybe the
next move should be the PGA of America's. If they can play this way
just for pride, imagine what they might do for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all happened like a dream,'' said Ben Crenshaw, the U.S.
captain. ``It's indescribable. It transcends any monetary value.
You play with your heart and your soul and brain. These are 12 of
the greatest guys I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Tiger Woods said. ``A dream come true.
They came out with courage and guts and got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all believed it last night,'' said Hal Sutton, referring to
a U.S. team meeting Saturday night, when it was behind 10-6. ``We
all cried in the room. This was a family. This was a team. This was
history being made today. This is the greatest moment in golf right
now, and I'm just happy to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben kept saying, `We can do this. I've got a good feeling
about it,''' said Davis Love III. ``I kept thinking, `Golly, I hope
this doesn't come back to haunt him.'''
</P>
<P>
   The ending scene resembled one from a Braves locker room in the
early 1990s. Crenshaw's silver hair was soaked in champagne foam.
David Duval went on a hug rampage. On the roof of The Country Club,
American players retreating from the chaos sprayed the bubbly down
below. Heavily favored because of their domination in the world
rankings but on the verge of another loss to Europe, the Yanks were
acting as though a lottery had been won.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in as massive underdogs,'' Scotland's Colin
Montgomerie said, ``and we gave America a hell of a fright.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a total love fest. The Europeans expressed anger about
the general fan conduct in the gallery and the Americans' premature
celebration at the 17th green, after Leonard's putt triggered
hysteria among his charging teammates. Europe's Jose Maria
Olazabal, who could have halved the hole with a matching birdie,
``called it very sad to see'' and an ``ugly picture.'' United
States players and Crenshaw apologized for the celebration, but did
not feel it affected the outcome of the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the controversy was, except that we were
enjoying it and they weren't,'' Leonard said. ``I don't think
anyone stepped in Jose's line.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger story, of course, was the U.S. comeback. As
impressive as the lopsided first six victories _ by Tom Lehman (3
and 2 over Lee Westwood); Sutton (4 and 2 over Darren Clarke); Phil
Mickelson (4 and 3 over Jarmo Sandelin), Love (6 and 5 over Jean
Van de Velde); Woods (3 and 2 over Andrew Coltart) and Duval (5 and
4 over Jesper Parnevik) _ the unexpected plays came later. Mark
O'Meara's loss to Padraig Harrington was negated by Steve Pate's
victory against Miguel Angel Jimenez. Jeff Maggert's loss to Paul
Lawrie was negated by Jim Furyk's upset 4 and 3 victory against
rookie sensation Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   With eight points earned from singles, crunch time came down to
the Olazabal-Leonard and Montgomerie's-Payne Stewart matches. The
U.S. needed only to halve one of them and nearly clinched it when
Leonard, so ineffective in team play and 4-down to Olazabal after
11 holes, sank the uphill 45-footer from the front of the 17th
green. The half-point materialized when Olazabal missed from 25
feet. Montgomerie won when it no longer counted, on a conceded
birdie putt from Stewart, who spared the heckled Scot another time
over the ball.
</P>
<P>
   No Ryder Cup team from either side had ever trailed by four
points going into singles and won. No American team had ever
trailed on U.S. soil after two days and won.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody's laughing at Crenshaw any longer. While every sane
soul in Massachusetts figured a third straight European victory was
in the books, Crenshaw, who had managed a second Masters victory
through some divine guidance in 1995, said fate would take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned,'' said Crenshaw, who had kissed the ground of the
place where he competed as a junior player in 1968. ``I'll tell
you, it's in the trees _ it's fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain to be criticized for not playing Coltart, Van de Velde
or Sandelin until singles and watching them be thumped, European
captain Mark James said, ``I think we were outplayed. I don't think
we were outmaneuvered. That's what you've got to do in this game,
ride the streak, and they rode the streak all too well today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
