<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-GARCIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWD FAVORITE GARCIA TAKES THE LOSS HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The dream run of Sergio Garcia at the Ryder
Cup got a rude awakening Sunday, but the 19-year-old phenom from
Spain kept his composure and didn't let a bad day stop him from
having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he was three down to Jim Furyk and facing elimination,
Garcia continued to crack jokes, chat up his fans, and personally
acknowledge their cheers with a tip of the hat or a wink.
</P>
<P>
   Only after he was eliminated and waiting with his countrymen on
the 18th green for the final matches to conclude did he break down
in tears, the emotion of the stunning American turnaround finally
getting to him.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of stunning golf, racking up victory after
victory with partner Jesper Parnevik, Garcia's game deserted him
against Furyk. He struggled with accuracy from tee to green and
never seemed to get on track. Of the 15 holes he played, he hit
only eight in regulation, forcing him to scramble on the other
seven holes. He had only one birdie all day long.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th hole was typical of his tough day. He knocked his drive
far right into a patch of evergreen trees, ending up five inches
behind a huge tree root. Garcia sighed when he got to his ball and
ignored the laughter of some American fans, delighting in his
misfortune and daring him to make the same sort of miraculous tree
shot he made at the PGA Championship at Medinah, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no miracles on this day for Garcia. His only shot
was to take a wedge and chip the ball back into the fairway. He
still managed a bogey and succeeded in halving the hole when Furyk
hit his approach shot poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did Garcia lose his cool, on the par-4 13th. After a
solid drive, he hit his approach shot into the right bunker. Angry,
he then took another vicious swing with his club, taking a huge
divot out of the turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you, it was different without playing with
Jesper,'' he said. ``I just did my best. I felt maybe a little
tired when I was three down, but I was trying. I was trying all the
time to help my team.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates seemed to anoint him the European player of the
match. With partner Parnevik he won three matches and halved a
fourth. But he seemed to run out of gas _ and shots _ Sunday. The
slow, steady consistency of Furyk was just too much for him to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his amiable personality made him a crowd favorite.
Everywhere he went there were chants of ``Sergio,'' all of which
brought a smile to his face. And even meeting with the press after
the team's devastating loss, he was still cracking jokes and having
a good time with his buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of myself and all of the team. I think we did a
great job,'' he said. ``And once you play a Ryder Cup, you realize
how big this is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
