u s BC-GLF-RYDER-EUROPEANS-B     09-26 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-EUROPEANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS' BAD MANNERS PEEVE EUROPEAN PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Europe's Ryder Cup players, heralded for
their gregariousness, their ease in chatting with fans, and obvious
team spirit, exited The Country Club rankled by a lack of American
hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans were disgusted, first and foremost, by the
American squad's overzealous celebration on the green that erupted
when Justin Leonard drained a 45-foot putt on the 17th hole,
essentially clinching the championship. And, while commending most
of the 30,000-plus fans who ringed the course each day, the Euros
were peeved by a small but vocal group of hecklers, many of whom
targeted Colin Montgomerie for their nastiest insults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was very sad to see,'' said Spain's Jose Maria
Olazabal, referring specifically to the band of jumping US players
who hugged, guffawed, and otherwise held up his putt attempt after
Leonard's sensational putt. ``It was very ugly to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Even-tempered but firm in his remarks, Olazabal repeatedly
stated that he didn't want his words perceived as excuse making.
The celebration didn't lead to his missing the putt, he said,
emphasising over and over that the Americans played better and
deserved the victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the US team, said Olazabal, should have been more mindful of
golf etiquette and some fans should be ashamed by the words that
came out of their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheer for your team all you want,'' said Olazabal, who
frittered away a 4-up lead, ``just show respect for your
opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a news conference attended by the American squad, a
diplomatic Leonard apologized for the outburst and said he would
shoulder full responsibilty. He was caught up in the excitement of
the moment, he said, and wishes he had jumped up and down rather
than run to embrace the charging troupe of Yanks that included
players, wives, caddies, and hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   One reporter, in a question posed to Tom Lehman, said some
European members said Lehman should be embarrassed by his behavior
on 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never ill intent on anyone's part,'' said Lehman.
``In retrospect, I wish we all had jumped up and down in place
rather than on the side of the green. But I'm not going to
apologize for being excited.''
</P>
<P>
   European captain Mark James also said he didn't like the
outbreak on 17, but he also wasn't expecting, nor would he request,
an apolgoy from US captain Ben Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Ben was responsible for that behavior,'' said
James. ``So I wouldn't expect an apology from Ben. It's not
something I'm very concerned about. I agree with everthing Jose
said. ``And I'd like to think it wouldn't happen with my players.''
</P>
<P>
   Although not asked, Crenshaw quickly offered an apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something we are proud of,'' said Crenshaw, a man
whose sincerity during Ryder Cup week often led him to tears.
``We're sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, who was playing a hole behind the Olazabal-Leonard
match, caught glimpses of the celebration as he approached 17.
Later, as he came striding to the green, he said to TV commentator
David Flaherty, ``I don't know how you live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Montgomerie added, ``I couldn't believe what I was seeing
on the 17th.''
</P>
<P>
   European star Jesper Parnevik, who lives in Florida, was
disappointed by the taunts from the crowd Montgomerie was subjected
to during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the little American on the European tour. I live here,''
said Parnevik. ``It was embarrassing to hear all the heckling at
Monty. I understand Americans rooting for Americans, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart expressed similar distaste for the heckling.
``What's he got, a big bull's-eye on his back? He doesn't deserve
it. It's not golf.'' Some of that heckling, said Stewart, led to
some hecklers being ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Classy and calm, Olazabal said he raised his objection to the
outbreak on 17 because there will be another Ryder Cup in two
years, and many more to follow. He hopes the game's etiquette will
be preserved and the ugly heckling will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be to the benefit of golf, if they manage to behave
just a little bit better,'' he said. ``I understand in a way what
happened (on 17). They were carried by their emotions. At the same
time, it's not a nice situation for us. I'm not trying to find
excuses. I just think if we respect each other a little more, it
would be good for everyone. What I am trying to say is a simple
fact. I mean, what would you do or say, or what would an American
player do or say, if a European had done the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a simple matter of respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
