<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-CRENSHAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEARS SAY IT ALL FOR CRENSHAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Gentle Ben? Yes, as always. But also, it
turns out, Passionate Ben. And Inspirational Ben. And in full
public view Sunday, Choked Up Ben.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy ratified by victory, and his team all of a sudden
performing like a well-oiled, selfless machine, Captain Ben
Crenshaw found time Sunday to do in public what some of his team
members said he frequently did in private. He got all broken up. He
said, while casting his eyes heavenward, that fate had selected his
team for victory.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where leaders are urged to be emotionless lest they
fail, Crenshaw blubbered. He broke down on the 17th green after
Justin Leonard's historic putt. His voice quavered and tears
moistened his eyes as he stood behind the 18th green after the last
match ended.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he became so emotional that he said the fate that
had predetermined his team for victory might rest in the mighty oak
trees that overshadow The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative-appearing Texan, it turned out, is a '90s kind
of guy. As the victories rolled in, Crenshaw seemed to be hugging
everyone within reach.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the emotion so on display in the public
Crenshaw was often visible in private to the team he apparently
inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never gave us a rah-rah speech,'' his star pupil, Hal
Sutton, said. ``Everytime he spoke to us there was a quiver in his
voice. He kept saying, `I believe in you all.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But behind every successful emotional leader lies a clear-eyed,
clear-headed strategist. And Crenshaw had his. Despite all the
public notice to a team of pampered athletes who had little
understanding of, much less any use for, teamwork, Crenshaw
insisted the facts suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   His 12 players, he said _ matter-of-factly and not I-told-you-so
in tone _ had ``an indomitable spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not ever lose sight of what we were doing. They
believed in themselves,'' he said. And despite widespread sentiment
that his charges were ill-fitted for such a team event, he said it
was only the extraordinary quality of the European play that left
the US team at such a deficit entering the singles matches.
</P>
<P>
   His players, he said, ``believed in themselves. They knew how
close these matches were _ despite some fantastic play by the
European team.'' Many of the matches the Europeans won Friday and
Saturday, he reminded reporters, were by ``razor-thin margins.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the US team agreed Saturday night that they
had a chance. ``I said to them, `Look, we can whitewash them.'
That's exactly what we all agreed to try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But at times, it seemed that Crenshaw was convinced his team
would win no matter what. The ``chain reaction'' generated by his
team's victories in the first six singles matches that were
decided, he said, ``happened like a dream force pulling us
together.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Leonard's long putt that clinched victory, Crenshaw said,
``I think the ball was just destined to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   But fate and passion aside, there lurked just beneath Crenshaw's
tear-stained demeanor a sense that emotions seldom interfered with
his judgment. In one rare cold-blooded comment afterward, Crenshaw
remarked: ``I'm a pretty good judge of talent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
