<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR BETTER OR WORSE, METS SEEM CALM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ They do not have the thousand-mile stare of
soldiers that James Jones once described. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   They seem like perfectly stable professional athletes who have
just had a bad week _ a very bad week _ but are not haunted by it.
At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to do. Just play the game,'' said Robin
Ventura, one of the many adults in the Mets' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no crude outbursts in public, no snarling at
fans or reporters, little grim inward brooding while staring into a
locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure everybody is frustrated with the way things have
gone,'' said John Olerud, another grown-up. ``I'm sure nobody
thought we'd lose six in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   If it keeps up, the Mets will be remembered for an epic
collapse. After the 3-2 loss to the Phillies on Sunday, they would
discover on their ride home that the Reds came from behind and now
have a one-game lead for the last spot in the playoffs. The Mets
have squandered all of their lead, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect them to go down cursing their fate. This may not be
about character or personality. They may not be a rowdy bunch that
absolutely refuses to be beaten, like the old Fightin' A's in
Oakland in the '70s or the feisty Yankees of the
Munson-Nettles-Reggie-Catfish era right afterward.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Mets do not yet resemble ancient mariners
like the Philadelphia Phillies of 1964 who lost 10 straight games
in the last two weeks of the season. Those Phillies were plagued by
injuries, could see their fate coming at them like the grim reaper,
no matter how much they struggled against it.
</P>
<P>
   These Mets do not carry any overt sign of a hex, so maybe it is
merely a matter of a day's rest, and back to work again _ against
the Braves, the same brutes who waxed them three straight in
Atlanta last week to start this whole downhill lurch.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything to be done, nobody seems to know what it
is. Bobby Valentine made a minor juggle of his lineup on Sunday _
there is some confusion about whether Edgardo Alfonzo was wild
about dropping from second to sixth _ but that had little to do
with the way the Phillies plucked balls off the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahh, you make your own luck,'' Valentine said with a sheepish
smile.
</P>
<P>
   The manager did not approach his weird outburst of Saturday,
when he said he would deserve to be fired if the Mets lost. Now he
seemed almost calm, a man who had done all he could.
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested that maybe it was time to stand in the middle
of the clubhouse and rage against the fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes you think I haven't done that?'' Valentine asked
reporters. ``Nah, I haven't. I saw some anger after the game today,
but that's only natural.''
</P>
<P>
   The time to pitch a royal tantrum might have been after
Saturday's loss, when the rap music was at full boom and a dozen
players devoured a huge box of luscious-looking soft-shell crabs in
the center of the clubhouse. Valentine could have heaved the
crustaceans the way Gene Mauch of the Phillies slung spareribs all
over the clubhouse during a slump, long before the 1964 collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, that doesn't work,'' Valentine said, adding that speeches
are dicey, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's phony stuff,'' Valentine said. ``I've been in
clubhouses where managers said things and we laughed. It's not some
magical thing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the music was off and the players wolfed down a
totally prosaic clubhouse spread. They were hungry, but not sullen.
There was no clubhouse agitator appealing to their pride or their
anger, no Keith Hernandez stirring things up, no Pee Wee Reese
tossing off bland barbs, no Bob Gibsons and Bill Whites making
purposeful noise. That's not this kind of team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one sentence, one speech,'' Valentine said. ``I don't
think this mix is bad. Look, we're in a very tough marketplace and
I think we're doing a fine job.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he saw any sign of tension on the team, Valentine said,
``We haven't had our deep counts,'' meaning the players might be
overanxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get extended at-bats, you still have to hit the ball,''
Ventura said, mildly disagreeing, but admitting the players looked
tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say we're going to have a hot streak in July,
because it's September,'' Ventura added.
</P>
<P>
   They tipped the clubhouse man, headed for the bus or their car
pools, no obvious gloom cloud hanging over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, boys, it's Tuesday,'' John Franco said, on his way out the
door. ``Everybody'll be smiling at the end of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the players have not yet grasped the severity of their
situation, but that is doubtful. They are too bright to miss the
numbers, and what history will say about them if this keeps up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
