<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-QUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND-RAISING GAP FORCING QUAYLE TO DROP OUT, AIDE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle, convinced that he
would not be able to raise enough money to keep pace with Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner for the Republican
presidential nomination, has decided to drop out of the race, a
senior official with his campaign said Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that Quayle had struggled to remain optimistic
about his chances of winning the nomination, but that a review of
his campaign's finances over the weekend had forced him to conclude
that the odds against him were insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Vice President Quayle was extremely bullish on the
campaign's progress nationally and in New Hampshire, it became
clear that he did not have the resources to compete effectively in
the 18 or so contests that occur in the 30 days following New
Hampshire,'' the official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire holds the nation's first primary contest, and
Quayle had invested significant time, money and hope in doing well
there.
</P>
<P>
   But, the official said, Quayle came to realize that ``even a
strong showing or win there would not provide the momentum needed
to achieve ultimate victory. And he's always said that the moment
he concluded that the campaign could no longer secure victory, he
would not ask supporters to continue expending their time and
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said that Quayle decided to pull out of the race
after talking extensively this weekend with his campaign manager,
Kyle McSlarrow, and his wife, Marilyn. Quayle plans to announce his
decision at a news conference Monday in Phoenix, where he lives,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is the fourth Republican to drop out of the race.
Preceding him were Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, former Tennessee Gov.
Lamar Alexander and Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire, who also left
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's exit narrows the field of Republican contenders to
eight, including the conservative television commentator Pat
Buchanan, who has said that he also might bolt the GOP to seek the
nomination of the Reform Party instead.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Quayle announced his candidacy in Huntington,
Ind., on April 14, it failed to catch fire. Like many other
candidates, he was eclipsed by Bush &UR; .  &LR;  Oddly, it was the Texas
governor's father, former President George Bush, who first put
Quayle on the national stage by picking him for the vice
presidency, which Quayle held from 1989 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But during those years, Quayle arguably became most famous for
his awkward, embarrassing verbal gaffes, and his campaign seemed in
part to be an uphill struggle to persuade enough voters to take him
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's fate seemed to be sealed when Quayle finished
eighth in a field of nine candidates who competed in Iowa's
nonbinding straw poll in mid-August. But advisers said that Quayle
was less troubled by his showing there than by the pace of his fund
raising, which lagged significantly behind that of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   By June 30, the end of the last fund-raising period, Quayle had
reported campaign contributions of $3.4 million. Bush, by contrast,
reported about $37 million, and has since gone over the $50 million
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also consistently led his Republican rivals in national
opinion polls by double-digit margins. Although one recent national
poll showed Quayle a very distant second, most others have put
Elizabeth Dole, the former president of the Red Cross, in that
position, and some have shown Quayle also trailing Sen. John McCain
of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The official with the Quayle campaign would not say whether
Quayle planned to endorse any of the other Republicans in the race.
He described Quayle as ``extremely disappointed, but, as many
people know, he possesses an indestructible optimism and faith in
the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
