<HEADLINE>
TEXAN SAYS HE HELPED BUSH JOIN THE GUARD IN VIETNAM WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A former speaker of the Texas Legislature said Sunday
that during the Vietnam War he personally contacted a general in
the Texas Air National Guard to help George W. Bush attain a
pilot's slot in a Guard unit upon his graduation from college.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Sunday afternoon, Ben Barnes, the
former speaker, confirmed that he had acted on Bush's behalf more
than 30 years ago after he was asked to do so by a wealthy Houston
oilman, Sidney Adger, who was also a friend of Bush's father,
George Bush, then a congressman from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether Bush, now the governor of Texas and the
early front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination,
received preferential treatment in joining the Guard has also
arisen in a lawsuit in which Barnes is scheduled to be deposed on
Monday in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to testify to the truth in my deposition,'' Barnes
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes refused to discuss any of the specifics of his meeting
with Adger, but he said the Houston businessman ``didn't tell me
that the Bush family was telling him to do it.'' Barnes said that
he had received numerous other such requests for help, and that no
one in the Bush family ever sought his help on the matter or
contacted him about it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has repeatedly denied that he joined the National Guard to
avoid the draft. Pressed on the question in recent days, he has
said that if anyone ever exerted influence on his behalf, he did
not know about it. Bush has said that neither he nor his father
ever intervened, a position that has been seconded by his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush did not need, and did not ask, anybody for help,''
said Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for the Bush campaign. ``He applied,
met the qualifications, was accepted, served proudly and according
to military evaluations was an accomplished fighter pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, 61, has been a major figure in Texas politics since he
was elected to the State House at age 22. He served as speaker, and
later as lieutenant governor, and President Johnson once predicted
that Barnes might make it to the White House. But he became
entangled in a state banking scandal, and though he was never
charged with a crime, his political career essentially ended.
</P>
<P>
   Now a businessman and lobbyist in Austin, Barnes is a major
figure in a federal lawsuit filed against Gtech, the company that
operates the Texas lottery. The suit, filed by Lawrence Littwin,
who was dismissed as director of the Texas lottery in 1997, centers
on alleged impropriety by Gtech. But lawyers for Littwin also want
to interview Barnes, a lobbyist for the company.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the lawyers have suggested in court papers that
Gtech was allowed to keep its state contract as a way of
maintaining Barnes' silence about Bush and the Guard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
