<HEADER>
A6784 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-LEONARD-BOS     09-26 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-LEONARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEONARD MOTIVATED FROM THE BROADCAST BOOTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Bob Riefke arrived for work, looking forward
to the supreme challenge that men in his profession live for. Then
he went looking for the boss. When he found Justin Leonard, Riefke
didn't like what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked a little down,'' said the caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What's the matter?' But he said nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Riefke can put a club in his player's hand, tell him how many
breaks are in a putt, and which way the wind is blowing. He can
also tell when something is bugging Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew. So I said, `It's Johnny Miller, right?' And he said,
`Yes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Riefke grabbed Leonard's golf bag, slapped his player on the
back, and headed with him to the range. ``I said, `Don't worry
about it. Let's go prove them wrong.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Four hours and a few unthinkable putts later, they did. Four
hours and an improbable victory later, the goat horns had been
tossed away, an 0-4-2 Ryder Cup record was ancient history, and
Leonard was telling reporters, ``It's just a good thing I didn't go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to a comment by Miller, an NBC commentator,
during Saturday's broadcast. When it was announced that Ben
Crenshaw had replaced Jeff Maggert with Leonard to play four-ball
with Hal Sutton, the US captain reasoned that it was a ``hunch.''
</P>
<P>
   The move raised eyebrows, for Sutton-Maggert had been a winning
team, and it led Miller to comment: ``My hunch is that Leonard
needs to go home and watch on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard read the comment before heading to The Country Club for
the singles matches and his spirits sunk. Riefke tried to give
Leonard and his psyche a lift. ``I told him we were in a perfect
spot in the lineup (out ninth against Jose Maria Olazabal) to make
an impact,'' said Riefke.
</P>
<P>
   Not in his wildest imagination could Riefke have envisioned
being so correct.
</P>
<P>
   But there they were, some four hours later, celebrating
something so small _ a mere half-point _ and something so coveted _
the Ryder Cup. But as much as it was a team victory, Leonard also
was celebrating a personal triumph, for he had done what his caddie
had told him to do. He had proven people wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He had rallied from 4 down through 11 holes to stun Olazabal.
His 45-foot birdie bomb on The Country Club's most historic hole,
the 17th, had put Leonard 1 up and ended a miraculous run of six
holes that enlivened a crowd that no one thought could get any
livlier.
</P>
<P>
   It had also carried Riefke to another memorable time, Royal
Troon in 1997, when Leonard overcame a five-shot deficit to win the
British Open. ``Deja vu,'' said Riefke. ``He had the big eyes and
the holes were big, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Take hole 14, for instance, where Leonard hit a 12-foot putt
that knocked some more life out of the Europeans. Olazabal had made
bogeys at 12 and 13 to help the American's cause, but now Leonard
took matters into his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, a 25-footer. All square.
</P>
<P>
   Two holes later, a 45-footer, up over a slope, turning right,
then disappearing into the cup and placing Leonard into golf lore.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour later, caddies and players, wives and assistant
captains had gathered on the balcony over the men's grill to
celebrate. Tiger Woods had champagne in one hand and his other arm
around Mike (Fluff) Cowan, his former caddie, and at any other time
this would have been big news. But for the first time in his pro
career, Woods was not the crowd's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jus-tin. Jus-tin. Jus-tin.'' They chanted in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Then it grew louder. And had more of a beat to it. ``Jus-tin
Leo-nard. Jus-tin Leo-nard. Jus-tin Leo-nard.'' Champagne bottles
were everywhere and the player who stood tallest had the tallest
bottle of the bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   He held it high and had a smile that shined brighter than the
championship hardware that he had just helped win. Payne Stewart
grabbed Leonard, hugged him, and kissed him. No doubt Stewart told
him that he hadn't gone home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has such a big heart,'' Riefke said. ``There probably
are some people who are more proud of him. But not many.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
