<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST HEAT IN EL CHEAPO MOLE COMES FROM THE STOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a notation on the cover of the menu at the Guadalupe
Cafe in Sante Fe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chilies are Hot! Chilies are Hot! Chilies are Hot!
</P>
<P>
   ``Not responsible for complaints that chilies are too hot.''
</P>
<P>
   I ordered the breakfast enchilada, which consisted of blue corn
tortillas baked under layers of pinto beans, fried potatoes, green
chili, green chili sauce and lots of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? It was pretty hot. Alice the Artist remarked that my
face was suddenly as red as the tail light on a baboon.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm complaining, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, green chilies come in two versions _ mild and hot.
In New Mexico there are three versions _ hot, hotter and fried
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   It is the habanero chili that fries the tongue and melts the
silverware. According to Santa Fe locals, the only antidote for the
habanero is a mouthful of fried-bread sopaipillas, loaded with
honey.
</P>
<P>
   Some natives claim New Mexico restaurants are rated on the
excellence of their sopaipillas. Others claim that green chili is
the state's signature dish. To trap the unwary, the word chili can
refer to an ingredient, a sauce or a stew often containing beans,
potatoes and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't want to go to all the bother of deep-frying a
batch of sopaipillas, New Mexico natives can opt for a stack of
tortillas from Leona's Restaurante de Chimayo to go with their
chili stew.
</P>
<P>
   Leona prepares traditional tortillas, but she also offers red
chili, jalapeno and pinon nut tortillas. Or customers can opt for
onion, garlic or pesto tortillas. Then, if they are looking ahead
to dessert, they will find tortillas prepared in strawberry,
raspberry, blueberry, apple cinnamon, chocolate and banana flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Leona's open-air establishment is next to an ancient church in
the small community of Chimayo. The church was built in 1816
without the use of nails. To the left of the altar is El Pozito, a
small well revered for its ``healing dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   You can order tortillas, biscochitos, dry mixes for green chili
stew plus sopaipillas and a video on the healing-dirt shrine. All
you have to do is send an e-mail to Leonas(at)Roadrunner.com via
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure healing dirt is an antidote for fried tongue, so
for dinner tonight you might want to cook up less incendiary
Southwest concoctions like:
</P>
<P>
   El Cheapo Mole
</P>
<P>
   7 large turkey drumsticks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken bouillon cube
</P>
<P>
   2 flour tortillas, torn in pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 1-ounce squares unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plus one-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have pumpkin seeds, you can substitute pine nuts or
shelled sunflower seeds. If you don't have tortillas on hand
substitute one slice of wheat bread.
</P>
<P>
   OK, dump the drumsticks into a large pot, cover with water and
add 2 tablespoons of salt. Bring the water to a boil, reduce heat
and simmer the drumsticks for an hour, or until the meat is tender.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the drumsticks from the water and let cool. No, no, don't
pour out the water. Save 2 cups of it, adding 1 chicken bouillon
cube. Use your hands to separate the meat from the skin and bones.
Refrigerate the turkey meat, covered, until needed.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before you plan to eat, saute the onions and garlic in
the canola oil until they soften. Plunk the pan contents into a
blender, add { cup of the poultry broth and lean on the button for
1 minute. Pour the resultant sludge into a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Into the blender bowl pour another one-half cup of broth. Add
the tortillas, chocolate, nuts and seeds. Blend, then add to the
bowl with the onion muck.
</P>
<P>
   Once again into the blender jar add one-half cup of poultry
broth, plus the chili powder, sugar, cumin, { teaspoon salt and
cinnamon. Blend until smooth then pour into the bowl with the other
blended ingredients. Taste to see if the sauce needs more sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce should be fairly thick but pourable. Add a bit more
broth if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Plunk the turkey meat into an oven casserole, top with the mole
sauce, then shove into a 350-degree oven for 30 minutes, or until
bubbling. Serves six or more.
</P>
<P>
   Corn and Chili Custard
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creamed corn
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup milk
</P>
<P>
   14 black medium olives, sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pickled jalapenos, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Tabasco sauce to taste
</P>
<P>
   Grease oven dish. Combine all ingredients together, dump into
the dish and shove into a preheated, 350-degree oven for 30
minutes. Serves four to six as a side dish.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, spread chocolate mousse on one of Leona's chocolate
tortillas, rolled up burrito style and topped with a
chocolate-dipped strawberry secured with a toothpick.
</P>
<P>
   That should hold you over until tomorrow morning's Sante Fe
breakfast enchilada, when you should remember one thing:
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, chilies are hot!
</P>
</TEXT>
