<HEADLINE>
LEADING CONTENDER FOR TOP EDITOR AT MIAMI HERALD  
 NEW MAGAZINE TO CHALLENGE LOS ANGELES  
 ABC PLANS SPEEDY ENCORE FOR NEW DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas)  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The four-month search for a new executive editor at The Miami
Herald is almost over, and Robert Rivard, editor and senior vice
president of The San Antonio Express News, is the leading candidate
for the job, according to one Knight Ridder executive, who asked
not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The Herald's publisher, Alberto Ibarguen, said on Friday that
other candidates were still under consideration. ``I guarantee you
there's no done deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rivard has met with Jerry Ceppos, Knight Ridder's vice president
for news, Knight Ridder executives confirmed. And the San Antonio
editor, who won prizes for his coverage of Nicaragua's Sandinistas
in the early 1980s and later served five years as Newsweek's chief
of correspondents, has discussed the job with friends and
colleagues. And Ibarguen said on Friday, ``I intend to wrap this up
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk Laffoon IV, the spokesman for Knight Ridder, which owns The
Herald, said late on Friday, ``No job offer has been made.''
Rivard, he said, ``is a leading candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are other candidates,'' Laffoon said. ``It is not
over.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible in-house candidate is the managing editor, Larry
Olmstead; another is Mark Seibel, the assistant managing editor for
metropolitan news. Ceppos saw both men at work during visits to
Miami in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   If Rivard, who is 46, gets the job, he will leave Hearst
newspapers after almost a decade editing in South Texas. He left
Newsweek in 1989 to join The San Antonio Light. When Hearst folded
that paper in 1993, he found a berth as assistant managing editor
at Hearst's Express News. He took over the top job two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Dickey, Newsweek's Paris bureau chief, said on
Friday: ``The first thing that would help him is that he's
bilingual. And he's ambitious in the best sense of the word _ to
run a great newspaper and win prizes.''
</P>
<P>
   A journalist at The Express News, who declined to be identified,
said that Rivard, who broke into the business as a sports reporter
at The Brownsville Herald in South Texas, ``is bright, intelligent,
quick on his feet and very complex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have strong feelings about him, favorably or
unfavorably,'' the journalist said.
</P>
<P>
   At The Herald, Rivard would inherit a newsroom bolstered by a
1999 Pulitzer Prize for investigative reporting but bruised by
repeated defections of accomplished journalists and persistent
circulation declines.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   New Magazine to Challenge Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Ask magazine insiders why Los Angeles cannot support more than
one city glossy, and they will offer a handful of theories: The
city is too disparate demographically; the upstarts are of poor
quality; Angelenos don't read.
</P>
<P>
   In 37 years, only one city magazine here, Los Angeles, has
survived. Next month, another challenger, Channel Los Angeles, will
be spun off from Channel Miami, owned by a former stockbroker,
Richard Bronson. It will be mailed to high-income households and
given away at trendy boutiques, with the hope of eventually drawing
paying subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   To distinguish itself, Channel is taking an approach that makes
the soft-focus Los Angeles seem hard-boiled. The first issue,
scheduled for Oct. 13, is heavy on celebrity sightings, with
profiles of the actress Angela Bassett and Randy Gerber, a
nightclub proprietor, and an article on the fashion accessories of
celebrities' dogs
</P>
<P>
   ``What Channel magazine won't be doing is nasty expose
stories,'' said Sue Cameron, the magazine's executive editor. What
there will be, she said, is a plastic-surgery column written by the
former New York madam Sidney Biddle Barrows.
</P>
<P>
   The economics of the industry require a delicate balance. The
key is reaching the most affluent readers in the city to draw
advertisers, though that market ends up being minuscule _ many
place it at around 200,000 readers. Los Angeles already has 183,000
of those readers, said its publisher, Liz Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the magazine business give the newcomer little chance.
``I don't think the world needs another celebrity-oriented
magazine,'' said Allan Mayer, former editor of Buzz.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Cameron said, ``I think Los Angeles is a city that can
support more than one magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN
</P>
<P>
   ABC Plans Speedy Encore for New Drama
</P>
<P>
   The ABC drama series ``Once and Again'' is both the network's
best-reviewed new show and part of its most-scrutinized new
business deal.
</P>
<P>
   The series, about a romance between two divorced parents, will
be shown on ABC on Tuesdays and on Lifetime on Fridays, thanks to
ABC's decision to sell reruns of the show to the cable network, of
which ABC's parent, Walt Disney Co., owns a 50 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the latest sign of the new strategy that is driving
the networks and the companies that own them: developing multiple
distribution outlets for programs they own, in an effort to
maximize revenue for ever more costly programming.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference in this deal is the short time frame between
a network play and a cable play. NBC already had a deal in place
with USA Networks for its new series ``Law and Order: Special
Victims Unit.'' That will enable the USA cable network to present
episodes of that new drama, but no sooner than 13 days after they
appear on NBC. The first episode played on NBC last Monday; it will
appear on USA on Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ABC agreed to the shorter window, a senior network executive
said, because Lifetime was simply willing to pay more money and
because Lifetime was considered a sister network. NBC actually
agreed to the USA deal somewhat reluctantly because it was
renegotiating a rights fee for ``Law and Order,'' the hit series
that spawned ``Special Victims Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, on the other hand, acknowledges that the network, as well
as the creators of ``Once and Again,'' Ed Zwick and Marshal
Herskovitz, eagerly agreed to Lifetime's offer. They say they view
the double play within the same week as an experiment in how a show
is affected by having a second run on a cable channel soon after
its network run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it may actually help the show,'' a senior ABC
executive said. The executive spoke on condition of anonymity out
of deference to ABC's affiliated stations, who were adamantly
opposed to losing their exclusive rights to broadcast ABC programs.
But in some tough negotiations this summer, ABC won from its
affiliates the right to replay up to 25 percent of its prime-time
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' happened to be an ideal program for Lifetime
because of its appeal to female viewers. But it is also certain not
to be the last show ABC finds a second use for in this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll do it again, if this works,'' the ABC executive
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
