<HEADLINE>
LUCK OF THE AMERICANS SHINES AT THE 17TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The sobs just rolled and rolled from deep in
Ben Crenshaw's chest. His wife, Julie, was hugging the United
States captain as firmly as any wife could hug a husband, but the
sobs just kept bursting out. From deep inside Ben Crenshaw, from
the very depths of his soul.
</P>
<P>
   Pandemonium was swarming around that 17th green. Spain's Sergio
Garcia was milling from here to there, tears streaming down his
cheeks, the 19-year-old crying openly, but his tears were so
different from Crenshaw's. Crushing tears from the boy, while
Crenshaw's were those of a defining moment of life.
</P>
<P>
   When that 50-foot putt of Justin Leonard dropped into the cup _
dropping so unexpectedly _ Bruce Lietzke raised both arms high and
jumped up and down like a pogo-stick man, first shouting, ``It's
history . . . it's history,'' and then the assistant US captain
kept repeating as loud as his lungs would allow, ``It's the
pairings! Ben, it was the pairings! It was the pairings.''
</P>
<P>
   Down near the front bunker, US golfer Tom Lehman grabbed Leonard
in a bear hug and would not let the day's hero down for at least a
full 10 seconds. Other members of the US team rushed Leonard, as
did their wives and girlfriends, and Leonard was nearly toppled
into the bunker in the Americans' joy and ecstasy. This scene, once
the Europeans cleared their tears and angst, would be seen as an
International Golf Incident.
</P>
<P>
   But not then. Soon the green was cleared, and eventually Jose
Maria Olazabal _ after one last step-back from the putt for a final
read _ would send his 20-footer up the bank on the 17th green and
watch it roll by on the low side. Ben Crenshaw toppled over at the
sight and kissed the ground of The Country Club three times.
</P>
<P>
   The sobs could not be stopped for many a breath but when
Crenshaw finally was able to speak only bits and pieces of thought
could be expressed. ``Lanny . . . Where's Lanny?'' were the first
words from Crenshaw's mouth, the Captain's tribute to Lanny
Wadkins, the 1995 captain whose US team had fallen apart in the
singles matches on Sunday and lost to the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Next from the captain's mouth came bits and pieces that only the
US captain could utter. ``Ouimet's horseshoe . . . '' and
``Ouimet's horseshoe is absolutely there.''
</P>
<P>
   And those were words that only a handful in that wild stampede
of thousands of delirious fans on the 17th green could grasp. But
Crenshaw knew exactly, knew precisely that the 17th hole of The
Country Club is where all important golf matches have been decided.
The luck of the Americans is buried there, somewhere, on that 17th
hole. Always US luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Ouimet's horseshoe did it,'' said Crenshaw again, and
Crenshaw has studied that picture of Francis Ouimet, the Brookline
caddie who upset Harry Vardon, Britain's best and the world's best,
to win the 1913 US Open at The Country Club. Crenshaw knew exactly
that Ouimet had made 20-footers on both the 17th hole in regulation
to tie the match and the 17th hole in the playoff to win it. ``It's
spooky,'' Crenshaw would say later.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment Sunday when US golf was rescued by Justin
Leonard, Crenshaw's mind flashed back to that picture of Ouimet
carried back to the clubhouse on the shoulders of adoring fans
after his upset in 1913. And in Ouimet's hand was a horseshoe. And,
Crenshaw would say, ``Ouimet's house (was) right across that
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on that 17th green were Olazabal and Brendan McCartain, his
caddie. Just moments earlier, when Olazabal was in the backswing of
his approach shot, a fan in the gallery had simulated a loud yawn.
Olazabal angrily looked back at the fan and McCartain shouted over
to the gallery, ``If you need to win the Ryder Cup that bad, then
you can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes earlier, on that same 17th green, there had been a
mini-stampede. At that moment, it was felt by one and possibly all
that the match of between Mark O'Meara and Europe's Padraig
Harrington would decide the Ryder Cup. The match was all square and
gamesmanship was paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, for instance, forced an impatient O'Meara to wait a
full five minutes or more as the Irishman walked all the way to the
green to inspect the pin placement and slowly ambled back to his
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that didn't really bother me,'' O'Meara would say later,
when all damage had been erased by Leonard's putt. ``It didn't
affect my shot.''
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly seemed it did because O'Meara fluffed his
second shot horribly, the ball traveling little more than halfway
to the green. But O'Meara was able to apparently save a halve when
he buried a snaky downhill 6-footer and the Americans erupted in
glee; Tom Lehman rushed onto the green in joy and Tiger Woods, Hal
Sutton, Davis Love, and the others jumped for joy.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, though, still had a putt to take.
</P>
<P>
   The Irishman gave a dark glance toward Lehman and the happy
Americans but, he, too, would say later that he hadn't been upset.
``I didn't even see Lehman,'' said Harrington, ``and then they
conceded the putt.'' Indeed, it was O'Meara who saw a mini-incident
in the making and shouted over to Harrington that his putt was
good; O'Meara would have made Harrington make the crucial putt if
it hadn't been for the US jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   Few scenes in Boston sports history have been as spontaneously
wild as those on 17. And if Ben Crenshaw felt that it was fate that
would cause that stampede on the 17th because the 17th ``has been
very, very kind to Americans,'' the result was a most tasty win for
the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
