<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE PETTITTE IS LOOSE, THE YANKEES FALL APART 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With his fastball going where he wanted it and his
sinker falling low, Andy Pettitte felt good warming up Sunday. But
once the game began, Pettitte lost his command, and a brutal day
for the Yankees' pitchers began to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, who was ripped for a double by Miguel Cairo on the
second pitch of the game, struggled through six innings, and Ramiro
Mendoza, the losing pitcher, was even worse. The two Yankee
pitchers allowed 15 hits in a 6-5 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
in front of 49,458 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees stroked 11 hits off the equally unimpressive Devil
Rays pitchers as the game took on the feel of a doubleheader,
lasting exactly four hours.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Yankees' second straight to Tampa Bay, which
they defeated 17 times in their first 18 meetings, including nine
straight in the Bronx. But their magic number for clinching the
American League East division title was reduced to three when the
Red Sox lost to the Orioles. Cleveland, which won, has the league's
best record at 95-61. The Yankees are 94-61.
</P>
<P>
   After surrendering the game-opening double to Cairo, Pettitte
retired the next three batters on ground balls. But he gave up four
runs and nine hits over the next five innings, including five of
the Devil Rays' franchise-record seven doubles and a home run. Two
of those doubles and the homer were delivered by Bubba Trammell,
who got his hits in the second, fourth and sixth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre said Pettitte pitched OK and
uncharacteristically mentioned that the umpire Travis
Katzenmeirer's strike zone might have been a factor. Katzenmeirer
started the game behind second base, but when the home plate
umpire, Jim Joyce, suffered a bruised cornea in the first inning
after catching mud in his eye, Katzenmeirer began calling the balls
and strikes in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmeirer, a minor-league umpire, fills in for vacationing or
injured major-league umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pettitte couldn't get enough balls down, and that strike zone
kept moving all around,'' Torre said. ``Sometimes they were strikes
and sometimes they weren't, and I think he couldn't figure how to
lock in. I haven't seen that umpire before and I haven't seen that
strike zone before either.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he ever figured out where to throw the ball,
Pettitte, who allowed 10 or more hits for just the third time in
his 30 starts this season, said that he had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good starting the game out,'' said Pettitte, who said
the five-minute delay after Joyce's injury might have thrown him
off his rhythm. ``But I wasn't able to locate like I wanted to. I
didn't think I was going to get through the second inning, to tell
you the truth. But I was able to scramble through six somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Pettitte's problems, the Yankees had a chance to win
when Derek Jeter broke a 4-4 tie with an awkward sixth-inning
double. Jeter's bloop hit took a strange bounce into the stands
along the right-field line and scored Chad Curtis, who had walked
and stolen second base, and gave Jeter his 100th RBI of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who had never had more than 84 RBIs in his three previous
seasons, joined Lyn Lary, who drove in 107 runs in 1931, as the
only shortstops in Yankees history to record at least 100 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was on me for staying on 99 for a while,'' said
Jeter, who had not driven in a run since Sept. 19, a stretch of
five games. ``I was wondering if I was going to get it. But my
teammates were getting on base a lot, so I figured one time I'd get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza started the seventh and gave up a walk and one hit, but
he stranded the two base runners by striking out Trammell with a
diving fastball outside.
</P>
<P>
   But Mendoza was not as fortunate in the eighth, when his
belt-high pitches resulted in four hits, two runs and a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inconsistent,'' Torre said in summing up Mendoza's
performance. ``If he keeps the ball down, he's very tough to dig
out of the dirt. When he elevates the ball, he's a lot easier to
hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
