<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: U.S. WINS WITH CHARGE FROM BEYOND THE FRINGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Justin Leonard's putt crawled up, up and
across the ledge on the 17th green and dived into the hole like a
field mouse.
</P>
<P>
   As Leonard struggled during the week, Ben Crenshaw, the American
captain, kept promising that ``Justin's going to make a putt.'' And
he already had, a 30-footer on the 15th green Sunday that squared
his match with Jose Maria Olazabal after having been 4 down. But
now the little Texan had made a 45-footer for a birdie 3 that will
be remembered as the most theatrical putt in Ryder Cup history.
</P>
<P>
   In their elation, several American players and their wives
rushed to celebrate with Leonard, but soon they remembered that
Olazabal still had to putt for what might be a tying birdie. So did
Crenshaw, now crouched behind the green, saying, ``All right.''
Next to him, Bruce Edwards, Tom Watson's longtime caddie, who was
here as an assistant to Crenshaw, turned to the captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he misses, you win,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God,'' Crenshaw said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're five seconds away,'' Edwards said, ``from the greatest
comeback in the history of the Ryder Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would be more like five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, the Spaniard who had played so well for the European
team in other cup matches, knew he had to make his 25-footer. He
studied the uphill line, walked around and peered at the contours
near the cup, finally took his stance over the ball, then stepped
back, studied the line again, took his stance again and putted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please miss.'' Edwards whispered what all the Americans were
wishing. ``Please miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal's ball moved up the slope and across the ledge, but
when it stayed left of the hole, the American players rushed
Leonard. But Crenshaw, who seemed to have been holding his breath
all that time, moved forward, knelt and kissed the green, then
joined the celebration as Olazabal shook hands with the American
captain.
</P>
<P>
   With Leonard 1 up going to the 18th hole, the U.S. Ryder Cup
team was assured of the half-point it needed for an unprecedented
4-point comeback in the 12 singles matches for a 14{-13{ triumph at
The Country Club that had both proper and improper Bostonians
roaring as if the Red Sox had won a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   And for Ben Crenshaw, his crusade had been a success.
</P>
<P>
   It hadn't been easy. In the August controversy over some
American golfers' request for money they could donate to their
individual charities, he had questioned the commitment of Tiger
Woods, David Duval, Phil Mickelson and Mark O'Meara. Critics had
second-guessed his two wild-card choices, Tom Lehman and Steve
Pate, as well as some of his Friday and Saturday pairings.
</P>
<P>
   And going into Sunday's singles, most observers thought his team
had no chance. But he emerged as a captain to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told them all week,'' he said, ``that I've been admirers
of their talent, their spirit, their will, their unshakable
belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the sentimentalist, Crenshaw remembered that when he played
here at age 16 in the U.S. Junior championship, his father had
followed his matches. And he mentioned that Mrs. Harvey Penick, the
widow of his golf tutor in Austin, Texas, was here for these
matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how these things happen,'' he said. ``I do know
how it happened, though. By these fellows and the way they can play
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal and the European captain, Mark James, complained about
the outburst of emotion by the American players and their wives on
the 17th green, but Olazabal declined to ``find an excuse'' in it,
saying it had no effect on the result. And ever the golf gentleman,
Crenshaw later ``sincerely'' apologized to the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   But this was more than just another miracle team comeback. This
was sports theater at its finest with a patriotic backdrop, up
there with the 1980 U.S. Olympic hockey team stunning the Soviet
Union and then winning the gold medal at Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the alternate-shot and better-ball matches on Friday
and Saturday, the galleries had chanted ``U.S.A.! U.S.A.!'' as the
Europeans grabbed a 10-6 lead. But Sunday Crenshaw wisely sent out
his six best players in the first six singles in order to blunt the
Europeans' opportunity for 4 quick, clinching points.
</P>
<P>
   And those six _ Lehman, Hal Sutton, Mickelson, Davis Love III,
Woods and Duval _ quickly created a 12-10 turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a force that was pulling us together,'' Crenshaw
said later, ``and it was building.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Europeans had taken an imposing 6-2 lead Friday,
Sutton said, ``We've got to dig deep in our souls now.'' He
certainly did, contributing 3 points, 2 in alternate-shot matches
and 1 in Sunday's singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a horse,'' Crenshaw said. ``He hit some great golf shots,
time after time. We drew strength from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago Duval, the world's No. 2-ranked player in his first
Ryder Cup, had described these matches as a ``big corporate
outing'' and an exhibition, but in his 5-and-4 rout of Jesper
Parnevik, the Swede who had played so well the first two days, he
reacted as if he were golf's Nathan Hale, with only one match to
give for his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you can't explain and can't appreciate until
you've been a part of it,'' Duval said later. ``The great analogy
is that it's like when you have your first child.''
</P>
<P>
   In the controversy over payments to be donated to charity, Woods
had described the Ryder Cup as an ``exhibition, because there's no
winner's check.'' All each player received was a $5,000 stipend.
But he didn't act as if Sunday's singles was an exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben did a great job of getting us together and keeping us
together,'' Woods said later. ``We did it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Steve Pate and Jim Furyk comfortably ahead in matches
they would win, the Americans knew they still needed another
half-point to win. O'Meara had a chance for it at the 18th hole,
but he drove his tee shot into a bunker, hit his approach into a
greenside bunker, then fluffed his sand shot into the rough. Bogey.
No half-point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation,'' O'Meara later said, ``when you know
you're not playing your best.''
</P>
<P>
   But by then, Leonard had evened his match and when he made that
putt on the 17th and Olazabal missed his putt, Ben Crenshaw, ever
the historian, kissed the same green where America's first golf
idol, the 20-year-old amateur Francis Ouimet, had made important
putts both in the fourth round and the 18-hole playoff of the 1913
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a little spooky,'' Crenshaw would say later. ``And
his house was right across the street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
