<HEADLINE>
ROOKIES HAVE HIGH HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ After the season, Jeff Williams is headed to the
Arizona Fall League, Alex Cora to Puerto Rico and Robinson Checo to
the Dominican Republic. The Dodgers hope their experiences this
winter will make them regular contributors to the club next year.
</P>
<P>
   Williams made his second start for the Dodgers on Sunday and
pitched impressively until the sixth when he allowed a game-tying
home run to Reggie Sanders. The Dodgers wound up winning 10-7 and
Williams certainly has gotten people's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of returning to his native Australia, Williams will
continue to start in Arizona and the club hopes he will compete for
the desperately needed left-handed spot in next year's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These past few weeks have been exciting,'' said Williams, who
is expected to make another start Friday in Houston. ``I mean, you
work your whole life to get here. When you step on that mound, it
is something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Before allowing one run in seven innings Tuesday against the
Giants, Williams pitched in the bullpen for three weeks. Even
though he gave up four runs (three earned) in 52/3 innings Sunday,
pitching coach Claude Osteen thought Williams had better command
and location than his first start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still trying to find his way,'' Osteen said. ``Sanders
hit a sinker that stayed up. Jeff will learn to get guys out with
that pitch. I know he can throw harder than he has here. He's
around 88 mph now, but I had him last year at (Triple-A)
Albuquerque and he threw 93 consistently in one game. But for now,
it's better to hit your spots and gain confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Cora played shortstop in the ninth inning and made two
spectacular defensive plays. But it is unlikely he will get a
chance to unseat Mark Grudzielanek, who is batting .320. Cora, who
missed half the minor-league season with a broken right hand, has
appeared in 10 games since his recall. Most were at second base,
but he has not been told to work out there during the winter league
in his native Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little harder position because I've been at short all
season,'' said the left-handed hitting Cora, who batted second at
Triple-A Albuquerque and hit .310. ``Shortstop is easier because
you are looking at the first baseman when you throw. I've just
gotten used to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Checo will head back to the Dominican League, but there is a
good chance he will not pitch because of lingering discomfort in
his right groin that forced him to miss 40 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing for me is to come back healthy,''
Checo said. ``By spring training, I'm going to be 100 percent. I
want to compete for a starting spot.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Last hurrah: The Dodgers are off today before opening a
three-game series Tuesday against the Giants in the finale for
Candlestick Park. After Thursday's final game, the Giants will host
a two-hour ceremony that will include an appearance by former
Dodgers manager Tom Lasorda. It is being called ``one last chance
to boo Tommy,'' who coached and managed during many memorable
moments the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   __ Matchups for the series: Tuesday (7:15 p.m. _ Fox Sports West
2) Ismael Valdes (9-14, 3.98) vs. right-hander Joe Nathan (7-3,
3.76). . . . Wednesday (7:05 p.m. _ Fox Sports West 2) Kevin Brown
(18-8, 2.29) vs. right-hander Livan Hernandez (7-12, 4.77). . . .
Thursday (1:05 p.m. KTLA/5) Chan Ho Park (12-10, 5.51) vs.
left-hander Shawn Estes (11-10, 4.79).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
