<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- TALBOTT-PROFILE, 9-26 --
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. Because of his expertise
on the Soviet Union and its newly independent fragments, Talbott
has become the target of critics of President Clinton's policy of
financial and political engagement with Russia as revelations pour
forth of massive money-laundering schemes, the looting of
industries formerly controlled by the state and organized
corruption in and around the Kremlin. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- OPERA-RECORDBREAKER-2,
9-26 -- Tireless tenor Placido Domingo, 58, during a performance of
``Die Walkure'' at the Metropolitan Opera in 1986, with Siegmund
Deborah Voigt as Sieglinde. Domingo's 18th opening night this
Monday comes as he begins his 31st season with the Met. His first
opening night was in 1971 with the title role in Verdi's ``Don
Carlo.'' Domingo's 18th opening night performance, will surpass
Enrico Caruso's tally of 17. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- OPERA-RECORDBREAKER-1,
9-26 -- Opera buffs will be cheering Monday night as the tireless
tenor Placido Domingo hits a few high notes into the top balcony of
the Metropolitan Opera House and breaks an operatic record that has
stood longer than Babe Ruth's 60-homer season did. The Metropolitan
Opera opens its season Monday night with a popular double bill:
Mascagni's ``Cavalleria Rusticana'' and Leoncavallo's
``Pagliacci.'' And for the 18th time in his career Domingo will
star in a Met opening-night performance, surpassing Enrico Caruso's
tally of 17. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- MILITARY-RECRUIT, 9-26
-- Staff Sgt. Joseph Mitchell, a military recruiter, spoke with
Damall Kellem, 17, at a Washington street fair. Enlistment is down,
and for most young people, Kellem says, the military is ``not even
in their vocabularies.'' Raising an all-volunteer military has
never been easy, but the difficulties with recruiting have been
mounting in recent years as the economy courses along and college
becomes an attainable goal for more young people than ever.
(Justine Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-6,
9-26 -- Team USA's Justin Leonard celebrates after sinking a putt
for a birdie on the 17th green, in his match against Jose Maria
Olazabal. Leonard had clinched the half-point that clinched victory
for the U.S. team, and the Europeans, who seemed in command
starting Sunday's play, lost the Ryder Cup for the first time since
1993. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-5,
9-26 -- The United States Ryder Cup team gathers around captain Ben
Crenshaw, who holds the cup as they pose for photos after the
closing ceremonies on Sunday. Despite a 10-6 deficit going into the
final round, despite the fact no team has ever come back from more
than two points on the last day, Team USA refused to give in. The
U.S. team stormed back to win, 14 1/2-13 1/2, winning eight and
splitting one of Sunday's 12 singles matches. (Bill Greene/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-4,
9-26 -- Fans run up the 18th fairway as Team USA defeated Team
Europe to win the Ryder Cup on Sunday. Despite a 10-6 deficit going
into the final round, despite the fact no team has ever come back
from more than two points on the last day, Team USA refused to give
in. The U.S. team stormed back to win, 14 1/2-13 1/2, winning eight
and splitting one of Sunday's 12 singles matches. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
