<P>
   (NYT8) CLEVELAND -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- KROLL-O'GARA-TROUBLES,
9-26 -- Kroll-O'Gara's chairman and chief executive, Jules Kroll,
right, and Thomas O'Gara, the vice chairman, at the Ohio-based
plant where cars are armored. Two years ago, Kroll and O'Gara were
all smiles. Now their internal dispute is said to be hurting the
company. People close to the company say they have disagreed on the
price and the timing of the company's biggest purchase to date, of
Securify Inc., a start-up specializing in Internet security that is
based in Mountain View, Calif. (Mark Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- PRIMEDIA-MULTIMEDIA, 9-26
-- Henry Kravis, the founding partner of the leveraged buyout firm
of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, left, hired Thomas Rogers of NBC to
head Primedia Inc. Rogers, the president of NBC cable who expanded
the NBC network into the cable and Internet markets, will fit right
into Primedia's plan according to Kravis. ``Today, what is really
needed for us is to become a full-service media company,'' says
Kravis. ``Tom brings to Primedia the leadership that is so
important, and the respect of the media world that comes from
founding CNBC and MSNBC.'' (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- MUD-THEATER-REVIEW-2, 9-26
-- Deidre O' Connell and Paul Lazar in ``Mud,'' part of a double
bill by Marla Fornes at the Signature Theater. In ``Mud,'' Ms.
Fornes explores the joyless existence of a small-town woman named
Mae, played by O'Connell, in a performance of splendid composure,
and the brain-dead men like Lazar who love, need and destroy her.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- MUD-THEATER-REVIEW-1, 9-26
-- From left, Marc Damon Johnson, Jed Diamond and Philip Goodwin in
``Drowning,'' by Maria Irene Fornes at the Signature Theater. Ms.
Fornes' plays have the meticulous composition of still lifes, which
means at times they are strikingly balanced and at others opaque,
impassive. The dialogue can be so flat, so lacking in the perfume
of real conversation, that the play could have been grown in a
hothouse, under artificial light. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DULLES, Va. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- COMPUSERVE-AOL, 9-26 --
Robert W. Pittman, America Online's president, with Audrey Weil,
general manager of the Compuserve unit, at a map showing AOL
locations. In a conglomerate-driven world, investors expect big
companies to own more than one brand. When AOL acquired Compuserve
in 1997, it predicted the dawning of a multiple-brand era in the
Internet access market, a view that industry analysts doubted would
be fulfilled so soon. AOL says so far in its fiscal first quarter,
which will end on Thursday, the long-struggling Compuserve added
300,000 subscribers. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- US-MAG-MEDIA, 9-26 -- Jann
Wenner, publisher of Rolling Stone and Us, in his Manhattan office.
Wenner has announced that he will challenge Time Inc.'s two major
entertainment weekly magazines, People and Entertainment Weekly, by
changing the frequency of Us magazine, Wenner Media's barely
profitable entertainment magazine, from monthly to weekly. (Jeffery
A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- PARIS-REVIEW-ARCHIVES, 9-26
-- George Plimpton, editor of The Paris Review, with proofs and
materials acquired by the Pierpont Morgan Library. Other literary
journals have been founded and then have foundered, but the Left
Bank quarterly created by several hopeful young American writers
has remained a vital part of the literary scene after more than 45
years of operation. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PROVO, Utah -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- INTERNET-RETAILING, 9-26
-- Fingerhut's distribution center near Provo, handles orders for
Etoys. Many Internet companies have focused on attracting
customers, but the bigger challenge is fulfilling orders. A worker
checks an invoice and begins preliminary sorting, top, and at an
automated bin, bottom, a worker receives items for a customer's
order, which is then boxed and sent by conveyor to workers who
prepare it for shipping. (George Frey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
