</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- TALBOTT-PROFILE, 9-26 --
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. Because of his expertise
on the Soviet Union and its newly independent fragments, Talbott
has become the target of critics of President Clinton's policy of
financial and political engagement with Russia as revelations pour
forth of massive money-laundering schemes, the looting of
industries formerly controlled by the state and organized
corruption in and around the Kremlin. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- OPERA-RECORDBREAKER-2,
9-26 -- Tireless tenor Placido Domingo, 58, during a performance of
``Die Walkure'' at the Metropolitan Opera in 1986, with Siegmund
Deborah Voigt as Sieglinde. Domingo's 18th opening night this
Monday comes as he begins his 31st season with the Met. His first
opening night was in 1971 with the title role in Verdi's ``Don
Carlo.'' Domingo's 18th opening night performance, will surpass
Enrico Caruso's tally of 17. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- OPERA-RECORDBREAKER-1,
9-26 -- Opera buffs will be cheering Monday night as the tireless
tenor Placido Domingo hits a few high notes into the top balcony of
the Metropolitan Opera House and breaks an operatic record that has
stood longer than Babe Ruth's 60-homer season did. The Metropolitan
Opera opens its season Monday night with a popular double bill:
Mascagni's ``Cavalleria Rusticana'' and Leoncavallo's
``Pagliacci.'' And for the 18th time in his career Domingo will
star in a Met opening-night performance, surpassing Enrico Caruso's
tally of 17. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- MILITARY-RECRUIT, 9-26
-- Staff Sgt. Joseph Mitchell, a military recruiter, spoke with
Damall Kellem, 17, at a Washington street fair. Enlistment is down,
and for most young people, Kellem says, the military is ``not even
in their vocabularies.'' Raising an all-volunteer military has
never been easy, but the difficulties with recruiting have been
mounting in recent years as the economy courses along and college
becomes an attainable goal for more young people than ever.
(Justine Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-6,
9-26 -- Team USA's Justin Leonard celebrates after sinking a putt
for a birdie on the 17th green, in his match against Jose Maria
Olazabal. Leonard had clinched the half-point that clinched victory
for the U.S. team, and the Europeans, who seemed in command
starting Sunday's play, lost the Ryder Cup for the first time since
1993. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-5,
9-26 -- The United States Ryder Cup team gathers around captain Ben
Crenshaw, who holds the cup as they pose for photos after the
closing ceremonies on Sunday. Despite a 10-6 deficit going into the
final round, despite the fact no team has ever come back from more
than two points on the last day, Team USA refused to give in. The
U.S. team stormed back to win, 14 1/2-13 1/2, winning eight and
splitting one of Sunday's 12 singles matches. (Bill Greene/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-4,
9-26 -- Fans run up the 18th fairway as Team USA defeated Team
Europe to win the Ryder Cup on Sunday. Despite a 10-6 deficit going
into the final round, despite the fact no team has ever come back
from more than two points on the last day, Team USA refused to give
in. The U.S. team stormed back to win, 14 1/2-13 1/2, winning eight
and splitting one of Sunday's 12 singles matches. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-3,
9-26 -- Champagne rains down from the porch balcony of the locker
room at The Country Club in Brookline, as Davis Love III, left,
sprays a bottle and Tiger Woods, right, looks on, after Team USA
won the Ryder Cup on Sunday. Despite a 10-6 deficit going into the
final round, despite the fact no team has ever come back from more
than two points on the last day, Team USA refused to give in. The
U.S. team stormed back to win, 14 1/2-13 1/2, winning eight and
splitting one of Sunday's 12 singles matches. (John Tlumacki/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-2,
9-26 -- Team Europe's Sergio Garcia puts his head in disbelief as
he leans on assistant captain Sam Torrance, by the side of the 18th
green after Team USA clinched the Ryder Cup on Sunday. Despite a
10-6 deficit going into the final round, despite the fact no team
has ever come back from more than two points on the last day, Team
USA refused to give in. The U.S. team stormed back to win, 14
1/2-13 1/2, winning eight and splitting one of Sunday's 12 singles
matches. (John Bohn/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-1,
9-26 -- Team USA's Payne Stewart reacts after sinking a huge putt
on the 15th green during the last day of play at the Ryder Cup on
Sunday. Despite a 10-6 deficit going into the final round, despite
the fact no team has ever come back from more than two points on
the last day, Team USA refused to give in. The U.S. team stormed
back to win, 14 1/2-13 1/2, winning eight and splitting one of
Sunday's 12 singles matches. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CLEVELAND -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- KROLL-O'GARA-TROUBLES,
9-26 -- Kroll-O'Gara's chairman and chief executive, Jules Kroll,
right, and Thomas O'Gara, the vice chairman, at the Ohio-based
plant where cars are armored. Two years ago, Kroll and O'Gara were
all smiles. Now their internal dispute is said to be hurting the
company. People close to the company say they have disagreed on the
price and the timing of the company's biggest purchase to date, of
Securify Inc., a start-up specializing in Internet security that is
based in Mountain View, Calif. (Mark Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- PRIMEDIA-MULTIMEDIA, 9-26
-- Henry Kravis, the founding partner of the leveraged buyout firm
of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, left, hired Thomas Rogers of NBC to
head Primedia Inc. Rogers, the president of NBC cable who expanded
the NBC network into the cable and Internet markets, will fit right
into Primedia's plan according to Kravis. ``Today, what is really
needed for us is to become a full-service media company,'' says
Kravis. ``Tom brings to Primedia the leadership that is so
important, and the respect of the media world that comes from
founding CNBC and MSNBC.'' (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- MUD-THEATER-REVIEW-2, 9-26
-- Deidre O' Connell and Paul Lazar in ``Mud,'' part of a double
bill by Marla Fornes at the Signature Theater. In ``Mud,'' Ms.
Fornes explores the joyless existence of a small-town woman named
Mae, played by O'Connell, in a performance of splendid composure,
and the brain-dead men like Lazar who love, need and destroy her.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- MUD-THEATER-REVIEW-1, 9-26
-- From left, Marc Damon Johnson, Jed Diamond and Philip Goodwin in
``Drowning,'' by Maria Irene Fornes at the Signature Theater. Ms.
Fornes' plays have the meticulous composition of still lifes, which
means at times they are strikingly balanced and at others opaque,
impassive. The dialogue can be so flat, so lacking in the perfume
of real conversation, that the play could have been grown in a
hothouse, under artificial light. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DULLES, Va. -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- COMPUSERVE-AOL, 9-26 --
Robert W. Pittman, America Online's president, with Audrey Weil,
general manager of the Compuserve unit, at a map showing AOL
locations. In a conglomerate-driven world, investors expect big
companies to own more than one brand. When AOL acquired Compuserve
in 1997, it predicted the dawning of a multiple-brand era in the
Internet access market, a view that industry analysts doubted would
be fulfilled so soon. AOL says so far in its fiscal first quarter,
which will end on Thursday, the long-struggling Compuserve added
300,000 subscribers. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- US-MAG-MEDIA, 9-26 -- Jann
Wenner, publisher of Rolling Stone and Us, in his Manhattan office.
Wenner has announced that he will challenge Time Inc.'s two major
entertainment weekly magazines, People and Entertainment Weekly, by
changing the frequency of Us magazine, Wenner Media's barely
profitable entertainment magazine, from monthly to weekly. (Jeffery
A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- PARIS-REVIEW-ARCHIVES, 9-26
-- George Plimpton, editor of The Paris Review, with proofs and
materials acquired by the Pierpont Morgan Library. Other literary
journals have been founded and then have foundered, but the Left
Bank quarterly created by several hopeful young American writers
has remained a vital part of the literary scene after more than 45
years of operation. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PROVO, Utah -- Sept. 26, 1999 -- INTERNET-RETAILING, 9-26
-- Fingerhut's distribution center near Provo, handles orders for
Etoys. Many Internet companies have focused on attracting
customers, but the bigger challenge is fulfilling orders. A worker
checks an invoice and begins preliminary sorting, top, and at an
automated bin, bottom, a worker receives items for a customer's
order, which is then boxed and sent by conveyor to workers who
prepare it for shipping. (George Frey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
