<HEADLINE>
REV.   GRAHAM TELLS HARVARD AUDIENCE TO SEEK ANSWERS IN GOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HERMIONE MALONE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ After a battle with Parkinson's disease and a
dose of bad weather left him unable to speak at a scheduled service
last year, the Rev. Billy Graham was determined to preach at
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he returned to campus for the first time since 1982,
with a message that the answer for all of life's questions is in
the Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is so simple and plain, but changes a life so
dramatically,'' said Seppo Rapo, a Harvard Medical School graduate,
who attended the service with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for answers, and Jesus is the answer. That's
kind of exciting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, speaking to a standing-room assembly of students and
community members at Harvard's Memorial Church, spoke on the real
meaning of the Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to the Cross today and you'll find a life here and now that
you never knew existed, and you'll find a future life the moment
you no longer exist in this world,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-old minister also admonished young people to stop
searching for the meaning of life in material, often sinful things.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never really find an answer until they find it in God,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his sermon, Graham said that the Cross ``shows the depth
of our sin'' and that the love of God ``is the only way of
salvation'' to guarantee a future life.
</P>
<P>
   For many in attendance, it was the first time they had seen
Graham preach, and though the minister joked in his opening that he
hoped not to be an ``anticlimax,'' several students found him
inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know his health is not as good as it was, but he still has a
strong spirit,'' said Anna Katherine Coats, who was visiting from
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   One anecdote that stayed with many after the service was of a
little boy who was lost. A police officer happened upon him and
unsuccessfully tried to help the boy remember where he lived.
Finally, the officer looked up at the steeple of a church in the
town and pointed to the Cross. The boy, recognizing the symbol of
Christianity said to the officer, ``Take me to the Cross. I can
find my way home from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham will appear again Monday night at the Kennedy School of
Government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
