<HEADLINE>
IN SPECTACULAR COMEBACK, U.S. GOLFERS WIN RYDER CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add 2nd take of 500 words. In first take, rewrites 5th
graf for clarification and inserts information on scoring method in
17th graf, bgng The Americans ... )   (Eds: See also GLF-RYDER-BEHAVIOR) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It was incredible, emotional and historic,
the biggest comeback ever in golf's most compelling team
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup is once again American property, as the U.S. team
stormed back to win, 14{-13{, winning eight and splitting one of
Sunday's 12 singles matches _ in which scoring is determined by
winning holes instead of counting total strokes. No team had ever
overcome a four-point deficit on the final day; in fact, no team
had overcome a final-day deficit greater than two points.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 10-6 heading into Sunday's 12 singles matches, the U.S.
Ryder Cup team rose together as one, lifting one another, lifting
their games, lifting the pride of the thousands of Americans who
watched at The Country Club here and the many more who watched the
drama unfold on television.
</P>
<P>
   The cup-winning putt was made by Justin Leonard, who sank an
improbable 45-foot uphill birdie putt that became part of golf
history the instant it fell into the cup. Leonard held his putter
aloft and did a joyful dance as he ran off the 17th green, and he
was immediately mobbed to the left of the green by teammates, who
realized that their improbable dream had nearly become reality.
</P>
<P>
   When the green finally cleared, and when the ground finally
stopped shaking, Jose Maria Olazabal had a chance to keep Europe's
hopes alive. But his 25-foot birdie attempt slid just past the
hole, putting Leonard 1 up with one hole to play and assuring him
of at least the half-point that would clinch victory for the United
States. The Europeans, who seemed in command starting Sunday's
play, lost the Ryder Cup for the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   For Leonard, the 1997 British Open champion, it was a day of
redemption, after he played inconsistently early in the
competition. Leonard was 4 down to Olazabal through 11 holes, but
he won the next four consecutive holes, making a 30-foot birdie
putt on No. 15, then making his unforgettable putt two holes later.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his putt on No. 17, Leonard said, ``I didn't know if
I could make it. I just believe it was one of those putts that was
destined to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Europeans complimented the U.S for its victory, they
were also upset about the celebration on No. 17, because the cup
still had not been clinched, and Olazabal was still waiting to
putt. Olazabal was forced to wait several minutes before the
commotion subsided prior to attempting his putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of behavior is not what anyone expects to see,''
said Olazabal. ``It was an ugly picture. I understand there was a
lot of emotion, but you have to have both feet on the ground and
realize what the situation is. But the fact is, they played better
today, and they won.'
</P>
<P>
   U.S. captain Ben Crenshaw apologized for the outburst at No. 17,
as did his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened on No. 17 was unfortunate, but I'm not going to
apologize for being excited,'' said Tom Lehman, one of the
teammates who rushed to grab Leonard. ``It was a great day for the
American team.''
</P>
<P>
   When the competition ended, there was an outpouring of emotion
and champagne at The Country Club, in a festive scene that was the
climax of a fairy-tale day. American players cried tears of joy.
European players cried tears of sadness. Members of the American
team ran to the balcony of the clubhouse, spraying champagne on
each other, as adoring flag-waving fans watched from below chanting
``USA, USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Americans overcome a huge deficit, but they
overcame the tremendous play of an underrated European team, and
the heavy burden of being favored in a much-anticipated biennial
event. For two days, the Europeans played superb golf, making
spectacular shots that deflated the U.S. team, and it appeared the
Americans were on the verge of suffering another humbling loss.
</P>
<P>
   But at an inspiring team meeting Saturday night, Crenshaw and
every player talked about how much winning the Ryder Cup meant, how
they had not played up to their potential, and how they still
believed they would win.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw made a prophetic statement Saturday night, when he
proclaimed, ``I believe in fate. I have a good feeling about
this.'' Crenshaw helped deliver the motivation, and his team
delivered an impassioned performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only comments last night were that if we go down, let's go
down with all our oars in the water,'' said Hal Sutton, the best
player for America in the competition with 3{ points. ``Leaving
that meeting, we all felt we could go out and make a real run at
this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans seized control at the start Sunday and built
momentum. The American game plan was simple: to win the first four
matches, to even the competition (each match victory was worth 1
point and each halved match was worth 1/2 point) and to put
immediate pressure on their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans started even better than expected, sweeping
the first six matches in shocking fashion. Lehman defeated Lee
Westwood, 3 and 2. Sutton toppled Darren Clarke, 4 and 2. Phil
Mickelson beat Jarmo Sandelin, 4 and 3. Davis Love III dominated
Jean Van de Velde, 6 and 5. Tiger Woods defeated Andrew Coltart, 3
and 2. And David Duval dropped Jesper Parnevik, 5 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the U.S. team had a 10-8 lead, with the Europeans
still needing four points to clinch the tie they needed to retain
the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
