<HEADER>
A6835 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-CUP-1STLD-W     09-26 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-CUP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BROOKLINE, Mass.: Ryder Cup. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The momentum was definitely building,'' said Parnevik, who
played brilliantly Friday and Saturday, teaming with Sergio Garcia
to go 3-0-1 in foursome and four-ball competition. ``When they got
the first six matches easily, the crowd is going to get more
involved. They just got huge momentum going.''
</P>
<P>
   With each putt that fell, with each match that went in favor of
the United States, the crescendo of noise echoing through the trees
became louder. The Europeans heard every roar, and the pressure on
them became greater.
</P>
<P>
   There was nowhere to hide, nowhere to run. During the team
format Friday and Saturday, the Europeans played together
beautifully, but team captain Mark James gambled, asking his best
players to carry most of the load. Seven Europeans played five
matches in three days, while James benched Van de Velde, Coltart
and Sandelin until Sunday. Of the seven Europeans who played all
five matches _ Westwood, Clarke, Parnevik, Padraig Harrington,
Miguel Angel Jimenez, Colin Montgomerie and Garcia _ five of them
lost Sunday. The three players whom James benched until Sunday also
lost, but James disagreed that his strategy had backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were outplayed,'' he said. ``I don't think we were
outmaneuvered. They came out screeching. It was quite remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   After Steve Pate defeated Jimenez, 3 and 2, Jim Furyk delivered
another huge triumph for the United States by dominating Garcia, 4
and 3, before Leonard's match was over. That left the United States
only { point from victory, and Leonard's putter took care of the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the NBC golf analyst Johnny Miller felt that
Crenshaw should have played Jeff Maggert in the afternoon instead
of Leonard, who was struggling at the time. Crenshaw said he played
Leonard because of a hunch, but Miller said, ``I have a hunch
Justin Leonard should go home and watch it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's victory, Leonard said, ``It's a good thing I
didn't go home.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was a good thing for the Americans that they never
stopped believing. They were in bad straits, being criticized for
trailing a team they were expected to beat, facing the prospect of
losing the Ryder Cup for the third consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they created one of the most memorable team comebacks
in sports, rallying to win an event that seems to grow in magnitude
as the years pass. When the Ryder Cup began in 1927, who could have
pictured a scene like Sunday's, with more then 30,000 people in the
gallery, from all over the world, their emotions swaying with each
shot? It is the most pressure-packed atmosphere in golf, and the
U.S. players met the challenge. When the next Ryder Cup is played
in 2001 at The Belfry in Sutton Coldfield, England, Europe will be
determined to win the cup back. But Sunday, it was finally the
Americans' turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left here last night,'' Crenshaw allowed, ``I said,
`We're in good shape.' Darned if we didn't pull it off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
