u a BC-NY-BUTTERFLY-DEATHS-9     09-26 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUTTERFLY-DEATHS-900(TRIMS)&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRAYING OF INSECTICIDE BY CITY MAY HARM MIGRATING MONARCHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Each September and October, many thousands of monarch
butterflies pass through New York City on their way from the
Northeast and Canada to Mexico for the winter. But with the city
spraying insecticide to kill mosquitoes that may carry
encephalitis, there is concern that this leg of an already
treacherous migration could prove more dangerous than usual.
</P>
<P>
   And while this year's butterfly migration began with near-record
numbers, no one can know if it might have been even larger without
the spraying of the insecticide malathion.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Spevak, the curator of invertebrates at the Bronx Zoo,
said he received a call last week from a jogger who had found a
number of dead monarch butterflies in Central Park shortly after
the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was running shortly after the truck passed,'' he said,
``and she started noticing all these monarchs dropping around
her.''
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that it would be ``very difficult to determine'' if
malathion had killed the butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that Bronx Zoo officials have asked the city not to
spray over the zoo because of the danger to its Butterfly Zone
exhibit, a caterpillar-shaped tent that houses hundreds of
butterflies from around the world. Instead, zoo workers have
sprayed specific trouble spots themselves, Spevak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to destroy the migration,'' he said. ``But the
migration itself is an ecological phenomenon found nowhere else in
the world. This is just something else to hinder its progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the city does spray, it can wipe out a few hundred, even
a few thousand, and in a migration of 100 million monarchs, that's
very small. But every little bit seems to nibble away at the
chain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Glassberg, president of the North American Butterfly
Association, based in Morristown, N.J., questioned the wholesale
spraying of malathion, preferring more selective methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spraying for mosquitoes can have a dramatic effect on
butterfly populations,'' he said. ``I think it's an extremely
unfortunate situation.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Monarch butterflies are being spotted at a vigorous rate of 106
an hour at the Cape May Bird Observatory. On Sept. 19 and Sept. 20,
butterflies that might have been hunkering down during tropical
storm Hugo took wing in large numbers, said Nicholas Wagerik, an
amateur naturalist who studies wildlife in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed it in Manhattan, and in other places, people said it
was just spectacular,'' he said. ``Every flower in Brooklyn Heights
had a monarch on it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pesticides, migrating monarchs face another
obstacle particular to urban areas: they must leap tall buildings
using very small wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some research showing they don't try to go around
buildings,'' said Dick Walton, director of the Monarch Monitoring
Project in Cape May, part of the New Jersey Audubon Society.
Instead, he said, they go up and over buildings, riding rising air
currents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monarchs migrate by using thermals, rising columns of air, to
gain altitude,'' Walton said. ``Then they set their wings and go
south from that. It's like going up an elevator and going south,
then going up another elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had to flap the whole way, they just wouldn't make it.
It's a high-risk occupation, with some of that due to traffic, and
more to weather, when monarchs are blown out into sea.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as a very few monarch butterflies slid by in the
wind, Don Riepe, a naturalist at the Jamaica Bay Wildlife Refuge,
worried why there weren't more.
</P>
<P>
   Four thousand migrating monarchs passed over Rockaway Beach on
Sept. 19, according to Riepe's count, but late in the week, the
wind had shifted, so any southbound butterflies were probably
waiting for a tailwind in the shelter of the undergrowth. Still, he
wondered if the city's spraying campaign might have had something
to do with the absence of wings in the air. He also worried about
damage to eggs and caterpillars, which grow into monarchs and other
butterflies, after the spraying of the leaves they live on.
</P>
<P>
   New York City has 85 species of butterflies, more than are found
in all of England, Glassberg said. The Jamaica Bay refuge counts
among its visitors the wild indigo duskywing, the little wood
satyr, the swarthy skipper and the cosmopolitan painted lady.
</P>
<P>
   Honeybees are also at risk from malathion. Labels on some
packages of malathion read ``Toxic to bees, do not spray blooms.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   David Graves, who works with urban beekeepers and sells New York
City honey to markets in Manhattan, said it was good for the bees
that the spraying occurs at night, when they are back in their
hives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This encephalitis is quite dangerous, and human life is the
number one concern,'' he said. ``So certainly, if it can save one
or two lives, then the spraying is a good thing.'' Because the
nectar that bees use to make honey is sealed within a flower's
blossoms, it is unlikely that the spraying would contaminate urban
honey, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Mullin, a spokeswoman for the New York City Health
Department, acknowledged that insecticides like malathion can
affect other insects, but she said she could not talk specifically
about bees and butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it remains to be seen what impact that may have had on
insects other than mosquitoes,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After a long, dry summer that did not inspire her rooftop bees
to produce much honey, Jill Laurie Goodman, of West 113th Street,
added over the weekend another ``super'' to one of her hives _ a
box of honeycomb that would accommodate a recent overflow of
nectar.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Melvin Bukiet, had different ideas about
the effects of the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are tough New York City bees. They can handle it,''
Bukiet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know,'' Ms. Goodman replied. ``These are tough
New York City mosquitoes, unfortunately.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
