<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETDOC-HOUSECALLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW MEDICAL TECHNOLOGY CREATES ONLINE `HOUSE CALLS'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BENNY EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Each morning when 82-year-old Jack Watt awakens, he
takes his blood pressure, times his pulse and checks his weight.
</P>
<P>
   Watt has a continuing heart condition and a high red blood cell
count that require constant medical monitoring. But thanks to an
emerging use of technology in the medical field, he doesn't have to
leave his Scotts Valley trailer home to check in with his doctor.
</P>
<P>
   He just sits at his computer, logs on to the Internet and enters
his daily vital signs, which then can be read by a nurse at a
health company data center in South San Francisco, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those numbers begin to bounce around, then I can expect a
call from one of the nurses, who asks me what's going on,'' Watt
said. ``There's a sense of security and a feeling that I just can't
lose as long as I keep putting (the data) in.''
</P>
<P>
   In-person doctor house calls, a common practice when Watt
started his career as a building inspector for the city of San
Mateo (Calif.) shortly after World War II, have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But now Watt is on the leading edge of a new medical trend that
could become commonplace in just a few short years: the virtual
house call.
</P>
<P>
   Digital doctors and Net nurses won't replace their real
counterparts in hospitals or clinics. But a combination of
computers or new home medical devices and the Internet could keep
certain at-risk patients from winding up in the hospital for urgent
_ and expensive _ treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Web already is littered with thousands of health care sites
that dispense every type of medical advice imaginable. Now, experts
say, personalized online home health management is the next big
revolution in the medical industry.
</P>
<P>
   Watt, who had an aortic valve replacement two years ago, is part
of a pilot online network set up by LifeMasters, a disease
management company with headquarters in Newport Beach (Calif.) and
a call center in South San Francisco (Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   With the LifeMasters system, Watt types his vital signs and any
symptoms daily into a computer and transmits them to the data
center. LifeMasters provided the computer and the service free for
the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses hired by LifeMasters monitor his health data and look for
any unusual changes, such as a sudden weight gain, that might
require immediate attention. The patients and their doctors can
access the information on a private Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Starting October 1, LifeMasters, which has Intel Corp. as a
major investor, will team up with TheHealthNetwork.com, which
operates a consumer health cable TV network and an Internet site,
to offer the same type of online medical services directly to
consumers. LifeMasters will launch  &LR; both  &LR; a free service and a more
personalized version for an undetermined subscription fee.
</P>
<P>
   Online monitoring programs are best suited for chronic diseases
like congestive heart failure, diabetes and high blood pressure,
which are the most costly for health plans to treat if left
unchecked. The programs can also be used to monitor conditions such
as asthma and depression.
</P>
<P>
   Health Hero Network Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., is marketing
an answering machine-size home appliance called the Health Buddy
for patients with chronic problems. As with the LifeMasters system,
the Health Buddy asks patients to punch in their vital signs and
answer questions posed by their doctors such as, ``Did you have
trouble breathing last night?''
</P>
<P>
   The answers are transmitted to an Internet site, where they can
be accessed by the physician.
</P>
<P>
   Alere Medical Inc. of San Francisco announced last week during a
meeting of the Heart Failure Society of America that it is
launching a physician-to-patient Internet system using its device,
the DayLink Monitor. The monitor is an electronic weight scale with
a view screen that displays daily health questions and transmits
the answers to a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   At the same trade show, held in San Francisco, Hewlett-Packard
Co.'s $1.3 billion-per-year medical products division displayed new
home medical devices equipped with cordless radio transmitters.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic blood pressure cuff, electrocardiogram and weight
scale each can automatically beam the patient's data to a home
network hub, which is plugged into a phone jack. From there, the
data are transmitted to an Internet site for retrieval by the
patient's doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to keep the patients out of the hospital by
keeping them healthier and happier, which helps health plans save
money,'' said Tom Shoup, operations manager for HP's New Clinical
Ventures group, which is seeking Federal Drug Administration
approval to market the new devices.
</P>
<P>
   All major health care providers around the country are looking
at some type of online patient monitoring to lower costs, said Dr.
David Kaplan, a health industry consultant for management firm
Towers Perrin &UR;  &LR; of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   There are new online health tracking products ``coming up every
day'' and the market is potentially huge, Kaplan said. ``With the
aging of the population, there will be more people with these
chronic diseases who might indeed benefit from this kind of
technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 1997 study by the American College of Cardiology
found that treatment for the estimated 4.8 million Americans with
congestive heart failure costs as much as $38 billion per year,
including $23 million for hospitalization. Other studies showed
education, daily review of medications and close monitoring could
reduce readmissions by more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Online monitoring can reveal subtle symptoms not normally
detected unless the patient visits the doctor daily. For example,
an overnight weight gain of 5 pounds may be caused by eating too
many pieces of a large pepperoni pizza, or could be a sign the
patient is retaining fluid that is making it more difficult for the
heart to pump.
</P>
<P>
   Health Hero Network CEO Steve Brown said he can sell his
company's service to HMOs and other health care providers for less
than $1 a day per patient. ``Our basic value proposition to our
customers is to replace a $10,000 hospitalization with a $100
office visit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Software programs used with the online monitoring can flag a
sudden weight gain so a nurse or doctor can follow up to learn if
the patient has a simple problem or one that requires immediate
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 percent of the cases, we found it was not because they
ate something wrong,'' said LifeMasters CEO Christobel E. Selecky.
``We've created a feedback loop that never existed before.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry ``Hut'' Hutton and his wife, Shirl Hutton, have heart
conditions and use the LifeMasters online system.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Cruz (Calif.) couple, both in their late 70s, became
concerned when Hut Hutton's blood pressure was higher just after he
woke up than later in the day. So, two weeks ago, his doctor
changed his medication schedule to help even out his blood pressure
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can turn the tide by breaking his medication into
two doses,'' Shirl Hutton said. ``Without the daily blood pressure
monitoring, we never would have noticed his blood pressure was so
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Cupertino resident Ed Madden, 78, used the LifeMasters program
until his medical group, the Santa Clara County (Calif.) Individual
Practice Association, switched to the Health Buddy about three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Madden said he has had heart problems for 15 years and has
landed in the hospital several times ``because my heart goes wacky
on me,'' but the two online monitoring programs have helped him
lead a healthier lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go to the grocery store, we never buy anything without
turning it over and reading the nutritional facts,'' Madden said.
``The Health Buddy is a self-disciplining tool. You get to where
you're aware of what you're doing, what you're eating and what
exercise you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts in the medical community say there is no longer a debate
about whether online technology should be used to treat patients in
their homes, only a question of what is the most effective use of
that technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just at the tip of the iceberg in terms of using this
kind of technology to gather data and trying to figure out how to
implement this in a proactive way to keep patients out of the
hospital,'' said Dr. Alan Giberson, associate medical director of
the Santa Clara County Individual Practice Association, which has
800 physicians and 125,000 HMO members.
</P>
<P>
   Giberson said there are about 35 association patients like
Madden now using the Health Buddy. Although there is not enough
meaningful data available to prove how well the device works, ``we
think we have prevented some hospitalizations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Aria DiBiase, a cardiologist at the Palo Alto (Calif.)
Medical Foundation, said he has about 27 patients using the Alere
DayLink Monitor. While historically about half of congestive heart
failure patients are hospitalized in a year, DiBiase said only six
in the Alere group have required hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no substitute for face-to-face encounters,'' said
DiBiase, who is also a board member of Alere Medical. But, she
said, the daily monitoring has helped because ``I have several
patients who are not going to call me unless they are in dire
straits.''
</P>
<P>
   Having technology that is easy to use is key, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average age of the patients is 79. We're talking about
using technology in a way that can interface with very disabled,
very technophobic people. These are not people who are surfing the
Net; these are people who still have rotary phones.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirl Hutton said she has embraced the technology, which has
given her the information and support to cope with her own heart
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having my own cheering section for my health,'' she
said. ``It makes me more secure that I can function more
independently. I've never met my nurse face to face, but I feel as
though I have already hugged her. We have a warm log-in
relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
