<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JETS AND METS PRODUCE A SPLIT-SCREEN NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Fifteen days ago everything seemed so
certain: The football Jets began their Super Bowl quest on top of
the world; the baseball Mets were two and a half games ahead of
Cincinnati for the wild-card berth and breathing down Atlanta's
neck for the division title.
</P>
<P>
   Jets and Mets fans wake up Monday morning to a world of
shattered dreams and shrunken horizons. The Jets lost by 27-10 to
Washington Sunday and fell to 0-3. The Mets lost by 3-2 in
Philadelphia for their sixth consecutive defeat. A football team
that was thinking Super Bowl is wondering if it will win again; a
baseball team that seriously considered a division championship
might not even make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than two weeks, New Yorkers have seen the Jets
and the Mets unravel, have watched a manager offer his head on a
platter and a head coach who was said to be able to walk on water
consider using water wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough time for me,'' Jets coach Bill Parcells said
Sunday. ``This continues to be a tough time until we figure out how
to handle this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday I was at Giants Stadium with my radio, switching
between watching the Jets and listening to the Mets and not
believing what I was seeing and hearing.
</P>
<P>
   This was an afternoon of contrasting fortunes for the city's
Little Engine That Could teams, and if you walked around the
stadium you heard collective moans and groans from Jets fans who
were also Mets fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets took a 14-13 lead in the third quarter at the same time
Philadelphia increased its lead to 3-0 over the Mets. Just as the
Jets fell behind Washington for good, the Mets had a last-gasp
rally in the ninth, loading the bases with one out and Rickey
Henderson at bat. Giants Stadium was a cacophony of baseball cheers
and football roars.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans had their ears glued to radios and eyes riveted on the
field, ever hopeful of a double miracle. One seemed to unfold at
Giants Stadium when Keyshawn Johnson, the Jets' talented wide
receiver, caught an apparent touchdown pass that would have pulled
the Jets to within 27-24. But the play was reviewed and the catch
negated. Fans simultaneously received bad news from Philadelphia:
Henderson hit into a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Since just last Tuesday, these two franchises, which have
overcome so much stumbling to reach respectability, find themselves
in the midst of a nightmare. On Saturday, Mets manager Bobby
Valentine offered his head if the Mets were to fail in reaching the
postseason. ``If we don't go to the playoffs,'' he said, ``I
shouldn't come back next year.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Parcells, who would never admit that kind of
vulnerability or second-guessing, stood before reporters for the
first time up to his knees in Jets mess: fumbles, botched
assignments, blown calls and blown plays that ripped the heart out
of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm biting my lip,'' he said. ``This is the first time I had
to bite my lip in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Biting his lip about what? The officiating? The Jets were
penalized eight times for 86 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A pass interference call against Ray Mickens led to Washington's
go-ahead touchdown. An assortment of holding penalties killed other
Jet drives. Rick Mirer fumbled, Mickens was called for another pass
interference, and Washington then went ahead, 20-17. Late in the
game, the officials ruled that a Stephen Davis fumble, which was
picked up by the Jets' Aaron Glenn, was not really a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Parcells was biting his lip because of the failure of
his offensive coordinator to find a way to consistently get the
ball to Johnson. Johnson, the Jets' only game-breaking threat on
offense, had one catch in the first half. He finished with three,
even though he was being covered by a rookie defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Parcells was biting his lip to avoid blasting Mickens, who
was beaten on several plays and penalized three times for pass
interference.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Parcells is exploding at the frustration of an 0-3 team
and a free fall with no end in sight. He didn't offer his
resignation, as Valentine has, or take the blame for his team's
failure. He just said, ``It doesn't look very good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure if the Jets or the Mets have farther to fall. The
Mets open with Atlanta Tuesday and could be out of the playoff
picture by Thursday night. The Jets have to travel a longer, more
tortuous road: They have 13 weeks to figure out a solution or 13
weeks to dangle.
</P>
<P>
   This has the potential to be one of the most depressing autumn
interludes in recent New York sports seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the somber chaos of the Jets' locker room _ some players
staying to talk, others scurrying to get away _ Bryan Cox, the
veteran linebacker, said that all he wanted to do was get a hug
from his kids, relax and go home and listen to some jazz.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure whether Cox likes Miles Davis, but he might want to
try ``Kind of Blue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
