<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-BEHAVIOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATION ANGERS EUROPEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GLF-RYDER-CUP) 
(js) 
 By BILL BRINK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Flattened by a U.S. team that was roaring
toward the biggest comeback in Ryder Cup history, the best golfers
in Europe left here Sunday stunned by their defeat and irritated by
the behavior of the U.S. golfers and their fans. Though most of the
combativeness involved the galleries at The Country Club the past
week, on Sunday the Europeans targeted the U.S. players for what
they believed was an excessive celebration on the 17th green late
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   While many of his teammates sat by the side of the green and
cheered him on, Justin Leonard rolled in a spectacular 45-foot putt
that was, in effect, the winning stroke in the competition. He
pumped his fists and ran along the edge of the green to join his
colleagues in a joyous mob, all while Jose Maria Olazabal waited to
hit a putt that could have halved the hole and kept the match tied.
After waiting for the celebration to die down, and stepping away
from his ball once, Olazabal missed his putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of behavior is not what anybody expects,'' Olazabal
said later at a news conference in which a number of Europeans
conducted what seemed like a group lecture on civility. ``It was
very sad to see. It was an ugly picture to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotion, yes. But I think we proved that most of the time we
behaved like we should.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the 1997 Ryder Cup in Spain. ``I think we showed
that at Valderrama,'' he said. ``I don't want to make a whole thing
of this. It just shouldn't have happened. Show respect for your
opponent. As long as you do that, you can cheer all you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin Montgomerie, who sparred all week with American
spectators, was playing behind Leonard and Olazabal and waiting to
tee off on the par-3 hole. ``I couldn't believe what I was
seeing,'' he said. ``I couldn't believe it. I thought they'd all
just walk off and head to the 18th green. I couldn't believe it
cleared and he was left on his own to make a putt.''
</P>
<P>
   As Montgomerie was explaining that he did not think the incident
affected the outcome of the competition, Jesper Parnevik
interrupted and said, ``But that's not the point, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   The European captain, Mark James, said, ``I would like to think
it wouldn't happen with my team,'' but he added that he did not
expect an apology from his counterpart, Ben Crenshaw. He got one
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know what happened,'' Crenshaw said. ``We do apologize
sincerely. The celebration spilled over. It's really something
we're not proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard later took the blame, saying he should not have run on
the green toward his teammates but should have walked to them. ``I
do apologize for that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Europeans congratulated the Americans and praised
their play. ``We came up short because the Americans rode a great
streak,'' James said. ``It's as simple as that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-DISPUTE-510     09-26 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-DISPUTE-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S THREATS MAKE EXHIBITION A HOT TOPIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani accused the Brooklyn Museum of
Art on Sunday of resorting to ``disgusting commercial
sensationalism'' in planning to exhibit modern British works that
he said were offensive to Catholics, but it was the mayor's
repeated threats against the museum that kept the exhibit a buzzing
topic of conversation throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   In church services and across tables over Sunday brunch, on the
streets, in the parks and in the corridors of the Brooklyn Museum
itself, the brouhaha showed no sign of letting up. And the opinions
of New Yorkers suggested that the debate was not simply one of free
expression but of who should pay to put free expression on display.
</P>
<P>
   That the mayor's attacks have already drawn great attention to
the exhibit was clear Sunday afternoon, when Kim Gosa, 33, of
Jersey City, N.J., arrived at the museum thinking that the show,
which is to open on Saturday, was already on display. ``I'm going
to come back next week to see what it's all about for myself,'' she
said. ``I'm actually very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who last week threatened to terminate the museum's
lease with the city, cut all of its city financing and even seize
control of the museum's board of directors if the show was not
canceled, was unrelenting Sunday. Told that some museum officials
wanted to meet with him, the mayor, at his daily news conference,
said he did not think anything useful could come of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am baffled by what they have done,'' he said. ``I do not
understand why you would take a venerable institution like this and
reduce it to the worst kind of disgusting commercial
sensationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I understand they want to make money, but this is
what you do like on the 42nd Street of about 20 years ago, not what
you do at a venerable and great museum.''
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly homily at St. Patrick's Cathedral on Sunday,
Cardinal John O'Connor did not mention Giuliani by name, but he
expressed gratitude to ``city officials'' and said, ``It is their
right, if not their duty, to express themselves on such matters.''
He urged parishioners to write to the museum to express offense at
the show, which features a portrait of the Virgin Mary adorned with
pornographic pictures and elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am saddened by what appears to be an attack not only on our
Blessed Mother,'' the cardinal said, adding, ``one must ask if it
is not an attack on religion itself and in a special way on the
Catholic Church.''
</P>
<P>
   But in another church, in Harlem, Norman Siegel, the executive
director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, offered to go to
court on behalf of the Brooklyn Museum to protect the show.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel, who was a guest speaker at St. Mary's Episcopal Church,
said after the Sunday service that he was eager to represent the
museum against the Giuliani administration. ``If the museum wants
us, we will go to court for them,'' he said. ``We are ready,
willing and able to go to court. I think this would be a landmark
First Amendment decision that unfortunately has been created by the
mayor.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He noted that the show, called ``Sensation: Young British
Artists From the Saatchi Collection,'' had already been on display
in England and in Germany. ``London dealt with this exhibit,'' he
said. ``Berlin dealt with this exhibit. Are we saying that New York
can't do what London and Berlin did with regard to this exhibit?''
He also criticized other museums for not defending their sister
institution in Brooklyn more vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Herbert Daughtry, pastor of the House of the Lord
Church in Brooklyn, told The Associated Press on Sunday that he
disagreed with the mayor. ``If the mayor wants to protest this
artwork as a citizen, it's one thing,'' he said, ``but to say, `I'm
going to use the machinery of government to punish you,' it borders
on dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Field, 18, a freshman at Pratt Institute, who was visiting
the museum on Sunday, said he was outraged by Giuliani's threats.
``I don't believe the government should fund individual artists,''
he said. ``But funding shouldn't be taken away from the museum. To
say, `This show is offensive, we're cutting the funding,' is
absurd. I find the mayor offensive, but that doesn't mean I'm going
to stop paying my taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
