<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990926.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6845 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DELL-GATEWAY-SFCHRON &LR;      09-26 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-GATEWAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DELL AND GATEWAY PUSH DIRECT PC MARKETING
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Families planning to put a new PC under the tree
this Christmas are more likely than ever to bypass local dealers
and instead order directly from the manufacturer by phone or over
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   And while virtually every major PC-maker now sells some of its
products this way, the two big winners from this trend are likely
to be the two companies that pioneered direct-to-the-customer
sales, Dell and Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is coming on strong in the consumer arena, after
concentrating for years on business buyers. But Gateway still holds
a long lead and continues to build on its base with a new network
of local showrooms and other marketing innovations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Dell turned up the heat last week with a barrage of marketing
initiatives aimed at home users, backed by a new TV and print ad
campaign under the rubric ``Dell4Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the announcements: the first Dell notebook PC that isn't
black _ the Inspiron 3700, priced at $1,899 and up, will be
available in either ``Storm Grey'' or ``Tahoe Blue.'' Dell is also
moving to capitalize on The downloadable digital music craze,
announcing plans to include MP3 software and offer the RIO 500, the
latest version of the pocket-sized MP3 player from Diamond
Multimedia, as an option with some models.
</P>
<P>
   To further differentiate itself from retail competitors, Dell
also offers to preconfigure its systems with advanced networking
options. Last week it announced a deal with the ExciteAtHome cable
Internet service, under which Dell customers will be able to add
high-speed Internet access when ordering a consumer desktop or a
notebook PC. Dell promises it will take care of all the necessary
arrangements, so customers won't have to make extra calls to
ExciteAtHome or their cable company.
</P>
<P>
   Dell also plans to offer products and services to customers who
want to connect multiple PCs into a home network through their
telephone wiring. The company plans to launch the program within a
few weeks, when key players in the networking industry are expected
to ratify a new standard promising faster data transfers. Dell said
it's also working hard to simplify setup, previously a daunting
experience, by creating its own clear directions, an interactive CD
tutorial and a video guide.
</P>
<P>
   In offering such services, Dell is simply building on its
traditional advantages, said Dataquest analyst Van Baker. ``They're
just leveraging their longtime leadership in the direct market,''
he said. ``Competitors who sell through dealers can't very well put
together packages like these, because they wouldn't sell enough.
But Dell can strike these deals with the telecom companies and
music companies, and if even a few customers want the products,
they can get just what they want with one order.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's push into the consumer arena is built on its success in
the business market, where it recently passed Compaq as the No. 1
PC supplier. ``They have execution down to a science in the
commercial space,'' said IDC analyst Gabrielle Griffith. ``Now that
the consumer market is exploding, there's a huge opportunity for
them to leverage their success.''
</P>
<P>
   Dataquest's Baker pointed out another way its huge business base
gives Dell a leg up in the consumer race: ``A lot of people use
Dell PCs at work and like what they see,'' he said, ``so when
they're in the market for a home PC, it's natural for them to look
to the same supplier.''
</P>
<P>
   An experienced customer base has another advantage &UR;  &LR; for both
companies, but especially for Dell: Second- and third-time buyers
tend to purchase more powerful PCs and advanced options, such as
the company's new broadband and home-networking options. That
translates into higher average selling prices and much fatter
margins, compared with the sub-$600 systems that increasingly
dominate retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In the second quarter of this year, for example, the average
selling price of Dell PCs purchased by U.S. consumers was $1,765,
including a monitor and other add-ons, according to IDC. For
Gateway, the comparable number was $1,586, while for Compaq it was
only $1,301.
</P>
<P>
   While Baker and other analysts are bullish on Dell, Gateway
still enjoys a substantial lead and a record of innovation in the
consumer PC arena. And the company, which now has corporate
headquarters in San Diego, Calif., but still boasts about its roots
in South Dakota, has long cultivated a down-to-earth, just-folks
image, in contrast to Dell's image as a favorite of big business
and the high-tech elite.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway's most visible recent initiative is its Country Store
program, under which it has opened local showrooms and marketing
centers in 185 cities around the country. (The first in the Sab
Francisco Bay Area is in Colma.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the name, these facilities aren't stores in the
traditional sense, because they have no inventory, just demo units,
on hand. Customers can come in, examine Gateway products and talk
to salespeople, then place their orders at the store or go home and
order later over the phone or the Internet. The equipment is
shipped to the customer from Gateway's assembly plants, typically
arriving within five to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to satisfying some customers' need to ``kick the
tires,'' having local facilities allows Gateway to offer programs
it would be tough for Dell to match, such as training classes and
consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   The stores are by no means Gateway's first innovation in
consumer marketing. ``Gateway has always had the leading thinking
in the consumer space,'' said Lou Mazzuchelli, analyst at Gerard
Klauer Mattison. It was first among major PC vendors to create its
own Internet service, Gateway.net, launched almost two years ago;
Dell didn't come up with a similar program until July of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway also pioneered Your:)Ware, a financing program, launched
in May 1998, that allows buyers to pay for a PC in monthly
installments. It also offers some degree of protection against
obsolescence _ a major fear for many consumers _ by promising a
credit if the customer wants to trade in the machine for a newer
model. In June of this year, Dell launched a 48-month payment
program, but without the trade-up option.
</P>
<P>
   And while no one would compare Gateway to Steve Jobs' Apple in
innovative design, the company has shown some notable sparks of
creativity, with models like te Destination, which combines a PC
with a big-screen TV, and the Profile, a pricey but elegant
all-in-one unit built around a sleek flat-screen monitor. And
company officials say they'll have yet another eye-catching new
model later this fall.
</P>
<P>
   While Dell still focuses on experienced PC users, the Country
Stores and other Gateway innovations have helped it win over
increasing numbers of novices. Traditionally, many such buyers have
hesitated to deal with far-away direct vendors, on the theory that
a local dealer would provide better service and support. But that
logic, analysts say, no longer holds, because both Dell and Gateway
are so big, and have invested so heavily in customer service, that
they now offer much better support than almost any local dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the two leaders, for example, provide lifetime toll-free
support on most models, and it's available 24 hours a day, seven
days a week. Both have also developed sophisticated online support
technologies, making it easy for users to find help on the Web.
Dell licensed search technology from AskJeeves and used to build a
site called AskDudley, where customers can pose their questions in
plain English and get immediate answers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers' increasing familiarity and comfort with e-commerce is
also helping the two direct-sales leaders. For users who've learned
to buy CDs, pet food, cars and almost everything else over the Web,
it's no big deal to buy a new PC that way.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, both companies are in a strong position in the
consumer market, analysts say. ``There's more room for Dell to grow
in this segment, because they're starting from behind,'' said
Baker, ``but Gateway still has a big lead with consumers, and Dell
isn't likely to catch them anytime soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
