 HERB ADVOCATE CALLS FOR MORE RESEARCH AND RULES ON SUPPLEMENTS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Bill McGlashan is one of those rare executives who
wants more &LR;   &LR; regulation of his industry. As president of Pharmanex,
a Burlingame (Calif.) maker of herbal remedies, McGlashan explained
his unusual wish.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmanex is among dozens of firms that sell herbal supplements
like St. John's Wort, echinacea and ginseng. Many Americans seem to
believe that an herb a day keeps the doctor away. That might
account for the fact that domestic spending on herbals has doubled
since 1994, to an estimated $4.5 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   But McGlashan isn't content to rely on folk wisdom to sustain
the American appetite for potions. He wants to do scientific
studies that would ask, for instance, whether a chemical in green
tea fights cancer.
</P>
<P>
   As consumers, we might applaud Pharmanex for funding such
studies, but as investors, we'd have to ask whether McGlashan
hasn't been smoking something herbal.
</P>
<P>
   It all gets back to the laws that govern his business _ laws
that McGlashan wants to tighten.
</P>
<P>
   At present, herb sales are governed by the Dietary Supplements
and Health Education Act.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike drugs, which must be tested and approved in advance by
the Food and Drug Administration, DSHEA assumes that herbs are safe
because people have been consuming them for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But DSHEA prevents herb vendors from making health claims. If a
manufacturer can't advertise that echinacea wards off flu, for
instance, what incentive would a company have to study whether the
folk wisdom is true?
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to spend $15 million on research this year, and a lot
of it ends up being like philanthropy,'' McGlashan says.
</P>
<P>
   If his study shows a health benefit for green tea, for example,
he can't tout it on his label. And even if health reporters
publicize the findings, Pharmanex has to share the benefit. Any
herbmaker can bottle tea extract and cash in on Pharmanex's
findings.
</P>
<P>
   That's why McGlashan wants Congress to draft stricter rules for
herb sales modeled after laws in Germany. According to McGlashan,
German firms that sponsor research about the health benefits of
herbs get two benefits: They can put the claim on their label and
get a 10-year monopoly on the sale of the herb to establish a brand
before competing makers can offer ``generic'' herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, funding a study isn't the same as discovering a drug.
Some might argue that this policy would give an unfair advantage to
vendors with deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Such a rule change is hardly imminent, but key members of
Congress are aware of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to manufacturers about how we might provide
incentives to do research on health effects,'' says an aide to
Rep. &QL; 
Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the government reform committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McGlashan, who formed his company to commercialize
Chinese medicine, might recall the proverb: Be careful what you
wish for.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD FEUD: ``We're crazy hippies gathered in front of this
place, singing songs and trying to be heard,'' said one speaker at
a protest against genetically engineered foods held Thursday at the
Pacific Stock Exchange in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people turned out for the noontime rally organized by
Bob Cantisano, an organic farmer from Grass Valley, Calif. His
basic complaint is that current rules assume genetically engineered
crops are safe. ``When pesticides came out in the 1940s and 1950s,
it was 30 years before we discovered the problems,'' Cantisano
said. ``We don't want to wait 30 years to find the problems with
G.E. foods. It should be `guilty until proven innocent.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, industry executives have started a counteroffensive
to make sure such activist sentiment doesn't become a mainstream
concern in the United States _ as already has occurred in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reassure (consumers) and be activists somewhat
ourselves,'' Ed Shonsey, president of Novartis Seeds Inc., told
Bloomberg News. Monsanto President Hendrik Verfaillie said dealing
with the controversy over genetic engineering has become ``my No. 1
priority besides delivering financial results.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The controversy over genetic crops may be affecting the
performance of firms like Monsanto, whose shares have slid nearly
50 percent since last fall. At least that was the argument made by
the one guy who wore a suit to Thursday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment banks have cautioned investors that G.E. foods are
a liability,'' said Thomas Van Dyck, who wore two hats _ as well as
his tie _ to the rally. Van Dyck is president of As You Sow, a
nonprofit group in Oakland, Calif., that supports organic farming.
He also is managing director of the socially responsible investing
fund for PiperJaffray in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest investors in America are teachers and their
pension funds,'' said Van Dyck, suggesting that investors, not
street protests, will determine the future of genetically
engineered crops.
</P>
<P>
   MICROBE HUNTERS: Viruses, fungi and germs, oh my!
</P>
<P>
   Those words will be on the lips of 12,000 scientists who will
gather at Moscone Center in San Francisco for the Interscience
Conference on Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy, which started
yesterday and runs through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the world's foremost gathering of microbe hunters, ICAAC
draws three types of people who are interested in these tiny,
disease-causing organisms.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third are clinical doctors who treat a variety of
diseases, said Dr. George Miller, research chief at Microcide
Pharmaceuticals in Mountain View, Calif., and a member of the
conference's governing board. Another third are academic scientists
who develop novel disease-fighting agents. Drug and biotech
executives round out the mix.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as in years past, the conference will focus on
discoveries in the field of AIDS, the most feared viral disease.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller also expects the conference to produce a buzz about
new remedies for less deadly viral diseases like the flu or the
summer cold.
</P>
<P>
   Another important strain of discussion will be new strategies
for fighting germs or, more specifically, bacteria, which are
becoming resistant to antibiotics. Microcide is among the firms in
the early stages of testing new drugs to combat such
antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Fungal infections and remedies also will be on the conference
agenda, but frankly, they haven't gotten the press of the
better-known microbes.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting microbes is a huge business. Antibacterials alone
command $23 billion in worldwide sales. So even though this is a
scientific gathering, drug and biotech firms set up commercial
displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies with products near approval want to create interest
among the clinicians,'' Miller explains. Companies about to launch
early tests also might want to set up a booth. ``It's the best
place to recruit the experimenters who will help in the clinical
trials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Look for BioScope every Monday in the Business section. Send
your biofeedback to Tom Abate by e-mail at abate &LR; sfgate.com; fax
(415) 543-2482, phone (415) 777-6213.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 4 of BIOSCOPE () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
