<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-PACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CALM FAVRE PICKS APART THE VIKINGS' DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre had the ball
in his hands, about two minutes to go on the clock, and the
undivided attention of the Minnesota Vikings. There was a sense of
dread that he was about to do something to ruin their day. They
were right.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most exciting games this season, Green Bay beat
the Vikings, 23-20, after Favre, his team trailing by four points
with one minute 51 seconds left, took the Packers 77 yards in seven
plays, calmly tossing for the winning touchdown as the clock hit 16
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After the score, Favre ran across the field, pumping his fists.
This is the kind of ending that could propel the Packers toward a
title and send the already struggling Vikings into a further state
of depression.
</P>
<P>
   Favre's final drive will go down as one of the best this season.
In almost John Elway-like calm, Favre slowly moved his team down
the field, eating up real estate in large and small chunks. The
Vikings, barely able to pressure him, watched helplessly as he
sliced up their defense.
</P>
<P>
   The final cut occurred on fourth-and-one at the Minnesota 23.
Favre stepped behind center with almost no visible emotion, as if
he were browsing through a library, and after dropping back and
feeling some pressure, rolled slightly to his left. That is when he
found wide receiver Corey Bradford streaking into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   When Minnesota got the ball back, quarterback Randall
Cunningham's first pass was incomplete. His second one, some 50
yards downfield, was intercepted by cornerback Antuan Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers improved to 2-1 while the Vikings fell to 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the way our offense constantly kept its composure,''
Favre said. ``That was just a great drive on our part.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's loss continues the bizarre downward spiral of last
year's final four teams. Atlanta, Denver and the Jets also lost
Sunday, bringing their combined record to a sorry 1-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough loss,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green said. ``But
we got beat by a very good team today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota-Green Bay rivalry has grown into one nasty affair.
Throughout the game, with 59,868 rabid cheeseheads cheering, there
were head butts, a few scuffles, lots of jawing by Vikings wide
receiver Cris Carter, and even a few punches to the groin.
</P>
<P>
   What there was not were those jaw-dropping deep passes to Randy
Moss. He had only one catch in the first half, a quick screen in
the flat. Superman looked very ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he was anything but average. In two games against
Green Bay last year, Moss burned the Packers for 13 catches, 343
yards and three touchdowns. In those two contests, Minnesota
compiled 885 yards of total offense and 65 points.
</P>
<P>
   The demolition of their defense through the air led the Packers
to completely revamp their defense in the off season. Green Bay
drafted cornerbacks Mike McKenzie, Edwards and Fred Vinson. Under
the new coordinator Emmitt Thomas, Green Bay is much more
aggressive on defense than it was last season.
</P>
<P>
   Something worked. Moss was nonexistent for more than three
quarters. ``They bumped Randy on almost every play,'' said Carter,
who had four catches for 85 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The game could have taken a dramatic turn in the Vikings' favor
if not for a close call involving Moss. Early in the third quarter,
with the score tied, 10-10, Minnesota faced a third-and-goal at the
Green Bay 4. Cunningham threw a fade pass to the corner of the end
zone, where Moss was sandwiched by McKenzie and safety Darren
Sharper.
</P>
<P>
   Moss made a spectacular, leaping one-handed grab, but bobbled it
on the way down. It was a close call, but the officials ruled that
Moss never had possession. Green challenged the call, but it was
not overturned.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, Cunningham went to Moss again. Same corner.
Almost the same coverage. This time, the pass was long and Moss
failed to haul it in. The Vikings settled for a 22-yard Gary
Anderson field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay later added a 35-yard field goal to tie the score at
13-13 late in the third quarter. Both Cunningham (18 of 32 for 244
yards, two touchdowns and two interceptions) and Favre (24 of 39
for 304 yards, one touchdown and no interceptions) struggled to
consistently move their offenses. Each would move his team
downfield, only to stall on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Moss finally made an impact on the game with two minutes left.
Cunningham drilled a pass 10 yards to a waiting Moss in the end
zone, and the Vikings took a 24-20 lead. Moss finished the game
with two catches for 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Then Favre performed his heroics. As if the two-time Super Bowl
winner was not already considered great, he added a spectacular
comeback to his resume. Elway may be forgotten sooner rather than
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
