<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-REDSKINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISTAKES RUIN JETS IN LOSS TO REDSKINS, 27-20 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It wasn't Vinny and it wasn't pretty and
although it nearly worked, the Jets were left in confusion and
their coach was left enraged.
</P>
<P>
   An improved performance by the Jets' impoverished offense was
wasted in the final quarter Sunday when the Redskins took advantage
of some charity and a couple of breaks for a come-from-behind 27-20
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The loss shocked some of the newer Jets, who had come here
confident that the team would be, at the least, a Super Bowl
contender. The Jets are heading to Denver for a rematch of last
season's American Conference championship game, but under quite
different circumstances. Neither the Jets nor the Broncos have won
a game.
</P>
<P>
   For the Jets to get to the Super Bowl now they would have to
become the first team to make it after starting 0-3. That start
represents their longest losing stretch since the infamous 1996
season of 1-15 and the longest of the Bill Parcells regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came off the chain,'' was one Jets description of how
Parcells reacted in the locker room when the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets led by 17-13 with 8 minutes 10 seconds to go, but
everything went the Redskins' way from there. First, Washington
built an 80-yard touchdown drive around two pass interference calls
on cornerback Ray Mickens. Five plays later, the Redskins recovered
quarterback Rick Mirer's fumble to set up another touchdown and
then held their breath while an apparent touchdown by receiver
Keyshawn Johnson was overruled and a possible fumble by their
running back Stephen Davis was ruled a dead ball.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Parcells said, ``This is the first time in many years
I'll have to bite my lips.'' He may have been alluding to
officials' decisions, but he refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   He was not so mysterious about his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall I thought we played a little better offensively and
defensively,'' he said. ``But it comes down to, in the end, you've
got to be able to make plays, and a couple of guys were just not
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Mickens is the newest millionaire, having signed
a deal that Parcells described last Friday as worth at least $6
million for three years. But Mickens is not the usual starter at
right cornerback. That is Otis Smith's job, and he remains
sidelined with a broken collarbone. Mickens was tagged with three
penalties on the two touchdown drives, and four penalties for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer finally showed signs that he might become a credible
replacement for Vinny Testaverde, who is out for the season.
Mirer's touchdown on the Jets' first possession Sunday was only his
second in 66 drives and nine games, dating from the end of the 1996
season. In his first 14 drives as a Jet he had produced one field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Mirer employed seven receivers, he had Curtis Martin
and Bernie Parmalee running effectively, and he connected on three
pass plays greater than 20 yards. Overall, he hit on 17 of 31
passes for 227 yards with one touchdown and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown pass came on a 35-yard connection to Dedric Ward
with 7:42 to go in the first quarter. The second touchdown came on
a 3-yard run by Martin and by the final period, the Jets were
nursing a 14-13 lead. The Redskins' offense, which had generated
touchdowns on its first three possessions in the 50-point outburst
against the Giants last Sunday, had only one at that point.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets committed five penalties in the first half alone,
and yet another one early in the final period proved costly.
Martin's 11-yard run to the Redskins' 5 was negated by a holding
call on Blake Spence, and the Jets wound up with a field goal by
John Hall.
</P>
<P>
   On the next possession, Washington's quarterback, Brad Johnson,
sent receiver Albert Connell against Mickens. Connell, who led all
wide receivers with five catches, was pushed on the play by
Mickens, who was tagged with a 35-yard penalty.
</P>
<P>
   That took the ball to the Jets' 18. Two plays later, Mickens was
penalized again, moving the ball from the 11 to the 4. From there,
Davis scored the second of his three touchdowns to put the Redskins
ahead, 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   On the next series, defensive end Kenard Lang stripped the ball
from Mirer, resulting in the sixth sack and Mirer's second
turnover. It positioned the Redskins on the Jets' 21. Johnson and
Connell connected again to take the ball to the 7 as the Redskins
declined another penalty against Mickens. One play later Davis
swept in for his third touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But on the following kickoff, Kevin Williams returned the ball
81 yards. Mirer then connected with a slanting Keyshawn Johnson for
a 16-yard touchdown. Replay officials overruled the call, however,
saying he did not have two feet down.
</P>
<P>
   Hall kicked a field goal and the Jets tried an onside kick, but
the Skins recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Davis tried to run out the clock, but on the third run, with
less than a minute remaining, the ball squirted loose as he was hit
by Bryan Cox. Cornerback Aaron Glenn picked it up, but was whistled
back. The play was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what can happen when you put yourself in that
position,'' said a beleaguered Jumbo Elliott later.
</P>
<P>
   Jets linebacker Roman Phifer, who left the Rams for the lure of
victory, said, ``I hate to say it, but I've been through this many
a year, and I thought it was behind me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
