<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UPSETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST CAROLINA FINDS THERE IS CALM IN THE EYE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a weekend for Ducks, for the Cardinal and especially for
Pirates who had survived a real hurricane to stun a bunch of the
football kind. There were comebacks and star turns by third-string
kickers and backup quarterbacks. It was a college football weekend
when the big hearts of the little guys triumphed.
</P>
<P>
   It was pretty great. Eight _ count them _ eight top-25 teams
were upended Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of them were beaten either by no-name teams or ones that
hardly figure to inspire ardor in sports-talk radio habitats.
</P>
<P>
   No victory was more dramatic than East Carolina's second-half
rally from a 20-point deficit that toppled the No. 9 Miami
Hurricanes, 27-23, as well as the goal posts of a borrowed field.
The Pirates were given zero chance against a reborn glamour team.
</P>
<P>
   They represented a basketball showcase, Conference U.S.A. They
practiced on high school fields in South Carolina the past week
because flooding and damage from Hurricane Floyd had displaced them
from their campus in Greenville, N.C. They even moved the game 85
miles west to North Carolina State's home field in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pirates fell behind by 23-3 in the third quarter to the
mighty Canes _ a team that had already upset Ohio State and had
come a play away from beating No. 2 Penn State _ no one would have
blamed them if they had packed it in.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, East Carolina  &UR; c &LR; oach Steve Logan watched his team turn
_ as he put it _ the tension of the past week into passion. The
Pirates (4-0) reeled off 24 straight points, capped by quarterback
David Garrard's 27-yard touchdown pass to Keith Stokes with a
little less than five minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to get a win to go home with because I knew
it's going to be a lot of troubles when we get back there,'' said
Garrard, who was 20 of 27 passing for 222 yards in the second half.
``This will help build us a little bit, and the guys will be a
little more happier going back home.''
</P>
<P>
   You could hardly blame the East Carolina faithful who stormed
the field and ripped down both goal posts at Carter-Finley Stadium
in celebration after downing the highest-ranked team the Pirates
have beaten. In fact, don't be surprised if a Save the Goal Posts
fund emerges to repay the Pirates for providing a cathartic moment
for a battered region.
</P>
<P>
   Just as interesting on a weekend when the nation's top eight
teams impressively kept themselves in championship contention was
the way teams in the bottom half of the rankings exposed themselves
as overrated, inconsistent or plain careless.
</P>
<P>
   In the only game between top 25 teams, No. 4 Michigan handled
No. 20 Wisconsin, 21-16, and, in holding Ron Dayne without a yard
rushing in the second half, proved the Badgers to be a
one-dimensional, second-tier team.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama (3-1) beat No. 14 Arkansas, 35-28, and probably saved
 &UR; c &LR; oach Mike Dubose's job for another week. It was too late,
however, to save the job of Athletic Director Bob Bockrath, who was
fired last week in the wake of Louisiana Tech's victory over the
Crimson Tide. While East Carolina was winning on North Carolina
State's home field, the No. 25 Wolfpack was losing on the road to
its neighbor Wake Forest, 31-7.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of wannabe powers from the new Mountain West Conference
were upset as well, when Virginia dumped No. 17 Brigham Young,
45-40, and Wyoming beat No. 24 Air Force, 10-7.
</P>
<P>
   And not that any more evidence was necessary, but the West Coast
teams proved again that they are an entertaining mess and
nonfactors in the Bowl Championship Series. The 16th-ranked
Southern California Trojans and 18th-ranked UCLA Bruins were the
latest Pacific-10 heavies to be embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon Ducks (3-1) outlasted the Trojans, 33-30, after three
overtimes.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Frankel, Oregon's third kicker of the game, converted the
27-yard game-winner. This was after Nathan Villegas, the Ducks'
All-America kicker, tied the game on a 26-yard field goal with 30
seconds left in regulation. His ebullient teammates hoisted him in
the air but, as he was being let down, a still celebrating Duck
banged into his kicking knee. Now he may be out for several weeks
with ligament damage.
</P>
<P>
   In the first overtime, Oregon let its kickoff specialist, Dan
Katz, try a 33-yarder. He missed. But the Trojans' David Newbury
set the stage for Frankel by missing three potential game-winning
field goals _ one in regulation, one in the first extra period and
another in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just self-destructed at every turn,'' USC  &UR; c &LR; oach Paul
Hackett said of his 2-1 team. ``We lost every opportunity under the
sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The hottest team out West is one that gave up 69 points to Texas
in its opener, Stanford (3-1). The backup Joe Borchard came off the
bench to throw five touchdown passes _ including a Pac-10 record
98-yarder _ to beat the Bruins, 42-32. A right fielder for the
Cardinal's baseball team, he entered the game in the second quarter
after the starter Todd Husak was banged up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd go in and run the ball,'' said an unfazed
Borchard, who led Stanford to its first 3-0 conference start since
1971. ``I'm still a backup, my job is still just to be ready when
called upon, but I'm glad to get the opportunity to win.''
</P>
<P>
   So were the small programs in the netherworld of the college
football galaxy and their second- and third-teamers. The big
victories on strange fields and glorious cameos can be just as
uplifting as hyped showdowns between the powers. It's pretty great.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
