<HEADER>
A6977 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SALVAGE-AZR &LR;      09-26 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS WANT TOUGHER RULES ON SALVAGED-CAR SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The almost-new, shiny-white Jeep Cherokee looked
awfully sweet when Warren Hill paid $23,024 for it at a Fresno,
Calif., auto dealership in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It even smelled new,'' Hill said in an interview on Sept.
24th. ``I thought, `Why would somebody have traded this in?' ''
</P>
<P>
   When he tried to trade it in himself two years later, Hill, a
telecommunications engineer, found out why. He said records
revealed the car had been in a terrible collision before he bought
it, that its left side had to be welded back together and that ``it
was structurally unsound . . . it was worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hill's case is among those being cited by dozens of
``lemon'' purchasers and consumer groups wondering why Congress
can't seem to pass a tough bill to prevent such rebuilt wrecks from
being sold to unwitting customers. Much of the groups' frustration
has emerged in letters to Senate Commerce Committee Chairman John
McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's committee has jurisdiction over the issue, and many
organizations, including the U.S. Department of Transportation,
aren't satisfied with the legislation he has co-sponsored to
address the problem. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., is
the bill's prime sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's Republican and Democratic staff members have
been bickering over whether the bill is sufficient. Meanwhile,
Public Campaign, a citizens' advocacy group, has accused Lott and
other co-sponsors of being influenced by auto-dealer lobbyists to
make sure the bill is a weak one, a charge that McCain denies.
</P>
<P>
   McCain believes the bill, while not perfect, ``represents a good
step forward in protecting consumers,'' said his spokeswoman, Nancy
Ives.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tug-of-war over the legislation has gotten personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who was married for 20 years to a naval officer who
served over 22 years, I implore you to reconsider your
co-sponsorship,'' began a Sept. 7 letter to McCain from Rosemary
Shahan, a California consumer advocate. ``I know from experience
how auto dealers target enlisted service personnel for the sales of
wrecked vehicles, and (this bill) would make their predatory
practices even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a presidential candidate, is a formal naval aviator
whose father and grandfather were both admirals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are lured into buying what seems like a bargain, when
the real price of making it safe to operate is hidden, and beyond
what they can afford,'' Shahan wrote. ``Please think of the
families, who are already stressed from long tours and being
separated from their families and friends, being subjected to all
that goes along with being sold one of those junkers.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Shahan don't differ on the problem, just the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that unscrupulous sellers are sometimes able to
hide a car's accident history by transferring its title from state
to state. Because states have varying standards and designations
for listing a car as ``salvage,'' the sellers shop around until
they get a title that grossly underestimates the damage. Sometimes,
the titles are tampered with to eliminate phrases such as
``Previous Damage'' that would tip off buyers that the cars had to
be restored.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona law requires a special ``rest/salvg'' notation on the
title of rebuilt salvage vehicles, so consumers are made aware of
the car's history. Still, some Phoenix residents have tried to
tamper with the titles of restored wrecks, according to police. And
there is evidence that salvage vehicles bought in Arizona have been
transported to other states that don't require such a specific
notation, according to the California-based Consumers for Auto
Reliability and Safety. That practice is called ``title washing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lott-McCain bill would provide states incentives, in the
form of motor-vehicle grants, for ensuring that titles of totaled
cars are labeled ``salvage,'' and that the cars themselves are also
marked. It would also set uniform standards on what defines a
salvage car.
</P>
<P>
   States would be encouraged, but not required, to comply. Such a
voluntary approach ``gets around the very real concerns that states
and the Supreme Court have raised about Congress requiring states
to legislatively adopt federal regulations,'' Lott said on the
Senate floor in May.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, who plan a press conference in Washington, D.C., on
Wednesday to list their concerns, contend that the measure isn't
forceful enough. They also object to a provision exempting cars
that are more than 6 years old from having to be labeled as
salvage.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the cars bought by less-well-off Americans, people
who are already more vulnerable to used-car scam artists,'' said a
column written last year by Public Campaign, which studies campaign
contributions to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great example of the problem of money in politics,''
Eric Schmeltzer, a Public Campaign spokesman, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The group says domestic auto dealers and their political action
committees contributed more than $7 million to congressional
candidates and political parties from January 1995 to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Schmeltzer said the bill victimized ``those who can't afford to
give in the same numbers as auto dealers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's backers said the 6-year-old exemption is needed
because too many used cars would otherwise qualify as salvage even
if they weren't totaled. Under the bill, cars with damages
amounting to at least 75 percent of their worth would qualify for a
salvage label.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it (the car) is a $1,000 value, it would be minor damage''
that would push it over the threshold and cause it to be marked as
salvage, said Larry Greenberg, a vice president of the American
Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators, which supports the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was cleared by McCain's committee in June. It could
still be amended to address some of the criticism if it is voted on
by the full Senate this year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at (202) 662-7264 or at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
