<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS TAKE BIG STEP FORWARD WITHOUT GALLOWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ For three surreal minutes at the start of the game
Sunday, Jon Kitna was standing on the sideline. The Seahawks
quarterback kept looking out at the field, where everyone except
the Seahawks offense was scoring touchdowns for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna could not believe what he was seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny,'' Kitna said after the Hawks' 29-10 whupping of
the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Center) Kevin Glover finally came over to me and said, `Are
we ever going to get to play?' '' Kitna said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's great. I mean, to walk out onto the field and have
a lead like that before you ever take one snap, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, it was hard to believe that everything good Sunday was
happening to the Hawks. Usually, it seems, it's the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure is a little different,'' Kitna said. ``I mean, when
you're down 26-0, you're pretty much feeling out of it. But when
you're up 26-0, it's funny how you look at the other guys and think
they're just a couple of breaks away from coming back. Things
happen fast in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to an opportunistic start, fueled by Merton Hanks'
interception return for a touchdown and Charlie Rogers' 94-yard TD
punt return, the Hawks were up 14-0 with only 3:20 gone and before
their offense had even stepped onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach said jobs were on the line this week, and that is
definitely something we all understood,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Could these have been the same hard-luck Hawks who came into
this Steel City stadium exactly one year ago and lost a 13-10
dogfight in which the old Hawks were clearly shown how stagnant,
static and ineffective they were?
</P>
<P>
   Were these the same guys whose NFL hopes and expectations always
fell flat or short or were riddled full of folly?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this a franchise for which over the last decade everything
that could go wrong usually did, and no one could ever quite
explain it?
</P>
<P>
   And isn't this the team that lost ugly to the Lions in its home
opener and last week required a second-half comeback against the
Bears to avoid an 0-2 blemish on the face of the Mike Holmgren era?
</P>
<P>
   Well, that face is a little sweeter and it's smiling now. It is
a face flush with promise.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in what has been the intimidation palace of Three Rivers
Stadium, it was the Hawks who turned the tables not only on the
proud Steelers but also on themselves by rupturing a long-standing
aura of underachievement.
</P>
<P>
   The defense and special teams came out smoking, crushing the
life out of the Steelers and erasing the entire Pittsburgh game
plan. Meanwhile, the new Hawks offense also started to click _
surprising and encouraging since that offense is without its
game-breaking speedster whose contract holdout continues to fester.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Galloway may be missing in action with no end in sight, but
the longer this ridiculous standoff goes on, the more he has to
lose _ not the Hawks, who seem to be making good progress in their
new system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun. This is exciting. This is the creativity that a
Mike Holmgren can bring to this team,'' said receiver Mike
Pritchard, who had a team-high six catches for 90 yards _ including
an eye-opening, 51-yard strike from Kitna on the Seahawks' first
offensive play of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, what a difference from last year. We're moving the
ball around so much more. This offense calls on everyone, whereas
last year we were so predictable in what we were doing,'' Pritchard
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Pritchard said Kitna was the most confident and poised
he has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   And the Holmgren offense is so diverse, Pritchard said, that
Galloway should be concerned about missing out on an opportunity to
learn and grow with a team, since the Hawks seem ready to take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine him in this offense,'' Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're moving around. You're keeping the defense on its heels.
In all fairness to Joey, last year he would get double-teamed
because we were so predictable. But in this offense, you couldn't
double-team a guy like that. There is so much possibility that can
happen, and for me, to tell you the truth, I'm taking advantage of
the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Hawks never did score an offensive touchdown, instead
sending in Todd Peterson to attempt six field goals, Pritchard said
the offense was executing much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting to the line quicker. We're eliminating the
motion penalties. We're starting to move the ball up and down the
field better. Now, the next step is to get it in the end zone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Galloway sits home in Columbus, Ohio, waiting for some
lightning bolt to open the Seahawks bank vault for him, the rest of
the team isn't missing the beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand to a point,'' Pritchard said of Galloway's
holdout, ``but not when it comes to one guy being bigger than the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are moving forward, getting a taste of what kind of
banquet they could be feasting on if Holmgren gets his way with
this Seahawks team that appears ready to break through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next week is huge,'' Kitna said about the showdown with the
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our first AFC West game, and we've got to get a leg up
on that. If we can go 7-0 the rest of the way at home, we'll get a
leg up on everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in as far back as any good Seahawks fan can
remember, there's good reason for optimism. The Hawks are starting
to really move.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
