<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6981 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-QUAYLE-AZR &LR;      09-26 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE QUITS RACE `NO COMPLAINTS, NO BITTERNESS, JUST
DISAPPOINTMENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES AND CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Former Vice President Dan Quayle ended his long-shot
bid for the White House on Sept. 26th, a victim of his inability to
raise enough money to compete against the juggernaut of the
front-runner, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle arrived at the decision after determining that even a
good finish in New Hampshire's early GOP primary election followed
by moderate success in fund-raising would not be enough to beat out
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle will formally announce his exit from the 2000
presidential election at a late-morning news conference today at
the Arizona Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just decided, `I'm not going to hang around and wring my
hands and continue to ask people to go out and raise money from me
when I don't see my way through to winning,' '' said Kyle
McSlarrow, Quayle's campaign chairman. ``He has always accepted
that it was a long shot, but he realized that, looking at it
rationally, that even if we did well in New Hampshire it just
wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision came just as Quayle appeared to be making some
headway. A nationwide CNN/Time poll released Sept. 24th showed
Quayle running a distant second to Bush (53 percent to 9 percent).
But it appeared to be too little headway coming too late in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a small meeting Sept. 25th at Quayle's home in Scottsdale
that included only Quayle, his wife, Marilyn, and McSlarrow, the
candidate decided to pull the plug, a move that surprised even some
on his own staff.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, after attending church with his wife, the former
vice president announced his decision to staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The realities undermined the campaign, and the realities of
this case are money,'' McSlarrow said, but added that Quayle is not
bitter about having to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't in the cards,'' McSlarrow said. ``There are no
complaints, no bitterness. Just disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   One campaign aide blamed Quayle's inability to gain traction
against the front-runners on his own unwillingness to engage in
negative campaigning and his hesitancy when it came to
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most decent guy in the race, and he was unwilling
to do some the things that all of his advisers told him,'' said
Fred Davis, Quayle's media adviser. ``He wouldn't go to the slimy
depths that it takes to raise money and wouldn't attack his
opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle becomes the fourth candidate to leave the race. Rep. John
Kasich of Ohio, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and Sen. Bob
Smith of New Hampshire exited the GOP primary earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   One beneficiary of Quayle's departure may be Arizona Sen. John
McCain, who may now become the race's undisputed authority on
foreign policy matters, according to one Quayle aide.
</P>
<P>
   `McCain can immediately claim the foreign policy mantle now,''
said Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, Quayle's pollster.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest factors in Quayle's decision, according to
Davis, was his distaste for repeatedly going to friends for money
and support in a race that increasingly looks locked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, it began to look like an imposition,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Quayle will likely wait some time before deciding
whom to endorse for president. For now, they said Quayle will look
to become more involved in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a tough venture and an emotional venture, and I
think he wants to move on to something else,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's campaign efforts had looked increasingly gloomy after
the August Iowa Straw Poll, where he finished in eighth place,
behind conservative talk-show host Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   The showing was considered devastating for the former vice
president, and he took it seriously, telling his staff they would
have to rethink almost every aspect of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Quayle was struggling to keep his campaign
liquid, having to borrow from banks against federal matching funds,
which were due to arrive in January. As of this month, the campaign
had raised $4 million. Bush's war chest has reportedly ballooned to
more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's exit left many wondering what it will mean to the GOP
field. A number of Quayle's supporters said the decision will
benefit Bush, who now has one less competitor to worry about in his
so-far unimpeded march to the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it clearly strengthens George Bush,'' said Indiana
Sen. Dan Coats, national co-chairman of Quayle's campaign. ``One by
one, he is eliminating some of his stronger opponents, and I think,
clearly, this is going to be perceived as another feather in his
cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Coats said he had hoped to see Quayle remain in the race longer,
among other reasons, to allow the candidate to rehabilitate himself
in the eyes of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel bad that Dan did not have an opportunity to
re-present himself to the American people so that they could see
who he really was,'' Coats said. ``He outlined a very solid agenda
for the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Quayle's move may have caught his supporters off guard,
many political observers said they had expected it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only surprise was that he didn't recognize immediately
after the Iowa Straw Poll that it was over, and it really never
started,'' said Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the
University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who watched his career nearly consumed in 1988 by media
reports about his high-profile gaffes and privileged background,
ran a traditional Republican campaign. His campaign issued routine
press releases on issues such as U.S. foreign policy on China, and
Quayle himself spent considerable time giving speeches on
conservative themes.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidate was nonetheless unable to make a dent in
Bush's large lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, deep down, Quayle thought he could be the next
Richard Nixon _ that he could confound the critics and achieve a
comeback,'' Sabato said. ``His image was so damaged within his own
party that he was just never a credible candidate.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
